<HEADLINE>
HERNANDEZ SUBJECT OF CONDUCT INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles City Councilman Mike Hernandez
confirmed on Friday that a panel of attorneys and former judges
will review an allegation that he sexually harassed a former aide.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, still on probation after pleading no contest to
cocaine possession last year, denied the charge. He declined to
discuss details of the case, saying it is a personnel matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anything improper happened and I want to let the
(review) process take place,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators who searched Hernandez's City Hall office
shortly after his arrest on drug charges found sexually explicit
videotapes and other material.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel Department head William Fujioka, whose office received
the sexual harassment complaint, refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council voted in 1996 to create a Special Committee on
Investigative Oversight to review any allegations of misconduct
against elected city officials and department heads and decide
whether an outside firm should be hired to conduct a formal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The council voted Wednesday to activate the panel by approving a
list of people who might serve on the reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was created after women staffers for City Councilman
Nate Holden charged they had nowhere to go, short of the courts, to
press allegations of sexual harassment against Holden.
</P>
<P>
   Holden still faces a possible trial in one of the lawsuits by a
former aide, and the city has spent more than $1 million already to
defend the councilman.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of the special panel was to resolve issues earlier
before they turn into costly litigation.
</P>
<P>
   The panel will be made up of two retired judges, two law school
professors and a member of the American Arbitration Association.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a group that had launched a recall drive against
Hernandez after his arrest last year failed to collect enough
signatures by this week's deadline to qualify the recall for the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
