<HEADER>
A7642 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVALANCHE-RAINER-SPI &LR;      06-13 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVALANCHE-RAINER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY AVALANCHE TRIGGERED BY CLIMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE and KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGMIRE _ Tired but elated after scaling Mount Rainier, guide
Tyler Forman was crossing a treacherous ice face when he stumbled,
setting in a motion a deadly avalanche that swept nine of his
companions down the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's avalanche was ``triggered by my foot,'' bemoaned
Forman, still numb from the mishap that cost the life of a client
and injured eight others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My world's been turned upside down: my foot slipped, the snow
was wet enough, and that's what triggered the slide.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby climbers spotted the fast-moving snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We yelled, and they looked up, but they couldn't move fast
enough,'' Jeff Fisher, 38, of Burnsville, Minn., said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard people screaming `help,' screaming that they were
cold, screaming that they were going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, it was like tumbling bodies and they just kept
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The likely cause of the worst accident of the climbing season
was confirmed by Chief National Park Ranger John Krambrink, adding
the findings were ``preliminary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure looks like a team may have set off the avalanche,''
Krambrink said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Nestler, an avid outdoorsman with limited alpine
climbing experience, was carried by the heavy, wet snow more than
100 feet. He was battered from the fall. Worse, he dangled from a
climbing rope for hours while icy snowmelt dripped on him from
above.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old engineer from Connecticut died of exposure
before he could be rescued.
</P>
<P>
   Eight others received less severe injuries ranging from
abrasions to broken bones to hypothermia. All were treated and
released from local hospitals by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers, guides and rescuers agreed that the toll could have
climbed much higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we lost an individual climber, it could have been
so much worse,'' said 28-year-old park ranger Michael Gauthier.
``Everybody acted with amazing swiftness.''
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier was one of the first on the scene. He had been enjoying
a day off at the mountain's summit when his radio crackled at 2:11
p.m. with word of the avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier strapped on his snowboard and raced down the mountain.
Twenty-six minutes and 3,000 feet later, he was at the site about
11,000 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Nestler, who died on the mountain, was among a group of 16
students on a five-day climbing seminar lead by seven guides.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Nestler's death, there was little finger pointing Friday
among park officials and experienced mountaineers, who understand
the risks of a sport played out in the thin mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mountaineering has inherent risks,'' said Lou Whittaker, the
legendary climber whose company, Rainier Mountaineering Inc., was
hired to guide the student climbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the lure of mountaineering _ the risks. How
can you justify it? The mountaineer can justify it, but it is
difficult on others,'' Whittaker said at a news conference Friday
at Paradise, at the peak's 5,400-foot level.
</P>
<P>
   Krambrink, chief ranger, added: ``We know we will continue to
have accidents unless we ban people from the mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened on the mountain was mostly luck _ good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   The climbers had sunny, warm weather. But that followed bad
weather. In the 24 hours before the avalanche, an inch of rain fell
at Paradise, said Garth Ferber of the Northwest Weather and
Avalanche Center. It fell as snow in the higher elevations.
</P>
<P>
   The sun warmed the snow, making it unstable. ``People look out
and see that the weather is good. But what they have to consider is
what has occurred in the recent past,'' Ferber said.
</P>
<P>
   The group of Rainier Mountaineering climbers had reached
Disappointment Cleaver _ a rock outcropping that separates two
glaciers _ around 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Park rangers often advise first-time climbers to be off the most
dangerous parts of the mountain by early afternoon. On a warm day,
the snow on the higher elevations of the mountain gets soft and
conditions can become more hazardous.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's temperatures may have soared to as high as 80 degrees
above the 10,000-foot level, Krambrink said.
</P>
<P>
   Whittaker, however, dismissed timing as a crucial issue. There
is no hard and fast rule for when to be on a particular part of the
mountain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche occurred when most accidents happen on the
mountain _ as climbers descend. Typically, they are tired, and
having successfully reached the top, they may also have let their
guard down, said Gus Bush, operations chairman for Tacoma Mountain
Rescue, a volunteer group that helped in Thursday's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   But Ephram Ulmer who was on the mountain Thursday with another
of Whittaker's groups, saw no carelessness. ``I respected the
mountain when I went out,'' said Ulmer, 51, of Columbia, S.C. ``And
there is no one in any of groups that did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the climbers managed to scramble away from the onrushing
show. Others were not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people go right by me. The avalanche was just a few feet
from hitting us,'' said another member of the class, Mark Hunter,
39, of Westport, Conn. ``I heard yelling, and we thought we might
not make it.'' Hunter said he still has not decided whether he'll
return to climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Guide Ruth Mahre, 25, of White Pass, was at the upper end of one
of the ropes. Below her, Nestler dangled. She secured the rope from
which four climbers clung to Disappointment Cleaver:
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody moved it was all over for all of us. ... I wasn't
the heroine, I was just lucky,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know you're flying off rocks, and the snow is shoving
you down the mountain and you can't get an anchor and people are
pulling you down, you don't think you'll live,'' Mahre said.
</P>
<P>
   But now some good luck was coming the climbers' way. The rope
that held Mahre, Nestler and others was holding, even though the
slide had frayed it.
</P>
<P>
   From about 800 feet above, another climber saw the slide and
pulled out her cellular telephone to alert the rangers. It was 2:11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five years ago, you wouldn't have had cellphones, and
one of the victims would have had to climb down to Camp Muir for
help,'' said Gombu Nawang, who has climbed the mountain dozens of
times.
</P>
<P>
   In another stroke of good fortune, rescuers already were on the
mountain to help a climber who had broken a leg in a slide on Kautz
Glacier early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The weather remained clear as they worked to secure ropes.
Helicopters could get in, but none of the injured had yet to be
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the window of good weather had vanished, the rescue
had begun. Climbers were pulled up or rescuers helped them up by
descending on other ropes, Gauthier said.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuers saw Nestler go in and out of consciousness. By 7 p.m.,
the exposure and the freezing water that had dripped on him for
hours had taken his life.
</P>
<P>
   The injured came off Rainier on Thursday night. Those who
escaped the avalanche got to Camp Muir before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Cowen, one of the climbers who witnessed the slide, said
she was still shaking. ``My biggest fear about this trip was an
avalanche.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back up but not for a while. You think, `Is it worth
the risk?' But I love the mountains. It's more dangerous to drive
on the freeway than to climb Mount Rainier.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who were injured hurried down the mountain Friday,
arriving at Paradise tanned but physically and emotionally spent.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, other climbers _ these eager and rested _ were preparing
for their chance to climb Rainier. About 10,000 people try to scale
the mountain each year.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bills of Highland, Utah, was preparing to climb Rainier.
Much of it is so easy, he said, it's like hiking. It makes you
forget how dangerous it can be, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, Bills, 43, was bringing a cellular telephone
with him to reassure his wife that he was okay.
</P>
<P>
   The avalanche did not affect disabled climber Pete Rieke of
Pasco, who is using a hand-cranked snow vehicle to climb Rainier.
His party was camping at the mountain's 13,000-foot level Friday
and planning to resume the ascent at about 10 p.m., when
sun-softened snow begins to firm up again.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was another sunny day, even prettier than Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even on pretty days the best climbers are at risk in an
avalanche, said climbing school owner Whittacre, citing the 1979
death in a Rainier slide of veteran mountaineer Willi Unsoeld, one
of the first Americans to climb Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rainier has a lot of secrets,'' he said. ``We're always
learning, but it is indifferent. We love it but it doesn't
necessarily love us.''
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from the Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
