<SLUG> BC-GRAIN-BLAST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE FADES FOR MAN MISSING IN BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN PETTERSON and OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAYSVILLE, Kan. _ Hopes for the survival of the last missing
victim of a grain-elevator explosion faded Friday, the fifth day of
rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who had remained upbeat all week found it tough to
avoid the specter of a grim conclusion to the round-the-clock
search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is really against us now,'' Ken Cox, division chief of
the Sedgwick County Fire Department, said Friday evening. ``It's
hard for us to be as optimistic as we were before.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat was against rescuers too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really affected our speed,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers had to limit their activity in a tunnel to less
than an hour at a time. Temperatures near 100 degrees, and the
workers' heavy, protective clothing, made conditions dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   And as rescuers grimly noted, those oppressive conditions would
threaten any worker still alive and trapped in the facility.
Medical personnel regularly checked blood pressures and heart rates
of rescuers to make sure they were within acceptable limits.
</P>
<P>
   By 10 p.m., two rescue crews were working toward each other in
the tunnel, and were within 30 feet. They could see one another
through the debris.
</P>
<P>
   After shoring up holes in the ceiling, Cox said, the rescuers
begin removing the grain in the remaining, unexplored area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the void places we expected to be in there,''
Cox said, suggesting there was less chance that the missing man
might have been able to find a pocket of air to help keep him
alive.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, authorities were weighing the risk to the
rescuers' safety against the chance of finding the missing worker
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the remains of three other workers have been pulled
from the tunnel beneath the DeBruce Grain elevator, southwest of
Wichita. An explosion, believed to have been caused by grain dust,
made a shambles of the huge storage complex.
</P>
<P>
   With the two workers who were found dead immediately after the
explosion, the death toll now is five. Five other explosion victims
have been hospitalized. One is in fair condition, two are critical
and two are serious.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Duarte and Jose P. Ortiz died instantly. Services for Ortiz
are scheduled for today.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of Victor Castaneda and Raymondo Diaz-Vela were
identified this week after they were removed from the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   One other body was found in the tunnel but had not been
identified Friday. Rescuers did not release the name of the man
thought to still be in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Still unaccounted for are Noel Najera and Howard Goin.
</P>
<P>
   As the week dragged on, fewer family members maintained their
quiet vigil at Oatville Elementary School, about 1 miles from the
blast site.
</P>
<P>
   And optimism at the school became harder to find.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross coordinator Mike Wemmer, who has spent time with the
families at the school, said he could see the change. The mood in
the school started out somber, broken occasionally by hopeful news,
he said. That hope later faded.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no sign the rescuers were ready to quit. On Friday
afternoon, a staffer with the Federal Emergency Management Agency
team stopped by a Wal-Mart store to load up on 20 boxes of menthol
and cherry throat lozenges to relieve dryness caused by the grain
dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty caustic stuff after a few days,'' said Jim
Gruenberg, a member of the agency team.
</P>
<P>
   And they weren't ready to let go of the chance that the last
worker could be alive in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's always hope,'' said rescue worker Bret Davis
shortly after he climbed out of the stifling tunnel and ended his
12-hour shift.
</P>
<P>
   Another worker, Dennis Clark, said if he could send a message to
the family of the missing man it would be ``not to give up hope.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still trying to recover a victim,'' he said. ``We have
no way of knowing if this person is alive or dead. If they are
alive, we certainly want to get them out and get them taken care
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take whatever comes. If we find a deceased
victim, that's what we have to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
