<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE MAKES FOURTH SEATTLE VISIT IN 18 MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY and LARRY LANGE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vice President Al Gore delivered a barrel of political
tributes and bounty of favorable economic statistics Friday night
during a very political visit designed to boost the reelection of
Washington Democratic Sen. Patty Murray.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ventured onto a controversial subject only
once with a call to defeat Initiative 200 on the November ballot, a
measure that would eliminate the state's affirmative action
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``America's diversity can be our edge in a global economy ...
Initiative 200 here in the state of Washington puts all that at
risk,'' Gore told about 300 people at a Democratic reception.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's visit was his fourth to Seattle in 18 months. It followed
closely the pattern of a visit in December, with an event at a
public school followed by the day's true business _ political
fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was sealed off from the press. He answered no
questions and did not talk about such controversies as the Justice
Department suit against Microsoft or President Clinton's upcoming
trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton, who never loses a chance to work rope lines or
greet bystanders, Gore was driven without pause from one
invitation-only event to another.
</P>
<P>
   One incident marred Gore's smooth passage to a town meeting on
education issues at Hazel Valley Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran Seattle motorcycle officer, Allen Carr, was injured in
an accident. Gore's motorcade did not stop, but the vice
president's ambulance did provide quick treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit an oil patch and just wiped out: He suffered a broken
arm, a broken leg and a broken rib. He's talking and I hope he'll
be fine,'' said Seattle Mayor Paul Schell, who had his van pull out
of the motorcade to talk to the injured officer.
</P>
<P>
   At the elementary school, Gore touted a program championed by
Murray _ legislation intended to increase the number of public
school teachers by 100,000 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to bring the ratio of
student-to-teachers down so each teacher can spend more time with
students,'' Gore declared.
</P>
<P>
   Gore moved around in the sweltering gymnasium, asking the
grammar school students why it is important to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Timothy Marshall. I like books because you can make
fine movies from the words,'' one student told Gore.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of more than 60 people, most of them neighborhood
residents, gathered across the street to watch Gore enter and leave
the school. The crowd was peaceful and relaxed, mostly curious.
</P>
<P>
   Two local members of the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue
brought several large signs. The largest showed an aborted fetus,
others carried various anti-abortion slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Several who watched Gore's performance inside the gym said the
vice president seemed livelier than they imagined. They said he
struck a chord discussing education and getting pupils to talk
about the school's special ``Success for All'' reading program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like him,'' said Kerry Pierce, mother of two children at the
school. ``I think he's gotten some life in the last couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Wheeler of Olympia, who works in a state literacy program,
said she was surprised to see a more animated Gore than the one
she'd heard about. ``I think he's very good-looking and I loved how
he handled the kids. I was rather surprised ... he does have a
reputation for being maybe a little stilted.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of those who emerged from the talk said they'll likely
vote for Gore if he's a presidential candidate in two years,
believing his commitment to education, more teachers and smaller
class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally am better off now than before (Gore and Clinton)
took office,'' said Dennis Pierce, Kerry's husband. ``I think he
would carry it on.''
</P>
<P>
   The better-off message was carried by Gore to appearances at a
$200-a-person reception and $2,500-a-person Westin Hotel dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was playing the role of presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He lampooned Republicans, saying: ``The other party is in such
dissaray that the right hand doesn't know what the far right hand
is doing.'' He touted creation of 350,000 jobs in Washington since
the administration took office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Gore effused over Gary Locke as ``the single most effective
governor in the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also celebrated Washington, saying he ``long ago fell in
love'' with this region's mountains and oceans and Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The administration boosted its environmental record earlier
yesterday, as Clinton extended by 10 years a ban on oil drilling
off most of the American coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Local conservation and wildlife groups had hoped that Gore would
use his visit yesterday to announce a policy requiring the use of
escort tugs for laden oil tankers operating in the Strait of Juan
de Fuca.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is expected to endorse the tug escort
requirement, but Gore was mum on the subject last night. Instead,
Gore spoke of the environment in nonspecific terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party stands for a balanced approach that will
protect the environment and grow the economy,'' he said. ``Don't
ever tell me those two goals are incompatible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
