<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S PRESS AIDE TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Colleen Roche, the press secretary to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, announced Friday that she planned to resign but would
remain for several months while she finds another job.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the most rewarding, challenging and important
job that I've ever done,'' Ms. Roche said, ``and a very difficult
job to leave. I'm doing it to spend more time at home with my
family, my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roche joined the administration in 1995 as a deputy press
secretary, and was appointed to the top job two months later.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roche is responsible for the mayor's daily dealings with the
press, a tense job that during Giuliani's administration has often
involved presenting unpopular positions, deflecting unwanted
attention and helping to prepare quick responses to politically
charged questions.
</P>
<P>
   She runs the mayor's daily news conference, interrupting
reporters to say, ``Next topic!'' or ``Two more questions!''
</P>
<P>
   Her days at City Hall often begin at 7 a.m., and end late at
night when she stops by the press room to say good night to any
reporter who might remain.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Roche, 40, had been the spokeswoman for the district
attorney of Manhattan, Robert Morgenthau. She said she hopes to
remain in public relations, only in the corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wildest dream would be to do something involving sports,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
