<HEADLINE>
HEALTH CASE AT STATE HOSPITAL SPURS CONTEMPT QUERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pima County's presiding judge on Friday ordered a special
prosecutor to determine if state health officials should be charged
with contempt of court for refusing to accept patients sent by the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Michael Brown's order came after two Pima County
defendants were turned away from the Arizona State Hospital, which
is supposed to restore them to mental competency so they can stand
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The health department last week announced that it had no more
room for ``restoration-to-competency'' patients and wouldn't accept
any more because of overcrowding and dangerous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The health department says it will have a plan by Wednesday to
deal with the overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   The department will use the ``Alamo'' building, which had been
reserved for its new sexual-predator programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Alamo plan initially had been rejected because the building
was supposed to be used only for sexual predators and because it is
far away from the hospital's other units, Dr. James Allen, director
of Arizona Department of Health Services, wrote to Brown this week.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the best option in terms of time and disruption to
patients, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told the court we are working on this as quickly as we
can,'' said Brad Christensen, public information officer for the
health department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about a matter of days here, not weeks or
months.''
</P>
<P>
   When the state announced last week that it had no more room at
the hospital, there were 66 patients in two units licensed for 48
patients. There are now 56, Christensen said.
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Brown says that state law requires that criminal
defendants be committed to the State Hospital if they need
residential treatment and are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Allen and Jack Silver, the hospital superintendent, refused to
comply with the statute and honor valid court orders, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In Maricopa County, one defendant who should have gone to the
State Hospital was held at the county jail for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But jail officials say they don't have the space or the staff to
take restoration patients on a regular basis. Presiding Superior
Court Judge Robert Myers said Maricopa County would wait until at
least Wednesday to see if the state comes through on its plan.
</P>
<P>
   Myers said the courts, the health department and the Governor's
Office would discuss long-term solutions next week.
</P>
<P>
   The health department has been roundly criticized for not
talking with judges beforehand about the closure. Hospital
officials knew for months that the units were getting overcrowded
and didn't do anything about it, judges said.
</P>
<P>
   One solution may be for the state to pay the counties to house
the patients, Allen told Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The interim move to set up the Alamo unit will cost about
$250,000 to $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a stopgap solution and there has to be a
permanent solution. We might need some help from the Legislature.
We have an open-ended mandate but not an open-ended budget.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
