<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SHUT DOWN RANGERS, 5-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Perhaps one at-bat best captured the essence
of last night's events at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers first baseman Will Clark strode to the plate with two
outs and runners at first and third base in the seventh inning.
Anaheim Angels left-hander Greg Cadaret, who in his career had
surrendered four hits in as many at-bats to Clark, induced an
inning-ending ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Another threat denied.
</P>
<P>
   That would be commonplace during the first-place Rangers' 5-1
loss to the Angels, who moved within 1 1/2 games of the American
League West's best.
</P>
<P>
   Also commonplace: The inability of right-hander John Burkett to
keep the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (4-6) surrendered three home runs, including a two-run
shot to right fielder Garret Anderson with two outs during the
Angels' three-run seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it before and I'll say it again: Two-out base hits
are what win and lose games,'' said Clark, who went 0-for-3 with
runners in scoring position. ``Anderson hit his two-run homer with
two outs. We didn't get our two-out base hits, and that's the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went 0-for-8 with runners in scoring position. Five
of those at-bats occurred with two outs. That can be attributed to
the fact that the Rangers' leadoff hitter in each inning reached
safely only once.
</P>
<P>
   Angels right-hander Omar Olivares (4-2) made it a difficult
evening for the Rangers, who entered this game leading the league
with a .326 batting average with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares surrendered six hits and issued five walks during his 6
2/3 innings, but the right-hander utilized a hard, sinking fastball
and an effective changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of opportunities early, but it seemed like it was
always with two outs,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``He
didn't give us many pitches to hit, and I think we got ourselves
out a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer provided the Rangers their lone run
with a two-out, first-inning home run on a 2-1 changeup from
Olivares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar did a hell of a job,'' said Joe Maddon, the Angels'
interim manager while Terry Collins serves his eight-game
suspension for the June 2 bench-clearing brawl with the Kansas City
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers mounted their final threat during the seventh
inning. Olivares issued consecutive one-out walks to second baseman
Luis Alicea and Greer, and Alicea advanced to third on a ground
ball by right fielder Juan Gonzalez. That brought Clark to the
plate, and Maddon summoned Cadaret from the bullpen despite Clark's
past success against the left-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cadaret has been hot,'' Maddon said. ``He's been throwing the
ball extremely well. I'm a numbers guy, but sometimes you have to
go against the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Cadaret retired Clark and the next six hitters, including three
on strikes, for his first major-league save since Aug. 7, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers fell to 8-10 during their past 18 games, and their
lead over the Angels has slipped from six to 1 1/2 games during
that span.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Clark said of the remaining three games to
be played in this series, ``but it's not like it's life and
death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
