</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ SURPRISES BULLS, 83-81
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Postpone the coronation. Suddenly we've got a
competition.
</P>
<P>
   With the table set last night for the Chicago Bulls' sixth
championship and Michael Jordan's fond farewell, Karl Malone and
the Utah Jazz crashed the party with a stunning, dramatic, 83-81
victory before a shocked crowd at United Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the hunt, still kicking,'' Jazz point guard
John Stockton said. ``Now we can go back home, where we've fought
so hard to be all season.''
</P>
<P>
   The win, made possible via surprising production from Utah's
Antoine Carr (12 points) and a dismal night from Chicago's Scottie
Pippen (2-of-16 shooting), pushes the best-of-seven Finals back to
Salt Lake City for Game 6 tomorrow night. The Jazz, which got a
breakout, 39-point performance from Malone, trails 3-2 but has the
final two games, if necessary, at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the five games have been decided in the final 40 seconds
by five points or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went riding with Todd the state trooper and we went out and
weighed some 18-wheelers at the weigh station,'' said Malone, who
hit 17 of 27 shots after a below-par first four games. ``You guys
can laugh if you want, but I got totally out of the city, totally
away from basketball, and it cleared my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   No team has rallied from a 3-1 deficit to win the Finals, but
the Jazz has a chance because the Mailman finally delivered.
Malone, who averaged 20 points before last night, was so dominant
with turnaround jumpers and drives to the paint from the post that
the Jazz didn't have to use the pick-and-roll play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those nights for him,'' Bulls coach Phil Jackson
said. ``Everything he shot went down.''
</P>
<P>
   Nursing a four-point lead in waning seconds, Malone fouled
Chicago's Toni Kukoc on a 3-point attempt. But Kukoc, who scored 30
points on remarkable 11-of-13 shooting, missed the third free throw
to leave Utah leading by two. Carr, who started the second half
after not playing much at all in the series, knocked down two free
throws with 10.4 seconds left for an 82-78 lead. After Kukoc
drilled another 3-pointer and Jeff Hornacek hit one of two free
throws, Chicago had a final shot to win or tie. But with 0.8
seconds left, Michael Jordan took an inbound pass and lofted a
desperation 3-pointer that failed to hit the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most exciting thing in sports to see who will fight,
and tonight we fought,'' Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said. ``Our backs
are still to the wall, but we've earned a chance to play at home
again, and that's all we can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Utah's victory is a major travel inconvenience or a
permanent roadblock to Chicago's shot at history remains to be
seen, but for certain the Jazz was successful in scrapping a
planned celebration at Grant Park in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be hard. Nobody wanted to make this trip,''
Pippen said. ``We had our chance, but now we've got to win one on
their home court.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan scored 28 points, but made only one of seven shots in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would have loved to have won it here, it would have been a
great scenario,'' Jordan said. ``But when we get on that plane,
we've got to be very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 76-71, Jordan missed two shots and Pippen missed a tip.
After grabbing the rebound, Carr hit a crucial 18-foot jumper that
just beat the shot clock and pushed the lead to seven. A Kukoc
3-pointer and two free throws by Jordan edged Chicago within two,
but Malone drilled an 18-foot baseline jumper over Rodman to make
it 80-76 with 53 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   During the timeout, a commercial urging Chicagoans to
``Celebrate with Dignity'' was met with almost deaf silence.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Finals finally began with easily the
series' most intense 12 minutes. Trading two double-technical fouls
with the Bulls, the Jazz pounded the ball to Malone on the low left
block with positive results. He abused Luc Longley and began to
find a rhythm against Dennis Rodman with 17 points as Utah rode its
slow, physical style to a 59-55 lead in the fourth quarter. After a
lousy 30-point first half, the Jazz produced their highest-scoring
quarter of the series with 29 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scratched out a 36-30 lead after the lowest-scoring
first half in Finals history. The ugly 24 minutes, featuring 28
combined baskets and 24 turnovers, broke the mark of 69 set by
Syracuse and Fort Wayne in 1955. At one point in the second
quarter, they combined for bad passes or violations on seven
consecutive possessions. After Malone dunked to tie the game at 26,
he elbowed Rodman for a technical foul that sparked a 6-0 Bulls
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had its chance to build a lead early, but somehow
trailed 18-16 after the first quarter. Tight and tentative, Bulls
other than Kukoc missed their first 12 shots and didn't produce a
basket in the first 10 minutes. Utah, however, missed wide-open
jumpers, failed to convert two fast-break opportunities and
committed five late turnovers. Kukoc's 13 points kept the Bulls
within one, and Jordan's first jumper with 12 seconds left gave
them a two-point lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
