<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-650&AMP;AD     06-13 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-JAZZ-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE PUTS CELEBRATION OF DYNASTY ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Hold the career retrospective. Along with the
Champagne, ``Michael: An Appreciation,'' must wait another day.
</P>
<P>
   After a torturous week in the city of the Bulls, John Stockton
and Karl Malone spoiled the dynasty's party Friday night at the
United Center and finally get to go home to a hero's welcome.
</P>
<P>
   They and the Utah Jazz staved off Michael Jordan in Game 5 of
the National Basketball Association finals, an 83-81 victory that
forces the Chicago Bulls to return to Salt Lake City and play in
front of the league's most hostile crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 is Sunday night at the Delta Center, and while Utah
trails the four-of-seven-game series by three games to two, it is a
nice rowdy place to finish the season. Game 7, if necessary, is
scheduled for Wednesday in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   With bubbly on ice and amid the pageantry befitting what would
be their sixth title in eight seasons, the Bulls took a 36-30 lead
at halftime and appeared on the cusp of a blowout. But Stockton
(six points, 12 assists) and Malone (39 points, nine rebounds)
finally showed the resolve that had been lacking in their three
straight losses to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc scored 30 points. Jordan ended with 28 points.
Scottie Pippen had six points, 11 rebounds and 11 assists. Kukoc
had 17 points by halftime, hitting all seven of his shots and
helping the Bulls overcome a lackluster start. Malone was Utah's
only weapon early, but in the second half the Jazz regrouped and
decided to play its best 24 minutes of the series. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Malone's jumper made the score 80-76 with 53.3 seconds left.
Jordan had a chance to send the home crowd into a state of delirium
with eight-tenths of a second left, but his high-arching 3-pointer
off one foot at the buzzer hit nothing but air. The Jazz bench went
wild, piling onto the court like kids let out for recess.
</P>
<P>
   In the most dominant big-game performance in 13 years, Malone
made 17 of 27 shots. Stockton had 12 assists and made sure he got
the ball to his All-Star teammate when Malone asked.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was good, but certainly not great. He hit only 9-of-26
shots from the field in 45 minutes and often was trapped in midair
with nowhere to go in the second half. Kukoc led Chicago with 30
points on 11-of-13 shooting, while Pippen struggled mightily from
the field (2-of-16).
</P>
<P>
   The game did not end until the buzzer, thanks to a clutch
3-pointer from Kukoc with 5.5 seconds left. Stockton quickly found
Jeff Hornacek downcourt to take four seconds off the clock before
he was fouled.
</P>
<P>
   But Hornacek made only 1-of-2 free throws, giving Chicago one
last shot with 1.1 seconds left. After both teams took timeouts,
the Bulls took the floor, but Jordan was unable to hit the
3-pointer before the buzzer sounded.
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Carr had seemed to put the game away for the Jazz with a
jumper from the top of the key with 1:56 remaining, a shot that
made it 78-71.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls cut the lead to two with 1 minute 13 seconds left
on two Jordan free throws. Kukoc had nailed a 3-pointer with 1:47
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton was masterful, threading passes between defenders and
orchestrating the halfcourt set as he had not since Game 1. When he
was not working a two-man game with Malone on the left side, he was
ducking underneath Pippen and Jordan along the baseline and finding
Carr for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was no less impressive, scoring on a scoop layup with
3:50 left that gave the Jazz a seven-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kerr, who broke a million Utah hearts in Game 6 last
season with a clutch jumper in the final seconds, opened up all the
old wounds. He buried two 3-pointers to keep the Bulls within
striking distance early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Steve Kerr dropped in a 3-pointer to begin the
fourth quarter, slicing Utah's lead to one point, the Jazz would
not relent. Stockton drove the lane and distributed pretty passes.
Malone kept nailing everything he put up.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With 8 minutes 53 seconds left, the Bulls were in trouble.
Jordan had been thwarted on one end as he went to the basket, Bryon
Russell had just rattled in a dunk off a nice pass from Stockton,
and Utah led 68-60.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing his share of criticism all week, Malone began to
carry the Jazz on his shoulders as he had all season. He made five
consecutive medium-range jump shots. Over Dennis Rodman. Over Luc
Longley. For once, it did not matter who was guarding him.
</P>
<P>
   He had 30 points after three quarters, and the Jazz had a 59-55
lead entering the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Malone opened the second half by showing patience and tenacity
for one of the few times in the series. Inserting Antoine Carr into
the lineup to begin the second half did not hurt Jerry Sloan's
Jazz, either.
</P>
<P>
   Carr got underneath Jordan's skin by putting a forearm into his
chest on several forays to the basket. It was enough to make Jordan
begin mouthing profanities at the veteran forward as they ran
downcourt on one possession.
</P>
<P>
   If Utah was finally showing emotion, it was also triggering
Jordan's temper. Given his history of creating artificial
motivation to pull his team along, that might not be considered
smart basketball. But the Jazz had to try something.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan's club was awful in the first half. Malone and his meek
teammates missed point-blank shots, blocked each other out for
rebounds, committed 13 turnovers and basically looked as if they
felt there was no shame in losing to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that is how the last four games proceeded before the
second half. The Jazz played as if it did not want to upset anyone,
other than Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   Utah never showed the confidence that led the team to a
four-game sweep of the Lakers in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
