<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE REPAIRS TARNISHED IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Karl Malone hammered and banged away Friday night in a
frenzied attempt to repair a legacy in the making. His legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was desperate to alter an image that was surfacing in the
National Basketball Association finals when Game 5 arrived at the
United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Although his career has sparkled with achievements, he was being
seen as a superstar overwhelmed by the moment, and psychologically
overmatched by the one counterpart he has never been able to equal,
Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   He exited with the knowledge that he put the questions about his
passion and heart and mentality to rest for a night. He scored 39
points in the 83-81 victory by the Jazz to put off the celebration
plans of the Bulls. Down 3-2 in the four-of-seven-game series, the
Jazz will go home for Game 6 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's sudden impact left the Bulls to double-team him,
leaving Antoine Carr open on the perimeter to hit crucial jumpers
down the stretch. If Malone wasn't going to score, someone else
was.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was his turn, Malone turned and faced a
foul-troubled Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Then he lofted a high jumper over Rodman's glowing head with
53.3 seconds left in the game to give the Jazz an 80-76 lead over
the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   So often in the series against the Bulls, Malone appeared frozen
in the fourth quarter of each game. He had been frustrated by
Rodman, and hesitant in the face of double-teams.
</P>
<P>
   To see Malone take on Game 5, with his reputation and his team's
life in this series on the line, was to view a man breaking out of
his bulky shell.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, he was taking jumpers over Luc Longley, who had been
ineffective in stopping Malone. Before the game, Malone was making
54 percent of his shots over Longley.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rodman who was the bane of his existence. He had held
Malone to 32 percent, and had virtually shut him down in the fourth
quarter. Malone's passive ways against Rodman changed drastically.
He was staring Rodman down as he launched fade-aways over him.
</P>
<P>
   The truest show of Malone's rebirth occurred in the third
quarter. Malone, who had been called for a technical for elbowing
Rodman earlier, lowered his shoulder and drew a foul on Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rodman's fourth. Malone hit two free throws with 2
minutes left in the third, and gave the Jazz a 54-50 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was doing his best to change the tone of this series. And
repair the perception of Malone as a big-game failure. Malone
stepped into the pro world as a backwoods unknown from a school
appreciated more for its women's program, Louisiana Tech. So his
craving for recognition began more than a decade ago. Although he
has found comfort living in the mountains and protection playing in
small-market Utah, Malone has longed for the kind of attention and
respect the glamour stars in the NBA receive.
</P>
<P>
   This I'll-show-'em yearning, this chip-on-the-shoulder attitude
has served him well the last 13 years. He has made sure everyone
knows his name. But in the face of this series, when he really
needed that underdog's edge to push him to the ultimate proof of
greatness _ an NBA title _ Malone may have done himself in by
entering the NBA finals as a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had the home-court advantage. Malone and his partner,
John Stockton, had the confidence and fearlessness of cliff divers.
Many were picking them to beat the Bulls. With his second chance in
two years, Malone was expected to overcome the mystique of Jordan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the Jazz lost Game 2, gave up home-court advantage, and then
evaporated under the might of the Bulls with a 42-point loss in
Game 3. The moment Game 4 went by with only three fourth-quarter
shot attempts from Malone, this former MVP had shrunk beneath the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 was a chance to be the underdog again. No one thought the
Jazz had a chance to steal the celebration from beneath the Bulls.
Just a day before Game 5, Malone did not seem to believe it either.
The weight of his task seemed to be wearing on Malone, when he
began to talk freely about the what-ifs of his situation. What if
Malone, who will be 35 in July, walks out of the finals and does
not get another chance? After all, the Lakers are bound to grow up
at any moment. What if the window is closing?
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been saying that for how many years now? Six, seven?
Five, for sure,'' Malone said. ``I'm stubborn enough that I don't
believe that stuff. I think you all age us enough, and we still go
out and play. We are supposed to be older and have lost a step. I
don't buy any of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, playing this game for as long as we have and not to
have a ring, those things happen. I don't know if failure is the
right word. I don't think you measure success in your career by not
winning a ring. I'm not going to sit here and tell you there won't
be an empty spot if it happens, because there will. But we're not
conceding anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone was expected to run right over Rodman and bait him into
foul trouble. Malone was expected to lead the Jazz with such force,
the Bulls were expected to be on the brink of elimination before
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said, since I've been in the league, if you put a
star other than Michael Jordan out there, most superstars cannot
come through in the clutch,'' Rodman said. ``I would rather foul
Karl Malone than Michael Jordan down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the way Malone wanted to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 was an attempt to change that perception.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
