</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-VECSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORRY, FANS, BUT NBA IS ABOUT TO SPOIL THE PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What a perfect time to laud the miracle of a man named
Michael Jordan, whose will and skill have driven the Bulls toward
six NBA titles in a single decade and given Chicago dibs on a
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad that topic must be shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, please turn your attention to the only real meaning of
sports in the '90s: Free agency. Labor wars. Who's going to get
their hands on the biggest piece of the money pie.
</P>
<P>
   And, by the way, have a nice summer.
</P>
<P>
   In the oodles-of-money world of the NBA, the time has come again
to fight over who gets paid. It is time for a power play _ one that
will again expose the mega-riches of a sports industry against the
inevitable backdrop of suspicion and greed.
</P>
<P>
   (Please refer to the 1994 baseball labor war.)
</P>
<P>
   In front of me is a list of NBA players who will be free agents
as of July 1, the day owners are likely to commence a lockout. It's
a long list, dotted with the likes of Scottie Pippen, Jayson
Williams, Stephon Marbury, Damon Stoudamire, Ike Austin and Antonio
McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, this list tops out at an eye-popping 187 players. Ten
of the 30 NBA franchises _ Sonics, Rockets, Bulls, Spurs, Suns,
Magic, Pistons, Sixers, Timberwolves and Hawks _ have more than
two-thirds of their rosters up for free-agency.
</P>
<P>
   So remember: Buy those season tickets soon, folks.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to believe that a league so stable and
so glamorous is infected with so much uncertainty. But this is the
reason why certain NBA players are manipulating a public-relations
campaign that damns owners for being so cheap and wishy-washy: Why
spoil the party?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfair to the fans and it's unfair to the game,''
Jordan said about the upcoming NBA labor battle.
</P>
<P>
   Owners say they are paying players 57 percent of revenues. This
translates into $167 million more than the 48 percent minimum that
owners had expected to pay when a deal was signed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, owners have proposed phasing out the ``Larry Bird
exception,'' which allows teams to exceed the salary cap to retain
their own free agents. Because of this exception, Jordan was paid
in excess of $30 million by the Bulls this season.
</P>
<P>
   The players have rejected this proposal, and Jordan and other
top stars are threatening a boycott of the World Championships this
summer, should a lockout occur.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Jordan deserved every penny of his $30-plus million,
since the Bulls, NBA and NBC each can thank Jordan for their
incredible wealth and popularity.
</P>
<P>
   However, to state the obvious, Jordan is mind-bogglingly unique.
He is so far more valuable to his team, league and network than any
other NBA star that Jordan is in no way a representative spokesman
for his fellow NBA laborers.
</P>
<P>
   What big-ticket NBA players like Jordan, and to a lesser extent
Patrick Ewing, refuse to acknowledge is that the impact of the
existing collective-bargaining agreement is crushing the league.
</P>
<P>
   While every player should have a right to determine his ``fair
market value,'' the inevitable outcome is that the market overpays
and it can't erect a ceiling to help stem costs.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, ticket prices skyrocket while NBA club payrolls
become an uneasy mix of haves and have-nots. For every Kevin
Garnett making $20 million a year, there's a Rex Chapman making
$350,000.
</P>
<P>
   It also is forcing teams into making drastic personnel decisions
whose ramifications easily could bring down the house. Take the
Washington Wizards, please.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, while all these NBA players talk about how
bad they want to win a ring, they are more determined in their
quest for ``fair market value.'' It is this primary business
operative that is most responsible for your franchise's inability
to retain top stars and thus contend for a title.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, you need a nucleus of two or three $100-million
players to be a championship-caliber team. The problem is, which
NBA club can consistently solve this personnel/payroll puzzle?
</P>
<P>
   It's quaint to think about dynasties. However, at what cost are
such things kept alive? In Chicago, Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf
paid upwards of $80 million to put that history-making team on the
floor this season.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth it? Yes, because the Michael Jordan Bulls are
once-in-history unique. Reinsdorf made back his millions and more.
</P>
<P>
   The same is not true in Denver or Toronto or Vancouver or
Washington, D.C., or Minnesota, where a bright young franchise now
must decide who else to give $100 million to, Tom Gugliotta or
Marbury, without mortgaging its future into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The post-Jordan NBA future could look bright if every NBA
all-star could be convinced that the difference between Sir Air and
them is about $28 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   We're all for the NBA stars getting their fair share. And if
what Jordan insinuates is true, that owners are making more in
licensing than they're sharing with players, then that needs to be
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   But for everyone out here in the stands and TV land who's
ultimately paying the NBA's bills, the sky can't be the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
