<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7668 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     06-13 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   Mailman finally &QL; 
delivers the goods
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ The champagne was on ice. The confetti was hoisted up
into the rafters. The ropes were laid out to cordon off the court
for the trophy presentation. The windows of the shops were all
boarded up. The police were on standby.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Chicago was ready to celebrate. But the Bulls
weren't ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   So the Last Dance turned into a Jazz session.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone playing blue notes. John Stockton providing rhythm.
Antoine Carr on improvisational riffs.
</P>
<P>
   With a gritty, bound and determined 83-81 victory Friday night,
the Jazz took a page out of Charles Barkley's book, circa 1993, and
saved the city. And in the process might have saved the reputation
of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was confidence to Utah's game. Finally, there was
execution. Finally, there was backbone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our backs were to the wall,'' Jazz coach Jerry Sloan said.
``When you're in that position, that's the most interesting thing
in all of sports, to see who will come out and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of fight and drive that Utah had been expected
to bring to the Finals rematch with the Bulls. This was the
fourth-quarter execution that had stamped the Jazz's 62-win regular
season and march through the playoffs until this series began.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, this was the Mailman, making special deliveries,
going postal, seeing that neither rain nor sleet nor gloom of night
could keep him from his appointed round.
</P>
<P>
   After disappearing in the fourth quarter of each of the first
four games, Malone erupted for 39 points, nine rebounds and five
assists. This was the Malone who was on a rampage in the previous
round against the Lakers, hitting his jumper from the outside with
ease and wheeling into the lane to make the Bulls pay consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when we're good, that's exactly what we do, ride
him,'' Stockton said. ``Karl is the one who has gotten us here, and
when we're playing at the top of our game, it's usually the same
old story.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping up at crunch time
</P>
<P>
   But it was a far different story from the past three games when
Malone scored a grand total of only three points in all those
fourth quarters. This time, he stepped up and hit the big baskets.
This time, he didn't shrink from the spotlight but reveled in it.
</P>
<P>
   Malone listened to the criticism that has rained down on him
since the series began, and he soaked it all in. He read all of the
newspapers, and he filed away all of the words that had been
written.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he finished practice Thursday with his teammates and got
away from all the swirl and hubbub of the Finals by taking a ride
in a squad car with an Illinois state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all of you guys (media) are out there laughing at me
and the way I am,'' Malone said. ``But I don't care. I wanted to
get completely away from basketball and not think about everything
for a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got together with my friend Ty, and we went riding way
outside the city to a weigh station. We weighed some trucks. You
guys laugh, and that's what I did. I know he's going to be the most
famous state trooper in Illinois after this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what other people do on their off days, but I
wanted to change up and do something different. I've always wanted
to be, in my little world, a state trooper, so I got to ride with
one. You can laugh all the hell you want. It was a fun day for me,
and I enjoyed it. So, thank you, Ty. I wish I could take you to
Utah with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's taking the Bulls and all of the trappings of the
Chicago dynasty with him.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be denied
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz did it by beating the Bulls on the boards, slapping a
handcuffing defense on Michael Jordan (9-for-26) and Scottie Pippen
(2-for-16) and making all of the big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Malone scored eight points in the fourth quarter. Carr came off
the bench to add another eight in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bulls cut the lead to 78-76 on two Jordan free throws
with 1:13 to go, Malone came right back and stabbed in an
18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   When it was 80-78, Carr stepped up to the foul line and made a
pair with 10.4 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   And when Toni Kukoc hit the last of his 30 points on a 3-point
bomb with 5.5 seconds to go, Stockton made a clever move on the
baseline, eluded a would-be foul by the Bulls and lofted a pass to
Jeff Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, there was drama. Hornacek made just one of two free
throws. The Bulls had a chance. Jordan took the inbounds pass. He
turned, fired. It was an airball.
</P>
<P>
   The confetti stayed up. The champagne stayed chilled. The city
stayed in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz stayed alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
