<HEADER>
A7669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-13 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Malone comes up huge 
to keep alive Utah hopes
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ It was supposed to be the last dance for the Chicago
Bulls. But the Utah Jazz cut in.
</P>
<P>
   Any talk of retirements, breakups and the Bulls' final resting
place in basketball history was put on hold after Karl Malone
willed the Jazz to an 83-81 victory over the Bulls in Game 5 of the
NBA Finals on Friday night at the United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Malone had 39 points and surprise of the night Antoine Carr had
12 points, including eight in the fourth quarter, as the Jazz cut
Chicago's lead to 3-2 in the best-of-seven series that switches to
Utah on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's win kept alive the streak of no home team sweeping the
three middle games of the Finals since they went to the 2-3-2
format.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yes, we (still) have our backs against the wall,'' Jazz
coach Jerry Sloan said. ``But at least we regained the home-court
advantage that we worked 82 games to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were, and still are, shooting for their sixth NBA
championship in the past eight seasons. But for one night, talk of
Michael Jordan's retirement, Scottie Pippen's free agency and coach
Phil Jackson's status was drowned out by the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one loss,'' Jordan said. ``You can't let it eat at you to
where it becomes two losses. I said this is the toughest game to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   And was it a big letdown? Did Jordan have to cancel today's tee
time?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't have a tee time,'' he said. ``I anticipated
drinking so much tonight that I didn't think I'd make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan had one last chance to pull out a dramatic win for the
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   After Utah's Jeff Hornacek missed the first of two free throws,
the Bulls were down 83-81 with 1.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 1.1 seconds, I knew I was going to get the ball and nobody
knew what was going to happen,'' Jordan said. ``Everybody was
expecting a big shot. For 1.1 seconds, everybody was holding their
breath. You have a chance to determine happiness and sadness.
That's what you live for. I love those moments.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't love this one. When Jordan took the inbounds pass and
heaved a fallaway 3-pointer ahead of the buzzer, the Jazz exhaled
happily as the shot was way off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we blew an opportunity,'' Jordan said. ``But we've had
this happen before. Our job is to get past this.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question the Jazz salvaged considerable dignity with
the tenacious, heart-healthy play it exhibited. Malone was
virtually unstoppable as he posted up for midrange jumpers, and
Carr was an unexpected boon for Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said coming into this series that our guards would have
their hands full and we (big players) had to help them out,''
Malone said. ``Antoine was a big presence for us, and I think down
the stretch he was the difference. He hit a lot of big buckets for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   As did Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the criticism he (Malone) has received in these playoffs,
he put a lot of that to rest with this game,'' Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan said the strong play of Malone might also have helped the
Jazz get a level playing field regarding the officiating. Utah shot
18 free throws to Chicago's 20, a huge difference from Game 4, when
Chicago went to the line 40 times to 21 for Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Karl Malone was sensational,'' Sloan said. ``And I
thought our guys stood their ground a little more in this game, and
I think when you stand up for yourself, you get a little more
respect.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Jazz played with composure down the stretch, something
it lacked in the late going in close losses in Games 2 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   The finish was a vintage end to a hard-played, though
sometimes-ragged NBA playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Up 76-71, the Jazz just knew there was a final Bulls push
coming. Even after Carr nailed another jumper to build the lead to
seven, Toni Kukoc, who had 30 points, hit a 3-pointer with 1:47 to
go. After Shandon Anderson missed for Utah, Jordan was fouled and
made two free throws with 1:13 showing.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Utah's lead was down to 78-76. But Malone answered
smartly, rising over Dennis Rodman for an 18-footer with 53.3
seconds left to make it a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was a matter of making one stop against the
Bulls. And the Jazz got lucky. Kukoc was left free for a 3-pointer
after Jordan drew the double team. But Kukoc's shot was off.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Jazz couldn't score, it whittled valuable
seconds off the clock. Then, Malone made what could have been a
costly mistake when he fouled Kukoc on another 3-point try. Had the
shot gone in, Kukoc could have had a chance for a game-tying
four-point play.
</P>
<P>
   But the shot missed, and Kukoc made only two of the three free
throws, leaving Chicago down 80-78.
</P>
<P>
   Carr was fouled with 10.4 seconds to go, and his free throws
kept the pressure on the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But Kukoc hit a 3-pointer with 5.5 seconds left, and when
Hornacek missed one of his free throws with 1.1 showing, the Bulls
had one last chance, down 83-81. But Jordan's 3-pointer couldn't
create history.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had relied on Malone's 17 points in the third quarter
to go ahead by four points heading into the fourth period. Utah
also had gotten solid efforts from Carr and Hornacek.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Bryon Russell came alive. After a poor showing in the
previous three games, Russell hit a 3-pointer and got a slam to
rattle in, out and then in again with 9:01 to go, which put the
Jazz up 68-60.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls were struggling mightily, with Pippen leading the way.
A Most Valuable Player candidate in this series after four games,
he probably shot those those ideas down when he was 2-for-15 after
missing his first two attemps in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When Jordan missed with 8:40 to go, the Jazz had a chance to go
up by 10, but Malone's 16-footer was off. And while Malone was
yapping that he was fouled on the play, the Bulls quickly pushed
the ball downcourt for a Steve Kerr 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls got within three points three times, the last at 72-69
before Carr took a feed from Malone for a 16-footer and, after an
offensive foul on Pippen, Malone scooped in a bucket over Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago cut it back to a five-point game when Jordan was fouled
and hit two free throws with 3:07 left.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was about as artistic as a 4-year-old's
finger-painting effort _ only a parent could love it.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bulls fans couldn't be all that proud of the game that
might have been Jordan's last in the home arena. It took nearly the
entire first quarter before Jordan got his first basket. He scored
with 12 seconds left in the opening period, which put the Bulls up
18-16.
</P>
<P>
   That would turn out to be the higher scoring of the opening two
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   After the teams exchanged baskets to open the second quarter,
neither scored for the next 4:20. There were 15 possessions during
that stretch, and 10 ended in a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Utah threw away the ball six times in that span, and it seemed
like a bad sign for the Jazz that Chicago went so long without a
point yet Malone and Co. could not capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Jordan began to heat up, scoring 10 consecutive points.
</P>
<P>
   When Pippen and Kukoc scored back-to-back baskets in the final
minute of the half, the Bulls had their biggest lead to that point,
36-28. Utah got a running bank shot from Anderson with 1.9 seconds
left to nose up to 30 points for the half, but the Jazz wasn't
displaying the sort of execution that would be necessary to send
the series back to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was Kukoc's show. He hit all seven of his shots
and had 17 points and four rebounds. The only blotches on his
ledger were two missed free throws.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jazz could take some consolation out of the opening 24
minutes, it was that it had kept itself in position to make the
Bulls sweat.
</P>
<P>
   The intensity level, tilted to the Bulls' side in Games 3 and 4,
suddenly became hotly contested. Malone came out in the third
quarter with obviously upgraded desire and toughness. He had 12
points in the first 8:11 of the period.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive was the job the Jazz did on defense. Chicago
shot 1-for-5 and had three turnovers during a stretch in which the
Jazz outscored the Bulls 9-1 to take a 47-43 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz kept the lead for the rest of the third quarter,
stretching it to 59-52 until Kukoc nailed a 3-pointer with 13
seconds left to make it a four-point game going into the final 12
minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
