 sider-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pippen's bricks help Jazz rebuild hope
</P>
<P>
   Jackson not pleased about 3-point attack
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ Michael Jordan had Space Jam. Karl Malone starred in
Rockwell, an obscure western in which he played a sheriff, riding
the range while dealing out his brand of frontier justice.
</P>
<P>
   And Friday night, Scottie Pippen auditioned for his big movie
role, the lead in The Invisible Man.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who was vying with Jordan for Most Valuable Player
honors after the first four games of the NBA Finals, was missing in
action in Game 5 at the United Center, one reason the Utah Jazz was
able to walk off the floor with an 83-81 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The win pulls Utah within 3-2 in the best-of-seven series, with
the next two games in Salt Lake City, starting Sunday with Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who averaged 20 points in the first four games, scored
just six points Friday, making only two of his 16 points and
missing all seven of his 3-point attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie had a night to forget from the field,'' said Chicago
coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The odd part of Pippen's shooting night is that he was guarded
by Utah's Jeff Hornacek, who stands four inches shorter than the
6-8 Chicago forward. Jazz coach Jerry Sloan made the switch to put
6-7 Bryon Russell on Jordan defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen took Hornacek into the post, where he got what looked
like easy shots _ but most rolled off the rim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of opportunities,'' Pippen said. ``I can't say
that my shots weren't there. I tried to be more aggressive and take
the ball to the basket early on, but they (the Jazz defenders) were
getting away with a lot of fouls, trips _ whatever you want to call
them _ on the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we sort of pulled away from that (physical) play and
started shooting a lot of jump shots. Nothing fell for me tonight.
I have to be much more aggressive and look to attack the basket in
the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to put the ball in the basket down low, Pippen floated
out to the 3-point line. After draining five 3-pointers in Game 4,
he couldn't find the mark on any of his seven attempts Friday, a
number that seemed to irk Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got enchanted with the 3-point line a little bit,''
Jackson said. ``I think 20 attempts (making seven) is a little much
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had hoped to nail down the championship in front of
the home fans, especially with all the speculation about management
breaking up the team.
</P>
<P>
   Local television stations were running public-service
announcements telling Chicago citizen to ``celebrate with
dignity,'' referring to riots that followed championship-clinching
home victories in the past that featured fires and brick throwing.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Pippen who launched all the bricks Friday, the main
reason the series is heading back to Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very hard,'' Pippen said. ``I know no one
wanted to make this trip, especially the players. I'm sure you guys
(the media) didn't want to make this trip, at least you guys who
aren't from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have to do it. It's very disappointing on our part that
we have to do it. We wanted the season to end tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen had 11 assists and 11 rebounds before fouling out with a
second remaining. But in a game in which the Bulls needed his
scoring, Pippen couldn't find the basket, save for a layup with 48
seconds left in the first half and a tip-in of a Jordan miss with
7:05 left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a lot of distractions that took our focus away
from what we had to do tonight,'' Pippen said. ``We just didn't
come out with the same kind of intensity that we had in the last
couple of games. Tonight was a very important game for us. We
needed everything to work for us out there, but we just weren't the
aggressors out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
