<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-13 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: IT'S AS MUCH PIPPEN'S FIGHT AS JORDAN'S 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A year ago on a Friday night with a familiar feel,
Scottie Pippen stole the ball, secured title No. 5 and was
acknowledged by Michael Jordan in a poignant most valuable player
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said that he would keep the trophy, give Pippen the car,
and that the world should know Little Brother was all grown up, a
long way from riding the little red wagon on the Jordan gravy
train. Suddenly the question that arose Friday night was if Pippen
could actually be judged chief conductor of another Bulls'
championship run, MVP of the series, cast in the exalted position
of giving Jordan the wheels while keeping the hardware for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps Pippen would say so sorry, and take the trophy and
the car and drive off as a free agent to Phoenix, as the sun set on
the Bulls' globally renowned dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very good for my free-agency resume,'' Pippen
teased.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke too fast, shot too short and the city of Chicago
celebrated too soon. The only player who performed like an MVP
Friday night was Karl Malone. The Jazz beat the sluggish Bulls,
83-81, and got out of town alive. The next question the Bulls have
to answer is whether they know the way back to Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Malone partly atoned for Games 1 through 4 with 39 points.
Pippen shot a nightmarish 2-for-16, leaving Jordan too heavy a
burden. This time it was Jordan who sagged in the fourth quarter.
Malone, who said he wasn't interested in motivational speeches, let
his medium-range jump shot do the talking. A series that had looked
like Sinatra and Springsteen versus Simon and Garfunkel goes on,
with no one singing Where have you gone, Mailman Malone?
</P>
<P>
   If the series through four games had done anything, it was to
crystallize which noncenter ranks directly behind Jordan in terms
of impact, night in, night out. According to various opinions,
Pippen through four games was deserving of the MVP, in particular
for coming between Stockton and Malone, everywhere but in those
joint interviews that underscored their unwillingness or inability
to stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie's who I would vote for,'' said Bill Wennington, a lone
Bull with the gumption not to mouth party lines about tough choices
and co-winners. ``I think he's done a tremendous job disrupting the
Utah offense, and that's been the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockton and Malone _ original Dream Teamers, future Hall of
Famers _ had measured up like Muggsy Bogues, not only to Jordan but
also to Pippen. What does that say? Certainly not that these proud
if strangely dispassionate veterans have fooled us with screens,
rolls, smoke and mirrors, but that it's taken much more than having
the greatest player ever for the Bulls to dominate this decade.
It's taken Pippen, the unique multipurpose player of his time and
maybe all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the best defensive player ever,'' Malone took the
time to admit.
</P>
<P>
   What's amazing is how many people this week related to Pippen's
potency as if he were some wonder drug new to the market. He has
said and done his share of dumb things through the years, but if
you went back to study the Bulls' first five titles, you would find
Pippen's long arms reaching into many a crucial moment to block a
shot, cause a turnover in the passing lane, or stretching like clay
to lay the ball up to the rim.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of pure performance, never has such a deserving second
star been so lost in a teammate's luminescence, which makes sense
because never has there been such hysteria over an athlete as there
has been with Jordan. This is the root of Pippen's long-standing
melancholy, Toni Kukoc being nothing more than a convenient
scapegoat. Big Brother Mike got too much and Little Brother Scottie
too little, and every now and then the pouting Pippen just had to
threaten to run away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with free agency beckoning, Pippen has suddenly achieved an
even playing field, even if he is nowhere close to Jordan's equal
in popularity. Jordan, for his part, doesn't call Pippen Little
Brother anymore. He called him ``my twin'' earlier this week. What
Jordan really believes _ he did scream at Pippen for the ball near
the end of Game 1 _ may be another story, but this is how it is now
for public consumption, for the sake of luring Pippen back because
Jordan still wants to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any intention of coming back here,'' Pippen said
the other day, not 24 hours after saying he might.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he said he wouldn't be going back to Salt Lake
either. He and the Bulls leave Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
