<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7674 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-13 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLICKI, YOUNG SPARK DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dave Mlicki came to Los Angeles homeless, unhappy
and confused. But after finding an apartment and comfort on the
Dodger Stadium mound, the former New Yorker is feeling in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki combined an impressive eight-inning performance in his
Dodger Stadium debut with a surprising game-winning homer by Eric
Young in the eighth inning to give the Dodgers a 2-1 victory over
the Colorado Rockies in front of 39,163 on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki came to the Dodgers following a four-player trade with
the New York Mets on June 4 that included Hideo Nomo, and he
entered the game with a 1-4 record. But on this night, he allowed
just one run on five hits over eight innings while walking none and
striking out four for his first win as a Dodger. Besides pitching
his second complete game _ the first was on May 5 against Arizona _
tonight was the only time that he had lasted at least eight innings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also gave the Dodgers three consecutive wins, tying
their longest streak of the season set May 21-23 and April 24-26.
It is also the first time they are two games over .500 since May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a weird feeling, but it takes a couple days to
settle in,'' said Mlicki, who didn't walk a batter for the first
time in a start this season. ``I hope this is something I can build
on. It is still early and I have a lot of starts left, but
hopefully I can keep contributing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was great. I just went out there, went at them,
showed my stuff and we had some fun. That is what we did tonight.
That is the first time I had fun in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 1-1 with one out in the eighth inning,
Young walked to the plate with his last at-bat still lingering in
his mind. The Dodgers actually had Mlicki at second base with no
outs in the sixth and Young followed with a messed-up bunt that
resulted in a pop-out to the catcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers ended up loading the bases, but no one scored to
keep the game tied.
</P>
<P>
   Young came to the plate with just one home run on the season in
the eighth, April 26 against the Chicago Cubs. But he left with two
as he hit a solo game-winning blast off a 1-0 fastball from
Colorado's Darryl Kile over the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't recall ever hitting a game-winning homer,'' said
Young, the leadoff hitter who is more known for stealing bases.
``I'm not going to hit too many of those. I know I can hit home
runs. But I was probably as surprised as anyone in stadium when I
hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kile (5-9), who pushed his losing streak to six games, actually
had a no-hitter going through 41/3 innings. But the $5.6-million,
whose had only 13 runs in his past six starts, pitcher gave up his
first hit on a towering 430-foot homer by Raul Mondesi in the fifth
to tie the game at 1-1. Mondesi's homer was his 15th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my job to make that (one-run lead) stand up and I didn't
do it,'' said Kile, who stuck out seven and allowed five hits in
eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Mlicki was considered to have the best arm in the
New York Mets' organization. But during his time in the Big Apple,
he was a disappointment as he compiled a record of 24-29 after
joining the club in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki came to the Dodgers with jet lag and confusion on how he
should be pitching. Although the Dodgers won his first start 10-6
at Seattle on June 6, the newcomer allowed eight hits and five
earned runs in just three innings and was unsuccessful with
off-speed and breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, pitching coach Goose Gregson has tried to get Mlicki
to concentrate on first-pitch strikes, be more aggressive with his
fastball, throw strikes at his knees and trust his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After the first inning on this night, Mlicki not only seemed to
take heed of those words, he reverted to the pitching style that
made the Mets fond of him at one time.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Mlicki allowed a leadoff double to Neifi
Perez. A sacrifice and two outs later, Perez gave the Rockies a 1-0
lead on a RBI-single by Larry Walker.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, Mlicki recovered to allow only three hits in the
next seven innings. Only Kile, who led off the sixth with a single,
was able to reach third base after the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the potential to be a very good fifth-day starter
here,'' Gregson said. ``Here's a guy that has four pitches, decent
command on all of them and movement on his fastball. The potential
is there to be an excellent starter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers used Antonio Osuna and Scott Radinsky in the ninth
before Greg McMichael, also acquired in the Nomo trade, struck out
Vinny Castilla with a runner on first to end the game and earn his
first save of the season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
