<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-OCEANS (Monterey, Calif.) _ Clinton, navigating a narrow
course between environmentalists and oil companies, announced on
Friday a 10-year extension on the current moratorium on oil
drilling off virtually all American coastlines. Clinton also placed
several existing marine sanctuaries permanently off-limits to oil
exploration. The moratorium does not, however, protect any new
areas not already covered by the drilling ban first imposed by
President Bush in 1990. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-JUDGE-DELAY (Washington) _ Judge Sonia Sotomayor seemed
like a trouble-free choice when President Clinton first nominated
her to an appeals court post a year ago. But Republican senators
have been blocking Judge Sotomayor's elevation to the appeals court
for a highly unusual reason; to make her less likely to be picked
by Clinton for the Supreme Court, senior Republican congressional
aides said in interviews. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Prosecutors looking into President
Clinton's relationship with a former White House intern are
investigating contacts between one of his senior aides and
potential witnesses shortly after the investigation began,
according to lawyers who have read a sealed legal opinion
describing the contacts. By James Bennet. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   ASTRO-GLENN (Washington) _ When he rockets up in October for a
nine-day ride at the age of 77, Glenn, who 36 years ago became the
first American to orbit the earth, will once more be a space
pioneer, running a myriad of geriatric medical experiments on
himself as the oldest space traveler ever. But as a retrofitted
astronaut the Democrat from Ohio will also be ending his Senate
career in a bang and a rush that he tacitly acknowledges with a
sparkle-eyed smile. By Francis X. Clines. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NY-BUNKER (New York) _ Having tamed squeegee men and cabbies,
murderers and muggers, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has quietly been
bracing for all manner of human treachery and cataclysms, building
a $15.1 million emergency control center for his administration _
bullet-proofed, hardened to withstand bombs and hurricanes, and
equipped with food and beds for at least 30 members of his inner
circle. By Kit R. Roane. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-MOMS (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ As more mothers of young
children run for office, they are finding that the issue of
motherhood cuts both ways with voters. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-CHILD-ABUSE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ A judge ordered a new
trial for the woman who was convicted more than 10 years ago of
abusing children at her family's Fells Acres Day Care Center. In a
decision that could have implications for hundreds of child abuse
cases around the nation, Superior Court Judge Isaac Borenstein said
that the child abuse trial of Cheryl Amirault LeFave was tainted by
flawed interviews of children. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   NY-PARK-LAWN (New York) _ The Central Park Conservancy, the
private group now responsible for day-to-day management of the
park, is determined to protect the investment in the Great Lawn _
everything from 250 computer-controlled, pop-up sprinklers to more
than 2,000 new trees and shrubs to the centerpiece, 1 million
square feet of amazingly weedless grass. So it has created a new
position with a broad mandate and a grandiose title: Keeper of the
Great Lawn. By Douglas Martin. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TECHNOLOGY (Washington) _ Powerful evidence has emerged
that China has been using U.S. technology for military purposes,
taking advantage of the Bush and Clinton administrations' decisions
to encourage high technology sales in Asia. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (London) _ Reinforcing the NATO alliance's threat
of military action to stop the violence in Kosovo, the United
States, Russia and six other major industrial democracies meeting
in London on Friday demanded an immediate stop to Serb attacks on
ethnic Albanian civilians in the province. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi) _ An Indian proposal for talks with
Pakistan later this month on ways of lessening tensions in the
Indian subcontinent was quickly rejected by Pakistan on Friday, but
the exchange appeared to have moved both governments closer to
direct negotiations over the crisis set off by the nuclear tests
that both conducted last month. By John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-GUERRERO (El Charco, Mexico) _ The stucco walls of the
two-room schoolhouse are gouged with hundreds of bullet holes and
stained with patterns of dried blood: a handprint that slides
downward, a broad wash that spills into a thick puddle on the
floor. These are what remains of a three-hour shootout on Sunday
morning at the hilltop school between army troops and armed
fighters whom the authorities have identified as members of a
clandestine rebel group, the Popular Revolutionary Army. By Julia
Preston. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-COCA (Lauca Ene, Bolivia) _ Like congressmen all over
the world, Evo Morales hugs babies and makes fist-thumping
speeches. But that's where the similarities end. As Morales
returned to his district recently, he was not at all embarrassed to
be photographed caressing the coca bushes that grow on his
property. At age 38, Morales is the spokesman for six of the seven
coca grower unions in Bolivia, and he is the single most powerful
politician standing in the way of efforts by the United Nations and
the U.S. and Bolivian governments to fight the Bolivian cocaine
trade. By Clifford Krauss. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   MOSCOW-ILLEGAL-LABOR (Moscow) _ By some estimates, there are as
many as a million foreign workers in and around Moscow _ many from
Ukraine, Moldova and other parts of the former Soviet Union _ who
come here offering their labor at virtually any price. Some are
paid as little as $100 a month, some three times as much. Some get
paid virtually nothing _ once the cost of housing and food have
been deducted. By Celestine Bohlen. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Removing any lingering doubts that Japan is
in a full-blown recession, the Finance Ministry said that the
economy contracted at a 5.3 percent annual rate in the year's first
quarter. By Sheryl WuDunn. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Detroit) _ By Friday, about 50,500 workers had been
laid off at 13 assembly plants and 59 parts plants in the United
States, Mexico, and Canada because of a shortage of parts from the
stamping plant. That is in addition to the nearly 9,200 workers on
strike at both plants. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDED-DRUGS (Undated) _ With too many players in too many
parts of the business, companies that primarily sell generic drugs
often find themselves lost in the crowd, able to stand out on
pharmacy shelves only by cutting prices. More and more, though,
they are replacing the identically drab scientific labels on their
products with brand names of their own, raising prices in step with
a higher profile. By David J. Morrow. (With graphic and photo.)
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-CONFLICTS (New York) _ In the cozy world of corporate
finance, bankers and lawyers are finding themselves straddling both
sides of merger negotiations these days in what some critics say is
a risky move for companies and their shareholders. By Laura M.
Holson.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ The stock market continued to cascade
Friday, falling sharply for the fourth consecutive session on
renewed concerns about Asia's economic woes, before a rally late in
the day pushed prices higher. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   SIXTIES-REVISITED (Undated) _ Historians are beginning to
rewrite the history of the 1960s, saying that the culture wars have
distorted our understanding of the period. By Patti Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
