<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-13 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER PITCHES THREE-HITTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ After the Mariners scored two runs in the
first inning Friday night, Jamie Moyer was in no mood to give any
of the early lead away.
</P>
<P>
   And even when his supporting cast added runs on solo home runs
by Glenallen Hill and Alex Rodriguez, the Mariners' hard-luck lefty
kept throwing zeroes at the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Nine in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most impressive outings by a starting pitcher this
season, Moyer pitched a complete-game three-hitter in the Mariners'
5-0 victory before 11,533 fans at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen never stirred,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   No need to.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a mini-jam in the second inning, when Oakland used an
error and single to put two runners on base with none out, Moyer
never encountered serious trouble along the way to his fourth win
and second solo shutout of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a key moment in the game, he said, ``Not
really.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was nice pitching out there,'' first baseman David Segui
said. ``It was good to get him those two runs early, because the
way he was pitching, you knew it would be enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rodriguez: ``When Jamie gets in a groove like that, the
game just flows and it's fun playing behind him.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui knocked in the first run and scored the second as the M's
handed Oakland starter Tom Candiotti his eighth loss, although he
also pitched well enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Candiotti retired Joey Cora and Rodriguez in the first inning,
but walked Ken Griffey Jr. Segui unloaded what everyone thought was
a two-run homer to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   But the ball caromed off the top of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, preparing himself for an easy-going trek around the
bases, turned on the jets when he noticed the ball come back into
the park and raced home with the game's first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior had to run harder than he wanted and so did I,'' Segui
said.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez delivered a run-scoring single to left field past
shortstop Miguel Tejada, who attempted a backhanded stab instead of
getting in front of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer had an easy first inning.
</P>
<P>
   And a not-so-easy second, starting with third baseman Russ
Davis' 16th error of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Davis uncorked a wild throw to first base after fielding Kevin
Mitchell's broken-bat grounder and Matt Stairs followed the error
with a single to left, putting the tying runs on base with none
out.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer didn't blink, retiring Mike Blowers on a foul pop, Jason
Giambi on a fly out to left and Tejada on a force play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like typical Jamie Moyer,'' said Blowers, who played
for the Mariners last season. ``He changed speeds, threw strikes
and moved the ball around.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill's familiarity with Candiotti paid off.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out in the first inning, Hill hit his 11th homer
of the season in the fourth, giving Moyer a 3-0 lead. Hill entered
the game with a .414 (12-for-29) career average and four homers
against the knuckleball specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had good success against him and other knuckleball
pitchers and I don't know why,'' Hill said. ``He had a good one
(Friday night).''
</P>
<P>
   Hill tagged his fifth career homer off Candiotti in the fourth
inning and helped Moyer out two innings later when he made a diving
catch to rob Rickey Henderson of a leadoff hit.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer appreciated the support, both with the bats and gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his six losses came in games the Mariners were shut out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candiotti pitched well and that's a good lineup over there,''
Moyer said of the A's. ``The keys are keeping the top and bottom of
their lineup off the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what he did. And more.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the second-inning single by Stairs, Moyer allowed a
two-out double to Ben Grieve in the sixth and leadoff double to
Tejada in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Oakland runners reached third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners scored twice in the seventh inning, the first on
Rodriguez's 23rd homer of the season, to give Moyer a five-run
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez now has as many home runs this season as he did all of
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even count last year,'' said Rodriguez, who was hurt
for much of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
