<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE-LED JAZZ POSTPONE BULLS' PARTY, SEND NBA FINALS BACK TO
UTAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ With an opportunity to end the NBA Finals and possibly
toast one of the greatest sports dynasties ever, the Chicago Bulls
stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's 83-81 victory in Game 5 was more than a mere roadblock in
the Bulls' title quest. Not only is the series headed back to Salt
Lake City for Game 6 on Sunday, but the Jazz go home knowing they
just spoiled one big night in the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone was most defiant to the script that had the Bulls
claiming a sixth NBA championship in this decade. He scored a
game-high 39 points and finally came up big in the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish, Malone played aggressively and provided
clutch plays. It was clearly his most dominant performance of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Jazz lost the title to the Bulls in six games.
Utah trails this best-of-seven series 3-2, but this time, the Jazz
own home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Game 7, it will be played at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no easy cakewalk trying to win in Utah,'' Chicago's
Michael Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   At least in Utah, the Bulls won't have to worry about the
Illinois State Patrol officer who helped clear Malone's mind.
Malone spent most of Thursday riding in a state patrol car with a
friend, trying to escape the negative press about his poor showings
in the first four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize all the stuff that's been said. And I was able to
get away and get completely away from basketball,'' said Malone,
who made 17 of 27 shots. ``Thursday, I got totally out of the city.
After practice I left with a friend _ went and rode with him and
had a great time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds corny to you guys,'' Malone said. ``But I
don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz certainly rode Malone past the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was terrific. He made some big shots and in the (key) part
of the ballgame, too,'' Jazz point guard John Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's All-Star forward scored 25 points in the second half _ 17
in the third quarter and eight in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who is known for taking over games, watched Malone step
into the starring role this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got into a great rhythm,'' Jordan said. ``Dennis (Rodman),
Luc (Longley) ... no one could stop him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made up our minds to get him the basketball,'' Utah coach
Jerry Sloan said, adding that he thought his team fought and stood
up to the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to stand up. When you stand up in this business you get
more respect,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Game 1, the Jazz got the Bulls'
attention in the closing minutes with big plays. Utah had
floundered in crunch time of the three previous games. But from the
two-minute mark until the final buzzer Friday, the Jazz battled.
</P>
<P>
   Utah never unraveled _ even when its seven-point lead dwindled
to 80-78 with 18.9 seconds left. Antoine Carr just calmly stroked
two free throws for a four-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago, though, kept threatening. Toni Kukoc fired right back
with a 3-pointer that got the Bulls within 82-81. Then, Jeff
Hornacek split a pair of free throws to give Utah a two-point lead
with 1.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Chicago still had a chance to win the game with a
miracle shot, it was clear Utah would not be denied. Jordan heaved
a 3-pointer at the buzzer that didn't hit the rim.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz held the Bulls to 39-percent shooting. Utah hit 50
percent of its shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't the aggressor out there tonight. We were back
on our heels,'' Bulls forward Scottie Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz had their biggest scoring period of the series with 29
points in the third. Before Friday night's game, Utah had scored
less than 20 points in 11 of the 16 quarters played in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had stretches that nobody's very happy with, but I
don't think anybody's worried about it,'' Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   For as much as the Bulls have been praised for their defensive
stance in this series, they will work on getting better offense for
Game 6. With the exception of Kukoc _ who scored 30 points on
11-of-13 shooting _ the Bulls were harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan finished with 28 points but missed 15 of his 26 shots.
Pippen spoiled his series MVP bid with a 2-for-16 night despite
collecting 11 rebounds and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine. We know it was just a matter of things happening
down the stretch,'' Chicago coach Phil Jackson said. `` ... I
thought it was a matter of sequences. It's not a big thing with us
losing one close game.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Jazz see it, all they have to do is make sure the
Bulls lose another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to prove. We just have to continue to believe
in each other,'' Malone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
