<HEADLINE>
GOING, GOING, GONE  
 MCGWIRE'S GRAND SLAM IGNITES CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was some question as to whether a ball hit to right field
by the Diamondbacks' Andy Fox left Bank One Ballpark in the first
inning of Friday night's game against the St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The hit was ruled a home run, although Fox hustled around the
bases and slid head first across the plate just to make sure.
</P>
<P>
   When Cardinals first baseman Mark McGwire came to the plate in
the third inning, there was no need for him to sprint or get his
uniform dirty.
</P>
<P>
   There was no question as to whether the ball he hit to left
field off right-hander Andy Benes left the ballpark. The STATE,
maybe . . .
</P>
<P>
   McGwire made the slow jog around the bases, trailing the three
men who were on base ahead of him. The 438-foot shot was his 31st
homer of the season, his second grand slam of the season and 11th
of his career, and highlighted an eight-run inning as the Cardinals
pounded the Diamondbacks, 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton added a three-run homer off Benes in the
third inning to help the Cardinals raise their record to 31-34.
Arizona, which lost its second straight, fell to 21-46.
</P>
<P>
   After charging up the 11th sellout crowd of the season with some
gargantuan shots during batting practice, McGwire struck out on a
Benes fastball to end the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Benes) went right at me in the first at-bat,'' McGwire
said. ``It was the first time I ever faced him and I never
visualized him before.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes, who beat his former Cardinals teammates in St. Louis on
April 16, struck out two more in the second and looked to be on his
way to a strong performance.
</P>
<P>
   But he gave up the tying run on an RBI double by Tom Lampkin in
the third, then loaded the bases to set up the second duel with
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-0 pitch moved over the plate, McGwire swung his powerful
arms, made contact and quickly dropped his bat. He knew. So did
everyone else. Sayonara.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was on deck, I didn't realize the bases were loaded
because I was visualizing how he was throwing,'' McGwire said. ``It
was a fastball out over the plate and I was able to extend on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire now has 80 RBIs, tying him for the major-league lead
with the Texas Rangers' Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter stuck with Benes, and it
proved to be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   After getting Brian Jordan on a groundout, Benes gave up a
single to Willie McGee and a double to John Mabry before Clayton
connected for his three-run homer to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Benes (4-7) came out for a pinch-hitter in the bottom of the
third after throwing 73 pitches. It was his shortest stint as a
member of the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed I didn't give the team an opportunity to
win,'' Benes said. ``I've given up a lot of runs before, but this
is the worst I've ever had. I've never given up eight runs in an
inning before. I made bad pitches and they took advantage of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Showalter: ``He had good stuff early, just like in Oakland
(a 10-5 loss on Saturday), but he just couldn't get through the
inning. He threw 50 pitches in that inning and I didn't want to
jeopardize his health (by leaving him in longer).''
</P>
<P>
   Of McGwire's slam, Showalter said, ``Mark is great for the game
of baseball. Anybody who looks at it any other way is pretty
shallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Willie Banks entered the game and shut out the
Cardinals for three innings. Right-hander Felix Rodriguez pitched a
scoreless seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks came to life in their half of the seventh
against right-hander Todd Stottlemyre (7-5), the Cardinals'
starter. They cut the lead to 8-4 on a run-scoring single by David
Dellucci, a fielder's choice grounder by Jay Bell and a run-scoring
single by Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis picked up an insurance run in the eighth when Clayton
walked, moved to second on a passed ball by Stinnett (the
Diamondbacks' first passed ball of the season) and later scored on
a sacrifice fly by Delino DeShields. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
