<HEADLINE>
DE LA HOYA BECOMES MUCH MORE THAN BOXER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ Ali had Frazier. Sugar Ray Leonard had Roberto Duran
and Thomas Hearns.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar De La Hoya?
</P>
<P>
   He has it all.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs dangerous rivals?
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya has parlayed movie-star looks, an Olympic gold medal,
camera-friendly charisma, innate salesmanship and a disarming smile
into success previously unknown in a sport where the big winners
pay a punishing price.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya hasn't had to pay. For him, there are none of the
scars that other fighters have always worn like a combat veteran
with a Purple Heart. For them, there is victory in survival. But De
La Hoya already has won a lot more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The proof is in his amazing impact on El Paso and Juarez,
Mexico, during the days before he defends his World Boxing Council
welterweight title tonight against a little-known Frenchman,
Patrick Charpentier.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the fight. It's just the last stop in one long parade
with one example after another of De La Hoya's huge popularity,
despite lingering doubts about him as a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, look, I'm not expecting Armageddon here,'' said Bob Arum,
the promoter for the heavily favored De La Hoya (27-0, 22
knockouts), who was 147 pounds Friday at the official weigh-in.
Charpentier (27-4-1, 22 KOs) tipped the scale at 146, one less than
the welterweight limit.
</P>
<P>
   No, Arum is only expecting the largest outdoor crowd for a
boxing match in the United States in 43 years. About 45,000 tickets
had been sold by Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With 50,000 to 60,000 customers expected by opening bell (7 p.m.
on Home Box Office), the Sun Bowl crowd would be the biggest in the
United States since 1955, when Rocky Marciano beat Archie Moore in
front of 61,500 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning difference is that De La Hoya vs. Charpentier is
hardly Marciano vs. Moore. This is more like iceberg vs. Titanic.
It's a colossal mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the crowds are here just to see De La Hoya, who will pocket
$4 million to Charpentier's $600,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fans flew in from Phoenix. They drove down from Albuquerque.
They walked over the bridges that cross the Rio Grande from Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just by having the event here has me motivated,'' said De La
Hoya, who has been inactive since a victory Dec. 6 over Wilfredo
Rivera. ``All the people, all the fans. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya's status as a Latin sex symbol is the key. He may _
or may not _ be the world's best fighter, pound for pound. But
heartbeat for heartbeat, he has no challengers.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 shrieking girls greeted him a couple of days ago
when he stepped off his jet at a private El Paso airport. They
chanted, ``Oscar, Oscar.'' Some carried his picture in one hand as
though it were a religious item. Others reached through a
chain-link fence in an attempt to touch him. They threw underwear
at him. De La Hoya autographed at least one brassiere. No word yet
on whether he'll endorse a Victoria's Secret line.
</P>
<P>
   All those young women aren't there to see that face get bloodied
and bruised. And for now, De La Hoya doesn't appear to be in a
headlong rush toward that dangerous possibility.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest threats are International Boxing Federation
champion Felix Trinidad (32-0) of Puerto Rico, World Boxing
Association champ Ike Quartey (34-0-1) of Ghana and emerging
contender Jose Luis Lopez (40-3-2) of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Arum said he has talked to Trinidad about a fight in May. Money,
he said, has been discussed. From $7 million to $8 million would go
to each fighter, with De La Hoya getting a larger share of the gate
and television receipts.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very intriguing. The young Trinidad looms as a bout in
which De La Hoya, 25, could define himself as a truly great
fighter. A rematch Sept. 18 against an aging Julio Cesar Chavez,
badly beaten in the first bout, does not hold that promise.
</P>
<P>
   But why, oh why, tamper with success? De La Hoya earned $36
million to $38 million for five fights last year. ``Fortune''
magazine lists him as the world's third-highest-paid athlete in
1997 behind Michael Jordan and Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agenda, a schedule,'' according to De La Hoya, who
said he eventually will meet Trinidad and possibly Quartey. ``There
is no rush.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no need to. Just look around. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
