</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CARDINALS-MCGWIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE'S THE REAL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After another game or two, Michael Jordan no longer will claim
the title of ``Greatest Show in Sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Ronaldo fans, once-every-four-years kind of sports don't
count.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Chicago Bulls beat the Utah Jazz in the NBA Finals, or
even if they don't, the rest of the spring, the summer and the fall
belong to Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night at Bank One Ballpark, McGwire again demonstrated
his Jordanesque magic. He entertains. He amazes. Most important, he
delivers. It isn't much of a leap to ``I want to be like Mac.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony La Russa, who was McGwire's manager in Oakland and now in
St. Louis, called his first baseman ``the most incredible thing in
sports,'' being sure to pay homage to the likes of Jordan, Evander
Holyfield and, yes, Renaldo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's at that level,'' La Russa said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire put on another spectacular display during batting
practice before the Cardinals played the Diamondbacks, actually
sending a ball through one of the open advertising panels in
left-center field and out of the ballpark. That was cool. No one
had ever done that before. And La Russa, remarkably, said McGwire
``didn't have a great BP today.'' Regardless, it still didn't
count.
</P>
<P>
   What did count happened in the top of the third inning, when
McGwire stepped in against Andy Benes with the bases loaded, one
out and the score tied at one. An electric buzz of expectancy
surged through the crowd, which cheered when Benes struck McGwire
out in the first inning. The greatest home-run hitter alive (and
maybe, perhaps, ever) was coming up in the one situation in which a
home-run hitter can do the most damage.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Benes said he respects McGwire but doesn't fear
him, and welcomed the opportunity to challenge him. It worked in
the first inning. It didn't work again.
</P>
<P>
   Benes challenged McGwire with a fastball down the middle, and
McGwire _ like Jordan does at precisely the right moment _
delivered, sending the 1-0 pitch to a hasty exit into the
left-field seats for his 31st home run and second grand slam of the
season. It provided half the Cards' eight-run third inning and led
to a 9-4 victory.
</P>
<P>
   With 65 games played and 97 remaining, McGwire has reached the
halfway point in pursuit of breaking Roger Maris' record of 61 home
runs, although he is reluctant to admit he is chasing anything
except excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until somebody gets to 50 homers by September, then it's worth
talking about,'' he said. ``But now, there's a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   As is customary, McGwire acted as if nothing was unusual about
the blast, other than it came off a pitcher he never had faced
before. That partly explained the first-inning strikeout. It also
partly explained the home run (not to forget, too, McGwire's
rigorous training and ungodly strength), because McGwire said he
was able to ``visualize'' Benes after facing him.
</P>
<P>
   And it helps when Brian Jordan, not Brent Mayne (the guy
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter walked Barry Bonds with the
bases loaded to get to) is hitting behind you. Jordan is hitting
.340. McGwire leads the majors in walks, but he might never see a
strike if not for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either they've got to pitch to him or me,'' Jordan said.
``Teams know I can beat them, too. They're challenging him, and
they're paying for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
