<SLUG> BC-BBN-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES POUNCE ON GIANTS' ERRORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY SCHULMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ A 3-0 deficit means squat, because the team plays so
well at home, and gets such a charge out of its fans, it can pounce
on an opponents' slightest mistake and steal a game that seems
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar, Giants fans?
</P>
<P>
   The same formula that lifted San Francisco to the top of the
National League West got San Diego there as well. The Padres were
22-7 at home going into Friday night's first-place showdown, and
now they are 23-7 because they gave no quarter after the Giants
committed two late-inning misplays.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Rich Aurilia's first error of the season helped San
Diego tie the game 3-3 in the seventh, and a throwing error by
reliever Steve Reed in the eighth paved the way for a seven-run
bloodbath against Reed and Jim Poole that resulted in a 10-3 Padres
laugher.
</P>
<P>
   A fireworks-night crowd of 60,789, the largest in San Diego
baseball history and the biggest in the majors this year, reveled
as the Padres overcame homers by Rey Sanchez and Barry Bonds to
regain sole possession of first place by a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good game for a while,'' manager Dusty Baker said.
``In a big game like this, the team that usually makes mistakes is
the team that loses. Usually, we don't make mistakes like this. It
was very uncharacteristic. Hopefully we'll play better tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Two hours before the game, Baker closed the clubhouse doors and
conducted what he called a ``light meeting'' with his position
players to remind them that with cleanup hitter Jeff Kent out for
at least two weeks, everyone would have to do the ``little things''
right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small things become more prevalent than before. When you
take away your No.2 run producer, you've got to make it up in other
areas, like defense, pitching, baserunning and fundamentals, things
like relays and reading signs,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, with the Giants clinging to a 3-2 lead, Quilvio
Veras led off the seventh with a bouncer that pitcher Rich
Rodriguez deflected toward Aurilia, who threw awkwardly and bounced
the ball past Charlie Hayes at first base. Veras motored to second.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez struck out Steve Finley, and new pitcher Reed got Greg
Vaughn to fly out to left, But Ken Caminiti lined a two-out double
to right, and Veras came home to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   Reed was still pitching when Chris Gomez started the eighth with
a single to right. Mandy Romero knocked a terrible bunt back to
Reed, who had plenty of time to nail Gomez at second. Instead, he
fired the ball into center field. The big inning was on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was totally my fault,'' Reed said. ``It was frustrating
in a big game like that. I just stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole relieved Reed _ Rich Rodriguez, the other left-handed
reliever, had already been used _ and Veras quickly put the Padres
ahead 4-3 with a single to right. Finley popped up, but Vaughn
doubled home a run to make it 5-3. Wally Joyner singled home two
more, and Ruben Rivera completed the rout with a long three-run
homer to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to say I haven't felt anywhere near that bad this
year,'' Poole said. ``I picked a lousy night for it. The whole
night, out of the 30 pitches I heaved up there, only two or three
went where I wanted them to go. My body felt cranky, and I couldn't
react a darn.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a night that began so impressively for the Giants, with
Kirk Rueter striking out five Padres looking, with Sanchez hitting
his eighth career homer in 2,097 big-league at-bats, and Bonds
hitting the 26th of his career in this ballpark, ended in
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Giants left the park with the same tire
marks down their backs that their opponents often wear when they
leave San Francisco. Practically everything went San Diego's way.
Even Tony Gwynn, who was supposed to be out the whole series with a
calf injury, contributed a sacrifice fly when Padres manager Bruce
Bochy surprisingly sent him to bat in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of heart on this team,'' Vaughn said, mimicking
a quote heard often in the other locker room. ``It was nice to come
back like that. We're just trying to get some space between us and
them.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
