<HEADLINE>
CART, IRL STILL FAR APART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was late afternoon. The infield media room at Indianapolis
Motor Speedway nearly was deserted except for a few reporters, who
had Tony George surrounded two days before last month's 82nd
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony, do you foresee a Championship Auto Racing Teams and Indy
Racing League reconciliation?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony, do city fathers blame you for empty hotel rooms because
of the CART vs. IRL split?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony, do you anticipate CART drivers one day again converging
at Indy in May to do battle against IRL drivers in a one-day
shootout?''
</P>
<P>
   Yada, yada, yada.
</P>
<P>
   While fans and sponsors likely would embrace a CART-IRL merger,
chances of such a partnership are about as remote as peace in the
Middle East. Or so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   George, president of Indianapolis Motor Speedway, created the
IRL three years ago because he believed the sport was heading in
the wrong direction and wanted to establish an affordable series
that rewarded young American drivers with Indy-car opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as CART continues to expand its racing borders to
venues outside the United States, the IRL remains committed to an
all-oval series.
</P>
<P>
   Even if CART teams desired to make Indy 500 qualifying attempts,
several roadblocks _ primarily thin wallets _ make it virtually
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Because the two sanctioning bodies operate under different
chassis and engine formulas, CART owners would have to purchase
separate equipment at a huge cost.
</P>
<P>
   And the last time I looked, Bill Gates wasn't listed as a CART
car owner.
</P>
<P>
   So get used to it, folks. Although rumors along pit road
indicate CART driver Al Unser Jr. may wind up on next year's Indy
500 starting grid, there are no clear signs the factions are about
to sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody tries to characterize this as the IRL trying to keep
drivers away,'' George said. ``Drivers really don't have a lot to
say or do about the situation. I'm sure they miss being here. Some
probably don't know what it's like being here because they've never
been here. So they don't miss it. I know there are a couple who
very much want to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   George is wrong. Ask any CART driver, and under the right
circumstances, they'd all love to make plans in May at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   But as George insinuated, CART drivers get their paychecks from
CART owners, and we all know what that means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, I think everyone will come to appreciate the IRL
for what it represents, and that is the opportunity to come and
compete at a reasonable level and be a part of putting on a good
show,'' George said.
</P>
<P>
   No one can argue last weekend's race at Texas Motor Speedway
didn't deserve high marks on the thrill-o-meter. It was an exciting
race, breathtaking at times.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers provided enough side-by-side racing to satisfy even
stock-car fans.
</P>
<P>
   But while it's wonderful to see talents such as Billy Boat and
J.J. Yeley receive opportunities they likely would not have
received without the IRL, it's the opinion of many that the Indy
500 has taken a huge whack in the prestige department.
</P>
<P>
   And I agree. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Schedule expanding &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rumors that a NASCAR Winston Cup race at Homestead (Fla.)
Motorsports Complex will be added to next year's schedule escalated
into a newspaper report earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a possibility of growing or shrinking, but it's
still too early to address 1999,'' NASCAR Vice President for
Competition Mike Helton said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now I've got a rumor I want to start.
</P>
<P>
   How about a second race at PIR within three to five years? It
would be a night race, possibly held in May or June.
</P>
<P>
   International Speedway Corp., which owns PIR, just renewed its
contract with The Nashville Network for three years at a huge
increase. And ISC would like to add 25,000 additional seats within
five years, which would increase seating capacity to nearly
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   A long shot? Perhaps. But who would have believed 15 years ago
that PIR would one day become part of the Winston Cup schedule? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sing, sing &QL; 
 &QL; 
Country music heartthrob Randy Travis will sing the national anthem
at the NASCAR Winston Cup Dura-Lube 500 on Oct. 25 at Phoenix
International Raceway. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
