<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BKN-NBAFINALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ SQUELCH BULLS' CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STEELE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There was supposed to be champagne in the home team's
locker room. Instead, a half-hour after Game 5 of the NBA Finals at
the United Center on Friday night, there was nothing but discarded
tape and assorted refuse. In the Jazz locker room, there were bags
packed and stacked near the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz were going home, not to lick their wounds and count
their regrets, but to play ball and keep competing for the NBA
championship. The Bulls were headed not into a night of anarchy on
the streets of Chicago, but back to the Delta Center to try again
to take their sixth crown of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   It almost went according to the Bulls' plan; it wasn't until
Michael Jordan missed a 3-point heave at the buzzer that the Bulls
succumbed to the Jazz 83-81 and saw their lead in the series fall
to 3-2. The heroes were not Jordan or Scottie Pippen or Dennis
Rodman, but Karl Malone (finally) and Antoine Carr (surprisingly).
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls still have two chances to wrap up the title, but if
both are needed, both will be in Salt Lake City, starting tomorrow.
``We'll get on the plane (today),'' said Jordan, who scored 28
points, ``and I hope that everybody has forgotten about this game.
Sure, we blew our opportunity, but this has happened to us
before.''
</P>
<P>
   In the exact same circumstance in 1993, they lost Game 5 to the
Suns and then won the title in Game 6 in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But, Jordan added, ``I think the heart and determination and
desire was there, but our bodies weren't. We didn't move. Sometimes
the body doesn't react to what the mind is trying to tell you.
Tonight was one of those nights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz moved just fine, especially Malone, who scored 39
points, 25 in a second half his team dominated. Five days after
setting records for futility in a 96-54 thrashing, they ran off 53
second-half points against a previously-impenetrable Bulls'
defense, highlighting a comeback from a 36-30 halftime deficit that
was spurred by 14 Jazz turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what an individual guy does on this team,'' Malone
said, ``we're going to win it or lose it together, and that's our
motto. We have nothing to prove (against the Bulls). We just have
to continue to believe in each other as a team. When we make up our
minds as a team, as a group, to play defense, execute our plays and
rebound, we're a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   The group turned it up more than it had at any other time in
this series. Malone had been invisible in the fourth quarter in the
four previous games, but dropped in eight in the final period
Friday night _ none bigger than a turnaround jumper from the left
side with 53.3 seconds left that gave his team an 80-76 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That basket, as did so many others, came against Rodman, who was
completely ineffective, with three rebounds and five fouls in 24
minutes. Luc Longley did even less _ he was unable to present any
kind of a challenge to Malone and was held scoreless until 10
minutes remained, despite several early easy chances from in close.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Carr, meanwhile, started the second half at
center when coach Jerry Sloan went to his last possible option as a
fifth starter (Greg Ostertag, Greg Foster and Adam Keefe having
failed miserably before). Asked what inspired him to go with the
little-used Carr, Sloan deadpanned, ``First of all, he was able to
catch the basketball.'' He did far more than that, going 5-for-5 in
the second half and scoring 12 points, eight in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc was brilliant for the Bulls, with a playoff
career-high 30 points _ including 13 of the Bulls' first 14 points,
as Jordan and Pippen were out of sync. Pippen never got into sync:
After two days of being hyped for Finals Most Valuable Player,
Pippen went until the final seconds of the first half before
scoring his first basket and finished with six points on 2-for-16
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Despite everything Malone and Carr did, and everything Pippen
and Rodman didn't do, the Bulls had one last chance to pop the
corks.
</P>
<P>
   A 78-71 Jazz lead with 1:56 left was sliced to 82-81 with 5.5
seconds left, on the second of two late Kukoc 3-pointers. The
Jazz's Jeff Hornacek, a career 89 percent free-throw shooter in the
playoffs, managed to make just one of two with 1.1 seconds left _
and it was the second, which allowed the Bulls to call timeout and
inbound the ball at midcourt. After a deflection reduced the clock
to eight-tenths of a second, Jordan took the inbound pass and got a
good look from 26 feet, but left his jumper short.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, John Stockton said of the Jazz, ``We're still in the hunt.
Still alive, still kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
