<SLUG> BC-BKN-BICKLEY_NBAFINALS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, JAZZ TAKES A SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You wondered when they were going to take it personally. When
they were going to get angry. When they were going to get tough.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 quarters, it finally happened.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was the open debate as to which Bulls superstar would
win the MVP. Or the lady who received an autograph from Greg
Ostertag only to say, ``You're going to lose anyway.'' Or the slew
of derisive prank calls reaching them at their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 quarters, it finally happened. And the Jazz has a
chance to make this a series after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the hunt, we're still kicking,'' John Stockton
said. ``And we're going home.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, this was the injured pride of Karl Malone
swelling into uncontrollable rage, a man who finally joined a
series in progress. A man who shed two creatures clinging two his
back _ King Kong and Rodzilla _ and finally carried his team to
victory.
</P>
<P>
   With his entire legacy turning to mush, with a nation ignoring
his chiseled frame and focusing on his soft cranium, Malone
responded the way an MVP does. He rained in jumpers, he pounded
away inside, he treated Dennis Rodman like a chew toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the criticism he received in this series,'' Michael
Jordan said, ``he put some things to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and Malone found inspiration in the strangest place. On
Thursday, Malone went riding with an Illinois state trooper. Just
sat in a squad car and cruised the highways. Stopped at a weigh
station and watched trucks pull up on a cargo scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it sounds corny to you guys,'' Malone said. ``I don't
care what you guys do on your off day, but I wanted to change up
and do something different. I always wanted to be, in my little
world, a state trooper . . . So I got to ride with one. You can
laugh all the hell you want to, it was a fun day for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After a ragged first half that resembled a pickup game among
CEOs, Jazz Coach Jerry Sloan made two key adjustments. He started
Antoine Carr in the second half and received 12 points in 21
minutes. More importantly, it thwarted the Bulls' swarming defense
that had forced 13 turnovers in the first 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And in a moment of clarity, Sloan and the Jazz finally decided
to focus on Malone in the post, feeding him the ball on nearly
every possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to win ballgames with the Jazz, you go to Karl
Malone,'' Stockton said.
</P>
<P>
   As they did against the Suns in 1993, the Bulls lost a wonderful
opportunity to close out the series at home. They had not lost a
home game in the Finals since the night Charles Barkley saved the
city from riots, and they had vowed not to lose focus. But Scottie
Pippen had a horrible shooting night, Jordan never got rolling, and
Luc Longley continued to kill his team with a lack of production.
Oh, and Bulls Coach Phil Jackson placed part of the blame on
gridlock that made the commute downtown a mere two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad night, a bad day at the office,'' Jordan said.
``But I'm looking forward to getting the same room with a piano.
And I'd love to fly to Utah and toss the ball the moment we land.''
</P>
<P>
   For a brief second _ or 0.8 to be exact _ it appeared the
basketball gods were going to intervene and provide Jordan with the
ultimate moment. And really, who didn't expect his wild shot at the
end to find nothing but net?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't happen, and maybe it's an omen. After four games in which
the Jazz acted like ballerinas, shooting 10 free throws a game
fewer than its opponents, a passive bunch finally got tough. And
for all the wild mood swings, this is no different than two teams
that have defended their home court for five contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you stand up in this business, usually you get a little
more respect,'' Sloan said. ``To me, it's the most exciting thing
in sports. To see who will fight.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
