   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL: &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIRPOLLUTION (Beijing) _ The severity of China's air
pollution, now openly acknowledged by the government, has propelled
environmental issues onto the agenda of the Chinese-American summit
meeting that is to take place later this month. Chinese officials
say they are eager to have Washington's technical help in the
battle for cleaner air. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   CLIMATE-TALKS (Bonn, Germany) _ Six months ago in Kyoto, Japan,
delegates from around the world agreed for the first time to make
specific, legally binding reductions in industrialized countries'
emissions of heat-trapping gases believed to affect Earth's
climate. Now negotiators grappling with the details of putting the
first cuts into effect are finding the task as difficult as that of
hammering out the original accord. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-PRESS-LAWS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Turkey has some of the
most restrictive press laws of any country professing democracy.
Journalists who challenge long-established taboos risk falling
afoul of the anti-terror law, which bans propaganda for Kurdish
guerrillas or other groups that are considered threats to the
nation. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-CONTROVERSY (Chakothi, Kashmir) _ For the flashpoint of
a potential nuclear war, the fields in this Jhelum River valley
present a tranquil, bucolic scene. Water buffalo tug at crude
plows. Shoots of rice are beginning to sprout from watery,
mud-walled rectangles. But in the mountains jutting above, up the
steep dirt switchbacks, is the ``Line of Confrontation,'' a
550-mile chain of sandbagged trenches and concrete bunkers where
the Pakistani Army is dug in. Across the valley are almost
identical Indian fortifications. By John Kifner. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-AMWAY (Warsaw) _ A documentary that takes a caustic look
at the Polish operations of the American direct-sales company Amway
has set off an unusually strenuous debate here about press freedom.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Like an increasing
number of Protestant and Catholic people here, Penny Purdy says she
is beginning to feel, with some vestigial caution, that after 30
bloody years, peace may well have arrived to stay in Northern
Ireland. By James F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL: &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BENEFITS-GAP _ Since the 1970s, the gap in wages between skilled
and unskilled workers has widened sharply. But new research shows
the inequality doesn't stop there. Discrepancies in job benefits
and the quality of work life have also grown, pointing to a bigger
chasm than previously recognized. By Peter Passell.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-KILLINGS-TREND (Moses Lake, Wash.) _ While precise
answers may be elusive, the recent killing sprees in schools share
a remarkable number of common traits. The first of the rural,
multiple-victim student shootings, here in Moses Lake, looks in
many respects like a road map of what was to come. From this case
and interviews with police officers, prosecutors, psychologists and
parents of the attackers _ as well as the boys' own words _ several
patterns emerge. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-MORMONS (Salt Lake City) _ Over the last week, members
of two of the most determinedly missionary faiths in the United
States, the Southern Baptist Convention and the Church of Jesus
Christ of Latter-day Saints, have been coming face to face in what
has been a courteous if somewhat wary encounter. That it has been
happening here, on ground that the 19th-century Mormon leader
Brigham Young declared a modern-day Zion, is the work of the
Southern Baptists. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHINESE-THEATER (New York) _ For decades, Chinese immigrants
flocked to Chinatown's eight or so Chinese-language movie theaters
because the movies delivered about the only entertainment around
and because the theaters afforded a sense of community and comfort.
But soon, New York City's last Chinese-language theater, the Music
Palace, will take its final bow, its faded three-story structure to
be demolished and replaced by a gleaming office building. By David
W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-HAMAS-SUSPECT (Bridgeview, Ill.) _ The house on Thomas
Street in this suburb 15 miles southwest of Chicago has a red rose
bush growing under the front window, fishing rods leaning against
the door and two boys in Bulls T-shirts shooting baskets in the
drive. But, according to federal authorities, these stock images of
middle-American life are deceiving: this is the home of a man who
has operated secretly as a high-ranking member of the Islamic
terrorist organization Hamas, they say. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BILINGUAL-FOE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Ron Unz, the man who
beat bilingual education in the nation's most populous state, is no
slick demagogue or smooth revolutionary. By Frank Bruni. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SALAMANDER (Austin, Texas) _ Last year, Austin
environmentalists declared a major victory when, after a five-year
battle, the Interior Department agreed to add the Barton Springs
salamander to the list of endangered species. But now that victory
is looking hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-MEDIATION (Washington) _ Seeking to curb the sharp
rise in litigation over environmental disputes, Congress has
created the first federally financed institute to encourage
mediation as an alternative to trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-WHEAT (Washington) _ Under pressure from farmers,
the government is poised to re-allow the sale of wheat to India and
Pakistan despite economic sanctions by the United States against
those countries for their recent nuclear tests. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HOSPITAL-FRAUD _ A congressional effort to adopt a law
making it more difficult for prosecutors to bring cases against
hospitals under a federal fraud statute has lost support and no
longer has the votes to pass, sponsors of the legislation say. By
Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TOBACCO (Washington)_ The anti-smoking bill now before
the Senate has strayed far afield. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CATEGORIES (Washington) _ After years of study, the Clinton
administration decided last October that people could, for the
first time, identify themselves as members of more than one racial
group when they fill out federal forms. That was the easy part. By
Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
