<P>
   NY-CHINESE-THEATER (New York) _ For decades, Chinese immigrants
flocked to Chinatown's eight or so Chinese-language movie theaters
because the movies delivered about the only entertainment around
and because the theaters afforded a sense of community and comfort.
But soon, New York City's last Chinese-language theater, the Music
Palace, will take its final bow, its faded three-story structure to
be demolished and replaced by a gleaming office building. By David
W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ILL-HAMAS-SUSPECT (Bridgeview, Ill.) _ The house on Thomas
Street in this suburb 15 miles southwest of Chicago has a red rose
bush growing under the front window, fishing rods leaning against
the door and two boys in Bulls T-shirts shooting baskets in the
drive. But, according to federal authorities, these stock images of
middle-American life are deceiving: this is the home of a man who
has operated secretly as a high-ranking member of the Islamic
terrorist organization Hamas, they say. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BILINGUAL-FOE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Ron Unz, the man who
beat bilingual education in the nation's most populous state, is no
slick demagogue or smooth revolutionary. By Frank Bruni. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SALAMANDER (Austin, Texas) _ Last year, Austin
environmentalists declared a major victory when, after a five-year
battle, the Interior Department agreed to add the Barton Springs
salamander to the list of endangered species. But now that victory
is looking hollow.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-MEDIATION (Washington) _ Seeking to curb the sharp
rise in litigation over environmental disputes, Congress has
created the first federally financed institute to encourage
mediation as an alternative to trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN-WHEAT (Washington) _ Under pressure from farmers,
the government is poised to re-allow the sale of wheat to India and
Pakistan despite economic sanctions by the United States against
those countries for their recent nuclear tests. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HOSPITAL-FRAUD _ A congressional effort to adopt a law
making it more difficult for prosecutors to bring cases against
hospitals under a federal fraud statute has lost support and no
longer has the votes to pass, sponsors of the legislation say. By
Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TOBACCO (Washington)_ The anti-smoking bill now before
the Senate has strayed far afield. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-CATEGORIES (Washington) _ After years of study, the Clinton
administration decided last October that people could, for the
first time, identify themselves as members of more than one racial
group when they fill out federal forms. That was the easy part. By
Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12:30 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK TIMES PARTNERS: &LR;
