<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Sunday, June 14, Page 1. The N.Y. Times News Service Supervisor is
Tim Hilchey (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BENEFITS-GAP _ Since the 1970s, the gap in wages between skilled
and unskilled workers has widened sharply. But new research shows
the inequality doesn't stop there. Discrepancies in job benefits
and the quality of work life have also grown, pointing to a bigger
chasm than previously recognized. By Peter Passell. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIRPOLLUTION (Beijing) _ The severity of China's air
pollution, now openly acknowledged by the government, has propelled
environmental issues onto the agenda of the Chinese-American summit
meeting that is to take place later this month. Chinese officials
say they are eager to have Washington's technical help in the
battle for cleaner air. By Elisabeth Rosenthal. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 12:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-KILLINGS-TREND (Moses Lake, Wash.) _ While precise
answers may be elusive, the recent killing sprees in schools share
a remarkable number of common traits. The first of the rural,
multiple-victim student shootings, here in Moses Lake, looks in
many respects like a road map of what was to come. From this case
and interviews with police officers, prosecutors, psychologists and
parents of the attackers _ as well as the boys' own words _ several
patterns emerge. By Timothy Egan.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BILINGUAL-FOE (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Ron Unz, the man who
beat bilingual education in the nation's most populous state, is no
slick demagogue or smooth revolutionary. By Frank Bruni. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR-CONTROVERSY (Chakothi, Kashmir) _ For the flashpoint of
a potential nuclear war, the fields in this Jhelum River valley
present a tranquil, bucolic scene. Water buffalo tug at crude
plows. Shoots of rice are beginning to sprout from watery,
mud-walled rectangles. But in the mountains jutting above, up the
steep dirt switchbacks, is the ``Line of Confrontation,'' a
550-mile chain of sandbagged trenches and concrete bunkers where
the Pakistani Army is dug in. Across the valley are almost
identical Indian fortifications. By John Kifner. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHINESE-THEATER (New York) _ For decades, Chinese immigrants
flocked to Chinatown's eight or so Chinese-language movie theaters
because the movies delivered about the only entertainment around
and because the theaters afforded a sense of community and comfort.
But soon, New York City's last Chinese-language theater, the Music
Palace, will take its final bow, its faded three-story structure to
be demolished and replaced by a gleaming office building. By David
W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   ILL-HAMAS-SUSPECT (Bridgeview, Ill.) _ The house on Thomas
Street in this suburb 15 miles southwest of Chicago has a red rose
bush growing under the front window, fishing rods leaning against
