<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-AIRPOLLUTION-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA FINALLY CONFRONTS ITS AIR-POLLUTION CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ For 20 years, local officials carefully measured this
city's air pollution levels and equally carefully hid the results _
fearing that the truth might tarnish the capital's image or lead to
social unrest. This continued even as Beijing's famously blue sky
turned ever more gray and its surrounding hills disappeared behind
an acrid mist.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed a small miracle when, on Feb. 28, Beijing joined 38
other Chinese cities that have started to issue weekly air quality
reports in the last year. In newspapers and on television, they
parade a sometimes eclectic mix of statistics _ from levels of
nitrous oxides produced by car exhausts to the concentration of
tiny particles from coal burning in the air. And Chinese citizens
for the first time have hard information on the air they breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Despite technical flaws, the tangled mass of data has confirmed
what many Western scientists have suspected and at times measured:
that the air in China's cities is among the most polluted in the
world, and contains the highest levels of pollutants harmful to
human health. Recent research suggests that bad air in China causes
178,000 premature deaths each year.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of the pollution, now openly acknowledged by the
government, has propelled environmental issues onto the agenda of
the Chinese-American summit meeting that is to take place later
this month. Chinese officials say they are eager to have
Washington's technical help in the battle for cleaner air.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, the government's candor has created a new
political dynamic between the government and its people, feeding an
environmental consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air is bad _ you can read it in the newspapers,'' said
Zhang Jiyan, from her roadside bathing-suit stand in downtown
Beijing. ``Look, you can't even see tall buildings a few streets
from here.''
</P>
<P>
   People who six months ago might have peered out the window and
seen fog, or wu, now realize that it is pollution, or wuran. And
their anger in turn has encouraged local governments to develop
more ambitious, if not always realistic, programs to clean up the
air _ for example, requiring a number of car owners to install
catalytic converters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Releasing the numbers is a revolutionary concept for the
people and the government,'' said Lu Xinyuan, director of the
management division at the State Environmental Protection Agency.
``We were worried that the people would complain that air pollution
is too serious. Instead, the consciousness of people has been
raised. And they feel the government trusts them with the facts, so
we are gaining points by doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Others suggest another motive behind the sudden desire to bare
all: The weekly barrage of frightening statistics has generated
popular support for otherwise unpalatable government moves, like
shutting down inefficient state-owned enterprises, with the
inevitable loss of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they being so open about this?'' asked one Western
diplomat. ``It's because it dovetails with their economic agenda.
This way when the factory gets closed, the people want it to be
closed, even though the real reason it has to be closed is not for
pollution but for economics.''
</P>
<P>
   These days in Beijing, everyone is complaining about the air.
Since the weekly air quality reports began three months ago, the
city's air has ranked 4 on its 1-to-5 pollution scale (5 being the
worst) every week but two, said Yu Xiaoxuan, deputy director of the
Beijing Municipal Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Level-4 pollution can have serious health effects on people with
heart or lung problems, and could make others feel uncomfortable as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Many Beijing residents suspect that the truth is even worse _
after all, theirs is a leadership that until a few years ago shaved
degrees from summer temperatures in news reports in the name of
morale. Elderly people who used to exercise outside in the early
morning _ when pollution is usually worst _ are postponing their
exercises until later in the day, and ``fresh air'' weekend package
tours to the countryside have become popular.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beijing Children's Research Clinic, mothers carrying
hacking children and newly prescribed medicine are quick to
complain. Two-year-old Long Fei ``often gets sick with colds and
infections,'' said his mother, who identified herself only as Lin.
``You see it on TV. The air is not good, that's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the World Bank, five of the world's 10 most
polluted cities are in China, and despite some recent successful
efforts to combat the problem, pollutant levels are two to five
times the World Health Organization guidelines for safe exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is still among the world's most polluted countries,''
said Qu Geping, chairman of the National People's Congress' Natural
Resources and Environmental Protection Committee. ``Among 600
cities, 70 to 80 percent can't even meet our own air standards.''
</P>
<P>
   For years now, Qu has campaigned for greater openness in this
field, prodding China's cities to abide by a generally ignored 1987
law that required them to release data about their air. But last
year the State Council stepped up the pressure, and starting with
Nanjing in May 1997, dozens of cities have now complied.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many experts worry about the reliability of the reports,
according to Todd Johnson, an environmental economist at the World
Bank, since local environmental bureaus are often understaffed,
relying on old equipment and techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Experts also find the reports sometimes incomplete or confusing.
A number of cities, including Beijing, report only some of the vast
number of statistics they measure. And many report air quality
according to an ``air pollution index,'' with scores derived from a
formula that combines harmful and innocuous pollutants in such a
complex manner that even specialists have trouble interpreting its
significance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wang Lihua, a professor of environmental health at Beijing
Medical University, and her former student Xiping Xu, now at the
Harvard School of Public Health, have been studying pollution in
Beijing for more than 15 years. They say they do not entirely
understand how Beijing determines daily rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't always trust the data,'' Xu said. ``But in the end,
whether the number is 100 or 150 is not so important _ we know it's
very high. And this is a very good step to publish the information,
to let people gain knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   The most serious pollutant in most Chinese cities is tiny
airborne particles, measured as total suspended particles, produced
primarily by the burning of coal and, increasingly, car exhausts.
Mexico City's notoriously bad air contains different types of
pollutants, mostly small chemical compounds that are not thought to
be as dangerous to health.
</P>
<P>
   In China, coal also produces sulfur dioxide, the source of acid
rain. Cars add nitrous oxides.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of suspended particles, ``Chinese cities are among the
worst in the world _ that's just a fact,'' said Johnson, the World
Bank official. ``Because they are so dependent on coal, I can't
think of any city in the world that's as bad as the worst cities in
China.''
</P>
<P>
   No country is more dependent on coal. In China, which has only
limited access to oil and natural gas, coal powers huge factories,
fuels restaurant stoves and heats homes. In Beijing, where coal
produces 80 percent of energy, mountains of it fill courtyards,
especially in winter, and bicycles towing carts piled with coal
briquettes are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, there are 1.3 million cars registered in Beijing
today, compared with 200,000 a decade ago. And the average Chinese
car produces 10 to 15 times the exhaust of its American
counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Medical researchers have begun to document the toll that air
pollution is taking on human health here.
</P>
<P>
   In studies, Xu of Harvard and colleagues in China have found
that urban air pollution contributes to increased deaths from lung
and heart disease as well as to premature births and low birth
weight. They have also found that breathing Beijing's air depresses
lung function in otherwise healthy individuals and that on polluted
days, the number of hospital visits for coughs, shortness of breath
and wheezing skyrockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a city like Beijing, you've got 20,000 excess deaths at the
end of the year,'' Johnson said. (Beijing's population is 12
million.) ``You throw in a few badly polluted days and the old
person dies a few months earlier than otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The asthma rate has reached 5 percent in some areas around
factories. In tiny green exam rooms at the Beijing Children's
Hospital, respiratory specialists now see 60 wheezing, coughing
children a day.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hu Yiji, the hospital's director, said he believed
secondhand cigarette smoke was the biggest culprit, but
acknowledged pollution as a problem. ``With all the air pollution
reports lately many parents are very concerned,'' he said. ``We
tell parents if they smoke, to quit. And then we advise them to
take the kids to the suburbs when they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The central government recently announced plans to spend 1.2
percent of the GNP on pollution control and is desperately seeking
an alternative to coal. It is pumping natural gas to Beijing from
Shaanxi Province. It is negotiating with Russia to import gas. It
also has plans to close down urban factories and convert coal into
electricity near the coal mines to keep the pollution out of the
cities.
</P>
<P>
   At best, these changes could reduce reliance on coal to about 65
percent in 2000, from 75 percent this year. But they could have a
big impact on urban air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Cars have proved an easier problem to tackle. As of Jan. 1,
Beijing has banned the sale of leaded gas, and as of next year all
new cars must have catalytic converters. Police recently started
spot checks of tailpipe emissions, and fewer than 40 percent of
cars tested on the first day passed. Polluting owners have their
licenses revoked and are instructed to install catalytic
converters, at a cost of about $100.
</P>
<P>
   Yu, the environmental official, said that the city intended to
retire most taxis, which cannot meet standards even with the device
added.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has long required yearly emission checks, but enforcing
such laws is difficult. In a poor country like China, there is
persistent tension between wanting cleaner air and not having the
money to pay for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
