<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-CARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARR CHANGES ROLE FROM SUB TO SAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Utah's Antoine Carr stood before a flood of camera
lights in a pair of sunglasses that had wide camouflage-coated
plastic rims. And yet, Friday night was the first time Carr had
been visible in the NBA finals.
</P>
<P>
   The camouflage was gone the moment Coach Jerry Sloan tapped him
on the shoulder as he walked onto the floor for the second half. He
was going to put him on the floor to start the third quarter. And
for the first time in this series, Sloan was going to put Karl
Malone's sub on the floor with the superstar.
</P>
<P>
   After averaging 9.8 minutes a game in this National Basketball
Association championship series, Carr stepped in at center and
played in concert with Malone to lead the Jazz to a life-saving
83-81 victory in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I was going in,'' Carr said. ``Coach told me,
and I was like, `Hey, if we're going to go out, we're going to go
out fighting.' I was ready to get out there and bang someone and
hopefully make some shots.''
</P>
<P>
   When a very hot Malone was double-teamed underneath, it was Carr
who popped outside and hit jumper after jumper. After 21 minutes,
Carr ended the game with 5-6 shooting and 12 points, eight of which
were in the fourth quarter. So it was clear: the Jazz had a center
who wasn't missing routine shots and allowing passes to go off his
thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been the missing link they needed,'' said Scottie
Pippen, who was often caught leaving Carr open when he flashed to
Malone. ``He made me pay when I doubled. He was 5 of 6, and you
can't ask for anything else. They found something they've been
looking for. He was the difference in the game tonight, for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr's impact was most obvious down the stretch. He popped a
20-foot jumper with 1:56 left in the game to give the Jazz a
7-point lead. After the Bulls closed in and turned the pressure on
the Jazz, Carr came through again by making two free throws with
10.4 seconds left to put the Jazz ahead, 82-78. This is the kind of
clutch play the Jazz had been waiting for from a bench that had
been unusually quiet since Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   So Sloan shook things up. After staying the course by rotating
Greg Ostertag and Greg Foster and Adam Keefe in at center, it was
time for a change. If anything, Sloan needed a big man who wouldn't
lose the basketball under pressure. So he put in his 14-year
veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1, he was able to catch a basketball,'' Sloan said. ``He
was able to do something with it. And the way we were playing Karl,
we needed to have somebody step up to that. When we tried to drive
to the basket in the first half, we had the ball knocked out of our
hands. We couldn't come up with anything. Antoine made some
excellent plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The more the player his teammates call the Big Dog played, the
fewer mistakes there were for the Jazz. He was a calm hand to count
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my teammates call me butterfingers, but some of them
call me the good-hands man,'' Carr said with a smile. ``I just
wanted to get in there and do my Dog thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr had not had this opportunity before in this series. Often,
Sloan had opted to try and beat the Bulls underneath the basket
with his big men. Carr is an outside shooter. Most of the time,
Carr's appearances had been only cameo spots as Malone's
substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do it without the minutes,'' Carr said. ``He gave me
a chance to do my thing. I'm thankful to Coach Sloan for that. I
love playing with Karl. Whether I'm on the floor with him or not, I
just try to do what we need to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone was especially grateful. The more he burned the Bulls,
and shot over the foul-troubled Dennis Rodman, the more attention
Chicago was focusing on him. Carr gave Malone a break from having
to do it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said coming into this game that our guards had their hands
full,'' said Malone, who had 39 points. ``As the big guys, we have
to help them out. I think later in the fourth quarter, I think
Antoine's presence was huge. He made a lot of big buckets for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The camouflage had been lifted off Carr. He walked out of the
United Center knowing he had helped pull the plug on the
celebration the Bulls had planned for that evening, as the series
is shifting back to Utah for Game 6 on Sunday night and, possibly,
a Game 7 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the partying-type team,'' Carr said. ``Even if we
were to win this thing, I don't think you'd see us up partying all
night. That's not us. I think we are what we are. Tonight, we were
the Jazz of old.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
