<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SALAMANDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TEXAS, ENVIRONMENTAL VICTORY THREATENS SWIMMING HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Last year, Austin environmentalists declared a
major victory when, after a five-year battle, the Interior
Department agreed to add the Barton Springs salamander to the list
of endangered species. But now that victory is looking hollow.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Judge Sam Sparks of U.S. District Court here is
scheduled to rule on a lawsuit filed under the Endangered Species
Act that could force the City of Austin to close Barton Springs,
its popular spring-fed pool, to protect the salamander.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which is not the work of the environmentalists,
asserts that the city's pool-cleaning methods are harming the
federally protected Barton Springs salamander, which is found only
at the pool and at two adjacent springs.
</P>
<P>
   The judge will rule on an injunction that could prohibit city
workers from cleaning the 1,100-foot-long pool, a move that the
city says would force it to close the swimming hole, two miles
southwest of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   For Austinites, the chilly pool is a kind of holy grail. Every
year, a quarter-million people plunge into its 68-degree waters, a
temperature that remains constant, keeping many people swimming in
the pool the year around.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit has many environmentalists in Austin up in arms.
Among their complaints, the environmentalists say that Robert
Kleeman, the lawyer who filed the lawsuit, has a history of
representing developers.
</P>
<P>
   They point out that Kleeman has also worked as the general
counsel for Take Back Texas, a conservative property rights group
that has opposed endangered species protection programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bunch, the general counsel for the Save Our Springs
Alliance, an environmental group, said Kleeman was ``not motivated
by protection for the salamander.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the opposite,'' Bunch said. He contended that the
suit was designed to ``divert attention away from the real
problem,'' which he said was development in the pool's
354-square-mile watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Kleeman said he could not understand why the environmentalists
had not rallied to his cause. ``From 11 to 25 salamanders are
harmed or killed each time the pool is cleaned,'' he said. ``I
don't hear anybody else saying that's bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleeman denied that there were other reasons behind his lawsuit.
``People are going to spin it to avoid the real issue,'' he said,
``which is how the city has dealt with the Endangered Species
Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Kleeman said that the federal Fish and Wildlife Service had not
given the city a proper permit under the Endangered Species Act for
cleaning the pool and, therefore, the city had acted unlawfully.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing on June 3, federal officials denied that the
cleanings had hurt the salamander, and they said the city had been
working under a short-term permit that allowed city and federal
scientists to study how the pool-cleaning process affected the
Barton Springs salamander. They also said the city would very
likely be given a long-term permit to clean the pool in two or
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and lawsuits held little meaning for Josh Rivera, 14,
and Tido Juarez, 12, who were catching crawfish at the pool on a
recent hot afternoon. The boys have spent every day of their summer
vacation at Barton Springs and both were bewildered at the
possibility that the pool could close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why close something that's exciting for the kids?'' asked
Tido. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
