<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7810 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-13 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING A COSMIC MAP WORTHY OF DR. SEUSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cosmologists intent on understanding the origin of the universe
are faced with an insurmountable problem: there is no way to do a
controlled experiment. They can speculate all they like about how
the cosmos unfolded from the great explosion called the big bang,
but they can't directly test their ideas by growing universes in a
laboratory, nurturing them under different conditions and seeing
which ones live or die.
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary biologists are faced with a similar problem _ they
can't rewind the tape of history and study the various ways life
could have marched forth from the primordial soup. But they are
blessed with a powerful fallback. They can study a variety of
creatures and, through the process of induction, piece together a
persuasive story.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no such thing as a cosmological anatomist, jumping
from universe to universe gathering data on how different ones
behave. With no real universes to study other than their own,
cosmologists have turned to the next best thing. They build
computer simulations of the original fireball and watch it explode.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, at the American Astronomical Society meeting in San
Diego, Dr. August Evrard of the University of Michigan described
the biggest simulation yet: the entire visible universe, 10 billion
light years across, captured in a Cray computer at the Max Planck
Society's computing center in Garching, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Artificial life (simulating living creatures) and artificial
intelligence (simulating minds) have been joined by artificial
cosmology, the art of creating a universe in a box.
</P>
<P>
   With money coming from many sources here and abroad, Evrard
said, it was hard to put a dollar figure on the project. ``Whatever
the exact numbers are,'' he added, ``I'm confident that the
taxpayers in all countries involved will feel they got the whole
universe for a pretty fair price _ especially when compared to the
cost of building observatories.''
</P>
<P>
   In a mere three days, 10 billion years of cosmic history can be
replayed inside the supercomputer, tended by an international team
called the Virgo Consortium. What results are colorful computer
images showing how the matter in the universe may have been
distributed at various times in its life. Each of these snapshots
occupies 28 billion bytes of memory and can be compressed to a mere
16 billion bytes, small enough to fit on a few hard drives. One can
almost imagine tiny galaxies, solar systems and planets with
creatures clinging to them, like Dr. Seuss' Whos of Whoville,
faintly calling: ``We are here! We are here!''
</P>
<P>
   If only the grain were so fine. The artificial cosmos is more
like the rough simulations of the Earth people have mounted on
stands in their offices and dens. By giving the globe a spin in the
wrong direction, one can play God and make the sun rise in the
west. Though one can see continents and countries and a few of the
largest cities and mountains, there are no buildings, people or
trees.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest things in the new man-made universe are rather
coarse lumps of matter called particles, each representing 10
galaxies. Anything more detailed is washed away. No matter how hard
you squint, you aren't going to find the Earth, the Sun, or even
the Milky Way. The idea is to concentrate on the big picture, by
studying how tiny ripples in the embryonic universe could have been
amplified into the sprawling structures that appear today.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, an earthling, digitized and projected into the
artificial world, wouldn't see a thing _ not even starlight. For
reasons of economy, all that was actually simulated was the
invisible dark matter, currently believed to make up as much as 90
percent of creation. In the grand scheme of things, we creatures of
luminous matter, the very inventors of the simulation, were deemed
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But as computer power and memory size increase, the universe
will inevitably be captured with a finer mesh, becoming more
detailed and inclusive. One can imagine increasing the resolving
power until each separate galaxy snaps into focus. Make the
simulation finer still and the swirls and arms would emerge. Then
the individual stars would come out. Solar systems would congeal
from the stellar dust.
</P>
<P>
   Why stop at the planetary level? Cosmologist Frank Tipler has
proposed, to the consternation of most of his colleagues, that life
and intelligence are a necessary ingredient in the shaping of the
universe. A true simulation would thus have to include simulated
creatures _ artificial life.
</P>
<P>
   So let the simulated atoms cooked up in the simulated stars form
molecules and cells and plants and animals. If their nervous
systems evolve enough excess brain power, the inhabitants will need
something deep to think about. At some point they might start
wondering about the world around them, and start building
artificial spaceships and probes. They might even mimic creation on
their own simulated computers.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, computer scientist Edward Fredkin came up
with the entertaining notion that our own universe is a simulation
running on some kind of giant computer. Why not have within it the
simulation of another universe, and within that the simulation of
another, and on and on _ a cybernetic house of cards? Pull the plug
on one universe and all those it is supporting come crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmologists like to tell the story about the little old lady
interrupting a lecture by the great thinker, who is earnestly
describing the scientific view of the cosmos. In some versions it's
Bertrand Russell, in others Albert Einstein. ``You've got it all
wrong, sonny,'' the woman says. ``The Earth is sitting on the back
of a giant turtle.''
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, amused, answers, ``Oh, and what is that turtle
standing on?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Another turtle,'' she says. And before he can interrupt with
the obvious objection, she adds: ``Don't waste your time asking.
It's turtles all the way down.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the problem with models of the universe _ it's so
tempting to mistake them for the real thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
