<HEADLINE>
GOP ASPIRANTS FOCUS ON MORAL ISSUES IN IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Wis., Tenn., Mo., N.H., Ga., Ind., Mont.)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa _ A parade of prospective presidential
candidates converged here this weekend for a gala that the state's
Republican Party billed as a showcase of ``ideas and visions'' for
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the event more resembled a celebration of the
traditional nuclear family of the 1950s, and featured contenders
who were unusually aggressive in presenting themselves as morally
upright, vehemently opposed to abortion and, in some cases, hostile
to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a dozen Republicans sought to win over (or, at least,
catch the attention of) the particularly conservative subset of
voters who will participate in the crucial presidential caucuses
here in 2000, traditionally the first battleground of the primary
season.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this conservative state, the heavy emphasis on social
and moral themes was a striking shift from forums of past years,
when the messages were also dominated by clashes over specific
legislation or programs. The oratory here offered a preview of how
the intraparty jockeying will play out over the next two years and
may reflect a dearth of issues for Republicans to trumpet _ or a
great belief that the most rightward-leaning contender will capture
the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering featured some prominent Washington lawmakers like
Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, chairman of the Budget Committee, but was
dominated by lesser-known politicians who are seeking to test their
appeal on a presidential stage. Some of the more prominent
potential candidates like Gov. George Bush of Texas, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona, Jack Kemp, the vice presidential nominee in
1996, and Speaker Newt Gingrich, did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   The baldest appeal to the roughly 2,000 Iowa Republicans who
gathered in Cedar Rapids came from Gary Bauer, the president of the
Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared with Reggie White, the star defensive lineman of the
Green Bay Packers, who caused a furor three months ago for a range
of comments before the Wisconsin Assembly involving homosexuals and
racial and ethnic groups. Among other things, White, who is black,
said then that blacks ``like to sing and dance'' while whites
``know how to tap into money.'' Homosexuality, he said, is ``one of
the biggest sins'' in the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing cheers from the delegates here on Friday night, Bauer
declared, ``I stood with Reggie White. No to same-sex marriages! No
to saying that way of life is acceptable!''
</P>
<P>
   At a reception earlier in the evening, White, towering over
Bauer, thanked the conservative for jumping to his defense after
CBS removed him from consideration as a football commentator
because of his remarks. ``I said what I meant _ and I meant what I
said,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   As if to one-up Bauer, Steve Forbes, the publisher, sought to
prove his bona fides by appearing here with the Rev. Louis Sheldon,
chairman of the Traditional Values Coalition, who for years has
been one of the nation's most antagonistic voices against
homosexuality. Forbes has sought to enhance his ties with social
conservatives since his failed presidential bid in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In a display of the fierceness of this competition for
conservative voters, Alan Keyes, who is also weighing a second run
for the White House, angrily condemned Forbes as not being truly
against abortion because he has not criticized two Republican
governors who favor abortion rights, Christie Whitman of New Jersey
and George Pataki of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes' professed interest in the moral agenda is in my
opinion totally false,'' Keyes told reporters. ``I'm not interested
in phonies.''
</P>
<P>
   Refusing to engage Keyes, Forbes said simply, in an interview,
``My record has been clear and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri tried to prove his devotion by
carrying his usual anti-abortion prop: a sonogram of his grandson
at 24 weeks. He referred repeatedly to eliminating the ``marriage
penalty'' in the income tax and was also aggressive in portraying
himself as happily married, often taking his wife, Janet, by the
hand. She stood by his side during his speeches this weekend and
when they dished out sundaes to the delegates at their ``ice cream
social.''
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans and Democrats are gearing up for the midterm
elections in November, the two-day convention here was the latest
demonstration that, simultaneously, maneuvering for the White House
in 2000 is well under way. The jockeying is particularly intense
because, for the first time since at least 1964, there is no early
heir apparent on the Republican side.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals were more than just talk, for no delegate left here
empty-handed. Forbes, for one, passed out shopping bags for each
participant that included Forbes hats and a cassette tape of some
of his radio commentaries. While former Gov. Lamar Alexander of
Tennessee, one of the best-organized candidates in this state, put
forth a ``family-friendly tax plan,'' delegates flocked to his
down-home Tennessee supper that included chicken wings, corn on the
cob and pecan pie. Saturday morning, Alexander served sticky buns
and coffee in souvenir plaid mugs.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important opportunity for the candidates came
Friday night, when they were each given 11 minutes (the two or
three who went over found their microphones cut off) at center
stage in a darkened hall to sell themselves to Iowa Republicans. In
a demonstration of how wide open the contest may be at this stage,
the other contenders all drew respectable applause but no one
except Keyes, an accomplished speaker and radio talk show host,
drew an outsized response.
</P>
<P>
   Several delegates said in interviews that rather than have one
favorite, they had three or four.
</P>
<P>
   With a giant American flag as the backdrop, the prospects here
dwelled almost largely on moral issues, to the point that some
delegates complained that it was too much. ``It's a little bit
scary,'' Ron Rasmussen, 62, a small-business owner here, said of
the speeches. He said he would have preferred that the speakers
talk about ``states rights, citizens rights and getting taxes
reduced.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kasich emphasized the importance of faith and virtues. ``I have
been in politics now for 20 years,'' he declared, ``and I realize
that making more laws isn't going to fix the things that bother us
the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire was one of several speakers who
savaged President Clinton's character _ many also castigated
Clinton for his planned trip to China _ but then declared: ``My
life's goal is to stop abortion in this country _ and to protect
the lives of unborn children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia, who since last year has called for
Clinton's impeachment, said he hoped he could ride his
outspokenness on the president to the White House. ``I didn't hear
the `I-word' out there!'' he bellowed to the delegates when he
appeared on stage. ``Impeach! Yessir. Yessir!''
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle did not attend because he was
in Virginia raising money for his political action committee and
for local candidates. His wife, Marilyn, took his place but
appeared to spoil any efforts to repair her frosty relations with
reporters by snapping at them for asking whether she agreed with
the recent amended statement of beliefs by the Southern Baptist
Convention that a woman should ``submit herself graciously'' to her
husband's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only read what's in the newspapers, and coming from the
background I have, my dealings with the press, I really don't
believe those very much,'' she said. ``And I'd rather see the
actual statements themselves rather than take them from the
newspapers.'' Reminded of the actual, highly publicized statements,
Mrs. Quayle became testy, telling a reporter, ``I'd like to see it
in continuity, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker, Gov. Mark Racicot of Montana, said he was not
running for president. But after watching the other Republicans
sell themselves, he said at a news conference on Friday that he was
``a little bit startled by some of the strong rhetoric'' of his
colleagues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
