<HEADER>
A7831 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-90     06-13 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-905(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUCLEAR FEAR HELPS ENFORCE THE CALM IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KASHMIR-CONTROVERSY.) 
(ART ADV: Two photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   URI, Kashmir _ In this idyllic spot in the Kashmir highlands,
Indian troops hold ground overlooked on three sides by Pakistani
troops, some well within artillery range. But at sunrise the other
day, the only noticeable weapons around the headquarters of the
Indian army's 12th Infantry Brigade were the drivers, irons and
putters in the hands of the senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way, absolutely no way, that there is going to be
another war here,'' Col. Narendra Singh Mehta, 48, said as he took
breakfast beside an army golf course that nestles above the Jhelum
River. Three miles downstream, the river crosses the ``Line of
Confrontation,'' the term both sides use to describe the boundary
separating the parts of Kashmir held by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the stakes in the conflict rose immeasurably when first
India and then Pakistan conducted nuclear tests and declared
themselves nuclear powers. The tests raised worldwide alarm, with
President Clinton and other leaders appealing to India and Pakistan
to settle their differences over Kashmir to prevent the territory
from becoming the flashpoint of a nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 50 years, India and Pakistan have fought three wars
in the lush valleys that run through the Himalayas here. Two of
these, in 1947 and 1965, began over Kashmir; a third, in 1971, was
an outgrowth of another conflict 1,000 miles to the east, the civil
war in East Pakistan that drew in Indian troops and gave birth to
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   After 26 years without another war, India and Pakistan still
have hundreds of thousands of troops arrayed against each other
along the 550-mile confrontation line, and exchanges of gunfire are
as common as the rainstorms that sweep the mountains at this time
of year. Few weeks pass without casualties on both sides, mostly
among civilians.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Indian side, at least, few seem worried about another
war, much less one that would go nuclear. ``There may be some local
exchanges of fire, the sort of thing that's been happening here for
years, but nuclear weapons have made full-scale war unthinkable,''
Mehta said, to nods from fellow officers who joined him in their
regular golf foursome.
</P>
<P>
   The Kashmir dispute has its roots in 1846, when Britain
installed a Hindu maharajah to rule what had long been a
predominantly Muslim territory. When the subcontinent was
partitioned at independence in 1947, the Hindu ruler hesitated over
joining India or Pakistan, choosing India only after fighters from
Pakistan attempted to seize the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing war was halted by a U.N. cease-fire in 1949 that
left India in control of two-thirds of the territory and Pakistan
with the other third. Little changed in the two subsequent wars,
with India claiming all of the territory and Pakistan demanding
that India honor a pledge it gave in the 1940s that it would allow
Kashmiris a plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
   At bases here that are only 65 miles from Islamabad, Pakistan's
capital, Indian officers have traditionally been upbeat, especially
after getting the better of Pakistan in the three wars.
</P>
<P>
   But just as striking as the mood at the golf course, many
Kashmiri Muslims also say the situation in the Indian-ruled part of
the territory, after a decade of insurgency by Pakistan-backed
rebels, is as relaxed as it has been in years.
</P>
<P>
   All around the Kashmir Valley, the heartland of the insurgency,
there are signs that Kashmir is looking much more like the fabled
land it was for centuries _ a place noted for its adherence to the
gentle Sufi form of Islam, the romanticism of its writers and poets
and its fine craftsmanship in lacquerware, woven shawls and
carpets.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Indian tourists have returned for the first time in
years, filling graceful houseboats on Dal Lake in Srinagar, the
summer capital of the Indian state of Jammu and Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, India's winter games were held near here,
reopening resort hotels closed since 1989, when the Muslim
insurgency intensified. Hindu pilgrims are returning to ancient
shrines. Carpet workshops are busy again.
</P>
<P>
   In the lush orchards and rice paddies along the valley, whole
families are working from dawn to dusk in areas once made hazardous
by cross-fire. Abdul Rahim Bhatt, a 45-year-old farmer sitting with
his family in a rice-paddy near Srinagar sipping tea, said that
ever since the insurgency began, his wife and children had not
joined him in the annual task of transplanting rice shoots. ``By
the grace of Allah, life is nearly normal again,'' he said. In a
week touring the valley, dozens of Kashmiris offered similar views.
The impression was of a territory less troubled about its prospects
than the outside world was.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after India conducted its nuclear tests in May,
Indian leaders appeared to set out to raise temperatures over
Kashmir, saying that India's acquisition of nuclear weapons had
tilted the balance of power in India's favor. This alarmed
Pakistan, and helped tip the balance in Pakistan toward testing its
own nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   After its tests, the Pakistani government took its turn at
heightening tensions. But both sides now seem to be turning away
from confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Indian military commanders leave little doubt that they welcome
the turn toward moderation, not least because they believe they are
well on the way to achieving India's main goal in Kashmir:
eliminating the Muslim rebels.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Instead of 5,000 to 7,500 Muslim insurgents _ estimates used in
the mid-1990s _ Indian commanders say there may be fewer than half
as many now, and probably fewer than 1,000 ``active gun-toting
militants,'' in the words of Lt. Gen. Krishan Pal, India's
commander in the Kashmir Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation is much better, and improving fast,'' Pal said.
He said that Indian intelligence reports showed that insurgents
crossing into Indian-held territory from the Pakistan side had
slowed to a trickle, and that most of those were being killed by
Indian troops.
</P>
<P>
   As important, he said, nearly half the remaining insurgents are
``foreigners,'' a term Indian officers use to refer to Pakistanis,
and a ``scattering'' of Muslims from Egypt, Libya, Sudan and other
countries in the Middle East and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   According to Western human-rights groups, both sides have been
guilty of widespread abuses. Amnesty International, among other
groups, has chronicled cases in which Indian forces are said to
have abducted, tortured and executed suspected rebels and their
sympathizers, and to have fired indiscriminately on civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The reports have listed similar abuses by the rebels, including
killings of villagers, car bombings in Srinagar and Jammu, the
winter capital, and the abduction and killing of officials,
tourists and others.
</P>
<P>
   Among leaders of the Kashmir resistance movement who maintain
political offices in Srinagar, there is little effort to disguise
how weak the insurgency has become. Shabir Shah, a leading
proponent of independence for Kashmir who spent 21 years in Indian
prisons, has become an outspoken advocate of negotiations with
India, and has implied that something less than a complete
breakaway might be accepted. Other resistance leaders appear
demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   But if India has the upper hand in the fighting, there is little
sign that it is winning Kashmiris' loyalties. Many say they are
deeply disillusioned with India's political solution: a revival of
the Kashmiri-led state government that was disbanded when direct
rule was imposed in 1989. The man who headed the state government
then, Dr. Farooq Abdullah, a 61-year-old physician, returned from
England to run and win a 1996 election that many Kashmiris regard
as deeply flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah came back, in most Kashmiris' eyes, as New Delhi's
puppet. After 20 months in his old office as chief minister,
driving around Srinagar in a convoy of armored cars, he has yet to
get rid of the stigma.
</P>
<P>
   So far, according to many Kashmiris, his government has been
busier announcing new schools, hospitals and roads than actually
building them.
</P>
<P>
   The chief minister's worst mistake may have been his vociferous
support for India's nuclear tests. After a visit to the nuclear
test site with Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee, he outdid even
the Hindu nationalists with his polemics. ``The next war will be
fought on the soil of Kashmir,'' he said. ``But this time, modern
weaponry, including nuclear weapons, will be used.''
</P>
<P>
   But India's view seems to be that the risk of a nuclear war will
affect Kashmir in much the way that the American and Soviet nuclear
arsenals affected postwar Europe _ by freezing the territorial
division, since neither India nor Pakistan can rationally
contemplate trying to seize territory from the other.
</P>
<P>
   This could explain why Lal Krishna Advani, India's hard-line
interior minister, greeted Pakistan's nuclear tests by saying they
were good for India ``from every point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   The central government's top official in Kashmir, Girish Chandra
Saxena, who is the governor of Jammu and Kashmir, seemed to take
this view when he said in an interview that neither India nor
Pakistan would risk a full-scale war.
</P>
<P>
   ``No nation embarks on a course of nuclear suicide, and I don't
think there are any nuclear suicide bombers even in Pakistan,'' he
said. ``So the real answer is for both sides to cool it, achieve
what is achievable on other issues and leave aside the intractable
issues like Kashmir.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
