<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAPTISTS-MORMONS-ART-     06-13 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-MORMONS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAPTISTS TAKE THEIR MESSAGE INTO MORMON TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ In a college neighborhood east of the historic
Mormon Temple here last week, four young Southern Baptist men and
women bowed their heads with Clint Roberts, whose T-shirt asks,
``What's more important than eternal life?''
</P>
<P>
   After Roberts, director of the Baptist Campus Ministry at the
nearby University of Utah, asked God's blessing, the group set off
to knock on doors to talk with students about conversion and
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered at the first house, and a woman turned them away
at the next. But at the third, a university fraternity, the door
was opened wide and the group invited in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a personal testimony that God has helped me,''
Ann-Marie Sandy told five fraternity members seated on a long
couch.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts talked about the campus ministry and invited the young
men to visit.
</P>
<P>
   They listened attentively, answered a couple of questions and
then indicated they wanted to turn back to their studies. Later,
they agreed that admitting the group had been the proper thing to
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went on a mission, too,'' said Jonathan Nielsen, referring
to the months he spent in Bogota, Colombia, as a Mormon missionary.
``So I know how it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, in meetings like these, members of two of
the most determinedly missionary faiths in the United States, the
Southern Baptist Convention and the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints, have been coming face to face in what has been a
courteous if somewhat wary encounter.
</P>
<P>
   That it has been happening here, on ground that the 19th-century
Mormon leader Brigham Young declared a modern-day Zion, is the work
of the Southern Baptists. While holding their annual convention in
here last week, about 3,000 volunteers also began a weeklong
effort, ending Friday, to bring an evangelical Protestant message
to the 2 million inhabitants of Greater Salt Lake, Mormon and
non-Mormon alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the biggest evangelistic outreach in the Salt
Lake Valley in history,'' said Phil Roberts, an official with the
Baptists' North American Mission Board (and no relation to Clint
Roberts). ``There may be as many as 50,000 personal knocks on the
door,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by a $600,000 budget, Southern Baptists bought television
and radio commercials, put up billboards, dispatched mailings and
held block parties, all to draw attention to their message.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the plans began to circulate a year ago, prompting
speculation about tensions and raising the specter of
finger-jabbing debates between Baptists and Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the oratory within the Salt Palace Convention
Center, where the Baptists met from Tuesday through Thursday,
sometimes grew hot, as when one minister opened a sermon by calling
Salt Lake City the ``headquarters of a counterfeit Christianity.''
And pamphlets published by the mission board strongly criticized
Mormon beliefs, including that the church's president is a prophet
capable of receiving divine revelation.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets, it was mainly a case of the polite meeting
the polite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone was very concerned that there not be
hostilities expressed,'' Phil Roberts said. ``I've warned our
people that you may win an argument, but you may not win a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Mormon officials had offered similar counsel. In a
speech at Brigham Young University in February, Elder Boyd Packer,
a top church officer, said: ``If you meet someone who challenges
our right to the title Christian, do not confront them. Teach them
_ peaceably.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In an interview, another Mormon leader, Elder Alexander
Morrison, who supervises the church's work in northern Utah, said:
``If all you do is position yourself to respond to what other folks
say of you, you don't get much done in this world. The Baptist
convention has been interesting, but not very disruptive in terms
of our responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   During the convention, Southern Baptist officials kept a tally
of the fruits of their efforts. On Tuesday, after volunteers had
been in the field four days, John Yarborough, the mission board's
vice president, announced, ``We have seen over 760 people pray to
receive Christ on the streets and in the homes of Salt Lake City.''
Those numbers, he added, ``are not mere accounting digits, but
represent souls in the kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Baptist messengers, as convention delegates are
called, broke into applause at the announcement that conversions
had topped 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently relatively few were Mormons. Baptist officials
said that most of the converts seemed to come from among the
unaffiliated, a group that has grown as Utah's population has
swollen with arrivals from other states. Indeed, Mormons now make
up slightly less than 50 percent of Salt Lake City's population,
church officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the increasing number of non-Mormons, the Mormons
began their own continuing missionary effort in northern Utah in
the 1980s and now field a force of nearly 500 missionaries there.
They make about 6,000 converts a year, about 2 percent of the
church's annual total worldwide, Morrison said. ``In general, we do
very, very well where we are well known,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Southern Baptists, who were planning a special
outreach to the local Hispanic population this weekend, the
volunteer evangelists said what counted was making contact with
anyone who would listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to share with them as much as we can,'' said
David Paul, a senior from Baylor University in Waco, Texas. ``What
we're trying to do is plant seeds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1429EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
