u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-512&AMP;     06-13 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-TOBACCO-512&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURRENT TOBACCO BILL PLEASES NO ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The anti-smoking bill now before the Senate has
strayed far afield.
</P>
<P>
   Amendments added last week included a big tax cut for many
married couples, vouchers to pay for some children to attend
private and parochial schools and grants to the states for
child-care programs. Before the Senate is finished, which could be
as early as this week, more extraneous benefits will probably be
approved.
</P>
<P>
   What the bill does not have is what the cigarette makers and the
state attorneys general wanted most last June when they negotiated
the settlement that prompted Congress to take up the issue. It
would not give the tobacco companies immunity from lawsuits filed
by or on behalf of people with smoking-related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, from the perspective of the attorneys general, once
the tax cuts and anti-drug provisions of the Senate bill became
fully effective, little money would be left for the states to spend
on anti-smoking campaigns and other public health programs.
</P>
<P>
   So no one is happy.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies have walked out, saying it would be futile
for them to negotiate further with lawmakers who are mostly
interested in punitive taxes and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Donohue, president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, wrote
to all senators on Friday, saying that the Chamber was stepping up
its advertising campaign against the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Public health organizations like the American Heart Association
and the American Cancer Society are threatening to oppose the
legislation because the anti-smoking and medical research programs
they favor are being given short shrift.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans complain that the bill is the kind of legislation
they hate most _ a tax-and-spend approach to a social problem, in
this case teen-age smoking. Democrats say that the incremental
increase in cigarette prices, $1.10 over five years, is
insufficient to keep young people from becoming addicted to
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, if the bill comes to a vote in the Senate, it will
probably be passed by a large majority. The main reason is that
senators can be sure that the measure, as it stands now, will not
become law.
</P>
<P>
   So senators will feel free to vote for it even if they are
uncomfortable with important elements of the legislation. They are
less interested in the substance of a bill that will not be enacted
than they are in avoiding getting burned politically.
</P>
<P>
   The senators can be sure that the bill will be changed because
of the stance of the Republican leadership in the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich told The Washington Times that there was
``no chance, none'' that the House would even consider legislation
like the Senate bill. ``It's dead because we won't take it up,'' he
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   What Gingrich is contemplating, his associates say, is a much
less ambitious measure. He would not raise cigarette taxes. Nor
would he give the tobacco industry any protection against lawsuits.
Apparently, he plans to try to copy the low-budget ``Just Say No''
campaign that Nancy Reagan employed against drugs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In this respect, the difference between the way the House and
the Senate function is important. Senators are free agents. There
are few restrictions in the Senate on what amendments can be
offered. And a big, contentious bill like the tobacco measure can
conceivably pass even if the majority leadership is opposed.
</P>
<P>
   But the House is tightly controlled by its leaders. It is safe
to assume that the House will pass either the tobacco bill that
Gingrich favors or none
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that if an anti-smoking measure does become
law this year, it will be written in the conference committee where
the differences between the Senate and House bills will be
reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the White House has favored all along. The
president and his advisers have little influence when a bill is
being debated by 100 senators or being drafted by the House
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   But in the conference committee with perhaps a dozen lawmakers,
the White House will have a seat at the table. And at this stage, a
veto threat carries considerable weight.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions are risky about legislation that has been rescued
from more near-death experiences than Wile E. Coyote. Don't place
any bets, but as of this weekend, here is the best guess about what
lies ahead:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, is
expected to conclude soon, maybe next week, that the Senate has
spent all the time it can afford on the tobacco bill. Important
measures like the defense bill and all the appropriations
legislation needed to keep the government running are in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   So Lott will probably support a motion to cut off debate. If he
does so, he will get the 60 votes such a motion requires for
passage, and the bill will likely be approved with 70 to 75
senators voting ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans' task force on tobacco, headed by Rep.
Deborah Pryce of Ohio, can be expected to make its recommendations
along the lines Gingrich favors within a week or two after the
Senate acts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats led by Rep. Henry Waxman of California will fight the
Gingrich approach, holding that the Republicans are stooges for the
tobacco industry, but the Gingrich bill will probably be approved
before Congress leaves town for the monthlong August recess.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave September for the conference committee to meet.
The nature of the legislation these lawmakers and the president
agree on, if they can agree on anything, is impossible to predict.
</P>
<P>
   But usually, there is one big bill, often a budget measure, that
Congress deals with in a last heave before it adjourns for the
year. The bill is often loaded with ornaments to make sure that it
appeals to a majority of senators and representatives and gets
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Christmas tree bill this October is
the tobacco legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
