<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to locally heavy rains will douse parts of eastern New
England Sunday as a steadfast high pressure system over the
Canadian Maritimes blocks the advance of a low pressure system off
the New Jersey coast. The sluggish low will promote persistent
onshore winds from southeast New England to Maine, importing a
steady supply of Atlantic moisture. Rainfalls of an inch are
possible from Massachusetts to New Hampshire, where the brunt of
the import of ocean moisture occurs. Farther inland, isolated
clusters of showers and thunderstorms will speckle the central and
northern Appalachians as a pool of high-altitude cold air hovers
over the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop across the
middle Mississippi, Tennessee and lower Ohio Valleys as a sluggish
low pressure system north of Kansas City draws humid air north from
the Gulf of Mexico. A few of these storms may reach severe levels,
with the region at risk spanning from west Tennessee to Missouri,
Illinois and Iowa. Only a very small part of this region will be
affected by severe weather. Scattered showers and thunderstorms
will develop over parts of the northern Plains as moist air
circulates westward around the Kansas City low.
</P>
<P>
   Hot, dry winds from the southwest will surge into west Texas and
west Oklahoma. Winds will average 15 to 30 mph with higher gusts.
Blowing dust will reduce visibility at times. Farther east in
Texas, isolated thunderstorms will erupt along the boundary
separating the dry air from humid air from the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Merging Funnels
</P>
<P>
   A tornado spotter reported that three funnel clouds merged into
one over Riverton, Wyo., on Thursday. Below the base of a rotating
thunderstorm, a wall cloud dipped downward as the rate of
condensation increased from rain-moistened air drawn inward by the
storm's circulation. Three funnel clouds then spun up and lowered
beneath the center of the rotating wall cloud. The funnels, similar
to when ice skaters spin faster as they draw their arms toward
their bodies, rotated at a faster pace than the wall cloud. As the
system's spin got better organized, the funnels merged into one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
