</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOL-KILLINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON: HOLLYWOOD, ACCESS TO FIREARMS, LAX SUPERVISION FUEL
KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (bl) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ President Clinton on Saturday blamed the
glorification of violence in popular culture, easy access to
firearms and lax parental supervision for the recent rash of
schoolyard shootings that have left a river of blood from
Mississippi to Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly radio address, the president said Hollywood bore
much of the responsibility for the recent carnage by producing
movies, television programs and music lyrics that romanticize
killing and twist the minds of impressionable teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no wonder, as scores of studies show, that our children
are increasingly numb to violence,'' Clinton said in his radio
address. ``They see and hear it everywhere _ from TV screens to
movie screens to computer screens and in popular music.
</P>
<P>
   ``When mindless killing becomes a staple of family
entertainment, when over and over children see cinematic conflicts
resolved not with words, but with weapons, we shouldn't be
surprised when children, from impulse or design, follow suit,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   As he has done many times before, the president called on
Hollywood to exercise self-restraint in the barrage of violence
that pervades film and television entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But even as he lectured Hollywood for its share of
responsibility for violence in the American culture, he planned to
appear at an $800,000 fund-raiser for the Democratic National
Committee at the Beverly Hills home of the entertainment mogul Lew
Wasserman, founder of MCA Corp. The event, which was to include
many of the top names in Hollywood, was scheduled for Saturday
night in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, the president also called on Congress to pass
tougher gun laws and provide financing for after-school programs to
channel juvenile energy into positive pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced that he had ordered the Department of
Education and the Justice Department to produce an ``early warning
guide'' to help parents and teachers identify the signals that
often precede an outburst of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've learned that terrible threats and rage in the face of
rejection can be more than idle talk,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton arrived in Oregon on Saturday to speak at the Democratic
fund-raising event and to deliver the commencement address at
Portland State University. He also was scheduled to meet with
survivors and the families of victims of the May 21 shootings at a
school in Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, police officers found and detonated two bombs at
the airport in Eugene, Ore., where Clinton's plane was to land
today for the meeting in Springfield. Officials said they were
tipped by an anonymous caller, and found the two devices in a
culvert near the airport. It was unclear whether there was any
connection to the presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton devoted the graduation speech to a defense of diversity
and a plea for tolerance of the swelling wave of immigrants to
America.
</P>
<P>
   He said that citizens have a responsibility to welcome new
arrivals, not fear or shun them, and he recalled the xenophobia in
America's past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some Americans have met each group of newcomers with
suspicion, with violence and discriminatory law, and doubted they
could ever become truly American,'' Clinton said. ``So great was
the hatred of Irish immigrants 150 years ago that they were greeted
with signs that read `No dogs or Irish;' so profound was the fear
of Chinese immigrants in the 1880s that they were barred from
entering the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Such treatment of immigrants is not only wrong, the president
said, it is ``un-American.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that immigrants have responsibilities as well _ to learn
English, to study the Constitution, to obey the law and embrace
American culture. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
