A7881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HOSPITAL-FRA     06-13 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HOSPITAL-FRAUD-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO LIMIT PROSECUTION OF HOSPITALS LOSES SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Fla.)  (lb) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A congressional effort to adopt a law making it more difficult
for prosecutors to bring cases against hospitals under a federal
fraud statute has lost support and no longer has the votes to pass,
sponsors of the legislation say.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the bill had appeared almost certain to be
approved by Congress. But support shifted after the Justice
Department recently adopted guidelines requiring greater care in
using the fraud statute against health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   A key figure who has reversed course on the legislation is Rep.
Bill Delahunt, D-Mass., who was an original co-sponsor of the bill.
Delahunt now says that the Justice Department guidelines make the
new legislation ``inadvisable.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an interview, the lawmaker who introduced the bill in the
House, Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., said that while he still
believed the legislation should be passed, the guidelines had
probably killed its chances for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be support for this bill to pass
while these guidelines are being watched,'' McCollum said. ``But
there's no doubt the guidelines never would have been introduced if
it wasn't for this legislation. Only time will tell whether they
are satisfactory or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the legislation said they would be watching
carefully to see how federal prosecutors applied the guidelines,
which are intended to ensure that the fraud statute is used in a
fair way. They said the bill could once again pick up support if
the rules proved unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud statute, known as the False Claims Act, was used in
investigations as part of a national project by federal prosecutors
to battle fraudulent billing by hospitals of government health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials complained that they were receiving letters
from prosecutors demanding settlement, without a chance to present
their cases. Some also said they were being forced into considering
settlements under the threat of prosecution, which could require
the eventual payment of significantly larger sums of money as
fines.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that was written in response to those complaints
redefined how prosecutors could use the False Claims Act against
health-care providers. Among other changes, it called for raising
the standard that a jury must use to determine whether a civil
violation has been committed by a health-care provider.
</P>
<P>
   It also creates rules that would preclude the government from
bringing such cases under certain circumstances, including when the
amount of money in question is less than certain minimal levels.
Recently, some House members have discussed a plan to attach the
legislation to an appropriations bill this week to speed its
passage.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposals to change the False Claims Act, which for the
last decade has been the main tool used to recoup government losses
from fraud, created enormous concern among senior Justice
Department officials. These officials, while acknowledging that
there may have been cases in which individual prosecutors went too
far, said the new legislation would hinder their ability to bring
civil cases against health-care providers who defrauded programs
like Medicare.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The new Justice guidelines, which emerged after a number of
private sessions with members of Congress, have several
requirements for prosecutors seeking to bring cases against
hospitals using the False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines, prosecutors must allow hospitals a full
opportunity to be heard before making a demand for settlement; they
must establish an adequate factual and legal case against a
health-care provider before seeking a settlement, and they must
take into account the effects an enforcement action could have on
the availability of medical services.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has also established working groups in
Washington to coordinate national enforcement efforts involving
health-care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Those rules addressed a number of significant congressional
concerns about the national investigations of hospital billing. In
a June 11 letter to Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, Delahunt
wrote, ``I believe that the guidelines provide a basis for
resolution of this controversy that makes it unnecessary and
inadvisable to proceed further'' with the effort to reform the
False Claims Act.
</P>
<P>
   Still, sponsors of the bill said they would be closely watching
how the department applied the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be an effort for accounting of what they're
doing,'' McCollum said. ``And maybe an amendment to assure that
regular accounting is going to occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
