u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-SPAIN-NIGERIA-NYT     06-13 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SPAIN-NIGERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LATE SURGE HELPS NIGERIA WIN A STUNNER OVER SPAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ They play all season in scattered outposts from
South Africa to Russia, from Turkey to Kansas City. Their team
reunions are usually marked by financial squabbles and political
intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Nigeria staged one of the most spectacular games of
this World Cup, or just about any other World Cup, for that matter,
beating Spain, 3-2, as both teams ran and shot against each other
for nearly the entire 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal came in the 78th minute on Sunday Oliseh's
slicing right-footed shot from the right side that found the left
corner, past the desperate dive of Andoni Zubizarreta, the Spanish
goalie playing in his 124th international game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been difficult to get to this stage,'' said Oliseh, who
plays for Ajax of Amsterdam, ``and we have had more difficulty than
any other team in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Every World Cup has its so-called Group of Death _ the most
competitive pairings in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the consensus choice was Group D, encompassing these
two teams as well as Paraguay and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is ranked only 47th in the world, often skipping
important tests, but Saturday the Nigerians gave the
often-disappointing Spaniards a whiff of mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think ours is the most difficult group of all,'' said Javier
Clemente, the coach of Spain, before this cup. ``It's the group
with the most quality. Before coming I said, `Let's avoid the
Africans,' and we have to play Nigeria, the strongest African team,
with lots of international experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria is one paradox in this World Cup. It exports players to
the better European leagues, and it won the 1996 Olympics in
Atlanta, using many of same the players sloshing around the
rain-slicked field Saturday in the home city of Jules Verne.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians showed skill and courage that was there long
before the peripatetic Bora Milutinovic became the coach in
December, at the pricey level of $35,000 plus $250,000 if the Super
Eagles should win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic had done well with his three previous teams, Mexico,
Costa Rica and the United States, and Saturday he tied the cup
record by coaching a fourth team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy for the people of Nigeria,'' Milutinovic said in
his broken English afterward, while wearing a white tribal robe at
the news conference. ``They fought all the way against a very tough
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic, 53, has been under intense criticism by the
Nigerian news media, and the political intrigue increased last week
with the death of the strongman president, Gen. Sani Abach.
Milutinovic's preference for defense and his suspicion of
opportunism flies directly against the natural inclinations of the
Nigerians, who were burned in the 1994 World Cup, when they could
not hold a one-goal lead against Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Spain also was put out by Roberto Baggio and Italy in 1994, and
the Spaniards were disappointed again Saturday, if not terminally
dispatched. They came out organized and aggressive, scoring first
after Mobi Oparaku struck down Alfonso Perez for a direct free kick
25 yards from the Nigerian goal.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Hierro, the experienced free-kick specialist for Real
Madrid, lashed a right-footed shot that hooked around the Nigerian
wall and caught the right corner of the goal in the 21st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than be discouraged, Nigeria came right back and earned a
corner kick from the right side at 25 minutes. Garba Lawal, who
plays for Roda JC in the Netherlands, took a left-footed kick that
hooked back toward the Spanish goal. Hierro went up too soon in
front of Mutiu Adepoju, who plays for Real Sociedad in San
Sebastian, and Adepoju leaped and deflected the ball backward, into
the near corner, a perfect show of practice and instinct, to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerians put so much pressure on Spain that Zubizarreta,
the long-standing goalkeeper who will retire after this tournament,
had to venture out twice to use his foot skills as an extra
defender.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, Hierro and Raul showed the skills that
helped Real Madrid win its latest European championship. At 47
minutes, Hierro let loose a 40-yard bomb that soared high and long,
giving Raul time to break behind the Nigerian defense. The ball
landed on the instep of his left foot and never touched the ground
until he had whacked it past Peter Rufai.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria never gave up, as Lawal broke behind Spain's Ivan Campo
on the left side and had enough balance on the slippery pitch to
release a left-footed low shot that slithered off Zubizarreta tie
at 73 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, Oliseh's goal thrilled the large Nigerian
contingent, including a band of drums and trumpets, that had been
playing incessantly since leaving the Montparnasse Station in Paris
at 7:15 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian victory was a triumph for the world soccer body,
FIFA, which has enlarged recent World Cups to the current total of
32, to include more teams from the emerging nations. The joy and
heart of the Nigerians on Saturday showed they may indeed survive
this Group of Death. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
