<SLUG> BC-SOC-BIERHOFF-523&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO NEEDS RONALDO? GERMANY HAS BIERHOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICE, France _ While the Americans have camped at an isolated
vineyard for the World Cup, with only Beaujolais grapes to keep
them company, Germany has chosen the fun and sun of the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl dropped in for a visit on Friday. And
coach Berti Vogts has brought along classical music to the Cote
d'Azur, better to help him relax by the pool while he works on his
tan.
</P>
<P>
   And why shouldn't Vogts be so serene? While the Americans are
desperately looking for someone _ anyone _ who can put the ball
into the net during Monday's opener in Paris, the German team
enters the match with four of the best forwards in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Vogts will choose two, most likely Jurgen Klinsmann, making his
third World Cup appearance, and Oliver Bierhoff, the latest scoring
sensation in the Italian League who has revived a career that once
seemed destined to end without the slightest hint of international
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the great Ronaldo of Brazil who led Italy's Serie A
in scoring this season. Nor was it Gabriel Batistuta of Argentina.
Nor was it the Italian stars Roberto Baggio or Alessandro Del
Piero. It was the tall, slender Bierhoff, an economics student, who
plunked in 27 goals for Udinese, earning himself a handsome $12
million transfer for next season to help resuscitate the fallen
giant AC Milan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit strange to be called a superstar in the same breath
with those other athletes,'' the 30-year-old Bierhoff said. ``I
hope I am able to bear the pressure and perform to expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 2 inches, he is tall for a striker. While Klinsmann
roams the flanks, Bierhoff is a classic center forward who waits
like a poacher in front of the goal for the chance to score. Like a
basketball forward, he is an expert at backing in and using his
arms in the low post. For each goal that he scores in the World
Cup, he said, his sponsors will contribute a total of $6,700 to
UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be aware that he uses his body and his arms to
push you away,'' said Thomas Dooley, the American sweeper who was
born in Germany. ``He's very tall, so it's easy for him. He's very
good in the air; you have to try to hold him when he jumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon signing with AC Milan, Bierhoff said he hoped to outscore
Ronaldo in the World Cup, just as he outscored him in the Italian
League. He said he felt the need to get noticed. Perhaps that is
because he went so long without recognition. Playing in the World
Cup seems almost like a dream, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think I have to wake up,'' Bierhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Rolf, is the director of a regional power company.
As a young player in Essen, Germany, Bierhoff admittedly played
like the rich kid that he was. He was reluctant to dive on the
ground for balls, he said, and at the end of every match, his
jersey remained an unstained white. His father cured him of this
fastidiousness by having him dive 50 times in a row onto wet grass
covered with a scrim of ice. Three or four repeats of this drill
convinced the shivering teen-ager that daintiness was not an
admired trait in soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to learn to get dirty,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, he kicked around the German Bundesliga for years, moving
from one team to the next without exciting anyone, and finally,
during the 1990-91 season, Bierhoff struck out for Austria, where
he scored 23 goals in 32 league games for Salzburg. That got him a
ticket to the Italian League, but Inter Milan farmed him out right
away to Ascoli in the second division. Ascoli didn't want him
either. Bierhoff told Agence France-Presse that one day about 100
fans surrounded his car, spitting at him and issuing threats and
insults.
</P>
<P>
   The team's president told him not to bother coming back to
practice, Bierhoff said. Stubborn, he would not leave. A new coach
came in and encouraged him and, a season later, Bierhoff led
Italy's second division in scoring with 20 goals. That got him a
promotion to Udinese for the 1995-96 season, and caught Vogts'
attention when he was putting together Germany's team for the 1996
European championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my baddest experience but my most important
experience,'' Bierhoff said of Ascoli. ``Now, if I have some
difficulties, I'm not falling down. I have only to think about that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierhoff scored only twice in the 1996 European tournament, but
he delivered his second goal in sudden death overtime to defeat the
Czech Republic in the championship game. Once a nobody, he was now
a national hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so low, I could only go up,'' Bierhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It was very important to do something on the
international level.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierhoff has improved his conditioning, and the explosiveness in
his legs, by using weights, and his goal scoring has provided him
with muscular confidence. He has scored 17 goals in 26 appearances
with the national team.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Americans, Bierhoff said he knew little about them,
except that it was important for Germany to play its own game. The
three-time World Cup champions tend to start slowly and build
throughout the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've been warned,'' Bierhoff said. ``The Americans aren't
some little team. They've beaten Brazil. We know we have to be 100
percent now. But at the end we are one of the favorites, and we
have to accept it and show that we're a good team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1621EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
