<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOLUNTEER-POWELL-ART-     06-13 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOLUNTEER-POWELL-ART-910&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWELL'S YOUTH DRIVE GAINS STEAM AFTER SPUTTERING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Minn., Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The volunteers scrubbed, painted and hammered,
mending a peeling church and a crumbling community center, and then
gathered to bask in the praise of their leader, an imposing man in
a sport shirt emblazoned with a child's red wagon.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `So you had a big media event a year ago, but
what's happened since?''' said Colin Powell, recalling the verve
and hoopla, and more than a dollop of skepticism, that surrounded
what was called a ``summit'' on volunteerism, in Philadelphia. The
meeting spawned America's Promise, Powell's organization to help
children in danger of getting into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Florida, you're telling them what's happened since,''
Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the triumphant tone, the general's words seemed to
recognize clearly that there is still more than a little skepticism
surrounding his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   An American hero accustomed to ticker tape, the retired general
and former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff has seen his
profile fade somewhat from the national spotlight as he has
undertaken a mission that in some ways is more complicated than
battlefield logistics and whose success is harder to measure. And
there have been some stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   At the start, the organization used a part-time director, but
soon found that the job would require more attention, ultimately
settling on Peter Gallagher, a former top officer at AT&AMP;T, as its
full-time chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Powell concedes that his group was also taken by surprise by the
turf concerns among other philanthropic organizations, and he works
to dispel the notion that America's Promise is a new charitable
competitor. Rather, he says, it is an umbrella organization that
acts as a go-between for givers and social-service groups.
</P>
<P>
   And it has been difficult to sustain the kind of attention that
was lavished on the Philadelphia conference, officially the Summit
for America's Future, where President Clinton and former President
George Bush served as co-chairmen. In addition, the 61-year-old
Powell lamented that his efforts, especially in the first months,
were inevitably seen through a political lens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question seemed to be `What's Powell up to?''' he said,
once again ruling out any desire to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's visits to cities around the United States generate big
headlines in local newspapers, but he has been largely missing from
the pages of the national press.
</P>
<P>
   After the early obstacles and stumbles, the organization has
begun to build momentum, with a register of impressive commitments
from big corporations and an outpouring of workaday people willing
to roll up their sleeves for programs that reach out to children.
On three successive days recently, Powell exhorted big rallies of
volunteers and civic leaders in Minnesota, Michigan and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The general, who often cites figures showing that 15 million
children are at risk of following a wayward path, said he took on
the mission to help steer them away from trouble because there is
no greater obligation than helping young people on society's
margins. The campaign was inspired by former Gov. George Romney of
Michigan, who long called for a vast movement to help young people.
</P>
<P>
   As the unpaid leader of America's Promise, Powell seeks
donations of time and money from corporate leaders, matches donors
with charitable providers of services, and travels around the
country to inspire the local and state volunteer movements born in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere he goes, Powell cites the campaign's successes, which
include millions of dollars in contributions and millions of hours
in volunteer time pledged by companies like Allstate, Lenscrafters,
Eli Lilly and Pfizer. While the organization operates on a $6
million annual budget, provided by charitable organizations and
donors, America's Promise raises far more in donations that go
directly to social-service providers.
</P>
<P>
   As a measure of the nation's growing willingness to help guide
disadvantaged young people, more than 200 volunteer organizations
have sprung up around the country since the Philadelphia
conference. The Boys and Girls Clubs alone have begun more than 200
new clubs around the country, and the number of volunteer mentors
at Big Brothers and Big Sisters of America has increased 22 percent
in a year.
</P>
<P>
   America's Promise does not keep a tally of the amount of time
and money donated, in large part because the group simply gets
donors and providers together, and never touches the contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of major philanthropic leaders, it is much too early
to gauge whether Powell's efforts will translate into a serious
reduction in the number of young people who join gangs, go to
prison or die from gunfire. But the campaign so far has won mostly
favorable reviews, if not universal raves.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Rimel, president of the Pew Charitable Trusts, the
Philadelphia foundation that contributed $1 million to Powell's
organization at its inception, characterized its efforts thus far
as something less than a home run but more than a single.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard questions will need to be asked in three to five
years,'' Ms. Rimel said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other charitable groups, Ms. Rimel said, there had been
concern that America's Promise would ``come in and sop up a lot of
the resources.'' But as it had intended, she said, the organization
has worked as a deal maker and broker between donors and providers
of help.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Rimel said the campaign might initially have underestimated
its ability to raise money _ an enviable situation, but one that
has posed an enormous logistical challenge in figuring out how best
to earmark the money it raises.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Beene, the president of the United Way of America, said
Powell's organization had succeeded in elevating the importance of
volunteerism at the grass-roots level. ``I have never seen another
time with more focus on volunteerism in this country,'' Ms. Beene
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the progress being made by local groups inspired by
America's Promise ranged from heroically successful to something
less than had been expected, but she said such differing results
were inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beene also said Powell's group faced a mammoth challenge in
simply learning the players and abilities in the vast world of
philanthropy. Noting that there are more than 700,000 nonprofit
organizations, including 28,000 new ones each year, Ms. Beene said
Powell's group was ``learning a new landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``They've been at this about a year. United Way has
been doing it for 100 years _ and we're still learning the
landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's organization focuses on five goals it wants to achieve
for children who might otherwise go astray: a relationship with a
caring adult; a safe place during nonschool hours; a physically
healthy childhood; a marketable skill; and a willingness to ``give
back'' through community service.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goodwin, the president of the Points of Light Foundation,
a volunteer group started by Bush, said Powell's efforts had
succeeded in changing the way Americans view volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Volunteerism was something done by little blue-haired old
ladies or wives of corporate titans, but not the rest of us,''
Goodwin said. ``That view has changed dramatically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
