<SLUG> BC-CYC-LONGO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGO HAS BECOME THE LONE RIDER OF HER SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people in cycling think Jeannie Longo is the best female
bicycle rider ever. But not many like her as a person. They say
Longo, a 39-year-old Frenchwoman, is self-centered and selfish,
anti-establishment, anti-everything and anti-everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Longo says it is all envy and misunderstanding. She insists she
is a sensitive person, so soft that she often cries when
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not that tough,'' she said in an interview last week in
Philadelphia, where she was competing in the Liberty Classic. ``My
husband taught me to be strong in the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5 feet 4 inches and 105 pounds, she looks fragile. At home
near Grenoble, she raises chickens and organic vegetables and sells
her own line of vitamins. But most of the time on and off the bike,
she is a tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Patrice Ciprelli, who has coached her since 1979,
married her in 1985. Starting in 1985, she has won nine world
championships on the road and three on velodrome tracks. In the
1996 Atlanta Olympics, she won the gold medal in the road race and
the silver in the road time trial. She has broken 36 world records.
</P>
<P>
   Despite scrapes and bruises from a four-woman crash near the end
of last Sunday's $44,737 Liberty Classic, the world's richest
one-day bike race for women, she finished 25th. Her next stop will
be the richest stage race for women, the $100,000 Hewlett-Packard
International Women's Challenge, Tuesday through next Sunday in
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the scrapes she experiences seem to be of her own
making. Wherever she goes, the stories follow. She is always
different. She trains alone.
</P>
<P>
   When she rides for the French national team, she sometimes
refuses to stay at the team hotel and will not eat with teammates.
Those teammates seldom talk to her. French officials do, largely,
it is said, because they like the medals she wins for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   She further alienated French cycling in the 1994 world road-race
championships in Sicily. Four other riders, two of them French,
broke away near the end and built a big lead. France was sure to
win at least a bronze medal if Longo and the other French riders in
the main pack followed cycling protocol by staying there and
slowing potential pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   No protocol for Longo. She wanted a medal herself, so she
started chasing the leaders. The pack happily joined her and caught
up. As a result, no French riders finished in the top 10. The next
day L'Equipe, the French sports daily, summed it up with a blazing
Page 1 headline that read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Longo _ Traitre'' _ traitor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Longo won the world time trial championship in Spain.
The next day, the international federation fined her 50,000 Swiss
francs (about $34,000) because when she posed for pictures on the
podium, she put a sponsor's sticker on the world champion's rainbow
jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Longo, with an excellent command of English, told her side of
the story this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``The officials said I put on a sticker during the ceremony, but
I did not do it. After the ceremony, after everyone left,
photographers asked me for a picture with my medal. I put on the
sticker then. The next day, someone showed the officials a picture
with the sticker, and they decided to punish me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made me write a letter to explain, and when I did they
said the fine will be only 2,000 francs, not 50,000. That was
better because 50,000 francs is more than my sponsor paid me all
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Longo seems to feel everyone, starting with her opponents, is
out to get her.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time,'' she said, ``they don't want me to win. If
they want to win themselves, OK, but wanting me to lose? That is a
big frustration for me. And they watch me all the time in a race.
Sometimes I'll move a finger and they say, `Look, look, Longo is
moving her finger.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is a sign of respect, or at least recognition.
Sometimes I feel like a little mouse. I never say, `Look, I'm here
and I should win everything.'''
</P>
<P>
   The same scrutiny comes from officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they fair to me?'' she said. ``It depends. Some have been.
But some say: `This is Jeannie Longo. Watch her.' If I have a flat
tire in a race, the jury will stay with me to be sure I don't cut
behind a car to get a draft. They don't do that with other riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am paying the price of success. It is the price of my
personality because I always say what I want to say. It is better
to tell the truth as soon as you can because the truth will always
be known anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a victim because I am not the loser. I've had a good
time, good memories, a good life. But I am a pioneer, and it is the
destiny of each truth to be denied before being recognized. It is
not easy. It is easier to stay the same way as the others. If you
want to go further, you have to go through this. You have to fight
them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
