<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEATH HIS BOXER'S LOOK, GILKEY IS THANKFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Bernard Gilkey looked like he had just sparred with Roy
Jones Jr. Luis Lopez was calling the New York Mets left fielder
Pernell Whitaker. A mouse swelled over Gilkey's bloodshot left eye.
A tiny laceration dotted the top of his left eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   That Gilkey's teammates were able to joke about his appearance
was a good sign. Gilkey _ and every other Met _ felt fortunate the
damage was not worse. For a scary moment, Friday night, Gilkey
experienced first-hand what eventually cut short the careers of
Tony Conigliaro and Dickie Thon.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey was beaned by a high and tight fastball from the Marlin
rookie Ryan Dempster. Luckily for Gilkey, ``it wasn't a flush
shot,'' as he put it. Instead, the ball hit Gilkey above the eye,
before sending his helmet flying off.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was amazing that Gilkey wasn't seriously injured,
considering the ball hit his face first. X-rays and a post-game
examination did not reveal any further damage, and Gilkey was
listed as day to day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dodged a bullet by Gilkey not being hurt,'' Mets manager
Bobby Valentine said. ``The pitch got away from the pitcher and it
was in a bad area.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey, who had just snapped an 0 for 25 slide with a single in
his previous time at bat (he was thrown out trying to stretch the
hit into a double), did not think Dempster was throwing at him.
Neither did Carlos Baerga, whom Dempster hit three batters later in
the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old Dempster has hit five batters in three
major-league starts. Less than a month ago, he was pitching in
Class AA, where he made seven starts. Last year, Dempster spent the
season in Class A.
</P>
<P>
   What Gilkey was upset about was that the hard-throwing Dempster
_ who probably would not be in the majors on any other team than
cost-cutting Florida _ was throwing high and tight with little
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you throw that hard, up and above the shoulders and inside,
that's dangerous,'' Gilkey said. The left fielder was extremely
fortunate the damage was not worse.
</P>
<P>
   Cook Keeps Lid On
</P>
<P>
   The Mets let a game they should have won get away from them
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii pitched an adequate five and a third innings,
allowing two runs on two hits. The Japanese right-hander left with
the Mets ahead, 3-2. He also left reliever Dennis Cook in a sticky
situation, with runners on first and third, thanks to a two-base
error committed by Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook, who pitched on the Marlins' World Series championship
team last season, needed just two pitches to extricate himself from
the jam _ and then cruised through the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Cook recorded the first two outs, before allowing
a double to Mark Kotsay. On came the right-handed reliever Turk
Wendell to face the right-handed hitting Mark Kotsay. The Florida
right fielder delivered a run-scoring single. And the game was
tied.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bohanon relieved and induced Cliff Floyd into an
inning-ending comebacker. But Bohanon was nicked for a two-out
bloop single in the bottom of the ninth by pinch-hitter John
Cangelosi to give the Marlins runners on first and third. And then
Baerga could not glove Todd Dunwoody's grounder up the middle,
allowing Craig Counsell to score from third with the winning run in
a 4-3 Marlins' victory.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, Wendell and Bohanon were pitching in the late innings
because John Franco and Mel Rojas needed rest. Manager Bobby
Valentine said he thought both Cook and Bohanon threw well and
deserved better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wendell could do better,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Pondering Hundley
</P>
<P>
   After meeting in Port St. Lucie, Fla., with disgruntled catcher
Todd Hundley, Friday afternoon, general manager Steve Phillips said
he will decide ``in short order'' whether or not to grant Hundley's
request for a no-trade clause if the All-Star catcher is to play
any position other than catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to change positions to help the club's chances,''
Hundley's representative, Seth Levinson, said. ``He's not asking
for an extension, for more money or to be traded. He's asking not
to be traded. For the first time in his career, Todd senses that he
is part of an organization that has a good chance to make the
playoffs. It would be a crushing blow to Todd not to give him an
opportunity to be part of the experience. He very much wants to be
a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said his talk with Hundley ``went really well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's healing,'' Phillips said. ``He looked great. It
looked like he's getting in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
