<HEADLINE>
MEXICO BEATS SOUTH KOREA, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYONS, France _ It has been a most unpleasant year for South
Korea, and what happened Saturday afternoon at Stade de Gerland
will not change the national mood.
</P>
<P>
   For approximately two minutes, it appeared this might at last be
South Korea's opportunity to experience World Cup success. But
shortly after Ha Seok- ju's long free kick had deflected into the
Mexican goal in the 28th minute, Ha was jogging off the field after
becoming the first player in this tournament to receive a red card
for tackling an opponent from behind.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans would have had enough trouble holding their
unexpected lead over the flashier Mexicans with 11 players on the
field. With 10, it quickly became a question of when, not if, coach
Manuel Lapuente's team would find a way to put the ball past the
fine Korean goalkeeper Kim Byung-ji.
</P>
<P>
   A second-half substitute, Ricardo Pelaez, was the first Mexican
to succeed, slamming home a deflected corner kick with his right
foot in the 51st minute. Teammate Luis Hernandez would score twice
more in the 74th and 84 minutes to secure Mexico's 3-1 victory in
the opening Group E match for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be difficult, but we really wanted to give
Mexico a reason to be happy,'' said Hernandez, the striker with the
long blond hair who, like his team, was not particularly sharp in
matches this spring.
</P>
<P>
   With its tumbling currency and standard of living, South Korea
could have used a reason to be cheerful, too. ``Our players have
been paid and our national team well taken care of, but everybody
sees and hears what is going on at home,'' coach Cha Bum-kun said
prior to the match. ``There are players who have people close to
them who are suffering, so it's clear that the economic crisis is a
source of motivation for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic difficulties have had an impact on South Korean
soccer, which has traditionally been Asia's strongest. Several
players have been forced to play for club teams in Japan after
being dropped from the South Korean league, whose team owners
include major corporations like Hyundai, Daewoo and Samsung. The
falling won also kept thousands of South Koreans from making the
long journey to France to support their team, but after Ha's free
kick from 32 yards deflected off the side of Diulio Davino's head
and into the lower right corner of the goal, the South Koreans who
did make it to Lyons were making plenty of noise in their joyous
corner of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   This World Cup is still taking shape, but there already have
been several abrupt reversals of fortune. Brazil's Cesar Sampaio
scored the opening goal against Scotland and then gave the Scots
back the goal after his foul gave them a penalty kick. France's
substitute striker Christophe Dugarry scored a goal against South
Africa that immediately transformed him from the butt of jokes to
national hero.
</P>
<P>
   In the 30th minute Saturday, it would be Ha's turn to experience
the flip side, and after he slid into the back of Jesus Ramirez's
legs in a futile attempt to strip away the ball, the Austrian
referee Gunther Benko was soon showing him the red card that FIFA
had promised to any defender who tackled from behind.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   South Korea, already missing its star striker Choi Yong-soo
because of an injury, was now without another key player. In its
fifth appearance in the World Cup finals, the country is still
searching for its first victory, and considering the quality of the
other two teams in Group E _ the Netherlands and Belgium _ South
Korea's chances of getting the breakthrough triumph before it
co-hosts the next World Cup with Japan are highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's aim is to get past the quarterfinals for the first
time. It won the Gold Cup in February and has some remarkable
individual talent. Cuauhtemoc Blanco's ball-handling stretched the
imagination Saturday: On two occasions he trapped the ball between
his ankles and leaped through two Korean defenders to break free.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Manuel Lapuente, the Mexican who replaced Bora Milutinovic
in January, certainly looked satisfied after this match, but it was
still a better day all around for Milutinovic. Lapuente's new team
only defeated South Korea. Milutinovic's new team, Nigeria, stunned
Spain, 3-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
