<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A RARE SIGHTING OF NICK FALDO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ Nick Faldo was walking to his ball just off the
12th fairway at the Westchester Country Club's West course when a
voice in the gallery whispered:
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be the best player in the world. How would you like
that distinction?''
</P>
<P>
   Now it's almost as if Nick Faldo had dropped off the planet. He
was the world's No. 1-ranked golfer not so long ago, but lately he
might as well be the subject of an unsolved mystery: Has anybody
seen the three-time British Open champion and three-time Masters
winner?
</P>
<P>
   But every so often he has been sighted.
</P>
<P>
   When he appeared at his induction into the World Golf Hall of
Fame last month, he joked, ``I'm using this for inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   He needs it. He also needs a putting touc.
</P>
<P>
   Going into this weekend's Buick Classic, the 40-year-old
Englishman had skidded to No. 41 in the world ranking, to No. 104
in the PGA Tour's scoring average this year at 71.68, to No. 126 in
the money leaders with $144,996, down there behind R.W. Eaks, a
rookie from the Nike Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But after a shaky 74 in Thursday's opening round, the real Nick
Faldo was sighted again, briefly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Friday's rain that was sometimes steady and sometimes
soft, he was cruising along at 3 under par until play was suspended
because of standing water on the greens and fairways. But when play
was resumed in Saturday morning's fog, he had a bogey-bogey-par
finish for a 70 and 144.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have started,'' he said outside the scorer's
trailer. ``We couldn't see the pin on 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before he putted out on the 18th green, play was
interrupted again because of the fog that limited the visibility to
about 200 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the feel yesterday,'' he said of his putting on Friday.
``Things got a bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last eight holes Friday, he had five birdies, each with a
putt from inside 12 feet. In that stretch, he also had two bogeys.
One with a three-putt green at the eighth hole, the other after
hooking his tee shot on the 442-yard 11th hole into heavy wet rough
behind a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a Tight Lies metal wood that he endorses with a
multimillion dollar contract, he swung mightily, but his ball
squished no more than 30 yards. Still in the rough but with a clear
shot, he noticed several spectators moving behind the gallery ropes
ahead on the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep still, please,'' he called. ``Keep still.''
</P>
<P>
   Muttering to himself, he added: ``If I hit it over there, I'll
quit. I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   He hit it on the green, then two-putted from 30 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need to quit and he would not have quit, but for him
to even joke about quitting tells you how depressed he is with his
golf.
</P>
<P>
   His best finish this year has been a tie for 18th in the Players
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 36 rounds in 10 previous PGA Tour events, only five were
in the 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at the Masters about his putting touch, he replied, ``It's
silky smooth.'' That turned out to be a joke, too. He opened with a
par 72, but blew to a 79 and missed the 36-hole cut. This, of
course, was the same man (but not the same golfer) who in 1996 had
ripped up the green jacket ordered for Greg Norman when the
Australian had a 6-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' Faldo had said that Saturday night. ``If you
put a little pressure on him, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   In their final-round duel, Norman collapsed with a 78 as Faldo
shot an almost robotic 67 and won by five strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But except for his victory in the Nissan Open in Los Angeles
early last year, Faldo hasn't even come close to resembling the
golfer who won the British Open in 1987, 1990 and 1992, and the
Masters in 1989, 1990 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In his last five major tournaments, Faldo has missed the 36-hole
cut in three: the last two Masters and last year's PGA Championship
at Winged Foot.
</P>
<P>
   But with his six major titles, more than any of the current
golfers on the PGA Tour except Tom Watson (who has eight), Faldo
knows that history will measure him by his trophies, not by his
prize money and his endorsement contracts.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, he recently played the Olympic Club in San
Francisco where the 98th U.S. Open will begin on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rough there is brutal,'' he said. ``They've had 15 inches
of rain this year. Between the rain and all the fertilizer, it's
thick and heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the 5-inch rough there is as tall as the tales
already being told about the balls lost in it.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you know, there will be stories about the caddie
who put a golf bag down in the Olympic rough to look for a ball and
then couldn't find the bag. But when the Open begins, Nick Faldo
just wants to find himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
