<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WAYS TO IMPROVE HOCKEY  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The 44 hours between the end of Game 2 and the
beginning of Game 3 were filled with an unusually pleasant
afterglow. Even though it seemed as if the Detroit Red Wings were
poised to sweep the Washington Capitals in the Stanley Cup finals,
the conversational buzz was not about yet another one-sided
championship round or the absurdity of playing games on ice on
sultry June nights or the many mistakes of a tedious and ragged
season.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Joe Hardy and the musical version of the
long-ago Washington Senators, it seemed as if everyone was talking
about the game! The game! The game! Television ratings might have
been low, but those fortunate enough to see it in person or on ESPN
were not ready to forget the Red Wings' 5-4 overtime victory on
Thursday night in Joe Louis Arena. Game 3 was Saturday night in MCI
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's performance showed hockey at its visceral best. Even
those who try to stay neutral and detached could feel the little
hairs tingle on the back of their necks, their heart rates
increasing and their jaws dropping at what the eyes were enjoying.
</P>
<P>
   And did the players have as much fun as the witnesses?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we like to play,'' said Steve Yzerman, the
Detroit captain, who emphasized the word ``we.'' ``Our coach
doesn't care for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it in a nice way, not particularly critical of coach
Scotty Bowman. Few coaches in the current era encourage their
players to open up and entertain in this manner. The coaches prefer
low scores and boring games. It is said that they do this to
``protect their jobs.'' But they continue to get fired anyway, so
why not try to put on a show?
</P>
<P>
   The declining entertainment value of the product will be high on
the agenda this month, first in meetings of general managers, later
in the court of the board of governors. Many around the National
Hockey League are concerned that exciting games such as Thursday's
have become the exception rather than the rule, even in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely, the bosses will seek solutions. It is likely that the
league will try to increase offense by moving the goal line from 11
feet to 13 feet from the backboards to encourage creativity in the
radius of the net. Another possibility is the reduction of the goal
crease on each side. This would allow attackers to legally post up
to the right and left of the goal without putting their skates in
the forbidden blue paint before the puck enters it.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL also might use two referees, instead of one, to further
discourage obstruction fouls, particularly those behind the play
and away from the puck.
</P>
<P>
   One alteration that should be considered is the liberalization
of the off-side rule by eliminating the center red line as a factor
in the ``two-line pass'' from the defensive zone. Because it is
illegal for a team to complete even a 10-yard forward pass from
inside its blue line beyond the center line, coaches have learned
to stifle opposing attackers by clogging up the middle of the ice
with the neutral-zone trap.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the red line from off-sides rulings and allowing
passes up to the next blue line would force defending teams to
align themselves more vertically instead of horizontally. Spreading
them out in this way would create more skating routes and better
passing angles. This would generate momentum in the neutral zone,
resulting in more scoring rushes.
</P>
<P>
   This rule has worked for decades in college hockey. It will soon
be used for international tournaments. In that NHL owners are not
about to lose seating by widening the rinks, the liberalization of
the offsides rule is the best way to swing the balance away from
the defense and toward the offense.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another critical question this summer will concern the Olympics.
Because the Czech Republic beat Russia in the gold-medal game last
February, some North Americans think the experiment was a failure.
They would have preferred the United States against Canada in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   But those who stayed objective know that the Winter Games in
Japan produced many marvelous hockey games, and more of the same
are likely if the NHL sends its players to Salt Lake City in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the league learns from its mistakes of this season, the
next Olympic winter should not include an extraneous all-star game
and four-day break. Do one or the other _ not both. And while it
may hurt them in short-term revenue, even the most shortsighted
owners might acknowledge that it could make big-picture sense to
reduce the schedule in Olympic years _ from 82 games to maybe 78.
If not, at least shorten the exhibition season and begin the
schedule a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, stop stretching out the playoffs over nine weeks to
tickle the fickle flirtation with American television networks like
Fox. Hockey season must end in May.
</P>
<P>
   Horrendous camera work, longer television timeouts and
nine-month seasons are not going to attract new fans but they do
irk current ones. When the Fox robots took the ice during
intermission of Game 1 in Detroit, you could hear the booing
beneath even the incessant blare of the gratuitous rock music.
</P>
<P>
   It is time to call a timeout on all the shuck and jive and think
about the game! The game! The game!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
