</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WEANING THE WORLD OFF MICHAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Michael leaves us, I will also miss the breathless crushes
he evoked in other men. There has been nothing like it since Mickey
Mantle made middle-aged men cry by showing up, for a fee, at their
birthday parties.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Ali makes big boys melt with a frozen half-smile. But
the Mick and Ali reached their powers long after they retired, when
their fans had grown into their nostalgia years. Michael will make
his fans swoon again Sunday night with his tongue hanging out,
rising to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   And what a range of fans. The chairman of Harvard's
Afro-American Studies Department, Henry Louis Gates Jr., describes
Jordan in The New Yorker as ``both hulking and suave, and it's easy
to see why he has become a totem of black masculinity; he makes
Bill Cosby look like Uncle Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to Michael in the fanzine Slam, Scoop Jackson
writes that the few things that he, a ``brotha,'' could depend on
were ``Santa Claus, tax season, Tanqueray and you.'' And in last
week's Fortune cover piece, Roy S. Johnson calculates that the
``Jordan effect'' has helped pump $10 billion into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   What a loss! Post-Michael, the courts will be empty and young
men will run through the streets barefoot. Stock markets will crash
and greed will again be a sin. Desperately diversifying, David
Stern will declare American football, played by either sex, the
true national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be just fine. As you can see, I'm already in grief
therapy. Actually, we have been in the post-Michael era for some
time now; once there was public discussion of having to live
without him, we were already getting used to living without him.
There's always videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Some think we entered the post-Michael era two years ago when
Reebok's new Allan Iverson sneaker sold out more quickly in certain
cool stores than did the latest Air Jordan from Nike; the hip had
marked Jordan as establishment, without edge.
</P>
<P>
   Others think that Jordan's time passed when he had no
authoritative response to the charges that Nike was exploiting
Asian workers. In the booming '90s, few realists expected Michael
to feel the pain of sweatshop fingers, but they did expect him to
know about them.
</P>
<P>
   So much had been made of Michael's involvement in his many
business interests _ he helped design the shoes, smelled the
cologne, tasted the hot dogs, sat on the board of the sunglasses
company _ that he looked flabby or bogus by not at least saying, in
his detached, friendly, pragmatic way, that maybe in Indonesia the
Nike dollar was a reasonable alternative to not working at all.
</P>
<P>
   But, no, already more of a suit than a jock, Gates' ``greatest
corporate pitchman of all time'' and ``the ultimate winner-take-all
celebrity'' wiggled; he promised to look into the situation. After
the season.
</P>
<P>
   We looked past that. After all, Michael has given us more
moments than anyone since Ali, and his public image is as elegant
and clean as Joe DiMaggio's.
</P>
<P>
   He has never had a scandal stick or been involved in a major
legal action. So he liked to gamble. The spinners said that proved
how much he needed competition; he said he was no Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's baseball sabbatical was an endearing Roman holiday _
the world's greatest basketball player, just like you and me, had a
secret dream that failed. Michael came back and gave basketball its
last good years. As Stern well knows _ why else would he float a
challenge to the National Football League? _ the NBA is probably
over as a growth industry.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Bulls, expansion, violence, a star system that
promoted Dennis Rodman and Latrell Sprewell, as well as Jordan,
damaged brand equity far more than the slacker Shaq, Reggie (ET II)
Miller and Kobe Bryant can repair.
</P>
<P>
   Trust Nike to already have covered its assets; still the
monster, although slipping, it is branding more and more women and
soccer teams with the swoosh. Nike owns Brazil, which may someday
be as huge as Michael. And there's always Tiger Woods, who may be
boring but has already paid for himself by helping to fuel the golf
renaissance. Can you believe that Jack Nicklaus is building a
course in New York City?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of morality, Michael's passing may affect that
wonderfully cynical HBO sitcom ``Arliss,'' now in its third season.
In the first new show, the superagent Arliss arranges a
heterosexual photo-op for a client who has been having trouble
getting a contract as a backup quarterback, because of rumors he is
gay. In the second show, Arliss arranges better contracts for a
linebacker on steroids and a running back feigning injury. With
Michael's aura gone, Arliss may look like just another excellent
ESPN documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The final arbiter on all this, The Sporting News, rated Michael
the most powerful person in sports last year, the first athlete to
make No. 1 (up from No. 27 in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   The Sporting News looked beyond the hulking and suave brotha
worth $10 billion yet was still breathless in its own hard-core,
straight-arrow fashion. Michael proved himself a true role model
``by showing up for work, well prepared, enthusiastic and
respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   If he takes that away with him, post-Michael will be the
apocalypse. Who will make the shoes?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1659EDT &QL; 
