<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-ARTIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ARTIST SEES FAME VANISH, FAST AS IT CAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK, N.Y. _ The night his first solo exhibit opened in New
York, Don DeNarie was as jumpy as a rabbit. People wearing black
clothes and sophisticated smiles were strolling the little Gershwin
Gallery on East 27th Street oohing and aahing over paintings he had
done while he was still living in his car. It was too much.
</P>
<P>
   Don clung to a corner, looking as if he were ready to bolt. But
he stuck it out. People said big things were waiting for
Woodstock's most visible homeless person now that his talent was no
longer a secret. Some big things were happening already.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS Morning News team was working on a profile of him. A
producer-friend of one of his nine children was bankrolling an
apartment for him. He was painting nudes on canvases he bought
instead of scavenged; for the first time in six years, he was
sleeping in a warm bed.
</P>
<P>
   Not least, his son Duke, 15, product of the fourth of his five
marriages, was living with him. And Don had virtually stopped
hanging out on the Village Green, where for 25 years he had been a
leader of the long-haired, pot-smoking band of street people who
hit on tourists for pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   People like neat little stories that end happily ever after. But
nine months later, Don DeNarie is back living in his car (with a
dog this time) in a friend's driveway not far from the Village
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Try as he might, he can't figure out exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just kind of fell apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had problems with the apartment he and Duke were living in,
he said. ``Fumes were killing us.'' And when he finally got out of
there, after about a year of the fumes, he couldn't find another
apartment. ``Duke and I went away; we were in Arizona for two
months. Then, we came back and couldn't find a place. For an arts
colony, Woodstock hasn't been very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention, he was distracted by all the attention he was
receiving. After the gallery show and the CBS profile last
September (which led to an invitation to be honored at a dinner in
Rochester), he was stopped wherever he went. And that was all too
much. It stopped his painting cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the streets for five months now,'' he said, ``and
I'm only now just starting to get the visions in my head that make
me want to paint again.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people might say that Don DeNarie was homeless so long that
at 56, he had forgotten how to live any other way. That his life
had been so formless that the rigors of the creative life, with
people relying on him to produce, became too oppressive. That
homelessness can be like drug addiction, with relapses and a
perverse pull on the psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He had started painting as a young man, but life intruded. A few
years ago, he picked up an old canvas in the Woodstock dump and
started painting again. Two longtime friends, Lenny and Nancy
Kislin, noticed his paintings hanging in several living rooms _ Don
had traded them for favors and food _ and were so impressed that
they brought them to New York City for the 1997 Outsider Art Show,
the annual exhibit of work by untrained artists.
</P>
<P>
   Don's paintings were singled out for praise, which led to all
the attention he has received since the show.
</P>
<P>
   Kislin, who also exhibited several of Don's paintings in the
1998 Outsider Art Show in January, said he has tried to help Don.
But Don had his own ideas about what he wanted. ``If anyone wants
to help Don, I'll do what I can,'' he said. ``But I'm out of his
affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Don's paintings have sold for up to $3,500, but he owed
more than he made, especially to Steven Haberstroh, who paid for
his apartment and expenses. Haberstroh, a longtime friend of one of
Don's sons, runs a company, Habo Entertainment, in Brooklyn, and
has taken on the job as Don's manager. He still envisions big
things for his client. He has started filming a documentary of
Don's life, which has been full of adventures and drama.
</P>
<P>
   Don, meanwhile, said he'd rather have money than fame. ``Fame
means nothing,'' he said. ``I've got $40 in my pocket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
