<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      06-13 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEXPECTED PROBLEM IN COLORADO: SUBPAR OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shocking development at Coors Field:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you gave up four runs in the first, you knew you could
come back,'' Don Baylor said. ``Now you're always playing the
infield in early, trying to cut that run off. It makes you manage a
little differently. You can't give them up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies' manager was explaining the surprising
problem his team has encountered this season. If the highest-priced
Baltimore Orioles and the home run-hitting Seattle Mariners have
created the most serious head scratching with their poor,
underachieving play, the Rockies are close behind with the
disappearance of baseball's lustiest offense.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team that for three years hit for the highest average,
slugged the most home runs and scored the most runs. The only thing
that kept the Rockies from winning was their pitching. Now that
their pitching has improved, their hitters have lost their
lustiness.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the team that became notorious for playing under
two wildly different hitting personalities, overpowering at home
and feeble on the road, can't hit much of anything anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason most likely is the absence of Andres
Galarraga, but Bobby Jones _ not their own pitcher, but the Mets' _
also could be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given them probably all the information we can give them
on pitchers,'' Baylor said. ``Their preparation is there. Everybody
knows what everybody throws. One excuse guys tried to use before is
that the curveball rolls at Coors Field and then we go on the road
and it's a sharper breaking ball and it takes time to get
accustomed to that. That theory has been thrown out the window
night after night.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposing pitchers, Baylor said, no longer shy away from using
their breaking balls at the unfriendly confines of Coors. He
attributes the change in thinking to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with Bobby Jones of the Mets last May,'' he said.
``Before, he would come to Coors Field and abandon his breaking
ball. He went back to throwing it and pitching guys inside like he
does anywhere else. Each guy followed after that. They go with
their strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones recalled that game, which he won, 6-1, though his
explanation for the change in his pitching was slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you throw a curveball there, you have to change your
release point because it doesn't break as much,'' he said of his
big, over-the-top curve. ``That particular game, I started throwing
more of a slider or a slurve. I changed my release point in order
to get it down.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jones altered the Coors pitching style, Galarraga changed the
Rockies' hitting fortunes by defecting to Atlanta as a free agent.
The Rockies lost the first baseman because they would not guarantee
a third year of a contract and the Braves would.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, who will be 37 this week, showed no sign of age the
past two seasons, in which he batted .311, hit 88 home runs and
drove in 290 runs, leading the league both years in RBIs. His
departure has left a gaping void in the cleanup slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Galarraga was the guy you wrote in there, and you filled in
everyone else around him,'' Baylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor has used Larry Walker, Vinny Castilla, Dante Bichette and
Todd Helton, a rookie, in the fourth spot, but no one has replaced
Galarraga. ``You take Galarraga out of that mixture, and it seems
that pitchers aren't intimidated as much,'' the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Castilla has been the Rockies' major offensive force, hitting 22
home runs and driving in 61 runs. Bichette bulked up during the
winter and came to spring training with the announcement that he
was stronger and would hit more home runs. He has hit fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who staged a phenomenal performance last year and won
the National League's Most Valuable Player Award, has been slowly
recovering from a January elbow operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes and goes,'' Baylor said. ``If he has to make a lot of
throws to the plate or to bases, it bothers him. Then he's out of
the lineup for three, four days at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis Burks, the other remaining member of the once fearsome
fivesome, is having a dreadful season, hitting .196 at Coors.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Rockies are hitting .299 at home, compared with
.316, .343 and .321 the first three seasons at their new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before with the offense,'' Baylor said, ``every inning, every
other inning, you'd get a rally going. It just doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
