<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS AT THE PLATE  
 INTERLEAGUE WILD-CARD PLAY UNFAIR?  
 YANKEES ON THE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pitchers at the Plate
</P>
<P>
   So much for the complaint that American League pitchers are at a
disadvantage when they have to bat in interleague games played in
National League parks.
</P>
<P>
   In the first phase of this season's interleague games, AL
pitchers batted .155 (15-for-97), compared with .113 (9-for-80) for
NL pitchers. AL pitchers, in fact, did not hit much worse than NL
designated hitters (.190) in games played in AL parks. AL
designated hitters did not exactly distinguish themselves either,
hitting .226.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Burba of Cleveland hit the only home run among pitchers,
and Eric Milton of Minnesota and Doug Johns of Baltimore each had
two hits in one game.
</P>
<P>
   An Unfair Advantage?
</P>
<P>
   Does the current format of interleague play produce an unfair
advantage for one team over another in the wild-card race?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been an argument right from the start, but not a
serious one,'' said acting commissioner Bud Selig. ``Has there been
a lot of grumbling? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the format used this year and last, teams in one league
play against teams in the other league's corresponding division. If
one division is particularly weak and another strong, a wild-card
contender playing the weak division could benefit with a
significant number of victories.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the interleague subjects the owners addressed at
their quarterly meeting in Seattle last week, Selig said, as they
discussed whether they wanted to continue the same format or begin
rotating divisions.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no sentiment for adopting the kind of format the
National Football League uses in scheduling interdivision games:
teams are matched based on the previous season's records. That
system might appear to be fairer, but it would present its own
problems for baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Union lawyer Gene Orza cited one problem. ``Let's say you took a
West Coast team that was really poor and said, because you did
poorly last year, you play an equally poor East Coast team,'' Orza
said. ``What you gain in that, you lose in travel. This team would
be tired from a 3,000-mile trek. The travel is a very big component
of competitive integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The current system has potential problems, Orza acknowledged,
but ``the idea of matching up teams based on record and not where
they are is impractical.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a one-game matchup in the NFL is different from a
three-game baseball series. A weak NFL team has little chance of
beating a strong team on any given Sunday, but the outcome of a
baseball series can be determined by a hot team or a hot pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, the Chicago Cubs went to Minnesota with
a 37-24 record and a first-place tie to play the Twins, who had a
27-33 record and were nine and a half games out of first. The Twins
won two of the three games.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees on the Run
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lead the baseball world in just about everything
else, so why not stolen bases? Yet their major-league-leading total
of 80 is so alien to their recent history that it is mind-boggling
to think they have that many.
</P>
<P>
   Go back only a few seasons to the Buck Showalter years and look
hard to find the stolen bases. In Showalter's four seasons as
manager, the Yankees were last in the league twice and 12th twice.
Their 39 stolen bases in 1993 were the fewest for any Yankees team
since 1965. The total represented 2.5 percent of the league total.
This year's total is 12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't like us running that much, to tell you the truth,''
Paul O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's team now, the Arizona Diamondbacks, has a National
League-low 23 steals (3.6 percent of the league total).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have nine guys who can steal a base, who are
above-average runners,'' Showalter said. ``I've got a couple guys
who can steal bases when the right matchup is there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Showalter questioned the wisdom of trying to steal if the
percentage of success is not good. His team's percentage is 62.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're stealing at a 50, 60 percent rate,'' he said, ``is
that good baseball? Is it good baseball to run when you're not
capable of running? So much attention is being paid to the running
game nowadays. I look around and see some of the percentages of
stealing. It makes you wonder sometimes if it's as good a play as
people make it out to be. Twenty-seven outs are very precious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
