<HEADLINE>
KEVIN SUTHERLAND: HIGH AND DRY AND IN THE LEAD AT BUICK CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ The PGA Tour has taught Kevin Sutherland to be
patient. In his third full season on the Tour, Sutherland is still
waiting for his first victory. He is still waiting for the one week
in which everything clicks.
</P>
<P>
   So when rain forced the second round of the Buick Classic to be
suspended Friday before most of the field teed off, Sutherland
didn't mind. He was in first place. He was dry in the clubhouse.
And he could think of far worse situations to be in.
</P>
<P>
   With his opening-round 7-under-par 64, Sutherland held a
two-stroke lead heading into Saturday's second-round play at
Westchester Country Club. Bob Tway, J.P. Hayes, and Steve Lowery,
none of whom teed off Friday, were in a three-way tie for second
place at 66. Play was suspended Friday just a few minutes past
noon, with most of the second round still unfinished. Sutherland
was one of many golfers who never teed off on Friday, but when you
are sitting in first place, a lengthy rain delay is much easier to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the clubhouse talking mostly,'' said Sutherland, when
asked how he passed the idle time Friday. ``And I probably ate more
than I should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials planned to resume the second round Saturday
morning at 8 o'clock. After the second round is completed, a
decision was expected to be made on the rest of the schedule.
Several scenarios could take place, including playing 36 holes
Sunday, extending play until Monday or shortening the event to 54
holes. But none of those decisions had been made when play was
halted Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rain or shine, Sutherland was looking forward to the weekend. A
33-year-old native of Sacramento, Calif., Sutherland is coming off
his best season on the Tour, winning just over $455,000, and a
victory at Westchester would rank as his career highlight. Yet, as
Sutherland watched the rain fall, he was careful not to get too
giddy about having the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of golf to be played, and a lot can happen,'' he
said. ``It's too early to think about playing with the lead. I had
a great round Thursday, but I have plenty of work left to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Sutherland did not have to look far for morale support.
His younger brother, David, who also plays on the Tour, is also in
the tournament. And whatever sibling rivalry they have is kept off
the golf course. ``We're competitive at other things, but not
golf,'' Kevin said. ``We help each other, and it's really nice to
have each other on Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin and David, who is 38, have never been paired together at a
PGA Tour event. That is just fine with Kevin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a distraction for us,'' said Kevin,
thinking about the prospect. ``It would be a lot more difficult to
concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland hopes to concentrate well enough this weekend to win.
He finished second at last year's Houston Open, an experience that
gave him confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn a lot about how to handle different situations from
watching things that happen out here,'' Sutherland said. ``I was
also in contention at Hartford in 1996, but I shot a 74 on Sunday
and never really threatened. But that was still a great experience.
D.A. Weibring won that tournament, and I watched how he handled
being in the lead, how he worked the last day. That helped me a lot
in Houston, when I was in contention again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutherland had two chip-ins during his opening round, including
a 15-yarder for an eagle at No. 18. Those are the kinds of shots
that win tournaments. And Sutherland, who tied a nine-hole
tournament record by shooting 29 on the back nine, was encouraged
by his improved ball striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the ball better than I had for three months,''
Sutherland said of his opening round. ``I was struggling early in
the year, but I may have finally found something.''
</P>
<P>
   With Tom Lehman, Lee Westwood and Jim Furyk among the golfers
within striking distance, Sutherland knew it would take more solid
play to maintain his lead. Yet, it was nice to be the player that
everyone else was chasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great round Thursday to get in this position,''
Sutherland said. ``Hopefully, I can put three more good rounds
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
