<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK REAL ESTATE BOOMS, EVEN WITHOUT STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The West Side of Manhattan south of 42nd Street has
been the subject of intense real-estate speculation in recent
years. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has said that if a new baseball
stadium is built over the rail yards at 33rd Street and 11th Avenue
it will unleash a torrent of new development.
</P>
<P>
   But some of that is already under way, according to real-estate
brokers and developers. In the latest example, David Werner and
Credit Suisse First Boston emerged on Friday as the winning bidders
for the Starrett-Lehigh Building, a mammoth green and red building
near the West Side Highway in Chelsea that serves as a landmark to
the city's disappearing industrial past.
</P>
<P>
   Werner, his partner Mendy Wolfe, and First Boston bid slightly
more than $150 million, a surprisingly high sum for the aging,
19-story, 1.9 million-square-foot building that covers the block
bound by 26th and 27th streets, between 11th and 12th avenues,
according to real-estate executives involved in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   But it is another indication that industrial buildings on the
West Side have become hot commodities as midtown rents soar and
office tenants migrate toward the West Side in search of less
expensive space.
</P>
<P>
   Werner outmaneuvered rival developers Larry Silverstein and
Douglas Durst, Richard Kalikow and Laurence Gluck of Stellar
Management Co. All the bidders were planning to renovate the
building and boost rents from $10 a square foot to about $25, which
is still well below the midtown average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the latest example of the unchecked appreciation of New
York real-estate values,'' said Peter Hauspurg, the chairman of
Eastern Consolidated Properties. ``There's a strong move west now,
and it looks like some office development may actually take hold.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starrett-Lehigh Building, which is owned by Leona Helmsley,
was built in 1932 as a freight terminal and warehouse for steel,
tire and even wine companies. Train tracks once ran under the
building, which is marked by alternating bands of red-brick and
green-framed windows.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks can descend from driveways on 27th Street to gigantic
elevators that carry the tractor-trailers to various floors for
deliveries. The upper floors offer spectacular views of the Hudson
River and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Mrs. Helmsley has sold more than $1.2
billion worth of the real-estate holdings of her late husband,
Harry Helmsley. The Starrett-Lehigh Building was the latest
property to go on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Lambert, the chairman of Eastdil Realty who organized
the sale for Mrs. Helmsley, confirmed that a top bidder had been
selected, but he declined to provide details. ``We're getting ready
to make a recommendation to Mrs. Helmsley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Real-estate executives, however, say that Werner had the high
bid and would be the most likely buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever the new owner is, he will have to invest as much as $80
million to make the landmark building attractive to office tenants,
real-estate executives say. There are only four passenger elevators
in the 19-story building. The lobby needs to be refurbished, and
the heating system and many steel windows need to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   The current tenants range from a printing company to an
advertising photographer's studio. Nearly one-third of the building
is vacant. Buyers are betting that the demand for office space will
only increase, because there is little new construction.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prices for buildings in the garment district south of
Times Square have more than doubled over the last year as office
tenants have taken over showroom buildings and loft space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The redevelopment the city was hoping to stimulate on the West
Side is there without a stadium, and it shows no sign of abating,''
Hauspurg said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Charles Bendit and Paul Pariser of Taconic
Investment Partners acquired another sprawling industrial building,
at 111 Eighth Ave. in Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-story, 2.3 million-square-foot building covers the entire
block bounded by Eighth and Ninth avenues, between 15th and 16th
streets. Bendit said the neighborhood had benefited from the Sports
Center at Chelsea Piers and the improvements made to the West Side
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   Although many developers who pushed over to the West Side during
the last real-estate boom were hammered during the recession in the
early 1990s, the new crop of speculators believe the risks are
worth it, especially at the Starrett-Lehigh Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the last great opportunities to buy space at a low
price per pound,'' said William Adamski, director of the
real-estate finance group at First Boston. ``What other building
today can offer tenants large or small blocks of relatively
inexpensive space?''
</P>
</TEXT>
