<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A CELEBRATION IN CHICAGO IS ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The statue stood so tall, so proud, so reassuring for
those who came to worship as if it were a shrine. No doubt in its
eyes. No fear. No reason not to believe that the night would be
everything it was supposed to be. The guardian of the United
Center, the messiah of professional sports, would make the photo a
time piece to savor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' the people with the cameras would say. ``Could
you move just a bit?''
</P>
<P>
   Fathers would say to their children: ``Go over with your sister.
Stand up straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Some had walked past Michael Jordan's statue dozens or hundreds
of time without stopping to notice the inscription on the base's
front: ``The best there ever was. The greatest there ever will
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they mouthed the words, snapped photos from every angle,
tossed coins through the bars, into the impressions of Jordan's
hand and footprints.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-year-old Mike Chambers of Staten Island had flown in for
the intended occasion: last game of the season, of the Bulls' sixth
championship run, possibly of Jordan's fabled career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting married in August, my brother's my best man, and
this is his gift, Jordan's last game,'' Bill Chambers, 29, said,
holding the camera as his brother posed in his Jordan jersey by the
statue. ``I got tickets from Fox Sports, where I work in New York.
We flew in this morning, go back tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   David and Latisha Grummer were nearby, in from Los Angeles, with
their daughters Carissa, 5, and Dakota, 20 months. Tom Mader, a
season ticket-holder for 15 years from Geneva, Ill., brought his
9-year-old son, Anthony, who posed in front of the Jordan statue in
his Toni Kukoc jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' Mader said. ``Jordan won't be back next year.
I'm a numbers guy, work in finance. It'll cost Jerry Reinsdorf $80
million to bring them back. He doesn't have it. This is emotional.
This is sad. So we're all coming tonight, all the original season
ticket-holders I started with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety minutes before game time Friday night, it was as if
Jordan himself was up on the pedestal. Many had come without
tickets, just to be near the building, to gawk at the statue.
Traffic was backed up coming into the west side and Jordan, of all
people, was in it.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived only a few minutes late, the scene recorded by the
credentialed video mob, but it was an early warning that this was
no staged event, with no corporate script, and no guarantees.
Statues do not have nights when they take 26 shots and make only
nine. They do not go without a field goal in the first quarter and
shoot one for seven in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, for the first time in the NBA finals, the Utah
Jazz did not treat Jordan like a human shrine. Bryon Russell
challenged him with his elbows and chest. The Jazz swarmed him the
way Indiana did when he posted up. An old war horse named Antoine
Carr gave him schoolyard respect when Jordan drove the ball to the
basket. Carr sent the legend crashing to the floor, along with all
his plans for a postgame Champagne bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we have to go back to Utah,'' Jordan said,
after Karl Malone and the Jazz had extended the National Basketball
Association championship series to a sixth game, hanging on to win
Game 5, 83-81. ``It's a duplicate situation as in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   The statue, dedicated on Nov. 1, 1994, coldly lists only
Jordan's achievements through the Bulls' first three championships.
It makes no mention of Game 5 of the 1993 finals, the Phoenix Suns
written off like some Harlem Globetrotter prop. When the Bulls lost
that night, it was the last NBA game Jordan played on the cozy
Chicago Stadium court he loved. He came no closer to the scripted
finish that night than he did on Friday night's end-game 3-point
attempt off one foot from in front of the Chicago bench.
</P>
<P>
   Had he made that shot, there might have been a rally by the
statue to rename the building after him. Jordan shot an air ball,
muting the crowd, silencing a city, but reminding himself the chase
is more about such moments than it is about planning them like a
birthday dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 1.1 seconds, I knew I wanted the ball, but no one knew what
was going to happen,'' he said wistfully. ``That's part of my
personality, the way things have happened in my career. Everybody
was anticipating a big shot on our side, holding their breath. And
that's the beauty of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he often relives 1993, Game 6, in Phoenix, his send-off
to a 17-month sabbatical. The Bulls were losing by two on their
last possession. The ball, inbounded in the backcourt, touched
every player's hands before John Paxson launched a title-clinching
3-pointer, dispelling the doubt and eliminating the fear, that a
statue could never reflect.
</P>
<P>
   If this is Jordan's last season, then to see him in Utah is
going to be one last, special treat. Dealing with doubt. Facing the
fear. A photo opportunity, if there ever was one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
