<SLUG> BC-NY-HOMELESS-SHELTERS-760&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE SHIFT CAUSES CRISIS FOR SHELTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The sharp decline in New York state's welfare
rolls has created an unexpected crisis for financially struggling
homeless shelters in New York City's suburbs and upstate
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The shelters have fallen victim to a quirk in the state law
governing their state and local aid: Their financing is essentially
tied to the number of people ruled eligible for welfare benefits in
their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Because the number of people collecting welfare has plummeted,
financial support for the shelters in the 57 counties outside New
York City has also dropped sharply, even though the homeless
population has remained fairly steady.
</P>
<P>
   The situation _ an unanticipated consequence of changes in the
welfare system, particularly requirements that recipients take
workfare jobs _ has forced shelters to turn homeless people away,
reduce the number of days they are open and, in some cases, to go
out of business entirely, shelter operators and advocates for the
poor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shelters are being squeezed to such a point that they're
cutting back to a troubling extent,'' said Shelly Nortz, a lobbyist
and welfare analyst for the Coalition for the Homeless. ``We're
afraid that it is only going to get worse as welfare reform gets
implemented more aggressively around the state and the caseloads
are reduced further.''
</P>
<P>
   While the bulk of the state's homeless population is in New York
City, homelessness is a considerable problem in the rest of the
state. In 1997 alone, homeless shelters across the rest of the
state took in about 60,000 people, compared with the 100,000 who
stayed in city shelters, according to the Coalition for the
Homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing upstate shelters has its origins in the
system under which they receive public funds. Shelter operators are
paid for each night they house a person as long as that person is
deemed eligible to receive welfare benefits by the local welfare
office. That system was established to ensure that shelter
operators would act as advocates for the poor by encouraging
homeless individuals and families to apply for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But in an era in which local governments are aggressively
reducing the welfare rolls through a combination of sanctions and
stricter enforcement of eligibility requirements, the financing
formula is threatening to undermine the shelter system. Suddenly,
shelters are faced with a growing population of people who are
needy but unable to get public assistance because they have opted
not to take a workfare job or were disqualified for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funding system made sense in an era when the presumption
was that anyone who is homeless qualified for public assistance,''
Ms. Nortz said. ``But that is no longer true. It's an entirely
different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The financing crisis has not hit homeless shelters in New York
City, experts say, because of court orders mandating that city
officials provide shelter to all homeless individuals and families,
regardless of their eligibility for public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   State welfare officials said they were surprised to hear of the
problem, but they added that many individuals who have been cut off
from welfare can get their benefits back simply by complying with
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sanctions would be rather meaningless if people are able to go
to a sympathetic homeless shelter,'' said Dan Hogan, a deputy
commissioner for the state's Office of Temporary and Disability
Assistance. ``If we are talking about people who have been
sanctioned, the answer is for them to come into compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The response to the problem has varied from one county to
another. In Albany County, social-service officials have made
changes in which they pick up some of the cost of housing homeless
people who, for whatever reason, do not qualify for public
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   But shelter operators and advocates for the poor said the move
did little to ease the pressures that shelters are facing. Donna
DeMaria, who runs a shelter near the state Capitol, said her
shelter has devoted itself to taking in former welfare recipients
who are being turned away by other shelters that don't want to be
saddled with the expense of housing them.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, after sustaining major financial losses serving
that population, the shelter closed its doors. ``People are coming
off the welfare rolls, but they still need housing,'' she said.
``That's meant that shelters like ours are really struggling to
survive. It's a horrible situation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the neighboring city of Troy in Rensselaer County, the
operators of Joseph's House, a 30-bed shelter, said they have
suffered such steep losses that they have given thought to
operating only in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Neitzel, the shelter's director, estimates that nearly
half of her clients no longer qualify for public assistance. As a
result, she said, the shelter is losing about $100,000 a year.
``The reimbursement system just doesn't make sense anymore,'' she
said. ``Suddenly, we're seeing people on the streets of upstate New
York with absolutely no income. It's a shaky situation.''
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, things are not much better. Every day, the
Nassau-Suffolk Law Service, which provides legal services to the
poor, gets at least one phone call from a shelter operator who is
desperate to get a shelter resident back on welfare so they can be
paid to provide housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of concern among shelter operators is much higher
than I've ever seen it,'' said Tom Maligno, the agency's executive
director. ``They're asking us for legal help to appeal the local
agency's decision to sanction a person and take them off the
rolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the problem has been largely limited to single adults
in the state-financed program known as Home Relief, according to
the experts. That is because state and local officials have been
knocking them off the rolls in instances when they failed to
fulfill a host of new requirements. The most notable is the
requirement that recipients work in exchange for their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The state's own research has shown that many former Home Relief
recipients have left the program not because they have found
employment but because they have been penalized for failing to meet
the requirements of the workfare program. Between October 1990 and
September 1996, the number of times local social-service districts
penalized recipients for failure to comply with rules climbed to
72,771 from 5,593 statewide, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Operators of homeless shelters and advocates for the poor expect
the shelter crisis to grow because of recent state and federal
changes that give counties greater freedom to impose workfare
requirements on single mothers, who make up the bulk of the welfare
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already beginning to see some sanctions being applied to
women with children,'' said Tom Schmitz, the human services
director for the 17 shelters that the Salvation Army runs in
upstate cities like Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo. ``We're
worried that there will be more sanctioning of woman and children.
It poses a serious issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
