<SLUG> BC-SAIL-BERMUDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POSH AND THE POWERFUL MEET IN BERMUDA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Ky., N.C.)  (lb) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Given the Atlantic Ocean's propensity for
inclement weather, offshore racing can be a demanding sport. But
once a decision is made to set sail, the next question is how
quickly or how comfortably the voyage will go. Sailors rarely have
it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Speed and comfort are the differing priorities of two 60-foot
yachts competing in the Newport Bermuda Race, which begins at 1
p.m. Friday off Newport. The two sailboats, as dissimilar as
saltwater and freshwater, are the oldest and newest of 163
sailboats in the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   The older boat, Mistress, is a wooden schooner built in 1930.
Chris McCormick, co-owner with his brother, Glenn, would choose his
schooner hands down for sailing the 635-mile route to Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 40 tons of creature comfort,'' McCormick said recently.
``We'll have the best-looking boat out there. We have sheets,
blankets, towels, silverware and a walk-in shower with hot water.
This is a posh racer.''
</P>
<P>
   On the more streamlined end of the spectrum is Deep Powder, a
Carroll Marine 60 that is expected to be as swift as the
record-setting sloops in the recent Whitbread Round the World Race.
</P>
<P>
   Having never sailed before in a long-distance race, Deep Powder
_ and its new sister ship Rima _ are expected to be the showpieces
of the 1998 Bermuda competition.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Powder shows a glimmer of high style with wood veneer, a
compromise to the heavy mahogany interiors of yesteryear. But
freshwater showers will not be available during racing.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will there be staterooms to sleep in, or the cushioned
seating and lavish wood detailing one can expect in the main saloon
on Mistress.
</P>
<P>
   At night, much of Deep Powder's crew of 16 will be sitting on
the windward rail to keep the yacht under proper trim.
</P>
<P>
   On the two-masted Mistress with its crew of 12, having a sailor
sit on the rail is like watching a robin on the edge of a birdbath.
Nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Mistress competed in nine Newport Bermuda races from 1930
through 1954. In its 1930 Bermuda debut, Mistress finished sixth,
as one of seven schooners to finish at the head of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   But now Mistress is the only schooner racing to Bermuda. The old
style has been replaced by sleek, high-tech sloops that are the
future of yacht racing.
</P>
<P>
   At the finish, Deep Powder and Rima are apt to sail into Bermuda
at least a day sooner than the schooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistress probably won't see where the two new 60s went,'' said
Geoff Stagg, president of Farr International, the yacht designer
based in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be over the horizon. Only if the schooner has perfect
conditions, a broad reach where it can crack open the sails in a
strong breeze, might it be able to hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Mistress might reach 11 knots on a broad reach, Deep
Powder is likely to come up with at least 18 knots on a close
reach.
</P>
<P>
   So goes the difference in the caliber of racing today. The 41st
running of the Newport Bermuda Race includes boats ranging in size
from 34 to 80 feet.
</P>
<P>
   It includes Boomerang, the 80-foot maxiyacht that in 1996 set
the Newport Bermuda Race record of 57 hours 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Top sailors such as Russell Coutts and Chris Dickson are
expected to be on other maxis.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the allure of the Newport Bermuda Race. Still
revered as one of the nation's top amateur events, the competition
allows for professionals by applying updated handicap rules.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing which boat to sail becomes a matter of both style and
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Chigas, owner of Deep Powder, is set on winning above all
else. His 60-foot carbon-fiber sailboat weighs a mere 15 tons. It
has swept-back spreaders that eliminate the need for running
backstays, which in turn make sail-handling easier. But below deck,
life on board will be hard compared with the luxuries on Mistress.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes down to who is actually having more fun, only an
individual can say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have plenty of fruit, sweets, turkey, ham, cheese and
roast beef on board, and hot meals too,'' Chigas said. ``I'm
looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING WAVES
</P>
<P>
   TORI MURDEN, a 35-year-old lawyer from Louisville, Ky., was
expected to set out alone from Wanchese, N.C., Saturday in a second
attempt to row across the Atlantic Ocean. Her 3,635-mile trip will
be to Brest, France, aboard a 23-foot rowboat; the voyage is
expected to take 100-120 days. On her first try last October,
Murden and LOUISE GRAFF, her partner, withdrew after Murden became
ill. They were the only American competitors in the Atlantic Rowing
Race, a team competition from the Canary Islands to Barbados.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
