<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BODIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD D. BODIG, 75, ECONOMIST AND SINGER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard D. Bodig, an economist who was also a singer
and student of early music, died on May 26 at Lenox Hill Hospital
in Manhattan. He was 75 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said his wife, Joyce.
</P>
<P>
   Bodig served as economic adviser to the general counsel to the
Mobil Oil Corp. for 30 years, retiring in 1986. After retiring, he
worked on economic advisory projects for the National Executive
Service Corps.
</P>
<P>
   Bodig became interested in early music in the 1950s. Fluent in
10 languages, he also translated 16th- and 17th-century manuscripts
on performance practice from Italian and German into English and in
1995 published a collection of Renaissance duets.
</P>
<P>
   As a singer, Bodig performed with Richard Taruskin's Cappella
Nova, the Canby Singers, and the Dessoff Choir.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, who is concert coordinator for the
Frick Collection, he is survived by two sons, Christian, of Los
Angeles, and Paul, of New York City; and a sister, Alice, also of
New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
