<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPREDICTABLE OLYMPIC CLUB COULD GET EVEN TOUGHER AT U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a country smitten with underdogs and overachievers, perhaps
it is appropriate that golf's national championship will once again
be settled at the Olympic Club in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The course, after all, has a perfect record when it comes to
humbling the giants of the game during U.S. Open competition.
</P>
<P>
   When the 156 competitors tee off in Thursday's opening round,
they will be covering the same 6,797 yards of par-70 terrain that
produced improbable results such as Jack Fleck over Ben Hogan
(1955), Billy Casper over Arnold Palmer (1966) and Scott Simpson
over Tom Watson (1987).
</P>
<P>
   After closing a two-stroke deficit in the final four holes,
Fleck knocked off Hogan in an 18-hole playoff. Casper vanquished
Palmer in a Monday playoff as well, but had to make up a
seven-stroke deficit on the back nine during Sunday's round to
force the extra session. Simpson edged Watson, but did it in
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   During their PGA Tour careers, Fleck, Casper and Simpson have
combined to win five major championships. Palmer won seven,
establishing himself as low man on the totem pole among Olympic's
Open runner-ups. Watson has eight. Hogan, a longtime Fort Worth
resident who died last July, finished with nine.
</P>
<P>
   Such history is enough to jump-start the hopes of even the
longest long shot in this week's field, said Mark Calcavecchia, who
last cracked the top 20 of an Open leader board in 1987, the last
time the event visited Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you think anything is possible,'' said Calcavecchia,
who finished 17th in the 1987 Open, but has missed the cut the past
four years. ``This year, I've been telling myself, `I really should
play good at the Open.' I drive it good. I can chip with anybody.
And I'm a pretty good putter.''
</P>
<P>
   Those skills will be put to the test on a tract that features
few level lies on its fairways, let alone its small, sloping
greens. Hogan once four-putted the smallest green on the course,
No. 18, in the 1946 San Francisco Open. Nick Price, a three-time
competitor at Olympic, likened lining up putts at the hilly course
to ``trying to read Japanese.''
</P>
<P>
   To this inherent frustration, add the handiwork of U.S. Golf
Association officials. They have taken the 17th hole, a 522-yard
par-5 for club members, and turned it into a 468-yard par-4 for
Open competitors. By building a new tee box for this week's event,
they have added 40 yards to a hole that played to a scoring average
of 4.56 in the 1987 Open, when it was trimmed down to a 428-yard
par-4.
</P>
<P>
   The rough, unusually thick because of San Francisco's soggy
spring (courtesy of El Nino?), will be topped off at five inches,
one inch higher than last year at Congressional Country Club in
Bethesda, Md. Grounds crews have spent weeks digging in the bunkers
to soften the sand. In some spots, fresh sand has been added to
increase the possibility of buried lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to reproduce Hell Bunker or anything like
that,'' said David Fay, executive director of the U.S. Golf
Association. ``But it should be a hazard. If I can get a fried-egg
lie at my home course, why can't they in the U.S. Open?''
</P>
<P>
   At Olympic Club, USGA officials said, that possibility exists
more strongly than at any Open site in the past seven years.
Players are not necessarily thrilled by the USGA's subtle touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they need fresh sand? So when we hit it in the bunker,
it will be up to our ankles?'' said Calcavecchia, who is not in
favor of the USGA's tweaking of the Olympic layout. ``Why stop at
five inches with the rough? Why not 10-inch rough and ankle-deep
sand? That sounds like a USGA setup. I guess they felt like we need
some fresh hazards out there. It sounds to me like they want an
over-par score to win and they just might get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, the defending champ, does not dispute the possibility
than the Open champ could fail to break par for the first time
since Andy North won with a 1-over effort in 1978. Els, who posted
a winning total of 4 under in 1997, predicted that Olympic Club
will provide a ``much tougher test'' for players than Congressional
despite being 422 yards shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, every winning score at the Open has been under par
except one: Corey Pavin's even-par effort in 1995 at Shinnecock
Hills Golf Club in Southampton, N.Y. Els said a similar scenario is
likely in San Francisco, where Olympic will be the first seaside
course since Shinnecock to hold the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really know how the weather is going to be this time
of year in San Francisco, to start with. There's always a breeze,
and they've got a lot of tall trees, so it could swirl around a
bit,'' Els said. ``The greens are small, and they'll be firm. I
really think it's going to be the toughest test since Shinnecock.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest headaches, in no particular order, figure to be
found at:
</P>
<P>
   Quake Corner, the course's signature stretch (Nos. 2-5). In
addition to a view of the Golden Gate Bridge from the third tee
box, Quake Corner features two of the three toughest holes on the
course, according to the handicap index.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7, a reachable par-4 (288 yards) with a three-tiered putting
surface. Greg Norman once drove the green and four-putted for
bogey.
</P>
<P>
   No. 16, a 609-yard par-5 that doglegs to the left, making it
unreachable in two shots by even the longest hitters. With only two
par-5s on the course, Simpson said Olympic ``takes away a
disadvantage'' for shorter hitters like himself.
</P>
<P>
   No. 17, a converted par-5 that will play as a 468-yard par-4.
Even with a new tee box, the landing area is slanted and should
funnel shots to the right. Players also will be hitting long-iron
approaches to a green meant to handle 9-irons and pitching wedges.
Don't be surprised if players approach the 4.56 scoring average
from the 1987 Open.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18, a par-4 with a tiny green but a ton of tilt. During the
1987 Open, Fuzzy Zoeller likened the undulating surface to
something you'd find at Putt-Putt, saying: ``You one-putt this
green, you get a free game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the potential pitfalls at Olympic, players are most
concerned about No. 17, which has one of the most severely sloping
fairways on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally had to snap-hook the ball into a hill to keep it
on the fairway in 1987,'' said Watson, the reigning MasterCard
Colonial champ. ``If you hit a straight ball, it wound up in the
right rough ... It surprises me that they're adding length to that
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Calcavecchia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't be any tougher than it was. In '87, that fairway was
unhittable,'' Calcavecchia said. ``I played with John Mahaffey, and
he hit a 25-yard hook that landed in the first cut of rough on the
left. It wound up in the right rough. The landing area slopes that
much.''
</P>
<P>
   David Frost, the 1997 Colonial champ, has been a persistent
leader-board presence at Olympic Club. In addition to finishing
17th at the 1987 Open, Frost was second at the 1993 Tour
Championship and fourth at the 1994 Tour Championship, both played
at Olympic. The course, he said, reminds him of Colonial, with lots
of doglegs and tall trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are similarities. Both courses make you work the ball in
both directions off the tee quite a bit,'' Frost said. ``But
Colonial plays a bit shorter. Olympic is more deceiving. Being at
sea level, with all that heavy air and morning mist, you definitely
need to hit more drivers there. It's a much more demanding course
off the tee, especially when it's windy. And it's usually windy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Perry described Olympic as ``very severe,'' with a high
percentage of blind shots. ``It's a course that really wears on
you,'' Perry said. ``You don't feel like you get a break out there
on any hole. You feel like you're struggling on every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if firm and fast conditions prevail throughout the
week, as USGA officials hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything depends on whether the greens stay dry,''
Calcavecchia said. ``They're small to start with, so it's hard to
keep approach shots on them. And when those greens are firm, the
first hop is huge. You can play an entire round and never leave a
ball mark. And they're tough to read because you're always putting
in and out of shade from all the tall trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Underdogs, however, have a knack for working their way out of
the shadows and finding their place in the sun at the Olympic Club.
Just ask Fleck, Casper or Simpson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
