<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATURE-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LEGISLATURE WINDS DOWN, QUIETLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last week, just days before the end of the 1998
legislative session, state Sen. Nicholas Spano strolled through the
lobby outside the Senate chamber, chatting quietly with a few
colleagues and lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the session, usually I don't want to come out
into the lobby for fear of getting attacked by people who want
their pet bills,'' said Spano, a Republican from Yonkers who has
been in the Legislature for 20 years. ``This is the quietest I've
ever seen it at the end of session.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time of year when the Capitol would normally be the scene
of fevered negotiations and bill-drafting, it feels, instead, like
a resort town whose summer swarms have not yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of personal animosities among the major players
and election-year politics have made for an unusually quiet
five-month session. There have been few serious talks about pending
bills among legislative leaders and Gov. George Pataki, and most
lawmakers and lobbyists say that means there is little chance that
much will be done before the scheduled end of the session on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that there is any shortage of important issues left to
resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers of both parties hope to take the first step
toward changing the state Constitution to allow casino gambling.
But on Wednesday, the Republican majority leader of the Senate,
Joseph Bruno, declared the issue all but dead for the year because
the legislative leaders had barely talked about it. ``There isn't
any serious conversation going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The same inertia appears to be about to doom several other
proposals that have broad support, like streamlining the state's
multilayered court system, allowing mutual insurance companies to
sell billions of dollars in stock and joining a cartel of states to
allow dairy farmers to charge more for milk.
</P>
<P>
   Just two major issues are under serious discussion and appear to
have a good chance of passage, officials in both parties said.
</P>
<P>
   One is an expansion of the state's health-care program for poor
children.
</P>
<P>
   The other issue involves some kind of compromise on criminal
sentences. The Republicans want to end parole for violent felons.
The Democrats insist that as conditions for this change, drug
treatment must be substituted for mandatory prison sentences for
some drug offenses, and prison education programs that Pataki
eliminated three years ago must be restored.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In several other areas, there are competing proposals involving
the same interest groups: Republicans want charter schools, while
Democrats want to restore some of the education money that Pataki,
a Republican, vetoed from the budget; Republicans want to renew
laws favoring auto insurers, while Democrats want measures to lower
premiums; some lawmakers want a gay rights bill, while others want
the state to track people infected with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   In any normal year, each of these pairs of initiatives might be
a natural for a trade, ensuring enactment of both measures. But
this has been anything but a normal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, it's still possible that the last couple of days will be
like a hurricane,'' said Lester Shulklapper, one of the Capitol's
most prominent lobbyists who includes casino interests among his
clients. ``But right now, there's no energy, no feeling anything's
happening. Zero.''
</P>
<P>
   This year for the first time, the Legislature abandoned the
practice of having the legislative leaders negotiate the state
budget privately with Pataki. Instead, the leaders of both houses
worked out a budget publicly, through conference committees. As a
result, the Legislature passed a budget just two weeks overdue,
robbing both parties of a favorite ploy, delaying the budget to
gain leverage on unrelated issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, who is seeking re-election, used his line-item veto
power for the first time, eliminating $1.6 billion in spending that
the Legislature had approved. The vetoes pushed his relations with
legislative leaders to a new low. Although the governor appears to
have mended fences with the Senate Republicans, he and the
Democratic Assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, have barely spoken to
each other for months.
</P>
<P>
   After the governor's budget vetoes, many legislators expected _
wrongly, it seems _ that Pataki and legislative leaders would
negotiate to put some of the money back, and other business was put
on hold while they waited for an end game that never came.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is pervaded by a sense of the unknown,'' said
Assemblyman Steven Sanders, D-New York City. ``In many ways, we're
in territory where we've never been before.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, focused on his re-election effort, has been less active
than usual in privately lobbying and publicly exhorting the
Legislature to action. He has been crisscrossing the state at a
campaign-season pace to announce factory openings and environmental
cleanup grants, and promoting his new book in forums like the
programs of Montel Williams and Howard Stern, making him less of a
physical presence than in years past. Some legislators joke that he
treats the Capitol like little more than a mail drop.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has pressed hard for just two pieces of
legislation, an end to parole for violent felons and the creation
of charter schools, which are public schools with particular
missions that operate apart from the usual bureaucracy. He renewed
the debate over casino gambling with a letter urging the
Legislature to pass a constitutional amendment to allow it, but he
waited until mid-May to do so, and lawmakers say he has not
pressured them on the subject since.
</P>
<P>
   Last year saw two battles with great consequences, both
politically and in the lives of millions of people: the fight over
renewal of rent controls, and the overhaul of the state's welfare
system. In 1995 and 1996, Pataki successfully pushed for deep
budget and tax cuts and a revision of the workers' compensation
system, and he tried unsuccessfully to change welfare.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there is nothing as momentous on the calendar.
Lawmakers say that has eliminated much of the motivation to make
deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing anybody absolutely has to have before they go
home,'' said a prominent Assembly Democrat, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``That's a good thing, since Shelly and
George aren't on speaking terms, and everyone's already in campaign
mode, anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
