<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MURDER-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL STARTS IN KILLINGS OF 5 PROSTITUTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERHEAD, N.Y. _ A former postal worker who confessed to
killing five prostitutes and dumping their dismembered bodies in
trash bins is to go on trial Monday in Long Island's first death
penalty case since capital punishment was reinstated in New York
state in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Robert Shulman, 44, is charged with taking his
victims to his rented apartment in a small house in Hicksville,
where he is said to have beaten them to death and cut their bodies
into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   He signed a detailed confession after his arrest in April 1996,
but he has since insisted that details of the confession were
suggested to him by detectives and that he was coerced into signing
it.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman acknowledged taking the prostitutes to his apartment for
drugs and sex, but then said he ``blacked out.'' When he awoke, he
found their bodies, panicked and tried to hide them by disposing of
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyers argued during three months of evidentiary hearings
that Shulman's statements to police should be excluded because they
were made during an interrogation stretching over two days. His
lawyers, Paul Gianelli and William Keahon, also argued that police
never had sufficient cause to arrest Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Georgia Tschiember, an assistant district
attorney, argued that the detectives who questioned Shulman did
nothing wrong and that Shulman's confession indicated only that the
detectives' interrogation techniques were effective.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Arthur Pitts of Suffolk County Criminal Court ruled a week
ago that Shulman's arrest was proper and that the statements he
made could be used against him.
</P>
<P>
   Police were led to Shulman's apartment by prostitutes who worked
a section of Jamaica Avenue in Hollis, Queens, where Shulman would
often cruise for women. One prostitute who said she went with
Shulman but was not harmed, said she last saw one of the three
slain women leaving the Queens pickup area in Shulman's blue
Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are expected to argue that Shulman killed three of
his victims in Suffolk County. He is charged with murdering Kelly
Sue Bunting, 28, of Hollis, whose body was found in a trash bin in
Melville in December 1995; Lisa Ann Warner, 18, of Jamaica, Queens,
whose body was found at a trash-recycling plant in the Williamsburg
section of Brooklyn in April 1995, and an unidentified woman whose
body was found in a garbage container in Medford in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last several months.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman, who worked as a clerk at the post office in Hicksville,
several blocks from his apartment, was charged separately in
Westchester County last year with the murder of two women in 1991
and 1992 whose bodies were found in trash bins in Yonkers.
Westchester officials are awaiting the outcome of the Suffolk
trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his 17-page ruling dated June 5, Pitts said the authorities
had many valid reasons to arrest Shulman, including witnesses who
identified him as the last person to be seen with Ms. Bunting.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, forensic experts had identified fibers and
cat hairs linking Ms. Bunting and the unidentified woman found in
Medford to Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County district attorney, James Catterson Jr.,
announced in 1996 that he would seek the death penalty for Shulman.
Catterson said the case was ``the classic definition of a serial
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the law reinstating capital punishment, a suspect can be
charged with first-degree murder if accused of killing two or more
individuals within a two-year period in the same or similar
circumstances, or killing someone while committing another felony,
like rape or sodomy, or killing a police officer, among other
categories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
