<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-INITIATIVE-BOS &LR;      06-13 1643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-INITIATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S EFFORT TO BRING RACES TOGETHER NEVER GOT OFF GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If anyone needs convincing that President Clinton's
initiative on race has done at least a little good, let them talk
to Fannie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In the six months since Clinton went to Akron, Ohio, for his
first town hall meeting on race relations, Brown's ``Coming
Together Project'' has blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   The signup list for her workshops to promote racial
understanding has grown by the dozens. Money has poured in, desks
and computers have been donated to fill the one-room office, and
two full-time workers have been added.
</P>
<P>
   But as the curtain comes down Sunday on Clinton's yearlong race
initiative, Fannie Brown's experience stands out less as a success
story than as a sorry symbol of what might have been possible in
every nook and cranny of America.
</P>
<P>
   Bedeviled by ideological infighting, a vague sense of purpose,
and a president distracted by personal and political crises, the
initiative is widely viewed as at best a missed opportunity _ and
at worst as an exercise in futility. Few people inside the White
House or out expect anything akin to the lasting impact of the last
major presidential effort of this kind _ Lyndon Johnson's Kerner
Commission of 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kerner Commission is very high in our history, but there
is nothing distinctive about this commission,'' said Ron Walters, a
political scientist at the University of Maryland at College Park.
``And the discussions themselves never really took off.''
</P>
<P>
   No one faults Clinton for his ambitions. The challenge he took
on _ to prod Americans to talk to one another and get beyond skin
color and ethnicity _ was remarkable and unprecedented for a
president acting in the absence of a social crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Last June 14, standing before an adoring multiracial crowd at
the University of California at San Diego's commencement, Clinton,
his cap and gown blowing in the wind, said that 10 years from now
he wanted people to look back and say, ``This year of honest
dialogue and concerted action helped to lift the heavy burden of
race from our children's future.''
</P>
<P>
   He must have known how hard the work would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honest dialogue will not be easy,'' he said. ``We'll all have
to get past defensiveness and fear and political correctness and
other barriers to honesty. Emotions may be rubbed raw, but we must
begin.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Walters said, somehow the dialogue never got off the
ground. After the high hopes in Akron, one of the enduring images
is the look of irritation on Clinton's face when he showed up at a
meeting of his race advisory board at Washington's Mayflower Hotel
_ and then never showed up again.
</P>
<P>
   In the year of Lewinsky, Whitewater, and Starr, of crisis
management and frenetic foreign travel, there just wasn't much time
to dwell on America's most enduring social divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were unrealistically high expectations in terms of what
would immediately be accomplished by the initiative,'' said William
F. Winter, a former Mississippi governor who sits on the
seven-member race advisory board that Clinton appointed.
</P>
<P>
   The distractions also didn't help. ``It has obviously been
difficult for him to maintain the level of unimpeded leadership
that he posseses, but having these distractions forced upon him
every day is unfortunate,'' Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the White House admits that the dialogue never was as frank
as Clinton wanted. Emotions weren't rubbed as raw as he expected,
and a year later, the central question he posed, ``Can we become
one America in the 21st century?'' is arguably no closer to being
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, some would say that within the race board, the question
was never properly asked.
</P>
<P>
   One problem was the board's slow start. Several months passed
between the San Diego speech and the assembling of the board's
staff. The initial sluggishness reduced the amount of time
available to debate some hot-button issues.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, deliberations were considered public under the Open
Meetings Law. Some found that open-air dialogue and the early media
scrutiny constraining.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, having a situation where you are asking people
to bare their soul ... that is inhibiting,'' said the deputy White
House chief of staff, Sylvia Mathews.
</P>
<P>
   Far more damaging, many say, is that the board, hemmed in by
squeamishness in the White House, never settled on a primary focus.
Its conversations droned on, business-like, about such things as
the effects of racial disparities in education and employment. But
its shied away from the questions that preoccupy the racial
discourse elsewhere in America: What is the purpose and future of
affirmative action? What is to be done about the residual vein of
racial animus? Should the nation issue a formal apology for slavery
to get that ugly past behind us and help us move on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would any thoughtful, enlightened adult person in this
country really think we would get to the tough issues in a national
dialogue on race?'' asked board member Angela Oh, a blunt-talking
lawyer from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Walters, the political scientist, said: ``Just think about what
happened in Jasper, Texas,'' where three white men last week were
accused of chaining a black man to the back of a pickup and
dragging him to his death. ``That conjures up images of lynching,''
he said. ``One has to discuss those things, and at the end of the
day do something serious about it. You can't leap over that and get
to racial reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh said she wanted to deal with contentious issues such as
whether Clinton should apolgize for slavery. ``We were not
permitted to broach the subject,'' she said. ``Nobody raised it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked who would not permit it, she said: ``I just don't think we
were interested in taking something up that he (Clinton) was not
interested in pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   NAACP chairman Julian Bond, a longtime civil rights activist,
said such decisions made the race effort seem irrelevant and
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada has apologized to the Indians, Germany has apologized
to the Jews. The Southern Baptists have apologized for their bad
behavior, and part of coming to grips with this is the
acknowledgment of wrongdoing,'' Bond said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have not had any national acknowledgement of
wrongdoing, in the distant past or recent past. Apologies are not
just words. But words hurt and words can help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not often that Bond and Ward Connerly agree. But Connerly,
a University of California regent and a leading opponent of
affirmative action, agrees that the race effort is stained for not
dealing with the tough issues of slavery and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton should not be faulted for getting involved,'' Connerly
says. ``The fault is that he hasn't provided leadership. This is
going to be remembered as a lost opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said of Clinton's initiative: ``This all has been kind of
fuzzy from the start, and that's his fault. I'm just not clear what
was their charge, what were they supposed to do?''
</P>
<P>
   At times, it looked as if the race initiative had fallen off the
president's radar screen. There were often long stretches where he
did not mention it in speeches or devote much time to it.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, give a memorable speech in Little Rock, Ark.,
to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the integration of Central
High School. He also met with a group of conservatives like
Connerly who oppose affirmative action, with civil rights leaders,
and members of Congress on the race issue.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the board meeting at the Mayflower, where Clinton
was clearly irritated by the snail's pace of the race panel's work,
he has attended two town hall meetings.
</P>
<P>
   At the first, Clinton delivered an Oprah-esque performance,
walking across the stage, microphone in hand, at one point baiting
Boston scholar Abigail Thernstrom into a debate over affirmative
action in the military. At the second, Clinton was little more than
a spectator as professional athletes, coaches, and team owners
debated the overlay of race in sports. A third discussion on race
is planned for July 8.
</P>
<P>
   John Hope Franklin, the race panel's chairman and a noted
historian at Duke University, wrote Clinton monthly reports to
supplement weekly reports from the initiative's staff.
</P>
<P>
   In his first report, Franklin wrote: ``I would, of course, be
pleased to discuss these recommendations with you.'' His second
report ended with: ``I would, of course, be pleased to discuss any
of the above thoughts with you,'' before signing off with ``my best
wishes,'' as Franklin always did.
</P>
<P>
   For his entire year as chairman, Franklin never met face-to-face
with Clinton. Franklin stopped offering to meet with the president
after sending the second report.
</P>
<P>
   The race board's work now is nearly finished, except for a few
more meetings over several months and a final set of
recommendations for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who says he wants to be remembered for inspiring
Americans to appreciate its racial diversity, will have to use his
own findings and statements to set the foundation for his legacy as
a racial unifier.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Edley, an adviser to Clinton for the race
initiative, said the president's report will include not only
Clinton's vision but also a work plan for the nation with concrete
ideas for the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's report will contain a lot of policy ideas,''
Edley said, adding that those ideas are still being framed.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over the past year, Edley, who also teaches law at
Harvard University, said: ``We have our work cut out to realize all
of that potential'' from the initiative. ``But this is hard enough
that you just have to stay positive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
