u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BUDGET-1     06-13 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAUNTS AND TRICKERY IN CITY BUDGET NEGOTIATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAN BARRY and NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An aide to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani recently paused to
chat with a City Council member outside a men's room in City Hall.
But did the aide actually need to use the facilities? Or was he on
an espionage mission to glean vital information and confuse matters
with mayoral propaganda?
</P>
<P>
   The Council could not risk the chance. Just as the aide was
about to enter the men's room, a sergeant-at-arms ordered him to
leave the immediate premises. After all, this was war, and he was
in Council territory.
</P>
<P>
   The encounter is just one of several bizarre moments to have
sprung from the dispute between the mayor and the Council over the
city's budget. There was the day that the city's top budget
director, a man of linebacker proportions, snatched documents from
a Council leader's hands and literally ran away. Or the late night
when agents from both camps played budgetary brinkmanship over a
few beers. And the Council's days-long exploitation of a threat
from the mayor's office _ ``We will bring you to your knees'' _
that no one ever said.
</P>
<P>
   All these episodes, and more, were born of a wrenching battle
made more vitriolic by the memories of the combatants' formerly
cordial relationship. And it is all the more awkward because the
opposing forces operate under the same roof. Eyes are averted,
handshakes withdrawn. And certain courtesies are suspended.
</P>
<P>
   In the east wing of City Hall, leaders of the
Democratic-controlled Council have urged members to stick together,
swallow their fears and brace for the engagements to come. In the
west wing, the Republican mayor and his top aides jokingly call
themselves ``wartime consiglieres'' _ a phrase lifted from ``The
Godfather'' _ as they gird themselves with the fuel of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   It is a time for misinformation, media manipulation and
late-night debates over obscure passages in the city charter. As
Deputy Mayor Randy Mastro said, ``You plan for every possible
scenario, and you have responses for every possible scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago, both sides were optimistic that they could
reach a consensus budget for the fiscal year that begins July 1; a
$2 billion surplus has a way of creating good cheer.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiations soon soured between the mayor and Peter Vallone
_ the Council speaker and a gubernatorial candidate _ partly over
various tax-cut proposals but mostly over the future of the New
York Yankees. Giuliani insisted that Vallone drop his call for a
referendum on whether taxes should finance a new stadium in
Manhattan for the Bronx-based team; he argued that it would disrupt
sensitive discussions. The speaker refused.
</P>
<P>
   Budget talks ended abruptly, and the maneuvers, profound and
petty, began.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Menges, the mayor's legislative liaison to the Council, was
in mid-sentence with Councilman John Sabini when the
sergeant-at-arms ordered him to leave the restroom. He then moved
to a Council anteroom and struck up a conversation with another
Council member, but a sergeant-at-arms again told him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Menges declined to comment, and Council aides responded by
citing examples of similar insults from the mayor's side _ of
agency commissioners instructed not to provide the Council with
information. Still, the incident became a cause celebre for the
mayor's aides, who made sure that reporters were apprised.
</P>
<P>
   The Council developed a rallying cry of its own, after a brief
meeting between Mastro, the mayor's top negotiator, and Bruce
Bender, the Council's chief of staff. ``We discussed from his
perspective that the Council was going its own way, and from our
perspective that we would have to have a strong response,'' Mastro
recalled. ``No voices raised, no fancy rhetoric.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Bender briefed anxious Council leaders about his
meeting with Mastro, they interpreted his account to mean that the
deputy mayor had vowed to bring the Council speaker to his knees.
Within hours, the supposed threat had become another ``Remember the
Maine,'' used to unite Council members in the bond of outrage.
</P>
<P>
   The phrase resurfaced so often, in fact, that Vallone developed
a stock answer that he used several times: ``There's only one time
in my life that I was on my knees, and thank God my wife said
yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one problem: The threat had never been made, officials on
both sides say. ``The words that the speaker attributed to me, for
what he apparently perceived to be good campaign fodder, were never
uttered,'' Mastro said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Friday, June 5, the Council defied both the mayor and
precedent by adopting a $34 billion budget. Dozens of Council
members, reveling in their political courage, gathered in the City
Hall's rotunda that afternoon to cheer and chortle.
</P>
<P>
   Only Thomas McMahon, the Council's finance director, and his
staff tempered their celebration. They knew that at some point
before midnight, the mayor's staff would be issuing a figure _ its
estimate of city revenues _ that could foul up the calculations
that the Council had used in arriving at its budget. All they could
do was wait _ and drink beer _ at the Nathan Hale bar on Murray
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the mayor's budget director and McMahon's
adversary, was also waiting for his analysts to develop a revenue
figure. But his persistent questions so disrupted their work that
he left his Park Place headquarters _ where he uses the soundtrack
to ``Top Gun'' to prepare for budget battles, and recordings of
Gregorian chants to calm down _ to wait in City Hall. An analyst,
David Rubenstein, would walk the estimates over as soon as they
were completed.
</P>
<P>
   As midnight drew closer, McMahon's colleagues drank some more
and placed bets on what the mayor's revenue number would be. But
McMahon kept stepping out onto Murray Street to drag on a cigarette
and glance nervously toward the lights of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he recognized his budgetary enemy, Rubenstein, walking
up the street with the manila envelope clutched to his chest. As he
walked past McMahon, Rubenstein muttered: ``It's in here.''
</P>
<P>
   That prompted McMahon to start shouting for one of his own
analysts, Kurt Richwerger. ``Kurt! Kurt!'' he shouted,
half-jokingly. ``Let's get Kurt to jump him!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The shouting prompted Rubenstein to begin running. McMahon could
only watch him run across Broadway and disappear inside City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:51 p.m., McMahon's beeper sounded. It was Lhota: The
mayor's revenue estimate was $251 million short of what the Council
had used in its calculations, forcing it to come up with a way _
either by raising taxes or making budget cuts _ to make up the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, at least, detente was declared. Rubenstein
returned to the bar to drink and swap silly budgetary threats with
the Council analysts. As a matter of fact, he and Richwerger are
longtime rivals in the subterranean world of revenue estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the federal tax reform of 1986?'' Richwerger later
asked. ``We had different opinions about its implications for city
agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The truce was brief. For all the minor absurdities, both sides
see the budget battle as a defining moment in city history. Vallone
maintains that the budget is sound, and that it demonstrates that
two branches of government _ not just the mayor _ have a say in
city spending. Giuliani counters that the Council's budget will
create huge deficits in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Because both sides expect the fight to end up in court, they
have taken care not to violate the City Charter as they make each
move. But there have been gaffes.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a mayoral aide solemnly delivered copies of
Giuliani's vetoes, totaling about $196 million, to the Council's
chief of staff, Bender. But seconds later, Lhota, the budget
director, burst into the office, grabbed the documents from Bender
and dashed out of City Hall. Observers said that Lhota moved
quickly for a very large man.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, the mayoral aide appeared once again at the
Council's door with the veto documents. Lhota later explained that
a few pages of veto cuts were missing from the veto documents.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the Council's turn. Like a general rallying his
troops for a historic engagement, Vallone summoned the 51 members
to City Hall on Thursday to override the mayor's vetoes _ only to
postpone the vote until Tuesday. It turned out that the Council's
lawyers were concerned that they had not followed a requirement to
give the public sufficient notice of their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be no end in sight for either the squabbles or
the touches of the absurd. A few nights ago, leaders from the
Council and the mayor's office traveled to midtown Manhattan to
present their cases before television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   For a few awkward moments, the adversaries found themselves
sitting together in a studio lounge. They discovered that they had
little to talk about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
