<P>
   SCOUT _ The Cincinnati Reds and some other small-market baseball
teams are looking for talent in an unusual place _ America's inner
cities. As more and more teams concentrate scoutingefforts in Latin
America and United States suburbs and college campuses,
underfinanced small market-teams hope to stay competitive by
discovering overlooked talent in the inner cities. We follow Jerry
Flowers, a recently hired scout for the Cincinnati Reds whose job
is to scout players in some of the toughest neighborhoods in inner
city Chicago and Detroit in hopes of finding the next Eric Davis,
Kenny Lofton or Darryl Strawberry. This story will give readers a
first-hand look at Flowers' unusual job and the challenges he and
baseball face in reviving the sport in the inner city. (Vinella,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
