</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ADDICT-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING TO LIVE CLEAN AND KEEP HIS CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Dale Graham lumbers through the front door of
the Children's Aid Society in midtown Manhattan, and three small
boys begin shrieking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daddy! Daddy! Daddy!'' one cries as he and his two brothers
race toward the towering 6-foot-4-inch, 290-pound visitor in
stylish black jeans, black parka and gold chain.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest boy, 4, buries his face between Graham's shins. The
two older boys, 6 and 7, fiercely clutch his calves. Graham, a
recovering crack addict who has spent 23 of his 41 years cycling in
and out of jail, is ebullient. He stoops, collects all three in his
massive arms and gently squeezes them.
</P>
<P>
   It is Graham's first visit with his sons since he completed a
10-month drug rehabilitation program. The Children's Aid Society,
citing Graham's 14-year crack addiction and criminal record, wants
to put the boys up for adoption. Graham is desperate to win them
back. His success at blocking the adoption in court depends on how
convincingly he can complete the metamorphosis from addict and
inmate to responsible father.
</P>
<P>
   As the giddy children leap up and down around him, Graham hands
out three presents painstakingly wrapped in used gift paper: a $28
battery-operated train set and used $5 ``Lion King'' and ``Bambi''
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   But after the boys tear open their gifts, they begin fighting,
and Graham struggles to exert authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to me! Listen to me!'' he says, his frustration and
baritone voice rising. ``There's no batteries. There's no
batteries. It ain't gonna work!''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after it began, the visit is fraying as Graham betrays
the pressure he is under.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for Graham are high. A relapse, or another arrest,
would probably result in the boys' disappearing from his life
forever. If they are adopted, their new parent will control whether
Graham can ever see them again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids' best interest, that's what's keeping me from doing
something crazy,'' he says. ``I have never been as determined as
this in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's most vexing demon, and the source of much of the city's
crime, is addiction. A three-year study released in January by the
Columbia University Center on Alcohol and Substance Abuse found
that drugs or alcohol played a role in the imprisonment of 80
percent of the inmates in the United States in that period. City
officials estimate that 70 percent of the 41,000 children in foster
care in New York have a parent who is an addict.
</P>
<P>
   Graham and his drug counselor agreed to let a reporter spend
five months observing as Graham fought to end his addiction
permanently and regain custody of his sons. His struggle offers a
rare window into what occurs when a drug-addicted criminal does
what society asks and tries to salvage his life.
</P>
<P>
   On the February day of his visit with his sons, Graham is
entering a crucial period. After living in the relative cocoon of a
residential drug treatment program, he has just moved into a
single-room-occupancy hotel. No longer required to attend
counseling and abide by a curfew, he is free to roam streets that
consumed him only months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a month, his job-training program will place him in his first
legal job in more than a decade. And most important, a court
hearing that will most likely be his last opportunity to halt the
permanent adoption of his children is seven weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   After the uproar in the waiting room, Graham, his sons and a
social worker go into a small, colorfully decorated room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put these in these,'' Graham says, showing one boy how to put
together track lengths. The boys start quarreling over a piece of
track. ``Yo, yo, quiet!'' Graham shouts.
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Graham can be extraordinarily determined and
perceptive, openly and earnestly discussing an addiction that led
to prison and the loss of his children to foster care. At his
worst, he can be manipulative and short-tempered, a man vulnerable
to relapse and, judging from his past, prone to violence.
</P>
<P>
   All three boys were placed in foster care four years ago while
Graham was in jail and their mother was using drugs. Only the
6-year-old and 7-year-old are his; the 4-year-old is the child of
another man.
</P>
<P>
   He and the mother of his two sons also had a girl, now 14, whom
he lost to adoption. At the time, Graham was in jail and the mother
was using drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where she went,'' he says. ``I guess that's why
I'm so determined to not lose these two.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham also has a 13-year-old son with another woman.
</P>
<P>
   He and his children are part of a cycle. Studies by the Medical
School of the University of California at San Diego and other
institutions found that children of addicts are four times as
likely as those of nonaddicts to develop substance abuse problems,
even if they are adopted by another family.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics, Graham argues, explain why he should rear his
children. If anyone knows the temptations his sons will face, he
does.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour, Graham's biweekly visit with his sons ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Dad,'' one son says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, too,'' Graham says. ``Come over here. I'll hug
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys again clutch Graham's calves. He again gently envelops
them in his arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll call you,'' Graham says, and walks out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to Avoid Streets of `Triggers'
</P>
<P>
   That night, Graham saunters up the front steps of the Project
Create Drug Rehabilitation program in Harlem. He warmly greets
another former convict still enrolled in Project Create, a program
typical of the treatment available to poor addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is eager for company. His girlfriend, a 37-year-old
convicted felon and recovering crack addict nicknamed Cookie, left
for Virginia two days earlier to visit two estranged daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that he is lost without her. While he was dealing
drugs, Graham says, he moved from girlfriend to girlfriend, but
this relationship is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a good girl who doesn't want to get high,'' he says.
``I'd be a fool to lose her. I know I can't do it alone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
