<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-POLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACES IN MASS. HAVE VERY DIFFERENT VIEWS ON EQUALITY GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Are minorities close to achieving equality in
Massachusetts?
</P>
<P>
   Whites thinks so. In their view, conditions for people of color
in Massachusetts have gotten better in the last five years, giving
them about the same chance in life as themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Affirmative action has gone far enough, they say. Now it's time
for minorities to do more to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But African-Americans, Latinos, and Asian-Americans see a
starkly different state, one where equality remains a long way off.
Although Latinos see some progress in the last five years, blacks
are much more likely to say things have stayed stagnant rather that
gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   With one-quarter to one-third of minorities reporting acts of
discrimination within the last month, blacks and Latinos think
government should do much more to make things better for
minorities. Blacks in particular would like to see affirmative
action expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just some of the important differences revealed by a
new University of Massachusetts public-opinion poll that surveyed
white and minority attitudes on issues from affirmative action to
education to the bedrock institutions of American life.
</P>
<P>
   That survey, done as a cooperative venture by four institutes at
the University of Massachusetts, shows that on a number of
high-profile issues, the views of African-Americans, Latinos, and
Asian-Americans vary greatly from the white majority in
Massachusetts _ and in some cases, from one another. The new survey
doesn't exactly paint a picture of two separate states, but it
certainly shows a Commonwealth where different racial groups are of
different minds on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   With the state's demographic mix changing steadily, a closer
examination of minority sentiment is essential to understanding the
state, the academicians say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studies indicate that 30 percent of the state will be people
of color by 2010,'' said Russell Williams, research associate at
the Trotter Institute. ``We have to realize that there are
different perspectives that haven't been captured by previous
studies.''
</P>
<P>
   The new poll surveyed 381 whites residents and 348 minorities _
127 blacks, 114 Asian Americans, and 107 Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Although the individual minority-group samples would be small
for head-to-head coverage in a fluid political race, those sample
sizes are considered satisfactory for social and attitudinal
research. On those samples, the margin of error is about nine
percentage points; the sample of white voters has a margin of error
of about 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EQUALITY
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two of the starkest differences between the white sample and
nonwhite residents came on questions that dealt with the basic
status of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   By counts of 63 to 33 percent and 51 to 36 percent,
African-Americans and Latinos said they are still a long way from
gaining equality with whites. But Asian-Americans were split, with
44 percent saying there was a long way to go, and 47 percent
disagreeing.
</P>
<P>
   The white sample thought otherwise. Sixty-two percent thought
Asian-Americans had basically the same chance in life as whites,
with 25 percent demurring; 55 percent said equality had come for
African-Americans, with 37 percent disagreeing; and 48 percent
judged it true for Latinos, with 41 percent disagreeing.
</P>
<P>
   A similar difference came when the groups were asked whether
conditions in Massachusetts ``had gotten better'' for minorities in
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the whites surveyed thought so, but only 29 percent of
African-Americans agreed. Instead, 48 percent said things had
stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   Personal experience could inform the minority viewpoint.
One-third of African-Americans, 31 percent of Latinos, and
one-quarter of Asian-Americans said they had experienced
discrimination within the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Given those perspectives, it's probably not surprising that the
races were also in strong disagreement on two questions about the
role government should play toward minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six percent of Latinos and 46 percent of African-Americans
said government should make every effort to improve the social and
economic position of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But that proposition won support from only 26 percent of whites.
Forty-two percent said minorities should help themselves instead,
with 32 percent embracing an in-between position. Only 28 percent
of African-Americans and 20 percent of Latinos thought said
government should make no special efforts, but rather leave it to
minorities to help themselves, with 27 percent and 23 percent
endorsing an intermediate position or expressing no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Asian community sentiment was more mixed: 38 percent wanted
government to do more, 27 percent said it was time for minorities
to rely on themselves and not government, and 35 percent fell
between the two extremes.
</P>
<P>
   A similar split between whites and nonwhites came on the issue
of affirmative action. Forty-nine percent of African-Americans and
53 percent of Latinos felt the programs should be increased.
</P>
<P>
   But only 18 percent of whites thought so, with 28 percent
wanting to decrease those programs, and 36 percent favoring the
status quo.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, only 11 percent of blacks and 6 percent of Latinos
wanted to pare back affirmative action, while 30 percent and 21
percent, respectively, were satisfied with the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-Americans fell in the middle, with 31 percent supporting
an increase, 17 percent saying affirmative action efforts should be
decreased and 33 percent favoring the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BILINGUAL EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The races split in several different ways on bilingual
education. Asked if the public schools should teach only in English
or in other languages as well, Latinos backed bilingual education
by a margin of 81 percent to 14 percent, followed by
African-Americans, at 54 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Asian Americans were split on the question, with 48 percent
in favor and 46 percent opposed. Only 35 percent of whites backed
bilingual education, while 61 percent said instruction should be in
English alone.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Watanabe, co-director of the Institute for Asian-American
Studies, said those answers gave a clear view not just at the
difference between whites and minorities, but also between the
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   However, each racial group gave relatively strong support to the
idea of standardized tests as a gateway for high school graduation,
with three-quarters of whites and Asian-Americans in support, and
more than three-fifths of blacks and Latinos agreeing. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
IMPORTANT ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The four groups also cited different matters when asked what
they believed to be the most important issue facing Massachusetts
today.
</P>
<P>
   Crime was the biggest concern to Latinos, education most
important to Asian-Americans. Blacks were split between crime and
education. Whites, too, were divided, but between education and
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime and schools and education were clearly much higher
priorities for the nonwhite sample,'' said Carol Hardy-Fanta,
research director of the McCormack Institute's Center for Women in
Politics &AMP; Public Policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
