<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ADDICT-PROFILE-2ND     06-13 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ADDICT-PROFILE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: it alone.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He and Cookie met at Project Create a year ago. Counselors
discourage such relationships, reasoning that addicts should not
associate recovery with a specific person. Graham ignored the
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Project Create, a nonprofit agency, is on 111th Street near St.
Nicholas Avenue, an area with a stubbornly resilient drug trade.
During walks through the area, Graham occasionally bumps into
people he got high with.
</P>
<P>
   While commuting to his job-training program _ Binding Together,
a nonprofit agency in Manhattan that teaches recovering addicts to
use computerized copiers _ Graham avoids blocks where crack is
sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the whole thing is to stay away from your
triggers,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He is also staying away from another danger: Because of his
race, his size and his clothes, Graham says, he is a favorite
target of spot searches by the police. If he walks along a
dealer-infested block, he risks being caught in a police sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my record,'' he says, ``it would be very hard for me to
make a person believe I wasn't out there to do something wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bad Times Started Early
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Graham muses about a life gone wrong as he lies on
the floor of a half-renovated brownstone in Brooklyn. He is
providing security for a contractor who fears that addicts will
strip the former crack house of its new pipes and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   With all but $42 of his biweekly welfare check going to lodging,
the job provides spending money. Working a double shift on a
Saturday, he will stay in the small, dusty room from 8 a.m. until
midnight. ``It keeps me off the streets,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Born on Christmas Day in 1956, Graham grew up in Brownsville,
Brooklyn, one of five children of a coffee shop manager and a truck
driver who are still married. His mother, Mary, 72, answers her
phone, ``Good afternoon, God is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's older brother, James, joined the Marines; a younger
brother, Adrian joined the Army. Both now run businesses in
Florida. His sister, Gwendolyn, is a schoolteacher in Brooklyn.
Graham and another younger brother, Stephen, who is in prison for
stabbing a man to death while high on angel dust, have drug
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger is very smart,'' Graham's mother says. ``But he
outsmarted himself.''
</P>
<P>
   At 14, in his first theft, Graham stole a typewriter and a copy
machine from his junior high school. Jailed twice as a juvenile, he
grew up behind bars and became more comfortable there than on the
street. ``When I was young and running wild, jail didn't bother
me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, he started smoking angel dust, also known as PCP,
because he liked the high. In 1985, he turned to crack cocaine and
spent the next decade in jail or homeless. Only self-preservation
and threats of stiff punishment seemed to change his behavior. He
switched to selling drugs after robbery sentences were increased
and a man he tried to mug pulled a gun on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started selling drugs to get away from the violence,'' he
says without a trace of irony.
</P>
<P>
   His last jail term broke him. Sleeping in a Rikers Island
dormitory, he felt vulnerable to attack from other prisoners, and
his blood pressure rose. ``I used to actually feel relieved when
the cops arrested me,'' he says. ``But this last time, I didn't
feel relief until I was heading home.''
</P>
<P>
   Why it took two decades for Graham to change is complicated, he
says, but the largest reason was his failure to recognize how drugs
had shaped his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I didn't have a drug problem; I thought I had a jail
problem,'' he said. ``Now, I see that it was the drugs that was
leading me to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   And Finally, a Day in Court
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, Graham arrives 45 minutes early in Bronx Family
Court for the hearing on his bid to block his biological sons'
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when impressing a judge is pivotal, he wears a gray
suit, maroon shirt, black tie, alligator-skin loafers with red
velvet stripes, and a thick gold necklace.
</P>
<P>
   As he waits, he broods. He scribbles in a newspaper, fidgets and
picks at his fingernails. His feet twitch back and forth. ``Courts
make me nervous,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His hopes for keeping his children lie in a thin envelope with
``Diplomas'' carefully written on its exterior. ``I've got
everything I've done in the last year here,'' he says, referring to
papers certifying his enrollment in drug rehabilitation, parenting
class and job training. ``He's got to lay it out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'' is Harold Jones, a harried, graying man who is Graham's
court-appointed lawyer. The two have not spoken for seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After an hour-and-a-half delay, Graham, three lawyers and the
adoption agency caseworker shuffle into the courtroom. Judge Myrna
Martinez-Perez sits behind a small wooden bench.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Steinhagen, a Manhattan lawyer, represents the Children's
Aid Society. Cesar Molina, a Legal Aid lawyer, is the children's
law guardian, appointed to protect their interests.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Davis, the children's caseworker, takes the stand first.
Citing Graham's criminal record, she recommends that his parental
rights be terminated. Graham sits silently, his left knee furiously
bouncing beneath the wooden table.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Ms. Davis says the children have told
her they want to be adopted. Graham sighs and looks at his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call Graham,'' Jones announces. Nervously adjusting his
suit, Graham takes the witness stand. Finally, his chance to
explain his new life has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Jones leads Graham through basic questions, but Graham answers
awkwardly. His grammar, already bad, worsens. He fidgets between
answers. A muscle on the left side of his face twitches.
</P>
<P>
   Jones asks Graham to explain why he should have his children.
``I feel that I'm capable of taking care of the youths,'' Graham
says. ``I'm no longer thinking that way no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Places I be in the street, where I used to be there, I don't
go there no more,'' he stammers. ``I put myself in school, you
know. I've been doing everything positive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
