u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ADDICT-PROFILE-3RD     06-13 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ADDICT-PROFILE-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: everything positive.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jones concludes his questioning, and Ms. Steinhagen, the foster
agency's lawyer, wastes little time. After debating with Graham
exactly how many years he has spent in jail, she settles into a
simple, and devastating, line of questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true that in 1973 you were convicted of robbery?'' she
asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it true that in 1975 you were convicted of forcible entry
with a deadly weapon?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Graham's face twitches, Ms. Steinhagen retraces a criminal
history, conviction by conviction. Fifteen guilty pleas or
convictions over 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   Each question seems to drive a stake into Graham. His answers _
a grudging ``yes'' each time _ shift from defiant to angry to
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination by Molina, the children's law guardian, is
brief and also damaging. Graham leaves the stand and stares at the
floor as he shuffles to his seat.
</P>
<P>
   After perfunctory concluding arguments, Judge Martinez-Perez
says she is prepared to rule. Although she recognizes the efforts
Graham has made, she says the interests of the children are of
primary importance. After years of tumult, the boys deserve
consistency in their lives. She ends bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   The time has come ``to set these children on a course of
stability,'' she says. ``I grant the petition to terminate Graham's
rights as a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   In one fluid motion, Graham stands, grabs his diplomas and
storms out of the courtroom. He would later admit that, for a
moment, he was seized by his old instinct to lash out, to be
violent. He speaks with Jones about an appeal and holds his tongue
until he is inside the elevator. Boiling with rage, he curses the
court and the adoption agency, but most of all he curses his
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times am I going to be punished for what I did?'' he
later thunders. ``This is what I get for doing the right thing!''
</P>
<P>
   A Steady Course And a Night Job
</P>
<P>
   On June 2, Graham graduated from his job-training program. He is
off welfare and has held down an $8-an-hour job for a month,
working the graveyard shift for a Manhattan printing company.
MaryAnne Flynn, his drug counselor, says he shows no signs of
relapsing. His anger with the judge's ruling still simmers, but he
has stayed in control.
</P>
<P>
   He filed an appeal to block his sons' adoption on April 12. He
chose to work nights, he says, ``so I can have the days free, so I
can do what I need to do in court. I still want them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever delicate mix of forces is holding him together _ fear
of jail, a desire to regain custody of his sons, his love for
Cookie, Narcotics Anonymous or his counselor, Ms. Flynn _ remains
stronger than the roadblocks confronting him. For now, he is
beating his demon.
</P>
</TEXT>
