<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-EUROPE-630&AMP;ADD-NY     06-13 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-EUROPE-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD BOWL ENDS SEASON OF HARD SELL FOR NFL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Texas, Fla.)  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ While most of Europe is fixated on the
World Cup soccer matches in Paris, Mario Bailey's future may well
hang on what happens at a very different football championship here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who comes from Seattle, is the starting wide receiver
for the Frankfurt Galaxy, one of six teams in the National Football
League of Europe. For the past four years, he has played
professional American football in a country where he does not speak
the language and where most people remain baffled about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Along with his teammates, most of them Americans, Bailey spends
three months a year in a Holiday Inn and flies to games in Spain,
the Netherlands, Britain and Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey earns about $1,000 a game, on top of his living expenses,
and has become remarkably popular among Frankfurt fans who have
nicknamed him Super Mario. But his only real goal is to play
professional football back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going out on the field, and the guys are all calling me
`old man,''' Bailey, 27, said before a practice session on
Thursday. ``I used to be the young guy here, and now they're
calling me old.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday marks a crucial turning point. In a game that is expected
to draw about 45,000 spectators to Wald Stadium here, the Galaxy
will face the Rhine Fire from Duesseldorf in the National Football
League's European title game, known as the World Bowl. If things go
well, Bailey has a chance of being signed by an NFL team at home.
If they don't, he plans to hang up his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday will also be important for the NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after the National Football League reorganized and
relaunched what used to be called the World League, the title game
is expected to attract more spectators than any game yet.
</P>
<P>
   But American football has been a hard sell in Europe, and with
the exception of Germany, where U.S. military bases helped spark an
interest in American sports, the game is catching on very slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In Frankfurt, which was surrounded by U.S. Air Force and Army
bases throughout the Cold War and still has a big American
population, the Galaxy draws about 30,000 spectators a game.
Indeed, team officials say the German teams are making a profit and
they draw heavy attention from local radio and newspapers. SAT 1, a
national television network, now broadcasts a weekly half-hour
program of Galaxy highlights.
</P>
<P>
   But the other teams _ the Barcelona Dragons, the London
Monarchs, the Amsterdam Admirals and the Edinburgh Claymores _ have
had more trouble. Attendance in those cities is less than 10,000 a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest challenge is to put down roots,'' said Oliver
Luck, president of the NFL Europe and a former quarterback for the
Houston Oilers. ``We need the average guy in the street to care
about what happens to his team. We need people to have emotional
involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been progress. Luck said that league revenues _ from
ticket sales, television rights and sponsorships _ climbed about 70
percent this year to $20 million. That is still in the red, and
Luck said he did not expect the league to make a profit for another
three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   The losses are made up by the NFL franchises in the United
States, which view the NFL Europe partly as a farm league and
partly as a potential source of future income.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the obvious cultural barriers, both players and
executives say the league is struggling between conflicting goals.
On the one hand, the league wants high-caliber play, but that means
relying heavily on American players, who tend not to stay as long.
On the other hand, league officials want to foster fan loyalty,
which would mean using more local players whom the fans could
identify with more easily than an American who drops in for a year
or two.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American players overwhelmingly outnumber local players and
receive the lion's share of glory. There are no European
quarterbacks in the NFL Europe, and it is rare to have even two
European players on the field at one time.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, many of the best American players are athletes
who are already under contract with NFL teams in the United States,
and those athletes usually return to those teams after one or two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to alleviate the problem, the NFL Europe requires
that at least seven out of 45 players on each roster come from the
home country. The teams are also required to have at least one
national player on the field during every other series of plays.
</P>
<P>
   In another tactic to boost the role of local players, Luck has
actively recruited a number of well-known but retired soccer
players for the role of kicker. The most famous example is Manfred
Burgsmueller, now 49, who was the fourth-leading scorer in
Germany's soccer league. Burgsmueller has been the Rhein Fire's
kicker for three years now.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the problems, many American players say playing in
Europe is better than sitting on a bench in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get into any regular-season games,'' said Damon
Huard, the 24-year-old quarterback for the Galaxy who is injured
and will not play Sunday. He was allocated to the league from the
Miami Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get more game time here, and there's no substitute for
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not here for the money, you're here for the work and
the chance to polish your game. If you're dream is to play in the
NFL there aren't too many ways to get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
