<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/13/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 13, 1998 -- NY-CHINESE-THEATER, 6-13 --
The Music Palace, New York's last Chinese-language theater, in
Chinatown, is set to be demolished and replaced by an office
building. Like many newcomers, immigrants from China once relied on
movies in their native tongue as a bridge between old country and
new. As the immigrants became more familiar with their adopted
country, their adopted country became more comfortable with them.
And eventually, the specialty theaters lost much of their
relevance. The growing popularity of videotapes is partly to blame,
along with Chinese cable television programs. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BELFAST, Northern Ireland -- June 13, 1998 --
NIRELAND-PEACE, 6-13 -- Protestants and Catholics are cautiously
adjusting to the idea of a lasting peace in Northern Ireland. A
loyalist mural on the Shankill Road in the heart of Protestant West
Belfast serves as a reminder of the long conflict. Some experts
emphasize that justifiable hope must still be tempered with
skepticism -- that if the politicians do not move ahead toward new
governmental panels to carry out the agreement, voters -- and
gunners -- could change their minds. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SALT LAKE CITY -- June 13, 1998 -- BAPTIST-MORMONS, 6-13
-- Southern Baptist students praying before going door-to-door to
bring their message to a neighborhood in Salt Lake City. While
holding their annual convention here last week, about 3,000
volunteers also began a weeklong effort to bring an evangelical
Protestant message to the 2 million inhabitants of Greater Salt
Lake, Mormon and non-Mormon alike. Conversions topped 1,000 after a
week of effort by the volunteers. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) TAMPA, Fla. -- June 13, 1998 -- VOLUNTEER-POWELL, 6-13 --
Colin Powell, the retired general and former chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, talking to supporters in Tampa. Powell, now the
unpaid leader of America's Promise, a volunteer organization that
benefits youths at risk of a wayward life, travels throughout the
U.S. singing the effort's praises. Powell, who often cites figures
showing that 15 million children are at risk of following a wayward
path, says he took on the mission to help steer them away from
trouble because there is no greater obligation than helping young
people on society's margins. (Phillippe Diederich/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- June 13, 1998 --
CALIF-BILINGUAL-FOE, 6-13 -- Ron Unz, 36, left, the man who beat
bilingual education in the nation's most populous state with
Proposition 227, with an acquaintance. Unz, who owns a software
company in the Silicon Valley, does not have a particularly strong
personal connection to the issue of bilingual education. Unz,
unmarried and childless and has never set foot in a bilingual
classroom. Unz says he is driven by a pure conviction that
bilingual education, as a method of acclimating children into
English, defies both logic and test scores, and that the current
system is flawed. ``It's nice to be able to fix broken things,'' he
says. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHAKOTHI, Kashmir -- June 13, 1998 --
KASHMIR-CONTROVERSY, 6-13 -- Brig. Haider Khan, who commands
Pakistani troops in the Jhelum River valley, tracks Indian troops
in the mountains behind him every day. ``This is very tough
terrain,'' he says, pointing from his bunker to an Indian strong
point. ``Good for the defense.'' For Pakistan, the subcontinent's
nuclear arms race and the attendant hand-wringing by the great
powers has brought an unexpected boon: Kashmir, a cause
long-forgotten by the world, has suddenly moved to the top of the
international agenda. (John Kifner/New York Times Photo) (See also
BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SRINAGAR, Kasmir -- June 13, 1998 -- INDIA-PAKISTAN, 6-13
-- Gujar nomads in Srinagar, the capital of Indian-controlled
Kashmir. With a relaxation of military tensions in the divided
state, nomad families are returning more frequently to mountain
pastures with their herds. (John F. Burns/New York Times Photo)
(See also BC-KASHMIR-CONTROVERSY-NYT)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BRIDGEVIEW, Ill. -- June 13, 1998 -- ILL-HAMAS-SUSPECT,
6-13 -- Fadi Zanayed, speaking at a rally for Mohammed Salah,
suspected of illegally financing the terrorist organization Hamas,
in Bridgeview. Salah's niece, far left, and three children also
attended the rally. Prosecutors have not charged Salah with a
crime, but law enforcement officials say their investigation could
lead to his indictment and that they have evidence that accounts in
seven Illinois financial institutions worth nearly $1.5 million,
are being used illegally by Salah to underwrite the Hamas war of
terror. (Lloyd DeGrane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
