<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METACOMET-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: CONNECTICUT TOWNS IMPLEMENT RIDGE-LINE DEVELOPMENT
LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELEANOR CHARLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Traveling along Interstate 91, some motorists tend to
slow down as they gaze at the 44 mountains that pass through 30
communities along the central corridor of Connecticut from the
Massachusetts border almost to Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic gesture to cooperate in the preservation of these
mountains, called the Trap Rock Ridges, 17 towns in their path
signed an agreement called the Metacomet Ridge Conservation Compact
last April 22, Earth Day.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily wooded and largely inaccessible, most of the ridges are
undeveloped, visited only by intrepid hikers on the Metacomet and
Mattabesett Trails along the crest. That dry, rocky environment is
home to the rare electric blue skink lizard, the falcate
orange-tipped butterfly, prickly pear cactus, stands of Torrey's
mountain mint and delicate purple hair grass.
</P>
<P>
   Recently the relentless push of housing development has begun
creeping up some of the mountains, sending the towns scrambling to
implement a 1995 state law allowing them to restrict development on
the ridges. The measure was co-sponsored by Rep. Mary Mushinsky of
Wallingford and State Sen. Thomas Gaffey of Meriden, both
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Several towns have worked on new regulations, and among the
compact towns Meriden, Durham, Berlin, Simsbury, Middletown and
Farmington have passed or are in the process of passing zoning that
limits or prohibits development within 150 feet of the tops of the
ridges.
</P>
<P>
   But before the regulations can be enforced maps must be drawn
detailing how and where development, clear-cutting of vegetation
and any new quarrying operations are to be restricted or
prohibited. Existing quarries are not affected.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the 17 compact communities _ Branford, North
Branford, Guilford, East Haven, Wallingford, Middlefield,
Plainville, West Hartford, Avon, Suffield and Bloomfield _ are
still wrestling with zoning proposals or adding to existing
limitations along their ridge lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encourage the towns to do what they can, whether through
purchase, regulations or donations,'' said Norman Zimmer, author of
the compact and a member of the Meriden Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, royalty and wealthy individuals have favored the
tops of mountains as strategic and awe-inspiring sites for castles,
fortifications and baronial mansions. But these ridges, said
Zimmer, ``must be preserved esthetically and recreationally''
because ``they are the Central Park of Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the ridges, said Mushinsky, ``goes back to
the dinosaur era, when they were formed. They rise above the rest
of the state _ a continuous series of parallel basalt ridges, which
at one time were lava. One side is a sheer scarp, the other side is
a slope, but rocky and difficult to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   The name trap rock, she believes, evolved from a Swedish word
trappa, meaning step, describing the configurations that formed
layers of basalt in the Jurassic and Triassic periods.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 1900EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7973 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-METACOMET-REAL-2NDTAK     06-13 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METACOMET-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
NEW YORK: Triassic periods. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What triggered the legislation,'' she said, ``was one
landowner who wanted to put his foundation right on a section of
Connecticut's Blue Trail system.'' Existing development on the
ridges varies widely from none at all in Meriden, which is
surrounded by seven ridges, to about 30 homes built over several
years on Avon's ridges, where 10 additional houses have been
approved for construction and an additional eight are in the
approvals pipeline. They will be priced from $800,000 to $3
million. Stephen Kushner, Avon's town planner, said that the views
justified the prices.
</P>
<P>
   So far, restrictive measures have been hailed by townspeople who
regard the majestic chains of mountains as among their most
precious assets. In addition, ``they are major water-recharge
areas,'' said Zimmer. ``Water percolates down through the ridges to
reservoirs at the base of the mountains,'' he said, adding that
development could contaminate the water.
</P>
<P>
   But the new rulings are causing confusion and resentment among
individual ridge-land owners and developers who contend that their
holdings are being rendered worthless. Contractors, too, who have
been mining the century-old ridge quarries, crushing the rock to
build roads, houses, hospitals, storm sewers, schools and an
endless array of construction projects are suddenly concerned about
future supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stone that's mined in Connecticut, Massachusetts and New
Hampshire is the best in the world,'' said Joseph LaRosa, owner of
LaRosa Construction in Meriden. ``Perhaps they could designate
certain areas for new quarries'' _ a practice, quarriers say, that
has been followed in some Western states.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Francoline, a developer in Avon and chairman of the
Connecticut Developers' Council, is concerned that ``building
materials in this part of the country are extremely expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it will be a lot more expensive,'' he said, ``to bring
stone in from elsewhere, adding to fuel consumption and
pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   Meriden's City Council approved the new zoning last year, based
on a model set of regulations that conforms to the 1995 state
statute and was distributed to all the towns. But the city's
Planning and Zoning Commission rejected the Council's map of some
30 affected properties, the final step required to put the
regulations into practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stated that we ought to work on compensation for property
owners,'' said Stephen Zerio, chairman of the Economic Development
Committee of the Council.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation promises to be a major bone of contention. ``I need
to be compensated for five acres on which I pay $350 a year in
taxes,'' said Ross Gulino, a landowner and developer. Taxes on
undeveloped ridge land in Meriden, designated by the town as excess
land, are extremely low. and levied at a fraction of the full rate.
Assessor Steven Hodgetts said ``one person is paying $25 a year on
three acres, another with 315 acres is paying $14.50 an acre,'' or
$4,567.50.
</P>
<P>
   Gulino contends that ``pretty much all'' of his five acres are
within 150 feet of the top. ``I planned to market it as a single
lot or maybe three lots,'' he said. ``If the legislation goes
through I will wind up with 50 feet or less, not enough to build
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, as vice president of BRG Realty, a family-owned firm,
he was a principal in the purchase of a predeveloped subdivision of
40 lots on 41 acres at the base of the mountain, plus the remainder
of the slope including the top parcel. Fifteen lots at the base
sold for $60,000 to $100,000 each. ``Lots at the top would have
added value because of the view,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline Travers, a Meriden widow with 20 acres, lives on the
lower half. The rest is within 150 feet of the summit. The new
zoning, she said, ``will devalue my land _ it won't be very salable
for me or my children.'' Disturbed by what she perceives as
insensitivity on the part of thousands of people who favor the new
zoning, she said ``they don't own _ they just like to look at the
view.'' No doubt a protracted period of adjustment and probably a
spate of lawsuits is in store as the various towns struggle to
create regulations that will pass muster at the state level. Of the
towns that adopted new zoning, Berlin does not allow quarrying and
prohibits development higher than 350 feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   Simsbury does not allow clear-cutting and requires replacement
of trees in some cases, and Middletown may limit houses to one
story or require moving them to lower ground if they interfere with
views of the ridge line. Farmington, where development has produced
some clear-cutting and ``houses that stick out when you look up at
the ridge,'' according to Elizabeth Dolphin, assistant planning
director, is trying to deal with existing regulations that have
produced disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Branse, a Glastonbury lawyer who drew up the model
regulations for the 17 compact towns, said that most of the
confusion comes from flawed interpretations of the model and
ignorance of the state statute. On the subject of compensation, he
said:
</P>
<P>
   ``General law states that government may regulate land use to
protect the public welfare, but it cannot regulate it down to where
it has no value. Any regulation will cause diminution of value.
What is reasonable is what courts debate regularly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers of ridge land knew it was difficult to get up there and
to build on it,'' he continued. ``However, the regulations allow
what is deemed reasonable use of the property so as not to make it
worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Gulino, he indicated that the courts might not
sanction compensation for losing the use of one piece of property
when the owner has sufficient property nearby that is viable and
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state statute only allows restriction,'' said Terry
Tondro, professor of law at the University of Connecticut. ``If a
town had a flat prohibition, affected landowners could go to the
state statute, which takes precedence. The statute was designed to
protect ridge lines, using the word restrict rather than
prohibit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of zoning is not the maximum enrichment of property
owners,'' said Branse, paraphrasing a Connecticut Supreme Court
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
