<HEADER>
A7975 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORD-PLANTATION-REAL-     06-13 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-PLANTATION-REAL-750(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C., R.I.)  
 A FORD IN ITS PAST, A RESORT IN ITS FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND HILL, Ga. _ Henry Ford came to a spit of land on the
Ogeechee River here nearly 75 years ago, and nothing has been the
same since.
</P>
<P>
   He bought every house and parcel he could, assembling some
70,000 acres on which to build a grand manor beside a bend in the
river, 14 miles from the Atlantic Ocean and 23 miles south of
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Then 65 and a millionaire many times over, Ford transformed a
malaria-infested backwater village known as a moonshine haven into
a prosperous town with healthy residents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a group of local investors has bought the 1,800 acres left
of Ford's estate (most of the original estate was sold to timber
companies) with the intention of developing a second-home resort
community. The emphasis will be on boating and golfing, and there
will be artists in residence to help home buyers pursue creative
hobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Bluff Associates, a South Carolina investment group,
bought the property in March for $47 million from InterRedec, a
holding company once controlled by Ghaith Pharaon. In 1991,
Pharaon, of Saudi Arabia, was indicted in Washington, D.C., on
federal charges of fraud and racketeering relating to the Bank of
Credit and Commerce International scandal. He has never been tried
and remains a fugitive. Authorities believe he is in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Two principals in Sterling Bluff Associates are Peter Pollack
and William Dolan, who engineered a dramatic turnaround for Brays
Island, a former plantation turned resort near Beaufort, S.C., that
teetered on the brink of failure. They repositioned that property
as a hunting and sporting enclave and sold 265 lots in 18 months
for a total of $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the Ford Plantation development, Pollack and Dolan brought
in as their third director Stephen Schram, a former co-chairman of
the Boston Celtics who owns property at Brays Island.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly real estate salesmen on Hilton Head Island, S.C.,
Pollack and Dolan said they hoped to make careers of redeveloping
some of the former rice plantations left along the South Carolina
and Georgia coasts, many of which still belong to descendants of
the nation's great industrialists.
</P>
<P>
   Some that remain include the 18,000-acre Goodhope Plantation,
owned by the Pratt family (whose ancestor, John Pratt, was a
partner of John D. Rockefeller in Standard Oil of Ohio, now Exxon)
and Broad River, owned by the Marshall Field family. The DuPonts
still own property on the Coosaw River, while the Guggenheims own a
hunting camp in Yemassee, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Still standing on the Ford property is a rustic hunting lodge
that the auto manufacturer had built in a day at the suggestion of
his friend, Harvey Firestone, the tiremaker.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-hole golf course was built by InterRedec 13 years ago for
$11 million. Designed by Pete Dye, it has never before been played
by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Some 35 bungalows, with prices starting at $650,000, will be
built beside the golf course. At the yacht basin installed to moor
Ford's cabin cruiser, Little Lulu _ made in the Ford carpentry shop
here, town houses will be built to mimic a Savannah square. In all,
60 will be built with prices at about $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred lots of two to six acres will cost from $300,000 to
$1 million depending on their proximity to the river. With the lot
will come a topographic and tree survey. Deed restrictions
stipulate that a house must be sited with an eye toward
conservation. The main house may not exceed 6,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   But, Pollack said, he did not expect size to be the governing
factor among his buyers. ``It's quality people want,'' he
explained, adding that 90 percent of the home sites would have
water views.
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between this development and Brays Island is
the partnership's plan to offer all ranges of home-building
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come down here they're scared to death about what
builder to get,'' said Dolan.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership hired Daniel G. Paquette to oversee the building
program. Paquette worked for 25 years on a host of restoration
projects in Newport, R.I., including the landmark Redwood Library
and Trinity Church, the latter overlooking Newport Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Home design will be overseen by a review board. Paquette said
homes would be expected to be ``sympathetic'' to Lowcountry
Georgian homes but not replicas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to respect the indigenous architecture but fit this
time,'' he said. ``We also have a burning desire to maintain the
parklike significance that exists here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lots will go one sale next month.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1500s, the pine thickets here at Ogeechee Neck have
been inhabited first by explorers from Spain, then France and
finally England. Eventually, the land would become the site of
Revolutionary War skirmishes and later a rice plantation.
</P>
<P>
   During the Civil War, Gen. William T. Sherman in his ``march to
the sea'' destroyed the plantation homes and rice mills along the
Ogeechee. But the avenue of live oaks survived the fires, and the
huge trees still line the drive to the main house that Ford and his
wife, Clara, built in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Ford owned 31 automobile assembly plants, as well
as mines and timberlands, and employed nearly half a million
people. Ford Motor Co. made not only cars but also aircraft. He
selected this obscure site as his winter home because he had what
he thought was a better idea for rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone wanted to find a way to make rubber from
lettuce, which they knew would grow well here in the humid,
tropical climate. The two feared the British would corner the
rubber market and drive prices higher than they wanted to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Thomas A. Edison, they founded the Edison Botanic
Research Co. in Florida and later relocated it here on the
Ogeechee. By 1925, Ford began buying land here and lobbied to have
the town, then called Ways Station, renamed Richmond Hill _
combining the names of two plantations that he purchased, Richmond
and Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   He dispatched doctors and nurses to cure malaria, hookworm,
typhoid and diphtheria among residents. He worked with drainage
specialists to eradicate swamps where insects bred disease. Then he
turned his attention to educating the people of the area. He
established schools for boys and girls alike to teach them
academics and a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Local girls worked in the Community House, where they learned
homemaking, cooking housekeeping and how to play hostess and took
dancing lessons as well. Built in 1937, the structure now houses a
funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who was a teetotaler, destroyed 250 stills in this area
known for its fine moonshine and built a sawmill and timber
operation where stills once stood. He built his employees houses in
the town, which today has a worn look despite the rapidly
developing residential subdivisions surrounding it. The area serves
as a suburb for Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, the Fords decided to build a house on the Ogeechee.
They paid $10,000 for a nearby plantation house, destroyed it and
used the bricks to build a two-story Georgian mansion with gracious
white columns. Historians in staid Savannah fought the demolition
but in the end, Ford won with a promise of an even grander home. It
was finished in 1938, and 55 surrounding acres were landscaped.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Bluff Associates intends to use the manor as guest
rooms for property owners and for a dining area. In the kitchen
will be a chef from 45 South, one of Savannah's finer restaurants.
to run the food operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of people here whose parents or
grandparents worked for Henry Ford,'' said Dolan, the Sterling
Bluff Associates principal. ``The mayor's dad is one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
