<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RICH-TEX     06-13 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RICH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPARITY BETWEEN BASEBALL'S RICH AND POOR TEAMS CONTINUES TO GROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos are less than three weeks from their
self-appointed D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   Club president Claud Brochu has set June 30 as the deadline for
raising $250 million to build a downtown stadium. If a sufficient
number of luxury boxes and personal seat licenses aren't sold by
then, Brochu is threatening to sell the team to U.S. investors who
plan to move it to northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if the Pittsburgh Pirates, Minnesota Twins or Oakland
Athletics don't get there first. Baseball's economic turmoil is
liable to lead to a major collision of moving vans somewhere along
the Washington, D.C.-area Beltway in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about that,'' interim commissioner Bud Selig
said. ``We're very proud of the fact we haven't had a team move in
27 years, but, as I've said many times, you can't consign a team to
economic bankruptcy. We're going to try to make things work. But if
we have to move a club because they can't compete economically,
then we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While meeting in Seattle last week, major-league baseball owners
needed only a few minutes to unanimously approve Tom Hicks as owner
of the Rangers. They spent much more time discussing the
ever-widening gap between the haves and the have-nots among
major-league franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Although Selig might profess a lack of concern, any fan
following a have-not team has plenty of concern. In the past three
years, teams with the highest payrolls have dominated baseball. Of
the teams that had the top four payrolls each of the past three
years, all but one reached the playoffs. This year, at the end of
May, 14 teams had more victories than losses. Eleven of those teams
were among the top 15 teams in salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a continuing problem in baseball,'' National League
president Leonard Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Brochu: ``Something has to be done because it's getting
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's only solution appears to be an all-out assault on
local taxpayer pocketbooks for the money to build ballparks. Those
who succeed expect to repeat the miracle in Cleveland, where Jacobs
Field turned a derelict franchise into a financial powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, people will have to have that type of facility
to have a realistic chance of competing,'' Rangers president Tom
Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Those having trouble convincing the local voters and politicos
immediately threaten a move to North Carolina, northern Virginia or
even Portland, Ore. where officials are mulling the possibility of
renovating a 70-year-old minor-league stadium to lure a
major-league franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles average 44,774 spectators per game at
Oriole Park at Camden Yards and can afford a $74.3 million payroll,
highest in baseball. The New York Yankees get $48.6 million a year
in local broadcasting revenues and have a $70.6 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Montreal Expos average 10,661 fans in cold,
barren Olympic Stadium and net about $2 million a year in local
broadcasting revenues. Their payroll is at a major-league-low $16
million, and they regularly trade their highest-paid players.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles owner Peter Angelos, while looking at a model of
Seattle's future stadium last week, said: ``If you have a facility
such as this, your success is pretty much assured, assuming the
demographics are there as well. Without that facility, there's no
way you can compete with teams that have them. But there has to be
a willingness in the community to build that facility. The
economics of baseball won't allow a franchise to build that
facility themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Prospective Florida Marlins owner Don Smiley said the club can't
survive in South Florida without a stadium with a retractable roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no future in operating a ballclub under these
circumstances,'' Smiley said. ``Sooner or later, fans won't put up
with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners are also trying other avenues to deal with skyrocketing
payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue sharing will transfer $125 million to $140 million from
the top six clubs to the bottom six the next two years. Baseball
continues to explore international marketing and broadcasting
opportunities, revenues that would be shared by all clubs. Clubs
are also allowed to go public with stock offerings, and the
Cleveland Indians, despite the success of Jacobs Field, were the
first to do so. Rangers owner Tom Hicks has said he is considering
such a move.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as the Yankees can pull in $48.6 million annually in
local television revenues and not have to share it with anyone,
they'll have a significant competitive advantage on the rest of
baseball. Other owners can only shudder at what might happen if
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner can persuade New York to build
him a $1 billion ballpark in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not deep pockets,'' Mariners chairman John Ellis
said. ``The issue is finding some way to get more parity in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brochu knows that even if he gets his 35,000-seat stadium,
there's no way he'll be able to compete with the Yankees for free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is we'll be able to keep our own players,''
Brochu said.
</P>
<P>
   The selling point for cities is the economic value that
ballparks bring to surrounding areas, especially downtown areas hit
hard by urban blight. Jacobs Field is a major centerpiece in the
renaissance of downtown Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Chema, executive director of the organization that oversaw
the building of Jacobs Field, said: ``In just admission tax, the
city of Cleveland on Jacobs Field had something in excess of $4
million in the general revenue fund last year. So there are ways to
measure the impact, and it is substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   But new ballparks aren't always the cure-all they're promised to
be. The Mariners are scheduled to move into their new ballpark next
year, but ``The Seattle Times'' has reported that the club will get
stuck for $70 million to $100 million in cost overruns. That can
eat into profits quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants are hoping for a bonanza from their
ballpark, scheduled to open in 2000. But they must first pay off
the $160 million loan on the place, and they're already borrowing
money to meet their payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox moved into the new Comiskey Park in 1991
and drew almost 3 million fans the first year. Now, they're
averaging 15,289 spectators per game and the stadium looks severely
outdated next to the architecturally inspired Camden Yards, Coors
Field and The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   It's also getting more difficult to convince voters to approve
hundreds of millions of dollars for new facilities, even though
Angelos and Schieffer insist that they can have major benefits to a
community.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area turned down the Giants on four referendums before
the club turned to private financing. Pittsburgh rejected a
publicly financed stadium last year, and the Minnesota Legislature
has thwarted all attempts by the Twins for a new ballpark. The
Marlins failed to stir interest in Miami, even after winning a
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the big-market clubs have a stunning change of heart
and agree to complete revenue sharing, struggling owners in
small-market towns feel they have no choice but to go begging for
new ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a utopia to solve all problems, but it's a must,''
Selig said. ``You're not going to change the media revenue streams,
but you have to change the game revenues. If you're playing in an
old ballpark, you negate the opportunity for new revenue streams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
