<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRICEY-HOMES-REAL-850     06-13 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRICEY-HOMES-REAL-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOME AREAS $1 MILLION HOMES ARE BECOMING COMMONPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LISA PREVOST   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The million-dollar home _ a phrase that not long ago summoned up
images of mansions and perhaps even liveried servants _ has become
so commonplace in the most affluent New York suburbs that in some
communities more than half the homes now on the market are priced
above $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   A $1 million price tag, brokers say, no longer necessarily
implies luxury living. Rather, a $1 million house in some areas is
almost, well, ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the most sought-after sections of Greenwich, Conn.,
such as Belle Haven and Round Hill, $1 million is now considered
entry level, said Susan Hughes, vice president of David Ogilvy &AMP;
Associates and president of the Greenwich Association of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   James W. Hughes, dean of the Edward J. Bloustein School of
Planning and Public Policy at Rutgers University, describes the
phenomenon as a ``crowding into the winner's circle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving the market are baby boomers, who are entering their
peak earning years, raising families, and settling into the
communities where they want to be for the long haul,'' said Hughes,
who is not related to Susan Hughes. ``And so they're bidding up
prices in these areas.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While new luxury-home developments are common now throughout the
region, the proportion of $1 million-plus properties is still small
in most towns. But in a few areas, primarily those with established
reputations as comfortable havens for the well-to-do, sales of
homes for $1 million or more make up an increasingly significant
chunk of the market.
</P>
<P>
   These areas include Greenwich, New Canaan, Westport and Darien
in Connecticut; parts of Westchester County, including Scarsdale,
Rye and Larchmont; on Long Island, the villages on Nassau County's
North Shore, as well as the Hamptons in Suffolk County; portions of
central New Jersey, including Far Hills, Harding Township,
Bernardsville and Mendham Township, and the Saddle River area in
Bergen County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what you're talking about is supply and demand,''
said Mrs. Hughes. ``There is such a demand for large family homes
with certain amenities that it pokes the prices up. And because
land prices are so high, people are also building larger homes and
expanding homes, so the high-end stock is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reflection primarily of the tremendous rise of value in
the stock market,'' said Lee E. Koppelman, director of the Center
for Regional Policy Studies at the State University of New York at
Stony Brook.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for high-end housing in the suburbs is even more
pronounced now than it was during the region's last period of great
prosperity between 1979 and 1985, he said. And the high cost of
housing in Manhattan is a contributing factor. For those with $1
million or more to spend on housing, Koppelman said, ``it does
occur to people that they'll get an even bigger bang for their buck
by investing in an estate property in the suburbs.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward buying more costly and larger homes appears to
have gained momentum. In Greenwich, for example, the average
selling time for houses priced between $1 million and $1.9 million
has dropped 40 percent since last year, to just 86 days, according
to Nancy A. MacDonald, manager of the Greenwich office of William
Pitt Real Estate. For houses priced above $2 million, the sale time
is down 30 percent, to 185 days, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of 1998, 49 homes sold for $1 million or
more in Greenwich, about 30 percent of all homes sold, according to
figures compiled by William Pitt. Ten years ago, only 17 homes, or
18 percent of first-quarter sales, were sold for more than $1
million. In 1984, the $1 million-plus percentage was zero in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I maintain that if you bought a house in Greenwich in the
early '80s, that was terrific,'' said Ms. MacDonald. ``If you
purchased for $200,000, $250,000 you could probably get $1.5
million for that house. And that's pretty darn good.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceiling on prices is lifting as well. A 24-room mansion on
the Greenwich waterfront sold this year for a record $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion, called Haroldlyn Manor, is a Georgian-style house
with a private yacht mooring on six acres. It was once a summer
home for Donald Trump, who purchased it for $3.7 million in 1984,
according to the Greenwich Town Assessor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A million dollars will buy you a comfortable family house in
Greenwich, but nothing fancy, nothing with extravagant amenities,''
said Mrs. Hughes. ``The fancy bedrooms, a finer kitchen, a very
large family room _ houses with these things are generally not
available under $1.4 million.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite the cost, houses just keep getting bigger,
noted Bernard Yudain, a longtime Greenwich resident who is a
columnist for the Greenwich Time newspaper. ``Even some of the big
old houses were never this big,'' he said. ``There used to be more
of a sense of proportion of house to lot size. Now we're seeing
huge houses on relatively small lots. I said the other day,
jokingly, that some of these buyers are bringing the wrecking ball
people to the closing with them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday the Representative Town Meeting, citing concerns
about ``oversized houses,'' passed a resolution urging the Town
Planning and Zoning Commission to give the highest priority to
amending building and zoning regulations to develop ``appropriate''
floor-area ratios, lot sizes, coverage and setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwich is not the only affluent town where the wrecking ball
has been swinging. ``Fifty percent of buyers are looking for what's
here,'' said Joan Quigg, owner of Joan Quigg Realtors in Saddle
River. ``The other 50 percent is looking for what they can knock
down. That wonderful, classic Saddle River look, which was so
understated _ well, all that is now to buyers is just a beautiful
piece of land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very demanding,'' she added. ``They want high
ceilings, and a very, very good kitchen _ whether they do takeout
for the rest of their lives, it doesn't matter. They want a
wonderful master bedroom and bath, and a great room off the
kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half the 53 properties currently on the market in
Saddle River are priced above $1 million. The shift toward more $1
million homes began in the 80's in Saddle River, Ms. Quigg said,
but then stopped during the economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
   The market picked up again in 1994, and has climbed upward
since, she said. Last year, the New Jersey Multiple Listing Service
recorded 25 sales above $1 million in Saddle River; according to
Ms. Quigg, as of May 31 this year, 13 had already sold in that
category. And new homes in Saddle River are selling for closer to
$2 million, she said. .
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, these buyers are making what Ms. Quigg described
as ``the leap to the big house.'' That is because, according to
brokers, the typical high-end buyers in the suburbs these days are
two-income couples with young children. And often they are
purchasing their first home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me my borrowers are getting younger,'' said Craig
Atkinson, a senior financial services officer with Sterling Capital
in Stamford. ``I'm amazed that people in their early 30s are buying
$1 million homes.''
</P>
<P>
   On a $1 million house, the usual loan amount would be about
$750,000, Atkinson said. ``The mortgage interest deduction is about
the only tax deduction any of us have anymore, so a lot of buyers
like to maximize the mortgage amount,'' he said, noting that
exceptions are often made to allow a mortgage of up to 80 percent
of the sale price for customers with adequate assets and income.
</P>
<P>
   The monthly payment on a $750,000 mortgage at a fixed, 30-year
rate of 7.375 percent, said Atkinson, is $5,180, $4,500 of which is
initially deductible as interest. Buyers who opt for an
adjustable-rate mortgage at a 6.625 interest rate for the first
five years pay $4,802 a month, he said, about $4,080 of which is
deductible.
</P>
<P>
   Customers rarely borrow more than $1 million, Atkinson said,
because the maximum deduction allowed is interest accrued on a $1
million mortgage. An additional deduction is allowed for interest
on a second mortgage of up to $100,000. ``A lot of the really big
deals get done in cash or through private loans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All-cash deals are sometimes used as a negotiating tactic,
according to Sheila Rice, director of the Fine Homes Division of
Prudential Long Island Realty. Buyers offer to pay in cash as an
incentive for the seller to come down on the price. Once the deal
goes through, she said, they often refinance.
</P>
<P>
   The high-end market in her North Shore territory, which includes
both horse country and beach communities, is enjoying a tremendous
upswing after an extended slump that lasted well into 1996. ``Then,
you could list a home at $1.7 million and it would sell for under a
million,'' Mrs. Rice said. But prices are recovering rapidly, she
noted.
</P>
<P>
   According to data compiled by Prudential, as of June 1, 14
houses had sold for at least $1 million this year in the villages
of Brookville, Old Brookville, Upper Brookville, Matinecock, Mill
Neck, Muttontown, Lattingtown, Laurel Hollow, Lloyd Harbor, Lloyd
Neck, and Oyster Bay Cove. An additional 36 listed in that price
range are under contract, Mrs. Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Should they all come in at more than $1 million, she said, the
five-month total will have already surpassed the 1997 year-end
figure of 44 million-dollar sales. In the majority of the villages,
more than half the inventory is currently priced above $1 million,
she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Though the hamlet of Locust Valley in the town of Oyster Bay is
often perceived as the center of wealth on the North Shore, Mrs.
Rice pointed out that some of the most expensive homes in the area
are found in Lattingtown, the Brookvilles and Muttontown.
Generally, she said, the closer to Long Island Sound, the higher
the home prices.
</P>
<P>
   Million-dollar bank investment properties are moving
particularly quickly, she noted, because ``buyers think they're
getting a bargain on foreclosures.'' A recent example was a
12-year-old contemporary in Oyster Bay Cove with peeling paint, an
overgrown yard and a pool full of murky green water. A foreclosure
listed at $1.199 million, the property sold in a single weekend.
</P>
<P>
   North Shore properties often come with two or more acres of
land. In contrast, a half-acre is ``a lot of land'' in the $1
million-plus market in Scarsdale, said Joan Frederick, an associate
broker in the Scarsdale office of Julia B. Fee. A couple of new
five-bedroom homes going up on .33-acre lots in the Fox Meadow
neighborhood close to the village center in Scarsdale recently
listed at $1.375 million. In portions of the Heathcote section,
which is less densely developed, one-acre lots alone start at $1
million, according to Mrs. Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   Prices fluctuate on either side of the million-dollar mark in
the older neighborhoods of Edgewood, Fox Meadow and Green Acres,
depending on how well the houses have been maintained and the
degree to which they have been updated.
</P>
<P>
   One five-bedroom brick colonial in Green Acres went on the
market earlier this year for $1.075 million on a street where
houses generally sell for $700,000 to $1 million, Mrs. Frederick
said. The 80-year-old house showed so well that the owners received
multiple offers and wound up getting $1.202 million. In 1984, the
same house sold for $510,000, according to Mrs. Frederick.
</P>
<P>
   About a quarter of the homes now on the market in Scarsdale, or
45 houses, are priced above $1 million. The number of $1
million-plus sales began climbing in 1994, when 22 homes sold in
that price range. Last year the number was 33, and this year, as of
May 27, 25 homes had already sold at more than $1 million each,
Mrs. Frederick said.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan is also experiencing an upswing this year, in what was
already a heady high-end market. ``Increasingly, when you're
talking about the $1 million market, you're talking about every
part of Manhattan,'' noted Frederick W. Peters, president of
Ashforth, Warburg Associates, a Manhattan real estate brokerage.
``A spacious three-bedroom apartment can run you $1 million on
110th and Riverside. And certainly there are any number of
2,500-square-foot lofts that can run you $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters said that $1 million-plus sales by his brokers in the
first four months of 1998 on the East and West Sides and downtown
indicate that if the current pace continues, volume in that market
could be up as much as 80 percent by the year's end.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lawrence Sicular, a broker and appraiser for Brown
Harris Stevens, the $1 million market currently accounts for 37
percent of all sales on the Upper East Side and Central Park West.
That is up from 33 percent in 1997, and 25 percent in 1996. ``It's
a strong but conservative market,'' he noted. ``So the biggest
price increases are for the best located and largest apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of properties selling for $1 million or more in
the suburbs. In Greenwich, according to Ms. MacDonald of William
Pitt, a home that recently sold in the prestigious shore community
of Belle Haven was snapped up almost immediately, despite a price
that would once have been daunting even by Fairfield County
shorefront standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people had been in the house for 40 years,'' she said.
``It was incredible waterfront property. They probably paid
$50,000, if that, and they were holding out for $3 million. I'm
sure they got close to that, if not that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
