<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7993 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS &LR;      06-13 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: New Jazz attitude brings site change
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ So Dennis Rodman gets to return to the state of
his discomfort, which is Utah or anyplace where you are expected to
act like something other than a calculated nitwit.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan gets to return to that swank hotel suite where he
and Ahmad can sit side by side on the piano bench and tickle the
ivories. Perhaps a little travelin' music.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bulls, it means packing up the tattooed man/lady, the
round, rumply, evil general manager, the whining, condescending,
manipulative coach and going back out on the road, which is where
you expect to find a three-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   For the Jazz, it's Home Malone.
</P>
<P>
   That short. That simple. It's all the men in purple ever wanted
out of their return engagement to the NBA Finals, a chance to get
His Airness and all of his court jesters back onto their home
floor, amid the din of the loudest arena on the planet, and take
their chances.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly things change.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight hours earlier, the confetti, balloons and
scaffolding for the portable stage were in place at the United
Center for another celebration of America's reigning sports dynasty
and all of the wretched excess it has come to symbolize.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after turbulence in the air on the way to the victory
party, we check in our bags at the Delta Center as the Jazz tries
to keep us all in our seats with the safety belts fastened on the
way to a Game 7 landing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mailman finally delivers with 39 points and instead of smoke
from the traditional victory fires, all that hung in the air of
Chicago was the haunting, taped voice of Frank Sinatra singing,
``Thaat's liife.''
</P>
<P>
   By the way, what might the ``Chairman of the Board'' have
crooned if Salt Lake City had been his kind of town _ ``I met a man
who danced with his wives?''
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know, but it also would be bigamy to say this series
suddenly has turned into a classic just because four of five games
have lurched through the fourth quarter with the outcome in doubt.
But there are people who think those Fox TV shows of police chases
and car crashes are grand entertainment too, so there is no
accounting for taste.
</P>
<P>
   What we have is basketball that is so fiercely played nobody can
shoot straight, pass to the intended target and run the proper
offense, or it is sloppy beyond belief.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, the Mailman and Rogaine pitchmeister, spent the first
four games of the series playing as if a side effect of the
hair-replacement tonic was a huge bald spot in the fourth quarter.
Then he stepped up Friday night and became an interloping John
Travolta with all of the fancy steps at what was supposed to be the
Bulls' ``Last Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally the Jazz got the kind of clutch performance it needed
from John Stockton, who kept delivering the ball to the right
places. And on a night when the Jazz finally showed some bark,
``Big Dawg'' Antoine Carr came howling off the bench with a dozen
points, including eight huge ones in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, mostly, was in attitude. Rather than tiptoeing
into church and worshipping at the altar of the Bulls, the Jazz
took on the role of attackers and never let up. The message was
delivered in the first half when Malone drew a technical for
tossing a shoulder into the chest of Rodman after scoring on a
fast-break dunk. It was a different kind of night for Malone, who
wouldn't allow himself to be deterred and it was Dennis the Clown
who was distracted, picking up five fouls and just three rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton drew half of a double technical for an exchange of
elbows with Scottie Pippen. Jeff Hornacek mixed it up with Rodman
and was whistled. But it showed evidence of the flame inside the
Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The debate quickly changed from whether Jordan or Pippen was
more deserving of the Finals MVP Award to which of them could miss
more big shots. The five-time champs were never impressive, as if
all they had to do was show up and NBA commissioner David Stern
would hand them another trophy.
</P>
<P>
   In a defining moment down the stretch, Jordan missed an open
jump shot, then missed a driving layup, followed by a missed tip by
Pippen and another foul by Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls seemed more preoccupied trying to make a grand exit to
their era than in finding the door to win one last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the hunt,'' Stockton said. ``We're still
kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a pleasant and surprising change from kicking
themselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
