<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-REGIS-HN     06-13 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-REGIS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
New American Regis adds solid citizenship, defense to U.S. team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LYON, France _ He is an American in France like so many others, the
notable difference being he gets along better with the maitre d's
at restaurants than the menus at McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   This David Regis is the rarest of finds. He can order for the
whole room and not cause French waiters to turn up their noses.
</P>
<P>
   He also can take the soccer ball to his left, unleash a
thunderous hooking cross to the perfect spot and not have to say a
word in English. Which is a good thing, because he can't speak the
language.
</P>
<P>
   But like his new teammates, Regis has come to France as an
American, albeit a new one. And he has come for all the right
reasons. He wants to try to help build U.S. soccer and fulfill a
dream by competing in the grandest tournament of them all, the
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he might have brought only a limited English vocabulary
and quite the ironic story, considering the chaotic road he took
toward U.S. citizenship and a trip back to France, which still is
his home. But a whale of a game came along for the Cup, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's defensive skills are at the top level in the world,''
U.S. coach Steve Sampson said. ``He gives us a dimension we haven't
seen a lot of before.''
</P>
<P>
   Regis made it onto the World Cup squad by the skin of his teeth,
or rather the recitation of the Bill of Rights, part of which he
had to memorize for the much-hurried citizenship exam U.S. Soccer
officials helped arrange only three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all, the game is the same and it speaks everybody's
language,'' Regis said. ``So for me it is not difficult adjusting
to the new situation. The American players are smart and have been
very willing to help me adapt as fast as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Regis, 29, who was born in Martinique and lived in Paris from
the age of 12, long has been considered a prime candidate to play
for the French national team. But after months of receiving mixed
messages from French soccer federation leaders while getting
inquiries from Sampson, Regis withdrew his name from consideration
for the French team and began looking for U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 while playing for the French side Racing Club de
Strasbourg, Regis met an American student from Decatur, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had coffee and a baguette at a cafe,'' he said of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Regis and Nikki Fogle married, which made him
eligible to become a U.S. citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were obstacles even after Sampson convinced Regis
to join the U.S. training squad in early May.
</P>
<P>
   First, U.S. immigration laws allow foreign spouses of Americans
to become citizens only after they have been married three years.
And David and Nikki Regis did not celebrate their third wedding
anniversary until the opening day of the World Cup this week.
</P>
<P>
   But the loophole in the process was Nikki worked with a travel
agency in France and would not return to the United States for a
year, which allowed the citizenship process to be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was helping Regis take a crash course in U.S.
history and study for the citizenship exam when he hardly knew a
word of English.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, defender Jeff Agoos, whose place Regis would take in
the starting lineup, spent hours going over points of history and
quizzing Regis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised that the players were so open to me,''
Regis said. ``In Europe, every man is out for himself. It was a new
experience for me. Everybody helped. I probably know more U.S.
history now than most Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Regis aced the exam, answering every question correctly and
completing the part of the test that worried him the most _ writing
a sentence in English.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence he wrote might have been something of a reflection
of how the U.S. team feels about their World Cup prospects now that
Regis is in the lineup: ``Today is a very nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Regis, whose friendly, low-key demeanor helped his transition to
the U.S. squad, immediately broke into the U.S. starting lineup
after passing the citizenship test.
</P>
<P>
   It was in an exhibition game against Kuwait in mid-May and
before the game his teammates serenaded Regis with the national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Regis starred in the game, helping the Americans shut out
Kuwait. Afterward, Regis got the game ball and has since showed all
the skills that impressed the French and Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a strong left foot, good straight-up defending ability
and is great heading the ball,'' teammate Cobi Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because he has spent much of his professional career in
Germany, Regis not only has strengthened a shaky U.S. defense, but
brought in a wealth of knowledge about how to play the powerful
Germans, who will be the Americans' first Cup opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is working out, that's why I came here,'' Regis
said. ``All the experience I have in Europe should help, especially
because I've played alongside a lot of German players. I know
almost all of their players, what they like to do and how they
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to play in the World Cup for your country is like a
dream. That never happened in France. To be here now is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to wear the colors and help this team. I want to learn
more about what it is to be an American and learn more about the
culture. It will take time, but once I learn more about the
language and spend as much time over there as I can, it will be
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, he is in France. An American in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``An American is an American is an American,'' Sampson said.
``This is a country of immigrants. David is doing what millions of
people have done for this country. He's living the American
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special to be in France,'' Regis said. ``I'm playing in
my country, for my other country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
