A8021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-GOP-HNS &LR;      06-13 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
TEXAS REPUBLICANS CALL FOR IMPEACHMENT OF PRESIDENT CLINTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   By R.G. RATCLIFFE &QL; 
and CLAY ROBISON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FORT WORTH _ More than 7,500 voting delegates to the Texas
Republican Convention approved a platform Saturday that urges
Congress to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sufficient evidence exists to indicate that President William
Jefferson Clinton has engaged in acts which in and of themselves
are impeachable offenses,'' the platform said.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP platform said those offenses include ``bribery,
influence peddling, obstruction of justice, perjury, subornation of
perjury and gross sexual misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   A special prosecutor is investigating whether Clinton lied in a
sworn deposition about having sex with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky and urging Lewinsky to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Republican chairwoman Susan Weddington said the
impeachment plank will send a strong message to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong statement. It says that we're sick, fed up,
tired of the obstructionism,'' Weddington said. ``We just want to
move on so we can feel proud of our presidency and our country's
leader again.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democratic Party spokesman Rafe Bemporad said the
Republicans were engaging in personality politics with the
impeachment plank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that the Republican Party continues to engage
in the politics of personal destruction,'' Bemporad said. ``The
majority of the people in Texas and the nation are ready to move on
and take care of the business of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican convention ended Saturday after two days of what
was largely a pep rally for the re-election of Gov. George W. Bush
and the possible GOP sweep of statewide offices this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to inspire, educate and motivate so the grass
roots will be energized,'' Weddington said. ``The message of the
convention at this point is: Democrats, you are in big trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   While the convention was generally harmonious, tempers flared in
the midday heat outside the Tarrant County Convention Center as
about 100 gays and lesbians staged a rally urging Texas Republicans
to open their party to them. The Log Cabin Republicans, a gay and
lesbian group, had been denied an exhibit booth at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gay protesters, most of whom were not convention delegates,
taunted rally participants with signs and verbal insults, but
police kept the peace.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. W.N. Otwell, a right-wing minister from Mount
Enterprise who unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination for
governor in 1990, organized the counterprotest, he said, to
``confront the Sodomites.''
</P>
<P>
   Weddington, in a speech to the convention later in the day
criticized protesters for ``attacking other people in such a
mean-spirited and derogatory way.''
</P>
<P>
   Weddington, however, reaffirmed her support for the party's
strong platform plank against homosexuality. And within the past
week, a party spokesman had called the Log Cabin Republicans an
``extremist'' group of ``deviant'' individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The only heated confrontation inside the convention occurred
before the convention deleted term limits for party officials from
the state party rules. The convention also eliminated from its
platform any mention of term limits for state and federal elected
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The adoption of term limits for elected officials has been a
core Republican issue for most of this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Platform Committee Chairman Michael Williams said the plank was
removed because state term limit laws for federal candidates were
declared unconstitutional by the U.S. Supreme Court. He said
platform committee members believed voters could limit the terms of
state officeholders at the ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Several planks in the platform appeared to contradict positions
taken by Gov. George W. Bush. In one instance, the platform said
the majority of bilingual education programs in Texas have not
worked and should be eliminated. Bush has said he supports
bilingual education programs that work.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he did not see the bilingual plank as a
contradiction of Bush's position. But he said no politician is
expected to agree with every platform plank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The platform is an expression of the beliefs, the values and
the principles of these delegates,'' Williams said. ``Individuals
here and there may have disagreements with the platform.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Friday said a platform is a statement of the delegates
of the convention, but he said he runs on his own agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I disagree with certain parts of the platform, I just move
on and campaign,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the convention also adopted a new party rule requiring
Republican candidates to be given a questionnaire on whether they
support specific platform planks. Weddington said it will be
voluntary as to whether candidates fill out the questionnaire.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates unanimously re-elected Weddington of San Antonio as
party chairman and David Barton of Aledo as vice chairman.
Weddington and Barton originally were appointed to their positions
last year by the party executive committee. Weddington is the first
woman to head either major party in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Weddington vowed to dedicate her service for the next two years
``first to God and then to the betterment of all Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   Convention keynote speaker U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm said the goal of
Texas Republicans this year is to sweep all statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win every statewide office in this election in Texas, we
will see dinosaurs walk in West Texas and the Tyrannosaurus Rex
swim in the Brazos River again before we ever see a Democrat in the
governor's mansion in Austin,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the dinosaurs came back, they would be welcome. The
Democrats would not,'' Gramm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
