<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JACKSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMED CAFE'S FOUNDER DIES AT 93
</HEADLINE>
 By ANITA BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONDER, Texas _ Grace ``Pete'' Jackson, whose steaks and caramel
pies drew customers from everywhere to the Ranchman's Cafe in the
tiny town of Ponder, died Friday at 93.
</P>
<P>
   For more than four decades, the crusty, well-loved Denton County
native greeted customers, hugged children and served up the tender
plate-size steaks and homemade pies that earned raves in national
magazines and devoted followers in Fort Worth-Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   From the time she opened the restaurant in 1948, her reputations
spread by word of mouth, and ``the world beat a path to her door,''
said Don Swafford, a great-nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was in the grocery business when a small building became
vacant next door, and she decided to put in a restaurant, Swafford
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had no idea it would go over like it did. It just boomed.
Within a year, it kicked off big time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning the restaurant was a family operations, using
her mother's old recipes with help from her sisters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swafford said the recipes had been perfected when the women in
the family cooked for the large threshing crews that worked during
harvests.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't formally advertise, but over the years the word
spread, drawing the famous and the common folk.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Faye Dunaway ate at the restaurant while ``Bonnie and
Clyde'' was being filmed nearby, and Dallas Cowboys stars were
regular customers.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, merchandising prince Stanley Marcus celebrated his
wedding anniversary there. It drew authors such as Peter Benchley
and sports figures such as Johnny Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, it also drew real cowboys, who came into town
and tied their horses to the front porch post just to annoy
Jackson, her nephew recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a tough old gal,'' he said. Her husband, R.L. ``Jack''
Jackson, originally did a lot of the cooking. He died in the early
1960s, and she carried on, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was everyone's grandmother, hugging children and
greeting customers when they came in, recalled Dave Ross, who
cooked at the restaurant for years before buying it in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was adamant about how her restaurant was run.
</P>
<P>
   It was all simple home cooking, but always fresh. No frozen
meat. No store-bought pie crusts. Ground meat was made fresh from
steak cuttings.
</P>
<P>
   Steak sauce was not available, unless customers brought their
own. And Jackson chose not to get a liquor license; booze was
something else customers had to bring.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ross has added steak sauce, the restaurant remains
basically the way Jackson set it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is a memorial to her,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Visitation will be from 3 to 5 p.m. Sunday at DeBerry Funeral
Home, 2025 W. University in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   Graveside services will be at 10 a.m. Monday at Roselawn
Memorial Park in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
