<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Sunday, June 14.If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
BORDER _ The U.S. House wants to put troops on the Southwest border
to stem the flow of drugs and illegal immigrants, a proposal
critics say would make the region look like ``east Berlin during
the Cold War.'' The House plan has ignited protests from Arizona
Gov. Jane Hull and officials along both sides of the border. It
authorizes the U.S. military to be dispatched to join with civilian
law enforcement agencies to prevent the entry of ``terrorists, drug
traffickers and illegal aliens'' into the United States. By JEFF
BARKER and MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GROWTH _ It seemed like the unsinkable plan: Slapping tough
controls on uncontrolled growth. All the polls showed tremendous
public support for a ballot initiative to fight sprawl. It struck
so much fear into business interests and lawmakers that they put
together their own competing proposal. But the environmentalists'
plan to manage growth suddenly sank last week. It hit two icebergs:
Time and money. But unlike the Titanic, the growth management
initiative isn't permanently scuttled. By KATHLEEN INGLEY and
MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
POSADA _ Winslow, Ariz., is a town hanging in the balance. What
will make it or break it is the vitality of its downtown area,
whose rebirth is being led by the restoration of the 68-year-old La
Posada resort, designed by the female architect who also designed
many of the buildings at the Grand Canyon. If the beautful old
resort fails to bring tourists and business to town made famous in
the Eagles song, Take It Easy, Winslow could go the way of so many
other burgs along the old Route 66. By BARBARA YOST. Story will
move in the ``L'' and ``T'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COL (Phoenix) _ Get ready to laugh. Those rib-tickling
yuk-meisters of the Washington press corps are about to apply
several coats of monkeyshine on the tarnished shell of their
preordained prince of presidential candidates _ John Sidney McCain
III. War hero. Father. U.S. Senator. Comedian. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
