<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-WAC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Exodus could prove costly to WAC's breakaway eight
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Legal games could replace those on the field for the eight teams
trying to depart the Western Athletic Conference and the eight
schools they leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   WAC presidents have asked league commissioner Karl Benson to
seek legal counsel whether the eight schools leaving the conference
have breached the league's articles of incorporation and failed to
observe their fiduciary responsibilities to the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the process of identifying a firm in Denver to
review this matter,'' said Benson, who declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents of eight schools _ Air Force, Brigham Young, Colorado
State, New Mexico State, San Diego State, UNLV, Utah and Wyoming _
announced in late May they were leaving the WAC to create their own
league, dubbed the Great Western Eight by some, by the summer of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the departing schools said their decision is in
accordance with WAC bylaws, which require they give written notice
of their departure to each league member and the WAC commissioner
on or before Sept. 1. Those papers have yet to be filed, WAC
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents of some of the remaining WAC schools _ Rice, TCU,
SMU, Tulsa, Texas-El Paso, Fresno State, Hawaii and San Jose State
_ are trying to determine whether the split is proper under the
WAC's articles of incorporation.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the school with the loudest complaint is Hawaii.
University president Kenneth Mortimer said an economist has
determined the WAC split will cost the school between $9 million
and $11 million over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Mortimer said he asked Hawaii's attorney general for a ruling on
the legality of the split prior to the May 31-June 2 WAC board of
directors meeting in Pebble Beach, Calif., but has not received an
answer. Mortimer did, however, meet with a lawyer before going to
California and kept a legal brief that he shared with presidents
during the WAC board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (presidents of the departing schools) are the ones who
said it is just a business decision,'' Mortimer said. ``And it
looks to me like it is a broken business agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer researching the issues said he did not think it would
come to a lawsuit. But the possibility is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will look for an appropriate way to resolve those issues,''
said Leon Bennett, an SMU vice president and general counsel. ``We
will not be looking to litigation as the principal means of doing
that. We hope to enter into discussions with them in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the argument is the WAC agreement of incorporation,
which was signed by all 16 school presidents. Some WAC officials
believe the agreement limits the right of any school to leave the
WAC before the middle of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated that when we signed this agreement, that it was
pretty clear,'' Mortimer said. ``There is no out clause. It is a
five-year agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Western Athletic Conference was incorporated as a
Colorado corporation, the WAC presidents were named to its board of
directors. Such corporate boards bear a higher degree of legal
responsibility for their actions than do officials of
unincorporated bodies.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are five paragraphs of the articles of incorporation,
which were signed after the new members, including former Southwest
Conference members Rice, SMU and TCU, joined the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth paragraph of the agreement states that members
``believe that it is in the long-term academic, competitive and
financial best interests of each of them to incorporate and
continue the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-term continuation of the WAC, of course, is now in
jeopardy because of the possible split.
</P>
<P>
   The second and third points involve the money paid under
Articles 2 and 3 of the agreement. In Article 2, the members of the
old conference agreed to transfer all assets of the 10-team
unincorporated conference to the new 16-team WAC.
</P>
<P>
   In Article 3, new members agreed to pay $75,000 each to the
league in 1994 and then to pay $35,000 a year for five years from
July 1, 1996, to July 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Article 4(a) says that while each WAC member will share equally
in the corporation's revenues, each of the six newest members would
lose $100,000 from their shares for each year through June 30,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth point, in Article 8(a), said that the incorporation
agreement would remain in effect ``until it is amended or
terminated by all parties hereto or until all of the obligations of
the parties hereto have been fully performed.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight remaining WAC schools are prepared to argue that since
payments and income redistribution continues through June 2001, no
school or schools have the right to leave the league before that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State athletic director Tim Weiser said the issues were
complicated in the move. ``There certainly will be a great deal of
discussion in the coming months,'' he said. ``We are proceeding
with great caution and concern.''
</P>
<P>
   CSU president Al Yates, who organized the breakaway eight,
acknowledged the possibility of a lawsuit but said, ``We are not
just colleagues, but friends, and I hope that will be the way we
operate in the future. The eight departing institutions don't have
much (money). We don't have a conference. We have an idea and a
dream, but there is much work ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The eight remaining WAC schools, however, have seen that
friendship strained by recent events. Yates spearheaded a group of
five schools _ CSU, Air Force, BYU, Utah and Wyoming _ whose
presidents met secretly at Denver International Airport and decided
to leave the WAC. Some have questioned how Yates, who was chairman
of the WAC Board of Directors at the time, could move to break up
the conference when he was charged with the fiduciary
responsibility of doing what was best for the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic issue relates to the question: Is the WAC a
corporation? Yes, it is,'' Mortimer said. ``Do we have a fiduciary
responsibility to the corporation, and can a minority conspire to
hurt the majority? That's an interesting issue.''
</P>
<P>
   One source who asked not to be named said the five schools at
the original meeting have damaged themselves in terms of ethical
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the WAC had not incorporated, then none of this would be as
significant an issue,'' said the source. ``Rice president Malcolm
Gillis insisted on the incorporation because of what happened to
them during the demise of the Southwest Conference.''
</P>
<P>
   What do the eight schools remaining in the WAC want? Spokesmen
from some of the schools believe they have legal grounds to receive
monetary damages from the departing schools. Mortimer can cite his
worst-case scenario of $11 million that Hawaii won't receive over
the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   One WAC source, who requested anonymity, said it is very likely
every school remaining in the WAC could prove it will suffer at
least $1 million per year in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiply that by eight schools over five years, and that's $40
million,'' the source said. ``I think $80 million wouldn't be out
of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Those figures also may just be saber rattling. SMU president
Gerald Turner, the new chairman of the WAC's board of directors,
has said no one wants to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always the possibility, but in higher ed it is not a
probability,'' Turner said. ``By the time we got out of it,
everyone would have forgotten what it was about and been in three
more conferences the way things are going now.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Turner couches his comments, saying, ``For every stone
we pick up, we find another stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some damages,'' he said. ``After they are all
identified, we want to have as few damages as possible to the eight
(remaining in the WAC). We need to have some type of completion to
that so the WAC can continue.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the coin, the eight departing schools want
to claim the money their basketball programs earned from the NCAA
Tournament. Schools receive one unit for every round they advance
in the tournament. The WAC's share will total about $2.5 million
for the 1998-99 academic year and just over $3 million for the
1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The breakaway schools likely will try to use that money as a
bargaining tool in the legal negotiations with the eight remaining
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-eight of the 33 credits were earned by the departing
schools,'' said BYU's Lee Bartlett, assistant to BYU president
Merrill Bateman. ``There clearly are legal things to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   However, under NCAA rules, the departing schools cannot claim
the money they earned while in the WAC. Tulsa gave up units when it
left the Missouri Valley Conference for the WAC, and Arkansas gave
up units when it bolted the Southwest Conference for the
Southeastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA rules are clear that the conference receives the
money, not the teams,'' said an NCAA spokeswoman. The only way for
the Great Western Eight to receive the NCAA basketball money, she
said, is for the WAC to break up.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said the basketball money is non-negotiable and will
remain with the eight WAC teams.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of the schools remaining in the WAC have had
teleconference calls about the legal aspects of the breakup. But it
appears the angriest is Hawaii's Mortimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has had an economist look at the numbers, then he could
show economic damages, because they have been in the league 20
years and have the numbers to fall back on,'' another source said.
</P>
<P>
   Could the Hawaiian Legislature get involved? Gov. Ben Cayetano
previously had agreed to pay travel subsidies of $500,000 a year to
the eight schools that split from the WAC if Hawaii could join them
as their ninth team. Hawaii gave $250,000 a year to subsidize
travel from 1979 _ its first year in the WAC _ to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Also in question is the thorny problem of sovereign immunity.
Since seven of the eight schools that split are operated by state
or federal governments, they are shielded in part or completely
from liability in a lawsuit. So it remains uncertain if the
institutions can be held liable for their departure from the WAC.
</P>
<P>
   One source, however, noted state schools have been sued before.
``Sovereign immunity is just another moat around the castle,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since BYU is a private school, it does not have the protection
of sovereign immunity and thus could be tithing to the eight it
left behind. Also, as a member of the board of directors, Bateman's
personal fortune could be in jeopardy, said one lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the (Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints) is going to like what they see here,'' said one WAC school
official.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, currently traveling in Russia, has declined comment on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Adding fuel to the fire, according to one league official, is
that Mortimer is intent on a legal challenge, possibly with the
Hawaiian Legislature on his side, even if the WAC as a league does
not vote to sue the Great Western Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Rice officials say they plan to continue with the
eight-team league. When asked at the WAC meetings in California if
Rice intended to pay the $35,000 it owes the league this year
despite the future breakup, Gillis said, ``We will meet our
financial obligations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
