<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DARRENLEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS DRAWS RAVES AS SOX LEADING MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darren Lewis was one of several players auditioned in Florida as
Red Sox leadoff man this spring, but when the season began, manager
Jimy Williams abandoned that experiment and restored Nomar
Garciaparra to the top of the order.
</P>
<P>
   But when Garciaparra separated his shoulder diving for a ground
ball May 8 in Kansas City, Williams was forced to find an
alternative. He settled on Lewis, the Gold Glove outfielder whose
offense was an afterthought when the Red Sox signed him two days
before Christmas for the cut-rate price of $500,000, less than half
his 1997 salary.
</P>
<P>
   But what was supposed to be a Band-Aid measure has taken on the
look of permanence, as Lewis has exceeded all expectations in
jump-starting the Red Sox' offense. When Garciaparra returned,
Williams slid him into the No. 3 slot and kept Lewis, who had begun
the year hitting eighth and ninth in the order, in the No. 1 slot.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis doesn't have Garciaparra's extra-base power, but has given
the Red Sox everything a team looks for in a leadoff man: a smart,
patient hitter who knows how to get on base. His leadoff on-base
percentage of .399, which is 78 points higher than his career OBP,
ranks him second with Chuck Knoblauch of the Yankees in the
American League, .001 behind Texas's Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   In the 31 games since he has taken over the leadoff spot, Lewis
has failed to reach base by either a hit, walk, or as a hit batsman
in just five games. When the Red Sox scored 25 runs in three games
last week against the Braves _ the most runs allowed in three games
by the vaunted Atlanta pitching staff this season _ Lewis was on
base three times in each game and scored six runs.
</P>
<P>
   He went hitless in three trips against Tampa Bay Friday night,
but drew a leadoff walk and scored ahead of Reggie Jefferson's home
run, the Red Sox' only scoring until they broke up a tight game
with three runs in the eighth en route to a 5-1 win. With 25 walks,
Lewis has twice as many as the free-swinging Garciaparra (11),
whose more potent bat is needed in the heart of the order,
especially with the Red Sox short on righthanded hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Since last season, the Red Sox have subtracted Tim Naehring,
Wilfredo Cordero, and Mike Stanley as righthanded hitters who
batted in the middle of the lineup while adding just Jim Leyritz,
who has been struggling of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player, one who knows how to play the game,''
Williams said of Lewis. ``How many RBIs does he have?''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has 21, an unexceptional total but one that becomes more
meaningful in this context: Among Red Sox regulars, Lewis ranks
second only to Garciaparra in hitting with runners in scoring
position. Garciaparra is batting .339 (20 for 59), while Lewis is
at .318 (14 for 44) and has more RBIs (17) than hits in those
situations.
</P>
<P>
   While Bret Saberhagen has commanded far more attention on the
subject of comeback player of the year, Lewis, who was buried on
the White Sox bench for much of last season, will merit
consideration if he maintains this level of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   And his defense, along with that of another Sox newcomer, Damon
Buford, has elevated Sox outfield play to a level that hasn't been
seen in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is an unbelievable worker,'' said third baseman John
Valentin. ``He's out there early every day, hitting, in the weight
room, taking fly balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is one of the quietest players on the team but
listens to brain-thumping rap music on his headphones before games
to hype himself up, doesn't want to hear talk about comeback
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' he said. ``This is the way I've always approached
the game. Awards, like Gold Gloves and that stuff, are so
secondary. I want a chance to get to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis just missed in '93, when he played on a Giants team that
won 103 games but lost the division title to the Braves, two years
before the wild card was introduced into the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this team,'' he said, ``there was no pressure for me to be
an offensive factor, because it's such a great offensive ball
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, he has become a key factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you get older, you get a little smarter,'' he
said. ``I've had my struggles the last couple of years, but
hopefully you have some luck, and hopefully, the hard work pays
off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
