<SLUG> BC-SOC-USTEAM-DOOLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOOLEY AT HOME PLAYING FOR US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France _ Thomas Dooley remembers the
puzzled expressions of playmates when he was growing up in the
Fatherland in the '60s. ``Dooley? Explain how that is,'' they asked
him. ``That is not a German name.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as American as G.I. Joe. Dooley's father was a US
serviceman who vanished when Dooley was a toddler. Dooley spoke
German, not English, and played a dozen years in professional
leagues there. But he always considered himself a Yank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up like a German but I feel like an American,'' says
the man who will lead the US team into the Parc des Princes Monday
for their crucial World Cup opener against Germany in Paris. When
he hears the two anthems played before the kickoff _ ``The
Star-Spangled Banner'' and ``Deutschland Uber Alles'' _ Dooley will
know which one is his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-eight times I have played for America and 78 times I
have heard the American anthem,'' says the 37-year-old captain, the
oldest man on the US roster by more than two years. ``When I hear
the German anthem, I know the song, but there is nothing inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley has carried an American passport since 1992. He lives
much of the year in Mission Viejo, Calif. He listens to Metallica
before matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked American music,'' he says. ``Van Halen and
everything else. I watched the Super Bowl every year. It was the
one football game they would show in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   So when the offer came half a dozen years ago to join the US
national team, Dooley jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Germany, almost everyone likes America,'' he says. ``You
see so many magazines and movies and TV shows. Young people
especially would love to visit there, even for a few weeks. So when
they ask me, I say, `Of course I want to play there.' It wasn't a
strange thing because my whole life I wanted to go to America.''
</P>
<P>
   America represented more than an adventure to Dooley. It meant a
chance to do the one thing he had never done _ and never would _
for Germany: play in the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that good,'' Dooley shrugs. ``I was probably in the
top third of the league in man-marking, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   So the German federation had no problem with a guy named Dooley
playing for the Yanks _ especially at his age.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 30 when I left,'' he says. ``If I was maybe 22, they
might have said something.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Van Halen kid arrived in his spiritual home (somebody had
given him the Kingston Trio's ``Tom Dooley'' when he was 7), and
was fascinated. The skyscrapers he saw in Chicago delighted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't many high-rise buildings in Germany,'' Dooley
says. ``Only in Frankfurt.''
</P>
<P>
   And he was enthralled by California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the beaches, we went to Disneyland,'' he says.
``And Los Angeles is not a bad town.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until he opened his mouth that Dooley realized how
American he wasn't. He turned up in camp and couldn't understand a
thing. Paul Caligiuri, who roomed with Dooley and played in the
Bundesliga, became his round-the-clock translator. In uniform,
though, Dooley needed no translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field you don't have to talk,'' he says. ``Soccer has
its own language.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley's fluency with the ball was beyond question. The
Americans, who'd gone three-and-out in the 1990 World Cup, were
desperate for a seasoned Renaissance man who felt as comfortable
going forward as defending. Dooley, who'd been playing as a central
defender for Kaiserslautern, stepped in and started immediately.
</P>
<P>
   His mates quickly learned to look for him just about anywhere _
buttoning up the back line, prowling the midfield, dashing to open
space in his scarlet boots, even putting the ball in the back of
the net. Dooley's goals didn't come against Third World sides in
offseason friendlies, either. He scored against England in the huge
victory at Foxborough in 1993 and tallied twice against Germany in
a 4-3 loss that convinced the Americans that they could play with
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley quickly became the indispensable man, guaranteed to get
the call whenever the Yanks had to win. He was the only US
midfielder to play every minute of the last World Cup, and he never
left the field in last year's final five qualifying matches.
</P>
<P>
   When captain John Harkes had to sit out the crucial match
against Canada in Vancouver in November with a yellow-card
suspension, coach Steve Sampson handed the armband to Dooley.
``Bring the team to France today,'' Sampson urged him.
</P>
<P>
   When Sampson dumped Harkes from the roster in April, he went to
Dooley again before an important tuneup at Austria and gave him the
armband for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked if I would like to take some more responsibility,''
Dooley says. ``I said, `Of course I want to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he'll lead the American side in the biggest match
they've played since they met Brazil in the last Cup quarterfinals
before a full house in the Rose Bowl on the fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   It will be an odd thing to stand on the sideline and hear the
anthem of the country where he and his wife, Elke, and his two
children were born and his mother still lives and whose language he
speaks and then play against its team, all of whose members he
knows well. But Dooley says it will not be emotional. He will not
feel torn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never went into the German army,'' Dooley says. ``I never
played for the national team, never had the German anthem played
for myself. If something like that had happened, it would be
different.''
</P>
<P>
   He plays for the Columbus Crew of Major League Soccer now, and
when he retires from the game, he may well live in the States
forever.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yanks win Monday, Dooley has joked that he'll fly to
Berlin, rent a car, and drive through Germany with the stars and
stripes fluttering from the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked my Dad (stepfather) if he would wear an American
jersey,'' Dooley says. ``He said, `No, no, no, I am a German.' But
my mother told him, `If you jump up and cheer when Germany scores,
I will hit you with an umbrella.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
