</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DEVILRAYS-HATCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVIL RAYS FELT CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Hatcher, the former Red Sox outfielder who is now a coach
with the expansion Tampa Bay Devil Rays, had a simple piece of
advice for his outfielders when the team arrived at Fenway Park
Thursday: Don't be intimidated by the Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to teach them how to play the ball off the
wall,'' Hatcher said, as he sat in the visitors' clubhouse after
Saturday's game was rained out. ``You don't want to get caught on
the wall, because it's going to kick back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to tell them to make sure you've got a step on the
grass, so when the ball bounces, it won't bounce over your head and
you'll have an opportunity to throw somebody out at second.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-1 loss to the Red Sox Friday night, the Devil Rays may
have soaked up the atmosphere in their first visit to Fenway Park,
but it was their outfielders who attempted to soak up the knowledge
of how to play one of the most unique and challenging outfields in
all of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just that there are so many different angles,'' Hatcher
said. ``The ball will bounce different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely those times when a baseball caroms wildly off
the scoreboard in left, takes a funny hop off the wall, or darts
into one of Fenway's more unique corners that a major league
outfielder can look as silly as a Keystone Kop.
</P>
<P>
   After all, venerable Fenway is where right and center fielders
must learn to cope with the idiosyncrasies of angles, nooks,
crannies; and where the left fielder must constantly joust with the
Green Monster, the 37-foot wall that presides majestically over the
greensward in left.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Arrojo, the rookie pitcher from Cuba who started Friday
night's game for Tampa Bay, said he was unaware of the Wall when he
took the mound. He hardly noticed it. ``Maybe I'll notice it now,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the case for left fielder Randy Winn, who also
was playing at Fenway for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit overwhelming,'' said Winn, who became
intimately acquainted with The Wall when he crashed into it trying
to field a line drive in Boston's three-run eighth inning. ``It
makes you feel like you're playing really shallow. You do have to
play shallow, because if they hit it up in the air, it'll hit off
the wall. It does make it seem like you're playing right in the
shortstop's back pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not a place for the claustrophobic, is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that bad, but it definitely can change the pace of
the game,'' said Winn. ``Because balls you would have a chance to
catch are going to either hit off the wall for a single, or maybe a
close play at second, or a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went out early and took some balls off of it, but it's
different when somebody's throwing balls off of it, or hitting
fungoes off of it. The next best thing other than game experience
is probably batting practice, and we didn't have a chance to get
out there for batting practice because of the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really have to be careful when you go back there, you have
to know where you are and if you're near the scoreboard. Balls are
going to come off it different. There's a ladder there and the
scoreboard, and it can come off the face of the scoreboard, the top
of the scoreboard, so it's going to take some different bounces.
The center fielder has to come and back you up, because you never
know where it's going to hit, and that's one of the
idiosyncrasies.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't that the charm of Fenway?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it is,'' Winn said. ``But with all the little corners and
stuff, experience is going to be the best teacher. It's a good
experience and it's fun to play, but, like I said, you're not going
to feel really comfortable out there until you play a few games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
