<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SECONDRE     06-13 2254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SECONDREF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECONDED MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When the National Hockey League's general managers sit down in
Washington Tuesday to recommend rule changes, Washington's George
McPhee believes there will be strong support to put a second
referee on the ice next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would endorse it,'' said McPhee, who doesn't believe there
will be an excessive amount of tinkering with the game's on-ice
guidelines. ``It would give them more confidence and they'd be able
to cover more areas of the ice. A lot of the stuff that goes on now
is what is happening behind the play, and one ref can't see
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, two refs won't see it all, either, but there is no
doubt a second voice of authority out there would clean up much of
the junk. Under the current structure, linesmen have limited
jurisdiction to chime in when they feel absolutely necessary, but
the truth is, they keep to calling the lines and stopping the
fights. The latter isn't nearly as necessary as it was, say, 5 or
10 years ago, and the game at large has become far faster over the
last couple of decades, placing greater strain on referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty years ago, the league was very different,'' said
McPhee. ``The skaters weren't as good; they weren't as fast. I
honestly believe it would be better with two referees. The job's
just too hard now.''
</P>
<P>
   A second referee not only would make the workplace a more level
playing field, it could add years to referees' careers. Ideally,
the older the referee, the better his judgment, discretion, and
overall feel for the game. Play is so fast that referees are ready
to be phased out by their early 40s, their legs unable to keep up
with the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy in his late 40s, the first thing to go are his wheels,''
said NHL vice president Brian Burke. ``Usually you find that his
vision is fine and his judgment is great, but he doesn't always
have the speed. The NBA has guys on the job into their 60s. We want
to keep our best refs out there as long as possible. We've
experimented with this in preseason, and in games with two refs,
the average time of game has dropped by 14 minutes _ that's huge.
With two refs, you get less nonsense going on out there.''
</P>
<P>
   A second referee on the sheet could give the top whistleblowers
another 10 years on the job, and it undoubtedly would encourage
more en-listees. Earning power isn't bad: Senior referees make some
$200,000 per annum. Tack on another 10 years of earning power,
giving a guy a reasonable expectation to work 25 years, and there
should be no shortage of recruits.
</P>
<P>
   If it passes, the move to a second ref likely would come at the
cost of a linesman. Games still would be governed by three on-ice
officials, but it would be two referees and one linesman rather
than one referee and two linesmen. The league could give some of
their current linesmen a chance to move up to the referee ranks or
sweeten the pot for some of the older officials to retire.
</P>
<P>
   US college hockey introduced a two-ref system four years ago, in
the CCHA. Now, all of college hockey has had at least two years of
employing two refs. Hockey East commissioner Joe Bertagna has been
impressed with the mechanics and feels it makes for a better game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ref, and then two assistant refs, AR-1 and AR-2 _
to the point that we've done away with the `linesman'
designation,'' he said, noting that the second assistant still
whistles offside calls. ``It's that first assistant who stays
behind the play and serves as that constant reminder to the
players, telling them, `OK, cut it out back here.' It's that stuff
behind the play that really can turn into trouble, things that can
get ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colleges have the bigger, Olympic-sized sheets for their
home surfaces, another factor that moved colleges to use two refs,
said Bertagna. The bigger the rink and the older the ref, the
greater the chance that a senior official won't be able to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping your senior, or `A-group,' officials working as long
as possible is important,'' said Bertagna. ``You want those guys
with great presence out there, guys with judgment and a real feel
for the game. But if you've got this huge surface, and a guy who's
maybe a little long in the tooth, you're scared that he might not
be able to be around the net when a goal's scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the NHL adopt the idea? Yes, at least in part. If not
ratified in full, look for the idea to be implemented as an
experiment, with perhaps each of the 27 NHL rinks having at least
two games with two refs. Some GMs have to be convinced that it's
the way to go. Once they see the improvement it makes, they'll
endorse it in full for 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For those who remember  &UR; Dale Hunter  &LR; nearly decapitating
then-Bruin  &UR; Craig Janney  &LR; in the 1990 conference finals, or maybe
his pitchfork-like spear to  &UR; Terry O'Reilly's  &LR; groin when Hunter
was a Nordique, it's hard to imagine the Capitals' tough guy being
glorified. ``When I played against him, I thought he was a real
(expletive),'' said Washington teammate  &UR; Adam Oates &LR; . ``But it's
almost like a  &UR; Cal Ripken  &LR; situation: In 18 years, only once has he
missed games due to injury. Once! You look at the years, the games,
the numbers, everything, and you don't hear anyone mention him for
the Hall of Fame. But I mean, what have you got to do?'' ... McPhee
on the club he inherited last summer after the Capitals fired
longtime GM  &UR; David Poile &LR; : ``He deserves most of the credit here,
he and (the late)  &UR; Jack Button  &LR; and the whole scouting staff. They
did a great job building this team. All we've done is rearrange the
furniture, added a chair or two, and reupholstered a little.''
Perhaps the most valuable change was adding veteran forward  &UR; Brian
Bellows  &LR; for a total cost of around $40,000 in the stretch run.
Once the Capitals signed Bellows, he had to clear waivers, and
another NHL squad could have taken him for the $40,000 _ with the
understanding that he wouldn't have been eligible for the playoffs.
Byzantine, ain't it? ``There were some clubs out there who weren't
happy that we grabbed him,'' said McPhee. Nonetheless, no one
wanted to spend the $40,000, essentially to keep him away from the
Capitals _ what would have amounted to paying a kill fee. Remember,
it was Bellows who beat  &UR; Byron Dafoe  &LR; on a long bomb to clinch the
Boston series. And it was Bellows who muscled the puck to the net
in Buffalo, allowing  &UR; Joe Juneau  &LR; to knock in the series clincher
against the Sabres ... Rumor has it that Poile, now running the
expansion Nashville Predators, soon will acquire veteran blue liner
 &UR; Paul Coffey  &LR; from the Flyers. The Flyers want Coffey gone, which
could be bad timing, because Coffey should be a better player if
the league continues to crack down on obstruction calls (i.e. he
still can skate with the best of 'em). Coffey will make $2.9
million next season, and the Flyers might absorb two-thirds of that
just to move him, and pick up a draft pick or two from the
Predators ... You know it's a whole new era when ESPN is televising
Pro Beach Hockey. When do we see Indoor Water Surfing? ... The idea
of a woman entering the NHL on-ice officiating ranks has been
dormant the last couple of years. But with the outstanding
performances of both the US and Canadian women hockey players at
the Olympics, wouldn't it make great sense to see some of them,
those ready to leave their playing careers, try to move into the
NHL officiating ranks? There is not one good reason for a woman to
be denied a chance at becoming a ref. ``I think it's a great
idea,'' said Burke. ``The NBA has two women officiating, why not
hockey? It's only a matter of time.'' A case could be made that a
linesman must break up fights and a lineswoman might not be able to
handle it. But that depends on the woman. And it's a free world. If
she wants to get smacked around by  &UR; Eric Lindros &LR; , &UR; Chris Simon,  &LR; et
al, then welcome to the boys' club. Team USA's  &UR; Karyn Bye &LR; : &UR;  &LR; ``I
could see a woman doing it, if she could survive the junior and
minor league ranks, why not? Personally, I wouldn't be interested.
I refed a mite game back in my hometown, River Falls, Wis. It was a
boys game, and the parents booed the daylights out of me because I
was a girl. That was back in the '80s, and I'm sure things have
changed, but it still wouldn't interest me.'' ... Edmonton
president/GM  &UR; Glen Sather  &LR; recently let moviemakers use his home in
Canmore, Alberta, for the filming of ``Mystery, Alaska.'' In the
movie, Sather's house is the home of  &UR; Burt Reynolds &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Mystery
coach who directs his ragtag bunch of hockey players in a game
against the mighty New York Rangers. Sather's son,  &UR; Justin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; suits
up for the Rangers _ something his dad once did ...  &UR; Mark Recchi
 &LR; is looking for a new deal in Montreal that will pay him $7 million
a year. He is using new deals for  &UR; Mats Sundin  &LR; and  &UR; Mike Modano
 &LR; as his comps ... Habs fans in a recent poll by the Journal de
Montreal were adamant about not having  &UR; Vincent Damphousse  &LR; back
next year. It's one thing to be French-Canadian, but loyalty only
goes so far _ and not so far as 16 goals for $3 million ... Dallas
coach  &UR; Ken Hitchcock  &LR; worked two playoff series while suffering the
high fever and swollen glands that are part of mononucleosis ...
The Flames are willing to swap  &UR; Theo Fleury  &LR; and their No. 6
first-round pick to San Jose for the No. 2 pick. If they strike a
deal, the Sharks might look to send  &UR; Owen Nolan  &LR; to the Flames, too
... Former goalie  &UR; Mike Liut  &LR; is the latest to become an agent ...
Wildest rumor making the rounds at the finals: Pittsburgh to send
 &UR; Jaromir Jagr &LR;  and the rights to  &UR; Peter Nedved  &LR; and  &UR; Mario Lemieux
 &LR; to Philadelphia for Lindros.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Conditioning guru  &UR; Mike Boyle &LR; , his Sports Acceleration North
running at warp speed in Burlington, reports that Jumbo  &UR; Joe
Thornton  &LR; now weighs about 220 _ that's 25 pounds above his draft
weight. ``I see him every day, and even I notice the difference,''
remarked Boyle, who also has Bruins  &UR; Hal Gill &LR; , &UR; Steve Heinze &LR; , &UR; Kyle
McLaren &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Shawn Bates  &LR; going through daily paces. ``Guys like
 &UR; Joe Sacco  &LR; and  &UR; Ted Drury  &LR; are here, too, and they see him now and
say, `My God, he's big.''' Thornton's emphasis isn't solely on
adding upper-body mass, but also powering up his legs. ``You could
see last year that he needed leg strength,'' said Bruins assistant
GM  &UR; Mike O'Connell &LR; . ``If he adds that strength, he won't be
knocked off stride as easily, and overall getting bigger and
stronger should add to his confidence out there.'' ... O'Connell
reports that Group 2 free agents McLaren and  &UR; Jason Allison  &LR; will
see their new contract offers on or before July 1, as provided in
the Collective Bargaining Agreement. Each one, he said, can expect
the minimum 10 percent increase over their now-expired contracts.
McLaren made $750,000 last year, Allison $600,000. It's just a
starting point, folks. Both McLaren and Allison easily can justify
asking for about $2.5 million a year, based on comparable salaries
around the league. If they want to go long-term, say four or five
years, they justifiably could ask for $3 million a year or more ...
If the Bruins go shopping for free agents, they'll do it with an
eye on beefing up their Providence (AHL) squad. `` &UR; Pat
 &LR; ( &UR; Burns &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; did a great job making our younger guys feel
important,'' said O'Connell. ``And next year we want our young guys
to bring it up another level _ guys like Thornton,
( &UR; P.J. &LR; ) &UR; Axelsson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ( &UR; Sergei &LR; ) &UR; Samsonov  &LR; and ( &UR; Anson &LR; ) &UR; Carter &LR; . If
we fooled around too much with the roster, it might inhibit their
growth, and we're hoping some of our other youngs like
( &UR; Cameron &LR; ) &UR; Mann &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Bates, and ( &UR; Randy Robitaille &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; can step it up
next year, too. It could change, but right now that's the way we're
looking to go.'' ... Word around the rink is that the NHL slapped
Penguins part-owner  &UR; Roger Marino  &LR; with a $10,000 fine for comments
here three weeks ago critical of the league for not enforcing rules
better on obstruction. To wit: ``The game, in general, has slowed
to a crawl. We have to let our stars play, like the NBA lets its
stars like ( &UR; Michael &LR; ) &UR; Jordan  &LR; play. I've got twin 8-year-old boys,
and if I didn't own a hockey team, I'd never let 'em watch it.'' So
there's the lesson of the day: speak the truth, and pay for it. It
gets more bizarre out here, shift by shift ... Bertagna's
goaltending camps, now in their 25th summer and operating in five
rinks in Hingham, Burlington, Marlborough, Hamilton, and Hooksett,
N.H., still have a few openings (more info: 978-283-2662). ``We're
always looking for that next  &UR; Mike Richter &LR; ,'' said Bertagna.
``He's probably our most visible alum.'' ... Burke, who wants to
return to being a GM, a post he held in Hartford, has interviewed
in Atlanta and Vancouver, where he was the Canucks' assistant GM
prior to McPhee. ``I've had interviews in both places, but there's
been no followup, other than one brief conversation I had,'' said
Burke. One possible reason for the delay in both cities: Sather has
been recruited by both the Thrashers and Canucks. No one truly
expects Sather to leave the Oilers, but no one wants to hire anyone
else in the meantime. To wit: Anaheim's assistant GM,  &UR; David McNab
 &LR; (brother of  &UR; Peter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the former Bruin), was a candidate in
Atlanta, until the Ducks got fed up with Atlanta's indecision and
withdrew permission for McNab to continue negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
