<SLUG> BC-SOC-NETH-BELGIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLAND IN TIE WITH BELGIUM, 0-0  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1995 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST.-DENIS, France _ The Netherlands entered the World Cup with
the recent play and confidence of potential world champions, but
settled for a disappointing 0-0 draw with Belgium Saturday night
after losing forward Patrick Kluivert to a red card for what
appeared to be an insignificant elbow late in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Netherlands had plenty of opportunities to score, but could
not convert. Striker Dennis Bergkamp returned in the second half
after being out for six weeks with a hamstring injury, but he
missed an opportunity in the 73rd minute, shanking a left-footed
shot from 10 yards out.
</P>
<P>
   With nine minutes remaining, Kluivert was shoved slightly by
Belgian defender Lorenzo Staelens, then wagged his finger and gave
Staelens a small retaliatory jab in the chest with his elbow.
Staelens appeared to take a dive, but Referee Pierluigi Collina of
Italy drew the red card and sent Kluivert off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Even a man down, the Dutch had a great chance to score in the
88th minute when Frank de Boer redirected a volley from the corner
toward the left post, only to have the ball kicked away by Belgian
defender Eric Deflandre.
</P>
<P>
   Deflandre saved two goals Saturday night after coming on in the
22nd minute to try to contain the speed of the Netherlands' Marc
Overmars on the left wing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
