</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ NEED AN ENCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The arrogance of Chicago is more than a
thousand miles to the east. The champagne remains corked in
Illinois as the NBA Finals return to this dry state populated by
disciples of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   There is redemption in the fresh air here. Karl Malone has shed
the goat horns and answered critics who suggested he's a fraud _ no
better in the big games than Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Utah Jazz didn't make any foolish declarations after their
narrow, party-spoiling Game 5 victory at the United Center Friday,
but it was clear that they took satisfaction in denying Chicago the
opportunity to win the championship at home.
</P>
<P>
   The final running of the Bulls has taken on a life of its own
and, frankly, it's getting a little nauseating. It is the American
sports equivalent of the last ``Seinfeld'' episode, and there has
been no allowance that the Bulls could lose.
</P>
<P>
   The streets of Chicago were supposed to be flowing with
champagne after Friday night's game, but Malone &AMP; Co. spoiled the
fun and stopped the hideous debate about which Bull star deserved
to be Series MVP (LA fans were debating this very topic in 1984 _
Magic or Worthy? _ right up until the Celtics won the Series).
</P>
<P>
   Malone scored 39 points Friday night, including several
``(expletive) you'' jumpers right in the face of Dennis Rodman, the
attention-starved nitwit who ridiculed Malone as ``an awkward
player.'' Rodzilla said Malone could not beat him off the dribble,
so Malone did that, too, scoring on a finger roll after blowing
past Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago may yet win the series, but Utah at least was able to
salvage its reputation. Just when it looked as if the Jazz were
emerging as the Buffalo Bills of the NBA, grizzled vets Malone,
John Stockton, and fearless Antoine Carr proved there is a pulse in
the Utah locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago guard Steve Kerr conceded, ``The Jazz players were
sitting in their hotel watching all the stories about Grant Park
(where a championship rally is planned) and the police telling
people not to riot. The whole city seemed to be poised for a
celebration and I'm sure it ticked them off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Karl was going to come out and play,'' said Carr, a man
who's been around long enough to remember Larry Bird going for 60
in New Orleans against Atlanta in 1985. ``He had that anger in his
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no anger in Malone's voice. None. He wouldn't go for
the bait after losing Game 2 at home, after the historic Game 3
42-point drubbing, or after the Game 4 loss that caused Hoop Nation
to question his heart and his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to read the paper,'' said Malone. ``And I realize
all the stuff that's being said. Unfortunately, you don't have the
game you want to have all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he relaxed on Thursday by going out in a State Police
cruiser and weighing some trucks. Such fun. And he wasn't kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went out and canned 17 of 27 shots, grabbing 9 rebounds,
and dishing out 5 assists. He scored 17 points in the third
quarter, when Utah had its best run of the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said, ``For all the criticism he's received in this
playoff, I think he put a lot of things to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone didn't want to field a lot of questions about himself
after the victory. At one point, he said he would leave the podium
if asked another Karl Malone question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember this right here,'' he said. ``It's a
team game. No matter what an individual guy does on this team,
we're going to win it or lose it together. I know it sounds corny
nowadays, but that's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a corny guy. The Jazz are a corny team. Utah doesn't have
a loathed owner bent on tearing the team apart. Utah doesn't have a
Zen-master coach who wants to head to the mountains. There are no
free agent superstars pleading to leave town, or teasing fans with
veiled hints at retirement. There's no childish idiot skipping
practice to break chairs over someone's head at a wrestling event.
And there's no debate about which Jazz player should be the series
MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, the Jazz have just been the straight men for the
Bulls, setting up punch lines for Chicago's arrogant team and fans.
And the Jazz were downright bad in Games 3 and 4, and the first
half of Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is really nervous in Chicago. Not yet. Friday's loss was
just another interruption of the music for the last dance.
</P>
<P>
   But what if Malone and the Jazz win again tonight? What then?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
