<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CHICAGOO     06-13 1801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CHICAGOOWNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNER PLAYING GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The owner of the Chicago Bulls has, by my count
anyway, twice violated his own pledge to keep his mouth shut on the
topic of next year until, well, next year. He did it once a couple
weeks ago. He did it again Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jerry Reinsdorf, there is no plan to break up the
Bulls. According to Jerry Reinsdorf, there have been no
contingencies expressed by Michael Jordan. Gee, you mean all those
forests have been pillaged for no good reason?
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf did insert a nifty qualifier in his latest discourse
on the topic. He doesn't want to break up the Bulls as long as they
are winning championships. Not winning. Winning championships.
</P>
<P>
   They may well get No. 6 tonight, so does that mean all this talk
about the Last Dance and Michael's Last Stand is mere rubbish?
Apparently so. All those stories about the breakup of the Bulls are
fit to wrap fish if Chicago wins tonight or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be Red on Roundball to see what's going on
here. The owner is doing his best Pontius Pilate imitation.
Reinsdorf, who makes the final decision in consort with his
henchman, Jerry Krause, is saying it's not up to him. If Michael
retires, that's Michael's decision. If Scottie leaves, that's
Scottie's decision. If Phil goes, well, it was he who requested the
one-year deal, not us. If Bill Wennington goes, well, so what?
</P>
<P>
   As Reinsdorf said, ``It hasn't affected me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And what to make of this gem? ``Michael has never said anything
has to happen for him to return.'' Huh? Reinsdorf should have his
most computer-literate employee do a search with the words
``Jordan,'' ``Jackson,'' and ``retire'' and see how many stories
pop up. Now, having said that, Jordan may well find a way to squirm
out of his oft-professed stance of not to play for anyone but
Jackson. He has been known to change his mind, too.
</P>
<P>
   We have to figure that several key relationships here are beyond
repair, because it makes no sense for Reinsdorf to make drastic
changes. He has a good thing going. Additionally, one would think
the players might feel the same way. Just how bad can it be to be a
member of the Chicago Bulls these days, anyway? They are treated as
royalty everywhere they go. They win.
</P>
<P>
   We'll all have to wait, and the wait may be extended because of
this summer's labor situation. Reinsdorf can bide his time in his
box at Comiskey Park and watch Albert Belle, Wil Cordero, and the
rest of his irrelevant White Sox. He should know more than anyone
what it's like to run a sports franchise that operates in a vacuum.
He has one. Does he want another? Oops, I forgot. It's not his
call.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing saga of North Korean center  &UR; Michael Ri  &LR; has taken
another step in what he hopes will be the direction of the NBA.
United States and South Korean officials have agreed to meet next
month in Honolulu to discuss easing of sanctions against the North.
Any agreement out of those sessions could lead to Ri's
availability. Guess who's interested in the 28-year-old,
7-foot-8-inch center? The Celtics. General manager  &UR; Chris Wallace
 &LR; called Ri's lawyer last week. Wallace, who has seen just about
everyone on the planet, has yet to see Ri in person or on tape. But
he's intrigued. ``You have to take anyone seriously who's that
big,'' Wallace said. ``He falls into that
( &UR; Gheorghe &LR; ) &UR; Muresan &LR; -( &UR; Mark &LR; ) &UR; Eaton  &LR; category, and the hard part
is figuring out where he fits in. It's a little different even with
a European, but this is a first: No one has ever come out of the
Orient.'' Although Ri did hold workouts in Canada for some teams,
the Celtics decided to wait.  &UR; Rick Pitino  &LR; is a hands-on guy who
would want to be there to see it. And, Wallace said, it's always
preferable to see the player in a game or have him work out the way
you want him to work out. ``We'll take a look at him before it's
all said and done and see if it makes sense for us. I hope he's
legit.'' ... A foreigner both legit and available (we think) is
Germany's  &UR; Dirk Nowitzki &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who turns 20 Friday. He has applied for
the draft as an early-entry candidate _ the deadline to withdraw is
Wednesday _ and he could be a player. He's listed as 6-11 and was
supposed to work out last week in Chicago but had to decline
because of military obligations of which he was unaware. ``He's a
combination forward, young, raw, but with a lot of talent,''
Wallace said. The consensus seems to be that Nowitzki would be a
lottery pick. However, he instead may accept a scholarship to a US
college or take lots of lire to play in Italy. Would the Celtics be
interested in Nowitzki at No. 10? Wallace said it wasn't out of the
question, but, ``Rick has never had foreign players in college or
the NBA,'' he said, forgetting  &UR; Zan Tabak &LR; . ``The thing you don't
know is how they would fit into the system that he likes to play.
It's not like anything they are used to.'' There's also the
contract issue. Some Europeans weigh the NBA and opt to stay
overseas for more seasoning/dolce vita. ``We can't wait a couple
years simply to get a kid into a Boston uniform,'' Wallace said.
``We're not going to sweat the contract stuff.'' ... While we're on
the subject, two other foreigners merit a brief note.  &UR; Vladimir
Stepenia  &LR; is a 21-year-old Georgian (Soviet Republic) who is 6-11
and played center last year for a team in Slovenia. He also
participated in a European all-star game, and among his teammates
was  &UR; Dino Radja &LR; . Stepenia held a workout in Chicago and didn't
exactly leave everyone drooling. Plus, his contract situation for
next season isn't clear. ``He's maybe a couple years away,''
Wallace said. Another is  &UR; Radoslav  &LR; ``Rasho''  &UR; Nesterovic &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
played last year for Eurochampion Kinder Bologna (a team chasing
Nowitzki). He's a 7-footer too, a native of Slovenia, but,
according to Wallace, has a year left on his contract. ``He still
could go to a team with multiple picks (Orlando, Houston) or to a
team drafting in the 20s who can afford to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA imposes a lockout July 1, the players selected to
participate in the World Championships in Athens (July 29-Aug. 9)
will announce the next day their intent not to go. Then it will be
up to USA Basketball officials to get another roster and try to win
the gold medal, which gets them a bye into the Sydney Olympics. If
they don't, they may have to play a zone qualifier during the NBA
season (assuming there is an NBA season). But that's USA
Basketball's problem. The player agents are upset that commissioner
 &UR; David Stern  &LR; has equated the situation with ``trashing their
country,'' and one agent said he had been told that some players
already had been pressured by NBA security to participate. Sounds
like it's going to be a thermonuclear summer ... &UR; Kevin
Garnett &LR; , &UR; Bryant Reeves &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Corliss Williamson  &LR; represent the
only players from the 1995 draft lottery still with their original
team. Among the casualties of that lottery are No. 9 pick  &UR; Ed
O'Bannon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; last seen in the CBA;  &UR; Shawn Respert &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who may join
O'Bannon there soon; and  &UR; Kurt Thomas &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whose career hasn't gotten
off the ground because of injuries (he broke the same ankle four
times in one calendar year) ... The 76ers have had a slew of people
in for workouts and interviews, and they're all the same ones the
Celtics will be considering.  &UR; Larry Hughes &LR; , &UR; Michael Doleac &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and
 &UR; Bonzi Wells  &LR; were in over the weekend.  &UR; Nazr Mohammad  &LR; is due in
this week ...  &UR; Pervis Ellison  &LR; is concerned about his ankle, which
hasn't fully healed. Considering that he sprained it early last
season, there must be something else in there. Ellison has resumed
his weight training sessions with the maniacal  &UR; Bob Whelan  &LR; in
Washington, and also is scheduled to work on his conditioning this
summer ... Curious about the way the NBA decides who referees the
big playoff games? So were we. Here's the process, according to
league operations czar  &UR; Rod Thorn &LR; . There are 58 regular-season
referees, of which 32 are selected to work the playoffs. The field
is narrowed to 25 for the second round, 17 for the conference
finals, and 11 for the NBA Finals. There is an ongoing evaluation
process during the postseason, but, suffice to say, if a veteran
ref such as  &UR; Dick Bavetta  &LR; or  &UR; Joey Crawford  &LR; has a horrible game,
it won't stop him from moving on. The officials are paid depending
on what round they work, not on the number of games. And officials
are assigned only to games that are certain to be played; e.g.,
when the Finals started, only the first four games were assigned.
When Chicago won Game 2, the crew for the fifth game was notified.
For the first time in a long time, Thorn said, the NBA opted to
have three crew chiefs referee one game, the Eastern Conference
final between Chicago and Indiana. Of the 11 officials in the NBA
Finals, eight are crew chiefs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the zebras, Thorn was asked if he expected the IRS
hammer to drop after the playoffs. ``The government doesn't give us
any advance notice,'' he said. ``We heard they were going to do
something on April 15 and they didn't. We heard they were going to
do something before the start of the playoffs. They didn't. We
don't know.'' Thorn did say that while Stern has said the ousted
referees do not necessarily face a ``death sentence,'' he has heard
nothing further about rehiring them ... The Pacers know they have
 &UR; Rik Smits  &LR; and  &UR; Travis Best  &LR; as key free agent signees this
summer. There was conjecture that they also might have to deal with
 &UR; Jalen Rose &LR; . But, according to the team, that is not the case.
Rose signed a six-year deal when he was drafted by Denver and it
included an interesting ``out'' clause. It stipulated that Rose
could exercise the clause this summer but only if it made him a
restricted free agent, not an unrestricted one. The NBA did away
with restricted free agency in the last round of bargaining, so
Rose's clause is moot. He will earn $2.145 million next year and
$2.4375 million in 1999-2000, which is not a bad deal for a player
who, until this season, was generally deemed to be without a
position and without a clue ... We can fully understand the Lakers'
desire to deal  &UR; Elden Campbell &LR; . He has five years and $35 million
left on his contract. (Why is it that no one mentions his deal when
the talk concerns the genius of LA general manager  &UR; Jerry West &LR; ?)
But why would anyone (a) want him, despite his numbers, and (b)
want that contract on the cap? If West can unload him, then he is a
genius. He's also trying to unload  &UR; Nick Van Exel  &LR; (one year left
at $1.9 million), which may not be as hard a sell, although Van
Exel has some history.
</P>
</TEXT>
