<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-REVOLUTIONFIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION AIMING TO DOUSE FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Both teams are on streaks. For New England, it's a
five-game losing skid. For the Chicago Fire, it's a six-game
winning string. If the Revolution have their way, both streaks will
come to an end Saturday when the Major League Soccer teams meet at
3 p.m. at sure-to-be-soggy Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of injuries and red cards has spelled doom for the
Revolution over the last six matches. A combination of a renewed
offense and a rock-solid defense has fueled the expansion Fire's
recent success. Chicago owns the league's top defense, allowing
just 15 goals in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens in this league is at the beginning of the season,
coaches look at what they thought was going to work and then
there's an adjustment period and you go from there,'' Revolution
assistant coach Renaldo Capobianco said. ``You see a teammate wind
up from 20 yards out and score, and that helps your confidence that
you can take a shot you normally wouldn't take.''
</P>
<P>
   Streaks are nothing new for these clubs. New England dropped its
first three games, then ran off four straight wins before hitting
its current drought. Chicago opened the season with a pair of
victories and lost five straight before starting its current streak
of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think their defense is as good as people think,''
Capobianco said. ``I do believe that this league is very much _
with two exceptions, D.C., and Los Angeles _ this is a league of
streaks and when you're playing well, everybody plays with an
incredible amount of confidence. And when you play poorly, they
don't seem to go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fire's last loss was 3-1 against D.C. United May 2. Since
that time they have wins over Tampa Bay, Los Angeles (twice),
Colorado, Columbus, and San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   With Fire goalkeeper Jorge Campos in France with Team Mexico,
Zach Thornton, a former MetroStar reserve, has started all of
Chicago's games, posting four shutouts. Former Boston University
and Revolution standout Francis Okaroh is one of Chicago's top
defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working hard and working well together,'' said
Revolution forward Raul Diaz Arce (7 goals, 4 assists). ``That's
where we have to match ourselves and play that same way, working
hard together, to match their intensity. To be successful, we're
going to have to be patient and we'll get our opportunities. We
just have to take advantage of those and be consistent in creating
good scoring oportunities because they will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Peter Nowak (6 goals, 7 assists) is the Fire's best
scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to win,'' said Revolution midfielder Edwin Gorter.
``We've had empty hands the last couple of weeks and also we didn't
play that bad, but we didn't win. Everybody's healthy now, we have
no more excuses. It's time to start scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   With both teams paying particular attention to protecting the
ball, the rain-soaked field could cause extra problems. In the
Revolution's favor is that midfielder Oscar Pareja is making his
first MLS appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oscar gives us another person who is very crafty, very
offensive-minded, very experienced and he can maintain possession
in the midfield,'' Capobianco said. ``And on the attacking third,
he can spring other people as well as take shots on goal himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a winning formula for the Revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
