<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-TEAMMATES ON OPPOSITE ENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARC J. SPEARS  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ramon Martinez stood in the Dodgers bullpen and
chatted with Pedro Astacio through a fence during the Colorado
Rockies' batting practice at Dodger Stadium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the chain-link separation symbolized the pitchers'
relationship. The two close friends are trying to get used to
wearing opposing uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   When Astacio first made it to the majors with the Dodgers in
1992, it was Martinez, a fellow Dominican, who took him under his
wing, gave him a place to stay and told him about opposing batters.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, the two will face each other for the first time
when the Dodgers meet the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez compared it to facing his brother, Pedro, who is now
the Boston Red Sox's ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard because this is a guy who is your best friend,''
said Ramon (7-3, 2.88), who had Astacio over for dinner at his home
Thursday night. ``It is like when I faced my brother. You want
(Astacio) to do good and you want to do good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that I know it is going to be tough. But he also
understands that we are on different teams now.''
</P>
<P>
   After compiling a 48-47 record with the Dodgers from 1992-97,
Astacio was traded to the Rockies for Eric Young. Because of the
pitcher-unfriendly Coors Field, Martinez said Astacio believed he
couldn't have been traded to a worse place. Martinez also said
Astacio misses being a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Astacio is struggling with a 4-8 record and a 6.86
ERA. Aside from being hampered by Coors Field, Ramon believes
Astacio's mechanics need refining.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is just how the game is,'' said Astacio, who speaks
frequently with Ramon over the telephone. ``It is like facing Pedro
(Martinez) when he was with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I am in another city, I have to concentrate on where
I am at and win ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi in limbo: Dodgers center fielder Raul Mondesi was
scratched from the starting lineup shortly before the game because
of personal matters, according to a statement issued by executive
vice president Fred Claire. Mondesi, who hit his 15th home run on
Friday, was in the dugout during the game. He is expected to be in
today's contest and will also be re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi took batting practice and sat in the Dodgers' dugout
during the Rockies' pre-game workout. Manager Bill Russell also
said that Mondesi, who was not available for comment after the
game, is not injured.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.: For the first time in club history, the Dodgers will wear
their blue batting jerseys during games in their next homestand
(June 24-28) in honor of their annual Think Blue Week. On the road,
the 1944 Brooklyn team featured a pale blue uniform made from a
highly reflective fabric to improve viewing of the players under
the lights. . . . Three fans will have the opportunity to win $1
million if they can hit a home run at Dodger Stadium today. The
contestants, who have been receiving coaching from ex-Dodger Kirk
Gibson, will get three swings from a pitching machine beginning at
11:30 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
