<HEADER>
A8043 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ARUM-BOS     06-13 2612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-ARUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARUM THROWING JABS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Sometimes the pressure to produce mounts not
only on a professional fighter but also on the people around him.
Such is the case now for promoter Bob Arum.
</P>
<P>
   For Arum, these should be the best of times. He is handling the
affairs of the hottest commodity in boxing and, having realized
early the rising economic power of Hispanic fight fans, he has
catered to it with popular champions such as Oscar De La Hoya, Erik
Morales, and Genaro Hernandez as well as young prospects such as
Daniel Santos.
</P>
<P>
   But the 67-year-old promoter is facing a growing problem
satisfying De La Hoya, De La Hoya's father, adviser, and camp
followers, and his other champions, many of whom grouse that they
want ``De La Hoya money'' when Arum knows they will never see it.
</P>
<P>
   Discontent among those fighters over the obvious special
treatment De La Hoya receives from Arum is probably unavoidable,
but Arum now has a mounting and more serious problem because the
World Boxing Council welterweight champion and those closest to him
have grown weary of being criticized for the choice of opponents
like the one De La Hoya faced last night, a Frenchman named Patrick
Charpentier who will never make anyone in France forget the great
Marcel Cerdan.
</P>
<P>
   Charpentier was a mandatory defense forced upon De La Hoya by
the WBC, so neither Arum nor his fighter can be blamed; but since
De La Hoya won a controversial decision over Pernell Whitaker 14
months ago, he has not faced a single worthy challenge _ and he has
begun to hear about it in the media and in the streets. And he
seems to be looking for someone to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Like many great athletes, when such a time arrives, there are no
mirrors in their homes. The blame goes outward, not inward. De La
Hoya is not about to blame himself, and he can't blame his manager
because he manages himself, which leaves only one person.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I hurt my wrist and had the long (six-month) layoff, I
had time to ask myself what I wanted to do,'' De La Hoya said.
``Did I really want to fight or do something else? Did I really
want to prove that I'm the champion?
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose to fight, so I want to fight the best. I understand
Bob has a contract for Felix Trinidad but his Dad doesn't want to
sign it yet. (World Boxing Association champion Ike) Quartey is
having problems with his managers. I understand the promoters and
the negotiations, but those fights are out there and there's
pressure on Bob to make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a choice to box or focus on other things. Boxing is what
I chose. I've got four or five good years left and I can create
history. It's true that Arum is being pressured to make those
fights.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no coincidence Thursday that for the first time since De
La Hoya turned professional, both his father and his adviser, Mike
Hernandez, were introduced at the prefight press conference and
chose to speak. When it was over, not only De La Hoya was signing
autographs but so was his father, a chilling sight for any promoter
who understands the sordid history of father-son teams in boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Arum denies having problems with anyone but the company that
has paid De La Hoya millions to fight for it. In an odd manifesto
last week, Arum claimed his problem making a big fight for his
champion was not with the normal suspects _ rival promoters Don
King and Dino Duva _ but with his own partner in the De La Hoya
business, Time Warner's cable arm, HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put huge money on the table for those guys to fight
Oscar,'' Arum said. ``I've offered Trinidad $7 million and that's a
firm, firm offer. I've offered Quartey's people $3.5 million any
time they want it. I offered Whitaker $4 million to fight Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those offers are on the table and they can have them any time
they want. Whoever comes first gets the fight. But I can't even get
Trinidad's father to name a figure, and the people working against
me on the other fights are HBO. They're offering a lot more money
to Quartey-Whitaker because they want fights on HBO and know those
fights with Oscar are pay-per-view fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see HBO as my competitor now and it makes for a very
conflicted situation since Oscar is under a long-term contract with
them. Instead of helping us make these fights, they're bidding
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   While fight fans salivate over the idea of De La Hoya trying to
unify the title against Trinidad or Quartey, Arum has scheduled a
September rematch with Julio Cesar Chavez at De La Hoya's
insistence, followed by a fight with 154-pound champion Yory Boy
Campas in November. That would take De La Hoya through the end of
this year, and while Arum has been talking publicly about making a
match for next spring with one of the big three welterweights _
Trinidad, Quartey, and Whitaker _ he privately has already penciled
in such lackluster opponents as Oba Carr while accusing HBO of
working to block the big fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard of Bob saying that, I called and told him this is
a foolish spat and it's a one-way spat,'' said HBO Sports CEO Seth
Abraham. ``We have no argument with him. I really believe Oscar is
the best fighter in the world and Bob is the best promoter. Look at
what they did with Charpentier.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if Bob has an argument with someone, it's not with us.
It's simply not true that we blocked him from making De La
Hoya-Quartey, De La Hoya-Whitaker, or De La Hoya-Trinidad. This guy
is our bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fight we make at 147 and 154 pounds, I think about what
the implication is for Oscar. To us, he's Air Force One. He lands
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob never once even mentioned Quartey's name to us. The other
negotiations fell apart over money. HBO had no role in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arum claims they fell apart because HBO was offering more money,
but other sources say he indeed never sought to make a deal with
Quartey until De La Hoya recently began asking about him, and he
lost a Whitaker rematch through his own reluctance, not because HBO
paid Whitaker more to fight Quartey. In fact, Duva, who promotes
Whitaker, agreed to take less to try for a Quartey fight in hopes
of getting Whitaker a piece of the title back and improving his
negotiating position if a De La Hoya fight came along.
</P>
<P>
   Arum, said a source, ``couldn't make a rematch because the first
fight did big business and he tried to cut Whitaker's purse in
half. He attacked the guy and said it was a stinking fight and then
he offers him barely 50 percent of what he made the first time ($4
million as opposed to $7 million). He wasn't trying to make a
Whitaker fight and he didn't want a Quartey fight. He wants every
fighter in the division to sit around and wait for Oscar.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those fighters was another one under promotional contract
with Arum, former champion Terry Norris. People familiar with the
machinations the past year or so say HBO tried to make a
Norris-Quartey fight and was willing to pay Norris $3 million, but
Arum allegedly never relayed that offer to Norris's handlers
because he hoped to save Norris for De La Hoya, a charge he denies.
</P>
<P>
   As for Trinidad, industry insiders say offering him $7 million
may sound like big money but it probably is no more than 25-30
percent of what the pot would be, a split Arum has to know Trinidad
would never agree to.
</P>
<P>
   With guaranteed big paydays _ because of De La Hoya's loyal
Hispanic following _ for no-risk opponents like Chavez and Campas,
Arum, many believe, is simply trying to stall the bigger fights for
as long as he can to maximize income while minimizing risk.
However, that is the job of a manager, not a promoter, although
Arum counters by claiming there no longer are any risks for De La
Hoya at 147 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one guy is as easy as the next, then the biggest fights are
the ones to make,'' Arum claimed. ``Can he survive without them?
Yes, but in our opinion Trinidad and Quartey are as easy as Campas
and Chavez, so we'd rather have the bigger fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually they'll get made if we can keep HBO in check. I can
make a deal with King in a second for Trinidad. I can't pay
Whitaker $4 million any more because of the (drug) problems he's
had, but we'd pay him $3 million to fight Oscar. The fact is we've
got three offers out that are firm for big fights and whoever
accepts first gets the fight, but HBO is offering so much more to
Quartey and Whitaker that $3 million doesn't mean anything because
Seth wants some big fights on regular cable.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, HBO executives seethed at Arum's charge, but they
would say little beyond denying them. HBO Sports vice president for
programming Lou DiBella, who is usually effusive, would say only,
``That's Bob being Bob. There's no need to respond. He knows what
the truth is.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth is _ and historically it has seldom lain with
Arum in these situations _ the consequences of not making a big
fight for De La Hoya are what he soon may have to confront.
</P>
<P>
   If Arum is using HBO as a scapegoat for his inability or
unwillingness to make the major fights De La Hoya needs to make
history as well as money, he will pay for that down the road. As a
boxing insider said last week, ``HBO may not be saying anything
publicly but I know how they work. The sins of the father are
visited upon the son.''
</P>
<P>
   What that means to the future of Arum's other fighters is
speculative, but it is obvious what it will mean to him if De La
Hoya wakes up one morning and decides he has been forced to wait
too long to face his biggest challenges. His ironclad deal with HBO
will prevent him from blaming it, so he'll find someone else. Arum
knows that could be him.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always want to blame the promoter when fights don't get
made, but it's really the networks like HBO that tie everyone's
hands and feet,'' Arum said. ``If we were free to do a big
pay-per-view show with anyone, Trinidad would have been done a long
time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. I'm not mad at HBO. They're honest about
it. That's why I have no animosity about it. It's business. I can't
be angry. I can be chagrined. But we signed those long-term deals
with HBO because we wanted the money. We went for instant
gratification, so maybe Oscar and I got what we deserved. At the
time we signed, I wasn't in a position to tell him to forget the
immediate money because I knew we'd make more down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them options until he's 30 and now it's working
against us, but that's business. HBO is looking out for No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely it is, but it is not alone. So is Arum, a promoter who is
more in the Oscar De La Hoya business than the fight business these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya says the Chavez rematch came at his insistence
because he has grown tired of hearing his former idol make lame
excuses for why he lost their first meeting. ``Chavez is
personal,'' De La Hoya explained. ``That is my fight. He never gave
me the respect I deserved, so now I want to be the first to knock
him out. I'm very disappointed in the way he's acted, making
excuses. A lot of people are finding out the real Chavez. It's
terrible to find out my childhood idol is the way he is. I want to
punish him, actually. There'll be no more excuses for him.'' ... De
La Hoya claims his most dangerous opponent at 147 pounds is  &UR; Jose
Luis Lopez &LR; . ``He has fast hands and a good chin and he's very
powerful,'' De La Hoya said. ``He can really take a punch and he's
got the conditioning, too. I think he's the most dangerous opponent
for me in the welterweight division.'' ... A more confident De La
Hoya emerged last week, one that bordered on cocky for the first
time in his career. While talking to a packed press conference, De
La Hoya told his fans, ``As long as I'm in boxing, I guarantee I
will never, ever lose for you guys.'' ... De La Hoya's father,
Joel, was asked about the split between his son and trainer
 &UR; Emanuel Steward &LR; , &UR;  &LR; one insiders insist was forced by the father
over the son's objections. Smiling like a cheshire cat, the senior
De La Hoya said, ``We didn't have nobody (training De La Hoya)
before but Robert (Alcazar, his longtime friend). That was it, and
Roberto went to the Olympics with Oscar. We don't need nobody else.
We got the boxer. We don't need a good trainer.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are being explored once again to find a way to make
the  &UR; Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis &LR;  heavy-weight title unification
fight in the wake of the cancellation of Holyfield's bout with
 &UR; Henry Akinwande &LR; . The most immediate consequence of that
cancellation was that HBO withdrew its six-fight, $30 million
contract extension offer to Lewis when he didn't sign it by the
June 6 deadline. Abraham now says he's ``revisiting the landscape.
We didn't want to leave that deal on the table while we're figuring
out what to do next. We wanted to think about whether
Holyfield-Lewis can be made and then decide how to proceed. My
father-in-law,  &UR; Meyer Rubenstein &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is 76. He's a used-machinery
dealer. He always told me, `Time heals all wounds but time wounds
all deals.''' The words of Meyer Rubenstein had an ominous ring for
Lewis, who may have blown easy money by not signing the extension
when it was available ... Weirdness permeates all of boxing, so
it's nothing to find oddities abounding in the effort to make a
unification fight between  &UR; Roy Jones Jr. &LR;  and  &UR; Lou Del Valle  &LR; for
the light heavyweight title. Jones was stripped of the title when
he refused to defend it against No. 1 contender  &UR; Michael
Nunn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but when  &UR; Graciano Rocchigiani  &LR; beat Nunn, Rocchigiani was
declared ``interim champion.'' Well, the interim period ran out a
few weeks ago when the WBC handed the title back to Jones after he
blew out  &UR; Virgil Hill &LR; . What that had to do with poor Rocchigiani
is anyone's guess, but such is boxing. Which brings us to Del
Valle. When  &UR; Reggie Johnson's  &LR; shoulder injury prevented him from
taking a July 18 date with Jones, Del Valle accepted a unification
fight for big money but the WBA threatened not to sanction the bout
or to strip Del Valle if he takes it. A vote of the WBA
championship committee was supposed to happen this week and Del
Valle could, in the end, fight without the title because he knows
his biggest payday lies with Jones, so HBO is confident it will end
up with the fight one way or another. Failing that, International
Boxing Federation super middleweight champion  &UR; Charles Brewer
 &LR; reportedly is ready to step in ...  &UR; Prince Naseem Hamed  &LR; now says
he will not fight  &UR; Kennedy McKinney  &LR; until Halloween, which leaves
an Aug. 22 fight date open.  &UR; Arturo Gatti  &LR; is likely to fill it ...
WBC super bantamweight champion  &UR; Erik Morales  &LR; (29-0) has agreed to
fight former champion  &UR; Junior Jones  &LR; Sept. 12 in a Tijuana bull
ring ... A second hepatitis B test taken by Akinwande last week
confirmed the positive result that forced the cancellation of his
bout with Holyfield ... Holyfield would be the last to say he's the
next  &UR; Muhammad Ali &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but he does compare his 35-3 record _ with
wins over  &UR; George Foreman &LR; , &UR; Riddick Bowe &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Mike Tyson  &LR; _ with
what Ali did. ``If you put it on a piece of paper, Ali fought all
what you would call the great fighters in his era,'' Holyfield
said. ``In my era, I fought them all. We both have come back and
won. So when you look at that, we compare.'' ...  &UR; Orlin Norris  &LR; has
been offered a September title fight with World Boxing Organization
heavyweight champion  &UR; Herbie Hide  &LR; ... According to the WBC,  &UR; Floyd
Mayweather Jr. &LR;  (16-0) will oppose super featherweight champion
 &UR; Genaro Hernandez  &LR; (38-1-1) in Las Vegas Oct. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
