<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8044 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-REINSDORF-TEX     06-13 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-REINSDORF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS OWNER IS REVILED IN CHICAGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ There he stood, arms folded, champing a cigar in the
corner of luxury suite 31 as Game 5 of the NBA Finals ticked away
like a time bomb at the United Center. One of the most despised
people in sports _ certainly among the least trusted _ Jerry
Reinsdorf seemed oblivious to the approaching Bullmageddon.
</P>
<P>
   As judge and Jerry, the Chicago Bulls' chairman-owner says he
doesn't want to see the dynasty break up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not the end, of course it's not totally up to
me,'' Reinsdorf said. ``I don't want to be the person who breaks up
the Bulls while we're still winning.''
</P>
<P>
   As fans who have suffered from his past hypocrisy, Windy City
residents refer to that promise as ``Bull-loney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's shame on us now if we believe him,'' said longtime
Chicago sports fan Alicia Venstedt of Glendale Heights. ``Don't get
me wrong, he's done a lot of good things. He just doesn't have any
credibility left.''
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons that Bulls fans believe they are seeing the
last of coach Phil Jackson, Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and a
string of championships that could reach six in eight years tonight
in Game 6 against the Utah Jazz in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reinsdorf who, in the 1980s, voted against Edward
Gaylord's bid to buy the Rangers because he feared the new owner
would create a television superstation. Shortly thereafter, his
Chicago White Sox signed on with Chicago superstation WGN.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reinsdorf who, in the mid-1990s, pushed for a strike as a
way to halt escalating salaries. Shortly thereafter, he signed
Albert Belle to the richest contract in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reinsdorf who, last season, boasted of assembling a team
that would win the American League Central. Shortly thereafter,
with his team trailing Cleveland by 31/2 games, he traded four
top-flight pitchers for six minor-leaguers because, he said,
``anyone that thinks we can catch Cleveland is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Reinsdorf who, this season, talked about how he hates
wife-beaters, calling them ``cowards.'' Shortly thereafter, he
signed Wil Cordero, who had pleaded guilty to beating his wife.
</P>
<P>
   It is Reinsdorf, on the brink of an unprecedented Repeat
Three-Peat, who says he wants to see one of the most triumphant and
entertaining dynasties in American sports history stay together.
Shortly hereafter, fans reason, he will rip the beating heart out
of the team's proud chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't believe him, they're skeptical,'' said Jackson's
agent, Todd Musberger. ``And who could blame them? Right now he's
busy trying to put the responsibility of keeping this thing
together on the players. Meanwhile, he's doing nothing but break it
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf, who has turned the Bulls into a $400 million empire,
has supporters.
</P>
<P>
   His main cheerleader _ Bulls vice president of basketball
operations/general manager Jerry Krause _ has been at his side for
16 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take a bullet for him, because I know he'd turn around and
do all he could to save me,'' Krause said.
</P>
<P>
   Good friend and former Illinois State Sen. Bill Marovitz said
Reinsdorf's business acumen is misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the highest caliber person I know of,'' Marovitz said.
``A lot of people have a problem with the way things have been
handled, but look at his results. He is a shrewd businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to find a Reinsdorf fan at Jordan's restaurant,
where his image on a big-screen TV is greeted with the mute button
and boos. Or at Comiskey Park, where the lifeless White Sox are
struggling to attract fans. Or at Wrigley Field, where a Cubs sweep
of the Sox featured a sign that read ``Cubs Win! Reinsdorf
(Stinks)!''
</P>
<P>
   Said a Reinsdorf business associate: ``If Michael retires, I'll
be worried about Jerry's safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid criticism from people including Jazz owner Larry Miller and
Chicago Mayor Richard Daley, Reinsdorf isn't flinching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't affected me at all,'' Reinsdorf said. ``Like
everybody else, I'm just trying to enjoy the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Marovitz: ``This isn't eating at him because he has a game
plan. He wants this team back as much as everybody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Brooklyn in 1936, Reinsdorf is a lifelong Dodgers fan
with four seats from Ebbets Field in his office. A baseball fan at
heart, he made his fortune in real estate securities and as an
attorney before fulfilling a childhood dream of buying the White
Sox in '81. Adding the Bulls in '85, Marovitz said, was merely a
business venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd give up four of his basketball rings for just one World
Series,'' Marovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   He is a grandfather of six, but an ego-maniacal, cutthroat
businessman. He angered Chicago fans when he successfully
maneuvered to have Comiskey and the United Center built with public
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we took over the Bulls (in Jordan's rookie season) they
were in bad shape,'' Krause said. ``There was no marketing
department, an old arena and a bad team. Now look. But we get no
credit for what we've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do the Jerrys get little credit, they are on the verge
of getting the blame for the biggest breakup since the Beatles.
Only the Jimmy Johnson-Jerry Jones divorce after consecutive Super
Bowls compares with Bullmageddon, but this breakup involves
possibly shoving the greatest basketball player ever into premature
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is as endearing on our landscape as the Sears Tower,''
Daley said, adding that Jordan is by far the city's No. 1 tourist
attraction. ``And if given a vote, the people would probably pick
to save him.''
</P>
<P>
   The question on every fan's lips: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Why is Jordan being forced to seriously contemplate retirement
when he is at the top of his game and the Bulls atop the mountain?
</P>
<P>
   Egos. No doubt the Jerrys are salivating at the thought of
winning a title without this cast of characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have to fall apart just because one player takes
his uniform off,'' said Krause, responsible for acquiring every
player except Jordan. ``When Red (Celtics general manager Auerbach)
lost (Bill) Russell, he went out and got (Dave) Cowens. When he
lost Cowens, he went out and got (Larry) Bird and he kept winning.
Players don't win championships, organizations do.''
</P>
<P>
   Money. Reinsdorf is apparently tired of having the league's
highest payroll (more than $70 million this season) and not seeing
a profit to match the on-court success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very reluctant to try to second-guess them, but
nevertheless, it is bizarre that a breakup might happen,'' Miller
said. ``They are a true dynasty. To me, if I'm the guy making that
decision, if I can keep the thing economically viable _ which to me
means breaking even _ for the championship run that may still come
while this talent pool is together, then I'm going to do everything
in my power to keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   The path to apocalypse apparently goes directly through Pippen,
a free-agent-to-be whose animosity toward management is genuine and
long-standing. Tired of being underappreciated and underpaid, one
of the game's best defensive players is expected to entertain
lucrative offers from Phoenix and Houston this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any intention of coming back here next season,''
Pippen said last week. ``I'm looking forward to the opportunity to
go out on top, then throw my jersey in the trunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jackson: ``Scottie is the linchpin. A lot depends on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf said he will sit down with Pippen after the season,
but most are skeptical about him offering the four-year, $60
million contract it will likely take to sign Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Scottie is very, very important to Michael,''
Reinsdorf said. ``Scottie not returning could have an impact and an
effect on Michael's situation. We'll do everything we can to keep
it together. ... But it's not just my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who calls this season ``our last dance,'' said that
neither Jerry has congratulated him on advancing within one win of
the title and that the relationships have soured so that he rarely
speaks to either. After his contract expires in July, he will
likely be offered jobs in Denver, LA (Clippers) and Seattle, but
has often talked of taking a year off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this year is over, I'll probably break down and cry like
a baby,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who has won every individual and team award multiple
times, has said he won't play for a coach other than Jackson and
added last week that playing without Pippen would be ``a slap in my
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Although agent David Falk called the possibility of Jordan
playing for another team next season ``conceivable,'' not even
Jordan is sure of his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unanswered questions,'' said Jordan, who
this season suggested that Reinsdorf sell the team. ``To make a
decision now would be like walking in the dark, and I don't like to
do that. But if there's no Phil and no Scottie, I don't want to do
that. That's a sign of rebuilding, and at my stage, that's not
something I'm looking to do. I'm considering this to be the moment.
I'm not trying to twist Jerry's arm, though it probably sounds like
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, Jackson predicted that, ``All of us will
be forgotten in a few years, except Michael.'' Not so, according to
Jazz coach Jerry Sloan, who said the future will have a place for
Reinsdorf if this is the last running of the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they let this thing slip away, he'll be missing something
the rest of his life,'' Sloan said. ``He'll always be saying `Could
we have gotten one more, two more?' If you walk away from that it's
nothing but selfish. That kind of thing could haunt you in your
dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
