<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICOSOUTHKOREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO LEAVES KOREANS SEEING RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LYON, France _ How long could the nightmare continue? Ten, 15,
20 minutes the Mexicans had played a man up Saturday afternoon and
still they were losing to the South Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   How could ``El Tris'' explain this back home? Being held to a
scoreless draw by the 10-man yanquis and hooted off the field in
Mexico City last fall was bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   But losing to a country that had never won a World Cup soccer
match? Being all but out of the tournament before they were barely
in? Were the Mexicans, as their newspapers had been joking, really
the second sailing of the ``Tritanic''?
</P>
<P>
   Then Ricardo Pelaez shook them awake with a goal in the 51st
minute and Luis Hernandez, the blond angel, added two more and the
Mexicans, as their song goes, were singing, not crying inside the
Stade Gerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a great moment of joy for Mexico,'' exulted
Hernandez, after his goals in the 75th and 84th minutes pushed his
countrymen past the game but exhausted South Koreans, 3-1. ``We
didn't lose our heads, and that's why we won.''
</P>
<P>
   One rash moment _ a sliding tackle from behind by Ha Seok-ju on
Jesus Ramirez in the 30th minute _ cost the South Koreans
everything. Once Austrian referee Guenter Benko sent Ha off, just
two minutes after he'd put them ahead with a deflected free kick,
time and numbers were against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three to one may seem a substantial difference,'' conceded
South Korean coach Cha Bum Kun, ``but obviously, with 10 on 11 we
were at a numerical disadvantage. Unfortunately, chance was against
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the South Koreans hung tough, clinging to the lead for 20
more minutes before Pelaez banged home a loose ball off a ricochet
from a corner. And until Hernandez volleyed home a Ramirez cross,
it seemed the South Koreans might be able to escape with a point.
</P>
<P>
   They may be 0 for lifetime in this tournament, but the South
Koreans are the team everybody hates to play. They run and tackle
for 90 minutes and they keep coming. So the Mexicans knew they were
in for a bruising and breathless go. And after the way they'd
played in their spring tuneups, they couldn't be sure of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Though they'd easily qualified for the Cup, the Mexicans
finished their regional matches with four draws that drew disgusted
howls from their fans and press and got coach Bora Milutinovic
fired.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, when they watched Ha's kick bounce off the head of
defender Duilio Davino in the wall and past keeper Jorge Campos,
the Mexicans went into shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pep talk,'' said midfielder Jaime Ordiales. ``We said
that we were going to do everything in our power to get back into
the game. It was tough, but we rose to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as though the Mexicans hadn't been pounding on South
Korea's door all day. They had attacked with 10 men almost from the
opening whistle and had two gorgeous chances seconds apart in the
21st minute. But keeper Kim Byung-ji saved Hernandez's bid and
Cuauhtemoc Blanco's shot off the rebound was blocked by a defender
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   When Benko missed an apparent South Korean hand ball that would
have given them a penalty kick in the 50th minute, the Mexicans
began wondering if fate was overriding arithmetic. But Pelaez
pounced on the ball amid the hurly-burly after a corner kick
moments later, put it past Kim and slid on his knees, weeping and
thanking God.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Mexicans had only salvaged a point. They needed 3
if they hope to survive a group that includes perennial advancers
Belgium and the Netherlands, who tied, 0-0, Saturday. And as the
clock was running down, the South Koreans were still chasing the
Mexicans around the pitch like hounds.
</P>
<P>
   They could track down 10 of them, but not 11. Not indefinitely.
Finally, Hernandez slipped across the box and managed to tap the
ball just inside the post as he was running out of room. Ten
minutes later, with his back to the goal, Hernandez took a lovely
service from Blanco at the top of the box, whirled, and fired it
past Kim for the death stroke.
</P>
<P>
   When the whistle came, the depleted Koreans bowed their heads
and put their hands on wobbly knees. ``The red card was a harsh
decision,'' said midfielder Noh Jung-yoon. ``But that's the World
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans weren't complaining. The last time they played 11
on 10, their own fans mocked them and cheered for the Americans.
They'll take 3 points here any way they come, because most folks
have been settling for 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started very well, but it is only the first game,'' said
coach Manuel Lapuente. ``We've got to be very stable. Am I
confident? It is not a matter of confidence. It is a matter of
tranquility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-BULLSJA     06-13 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAFINALS-BULLSJAZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPS HAVE BEEN DOWN THIS ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ This isn't where Dennis Rodman wanted to be
Sunday. This isn't where any of his teammates wanted to be, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls couldn't close the deal at home Friday night,
so they'll try again tonight in the Delta Center. They may be upset
that they had to take an extra trip, but they have lost none of
their trademark confidence. They still like their chances against
the Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   History, if it means anything, still is on their side. Well,
sort of. No team has ever extricated itself from a 3-1 deficit in
the NBA Finals. And of the teams who came back home trailing, 3-2,
in the best-of-seven format, two of them, the 1985 Celtics and the
1993 Suns, lost Game 6 at home. The 1988 Lakers and the 1994
Rockets won both Games 6 and 7 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan talked after Friday's Game 5, an 83-81 defeat,
about how the road can be less burdensome, less worrisome, less
stressful. He's hoping for the same room at the downtown hotel, the
one with the piano. He won't have to worry about tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure we don't have to worry about the traffic,
either,'' he said. (Several Bulls talked about the brutal traffic
Friday. The Chicago highways make Los Angeles look like a deserted
Nevada road.)
</P>
<P>
   Jordan went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them deal with the scenarios that we just finished dealing
with,'' he said. ``Let's see if we can change places. It's tough. I
welcome the challenge. We've got a 3-2 lead. You know, sometimes
the body doesn't react to what the mind is telling you. You've just
got to go with the flow and forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah is not going away easily, which probably should surprise no
one. The Jazz already have looked elimination in the eye three
times this postseason and not blinked: twice against Houston in the
first round and again Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They had been humbled and humiliated in Games 3 and 4, but they
made the big plays to get the series back home. They play well
here. But they also lost once here to the Bulls and had to go into
overtime to beat them after having rested for nine days.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan pointed to a similar situation in 1993. The Bulls led the
Suns, 3-1, and everyone anticipated a Chicago win in Game 5. It
didn't happen. The series returned to Phoenix, where the Bulls
jumped to a big lead, lost it down the stretch, and then won the
game on John Paxson's 3-pointer and Horace Grant's rejection of a
Kevin Johnson drive.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on the road neither ruffles nor concerns them. They
realize they blew an opportunity Friday, but they also realize they
still have two chances left.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1993,'' Jordan said, ``I got on the plane to Phoenix with a
cigar and got everyone to relax a little bit. I don't know what I'm
going to do this time, but somehow, it's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Scottie Pippen, ``It's going to be very hard because no
one wanted to make this trip, especially the players. But we have
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone actually asked Pippen _ and we are not making this up _
if he wanted to get the series over tonight or in a seventh game.
Pippen tried the comic approach _ ``How long do you want to stay in
Utah?'' _ and then addressed it more seriously, as if he needed to
state the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want them to tie the series up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls will look to resuscitate Luc Longley, who has been
alternately dreadful and invisible. They have to assume that Pippen
won't go 2 for 16 again. Then again, what are the chances Toni
Kukoc will go 11 for 13?
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, meanwhile, was barely a factor in Game 5 after coming up
huge in the pivotal fourth game. He had only three rebounds in 24
minutes and was, along with Longley, ineffective in bothering Karl
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls haven't stopped Malone from scoring but, until Game 5,
they had stopped him from dominating. If he has, indeed, found his
rhythm, that could spell bad news for the champs.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing the Bulls want _ other than having to be here
Sunday _ is to be here for another three days. Rodman would get the
Vegas shuttle going again and Jordan might actually contemplate a
round or three of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Their reputation as the consummate, go-for-the-jugular closer
took a bit of a hit Friday. The Bulls didn't get it done in their
season finale in the United Center. They'll look for a different
ending tonight _ or face the prospect of yet another seventh game,
this one for everything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
