<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-OLYMPICCLUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC OLYMPIC CLUB SOMETHING TO SAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympic Club. San Francisco. History. This will be the grand
tableau when the 98th US Open opens Thursday at the storied Lake
Course, where favorites such as Ben Hogan (1955), Arnold Palmer
(1966), and Tom Watson (1987) saw seemingly certain victory turn
into disheartening defeat. Jack Fleck beat Hogan in a playoff,
Palmer's seven-stroke lead with nine holes to go dissipated into a
playoff loss to Billy Casper, and Scott Simpson ran down Watson.
</P>
<P>
   What does all this mean on the eve of the country's national
championship? Maybe it's Chip Beck's turn to claw his way out of an
interminable slump. He qualified Tuesday at Canoe Brook CC in
Summit, N.J. All we know for certain is that Olympic is short and
beguiling, with insurmountable rough and incredibly fast greens.
There also will be tight fairways, and the air this time of year
can be dense and moist in the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   When the final day rolled around 11 years ago, the skies over
Olympic were a deep blue and the Golden Gate Bridge was glistening
in the distance. Watson, who had won a dramatic US Open at Pebble
Beach on the Monterrey Peninsula five years earlier, seemed to be
in charge, but Simpson made three straight birdies in his stretch
run, and after Watson's shot into the treacherous 18th green spun
back, his putt to create a playoff died to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started out on tour,'' said Simpson that day,
``my aim was just to make a living for my family. This is a dream
come true. It was one of the best putting rounds of my life. I was
just concentrating on making a smooth stroke and, for some reason,
they went in. It was tremendously exciting. To win the US Open, I
can't think of anything bigger than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan and Palmer have left their hearts at this course in San
Francisco. Fleck birdied two of the last four holes to end Hogan's
dream of a record fifth US Open. Fleck won the playoff, 69-72,
after Hogan got lost in horrendous rough on the 18th hole. Casper
caught Palmer chasing Hogan's record. Neither Hogan, Palmer, nor
Watson won another US Open after their Olympic disappointments, and
Palmer and Watson can claim just a solitary US Open title to
Hogan's four.
</P>
<P>
   The defender is Ernie Els, the South African with the graceful
manner and seemingly effortless swing who has won the championship
two of the past four years _ at Oakmont (1994) and Congressional
(1997). He's ranked the globe's No. 1 player at the moment and
played this course competitively in the 1994 PGA Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very tough golf course,'' said Els. ``I think the
wind is going to play a big part there.''
</P>
<P>
   Els's style of play should be suited to the course as much as
anybody's in the field, but he withdrew after nine holes of this
weekend's Buick Classic with back spasms, leaving his status in
doubt. He rates Olympic as one of the toughest courses he has seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't too many birdieable holes,'' he said.
``Especially when it is firm. We played it in October and it was a
little bit wet. You could keep the ball in the fairways a little
easier. It all depends on the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's wet, I can see the guys maybe shoot 1 or 2 under par.
If it's firm and the wind is blowing, I can't see a score under par
really winning. We say this every year going into the US Open: `The
course might be the toughest ever played.'''
</P>
<P>
   The course may resemble Valderrama, the Spanish tract where the
Europeans retained the Ryder Cup last September over a US team that
included Masters champion Tiger Woods, British Open winner Justin
Leonard, and PGA champion Davis Love.
</P>
<P>
   It may be Colin Montgomerie's turn to win the Open. He was in a
playoff won by Els four years ago at Oakmont, and was there until
the fateful 71st hole last year at Congressional, when he missed a
5-foot putt to save par after waiting interminably for the twosome
of Jay Haas and Tommy Tolles on the nearby 18th green to finish.
</P>
<P>
   If Montgomerie doesn't break through, watch for England's Lee
Westwood to surprise. He's destined to replace Nick Faldo as that
country's best golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Woods's name will come up, but Els doesn't think it's his kind
of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this golf course really suits his game,'' said
Els, ``but we all really know he can hit 2-iron as far as I hit my
driver. So he can keep it in play that way, but he has got to hit
his irons his distances.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods withdrew from the Kemper Open two weeks ago, citing
shoulder problems and heading to Las Vegas for treatment. Butch
Harmon, his swing guru and instructor, just happens to be in
residence there.
</P>
<P>
   The player to watch might be Leonard, whose closing 65 at Royal
Troon in the British Open was arguably the best round of the year.
He also won The Players Championship and rises to the occasion in
the big tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   It is no secret that the US Golf Association enjoys bringing its
national championship to the Olympic Club, where the historical
background whets the appetite. The names of Fleck, Casper, and
Simpson will come up constantly; Simpson, in fact, has been granted
an exemption to participate.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Club. San Francisco. History.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Olympic Club has a heightened reputation because
of its setup, Augusta National's reputation suffered when Woods
dismantled it in 1996. Surprise, surprise. The course stood its
ground this past April, with the wind blowing in the faces of
golfers on the 13th and 15th holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was an unusual year,'' said Augusta National
chairman  &UR; Jack Stephens &LR; . ``The record was broken by one shot after
32 years. We don't think that's a great cause for alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephens stepped down, though, and  &UR; William  &LR; ``Hootie''  &UR; Johnson
 &LR; became the new chairman. So what was his first move? Changes.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said last week the changes came after consultation with
architect  &UR; Tom Fazio &LR; . The major alteration will be on the second
hole, a par 5 that is easily reachable in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting the fairway bunker back in play by moving the
tee back about 25 yards,'' said Johnson. ``The hole will continue
to be reachable in two but will require more accuracy off the tee.
We're shifting the fairway bunker to the right, making it a little
wider landing area. That area between the trap and the rough will
be about 40 yards. The spectators will be able to get back there
behind the tee. There is a road, and the tee will be fairly close
to the road. It's a beautiful spot, and I think that you're going
to find it very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Additional changes will be made to the 11th and 15th holes. The
11th green was washed out in 1990 by a flood that ravaged Rae's
Creek, so the green will be raised by 2 feet. ``We expect to pick
up some new pin placements on the back left of the green,'' said
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The fairway mounds on 15 will be ``cut down 80-85 percent and
clusters of pines will be put in that area,'' said Johnson. ``Again
this will call for greater accuracy off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're removing the mound to the right of the 15th green. This
will provide for more challenging recovery shots and it also should
give us an area there to put in a spectator viewing stand.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The qualifier at Canoe Brook was a bittersweet experience for
New Englanders  &UR; Kevin Johnson  &LR; of Pembroke (and the Nike Tour),
 &UR; Brett Quigley  &LR; of Barrington, R.I., Marshfield native and
defending Massachusetts Open champion  &UR; Geoff Sisk &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and Salem CC
professional  &UR; Kirk Hanefeld &LR; . They were part of a seven-man playoff
for the last three spots. And they were the four who didn't make
it. Johnson, who will be married next month, bowed out on the fifth
hole of the playoff. He left for Cleveland and this weekend's Nike
tournament. ``I'm hitting it real good,'' he said, ``but my short
game's poor. I'm playing a lot better.'' It's time to take the next
step at age 31. ``The short game's usually pretty good, but it
isn't clicking yet,'' said Johnson. ``It's better being in the
middle ground than the bottom ground.'' ... Quigley shot 77-69_146
and was the last to leave, on the seventh extra hole. He was on the
PGA Tour last year, just missed retaining his card, and performed
poorly in Qualifying School. He has been in limbo this year, but
has earned nearly $100,000. ``It's tough planning your schedule,''
said Quigley. ``Fortunately I've been ready when I've gotten in. I
made seven of the last nine cuts at the end of last year.'' He is
the first alternate out of Canoe Brook, but the pecking order of
alternates from the various sites has yet to be determined. ``If
they call,'' said Quigley, ``I'll be there.'' ... Sisk, who bowed
out with a bogey on the first extra hole, has played 13 events on
the Nike Tour and will defend his State Open title at Oak Hill
beginning June 22. He went 64-69-69-76 in the Nike event that
wrapped up two days before the Open qualifier. ``I finally started
playing well last week,'' said Sisk. ``I finally started putting
rounds back to back, but I had a very disappointing Sunday. It's
frustrating, when you need to play well and make some money. I
threw a lot of money away on Sunday. That's the game of golf. It's
a learning experience. Sooner or later, if I'm patient enough,
it'll come around.'' ... Hanefeld, who basically puts in seven days
a week in the pro shop at Salem, put it in perspective for the club
pros who nearly made it: ``I'll be in the shop at 6 a.m. tomorrow.
Business as usual.'' ...  &UR; Joe Kelly &LR; , &UR;  &LR; Brighton Center's most noted
raconteur, delights in retelling this story from the storied past
of George Wright GC. It seems the late  &UR; Eddie Kavanagh  &LR; of
Watertown became frustrated when he lost a ball in the dried-out
rough several years ago, before the course was restored. ``He
simply lit the rough on fire until he found it,'' said Kelly ...
 &UR; Harry McCracken &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the ageless custodian of the New England Golf
Association out of Charles River CC, will preside over the
inaugural New England Senior Amateur (Sept. 21-22) at Metacomet CC.
It's appropriate that the winner will receive the Harry McCracken
Bowl ...  &UR; Casey Martin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who qualified for the US Open, has
accepted a sponsor's exemption to participate in the Canon Greater
Hartford Open (July 2-5) at the TPC at Cromwell. It will be his
first appearance in a PGA Tour event.
</P>
</TEXT>
