<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTONOTES-IRVAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH OCTANE EMOTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ufdrop &LR; T &UR; xr &LR; riumphantly, and almost tragically, Ernie Irvan's
career has been closely linked with one track on the NASCAR Winston
Cup circuit: Michigan Speedway, the 2-mile, banked superspeedway
that will stage Sunday's Miller Lite 400.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, driving the star-crossed No. 28 Texaco Havoline
Ford Thunderbird for car owner Robert Yates, Irvan almost lost his
life when he crashed into the wall during a practice run at
Michigan. Then last year, in his final campaign with Yates and the
28 car, Irvan gained a new lease on life when he recorded a victory
at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   It perfectly punctuated Irvan's miracle comeback and left him
with an indelible _ you might say life-altering _ impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt I've changed somewhat as a person,'' Irvan
said. ``My whole attitude toward life has changed. I'm a more
patient person. I really pay attention to my family because it's so
easy for your family life to all of a sudden be disrupted. With my
accident, obviously, my family life got disrupted. I know that it's
very important, especially because of my two kids and my wife, to
be able to take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why Irvan, driver of the No. 36 Skittles Pontiac fielded
by MB2 Motorsports, would like nothing more than to pull off a
repeat victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a tough track to be able to win on,'' said
Irvan, who has not won a Winston Cup race since last year at
Michigan and is tied with Bobby Hamilton for 14th in the standings
with 1,400 points. ``I'd run second there before. But it never
crossed my mind that one of the places I was going to win at after
I came back was going to be Michigan. I probably thought that was
going to be a little far-fetched. I've been very fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he neared victory last year, Irvan said, ``There's no
doubt when I was going around the last four or five laps I heard a
lot of things going on (with the car). I felt like `Man, what's
going to happen now?'
</P>
<P>
   ``We had just come off a wreck at Dover not too long before
that, and were leading at the end of the race and slid in someone
else's oil and crashed. All those things were going through my
mind. I knew I was pretty lucky right there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it wasn't long before Irvan was out of a ride with
Yates, arriving at New Hampshire International Speedway as a
lame-duck driver. But he expressed no resentment over the split.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' he said. ``I feel like Robert did exactly
like he said he was going to do. He had a car for me to drive when
I was able to come back racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, I'm somewhat surprised how he actually maneuvered
and worked the whole thing'' _ taking on Dale Jarrett as a second
driver and then hiring rookie Kenny Irwin as Irvan's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as being bitter at Robert, I feel like he did
everything he had promised to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to bolster the sagging efforts of his two-car
Winston Cup team, car owner  &UR; Richard Childress  &LR; shook up his roster
last week, switching crew chiefs.  &UR; Larry McReynolds &LR; , &UR;  &LR; crew chief
for  &UR; Dale Earnhardt's  &LR; No. 3 Goodwrench Chevrolet, will now work
with  &UR; Mike Skinner &LR; , &UR;  &LR; while  &UR; Kevin Hamlin  &LR; will be Earnhardt's crew
chief beginning Sunday. ``It was a very difficult decision,'' said
Childress, whose drivers have combined for one victory, two top
five, and five top 10 finishes in 13 starts this season. ``It's the
toughest one I've had to make in quite some time. We were trying to
pick the pos-itives and negatives and see which would weigh out. I
think everyone, including the drivers, were ready for some type of
change. They were just sitting here saying, `What are we going to
do next?' Everybody ended up buying in on the change. It wasn't
what everyone wanted, but it's something that had to be done. It's
a change that had to be made.'' ... Jarrett, who made a quantum
leap in the last 10 races from 27th to a fourth-place tie with
 &UR; Mark Martin  &LR; in the Winston Cup standings, was fuming because he
felt a late-race red flag by NASCAR officials cost him a victory in
last week's Pontiac Excitement 400 at Richmond, Va. With 17 laps
left, Jarrett moved from fourth to first when the top three cars
pitted. Jarrett stayed out, gambling on making a victory gallop
with worn tires. But with seven laps remaining, NASCAR officials
unfurled the red flag and stopped the race to clear debris from an
accident. Instead of cruising around the track under yellow,
Jarrett was forced to wait for a restart with four laps remaining.
That enabled eventual winner  &UR; Terry Labonte  &LR; to bump his way past
Jarrett as the two drivers raced to the yellow flag when a last-lap
crash caused the race to end under caution. ``What hurt us most was
stopping with older tires and them having an opportunity to cool
off,'' Jarrett said. ``A used tire is not as good right there where
Terry and  &UR; Rusty  &LR; ( &UR; Wallace &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; had much fresher tires, so that kind
of threw our strategy out of the window.'' As for his run-in with
Labonte? ``I just think it's something you put in your memory bank
and at an opportune time, yeah, you may be a little bit rougher,''
Jarrett said. ``But it's not that I'm gonna go out and wreck Terry
Labonte. That's not the makeup of NASCAR at all. We're just gonna
race hard and, hopefully, one day I'll beat him.'' ... The
beneficiary of all the Richmond mayhem was  &UR; Jeremy Mayfield &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
surged to the Winston Cup points lead for the first time in his
career. Despite not having a victory in 13 starts, Mayfield leads
Penske South teammate Wallace, 1,868-1,843 points. Mayfield has six
top five finishes and eight top 10s ... Lycos Inc., the
Waltham-based Internet company, is the title sponsor of Sunday's
Lycos.com 250 Busch Grand National race at Pikes Peak International
Raceway in Fountain, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago,  &UR; Billy Boat  &LR; stood in Victory Lane at Texas Motor
Speedway and had his celebration rudely interrupted by  &UR; Arie
Luyendyk &LR; , who, after a subsequent all-night audit of timing and
scoring, was proven to be the real winner of the True Value 500k.
Last weekend, there was no such challenge to Boat's victory in the
Pep Boys Indy Racing League event at Texas. Boat, who put  &UR; A.J.
Foyt's  &LR; car on the pole for the Indianapolis 500, recorded his
first career victory in Foyt's Oldsmobile Aurora-powered Dallara.
``You just have to be able to put it all together on that one right
night,'' said Boat, who took the lead for good from runner-up  &UR; Greg
Ray  &LR; with seven laps remaining. Ray, a native of Plano, Texas, who
recorded his best career finish on his home track, said, ``This is
second place, but it is a victory for us. I can't say enough about
this small team (Thomas Knapp Motorsports).'' ... Hard luck
continued to plague  &UR; Tony Stewart &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who dropped into a tie with
 &UR; Scott Sharp  &LR; for the IRL points lead at 115. Stewart, who finished
dead last in the Indy 500, suffered another engine failure after
177 laps. ``I'd like to act down, like I did at Indy, because
that's how I feel inside,'' said Stewart, who won the pole in
record fashion with a lap of 224.448 miles per hour. ``But I don't
want everybody calling me a crybaby and everything else.'' ...
FedEx CART driver  &UR; Alex Zanardi  &LR; delivered Target/Chip Ganassi
Racing its fifth victory of the season with last weekend's triumph
in the ITT Automotive Detroit Grand Prix. Zanardi, the reigning PPG
Cup champion who has won three races this season, and teammate
 &UR; Jimmy Vasser &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the 1996 series champ and a two-time winner this
year, recently became the first CART team to be pictured on a
Wheaties box. ``Coming from Italy, I was not as familiar with
Wheaties as people in the United States,'' said Zanardi, who leads
 &UR; Greg Moore  &LR; in the PPG Cup standings, 113-96. ``Since we found out
we were going to be honored by being on a box, I really have come
to understand what an honor this is. People tell me, `Now that
you're on a Wheaties box, you've truly made it!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
