<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEILE HOPES FOR BRIEF FLORIDA STAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Todd Zeile always wished he could play for a
champion. He must have wished too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Here he was in the South Bronx, playing for a team the Yankee
Stadium marquee introduced as the ``World Champion Florida
Marlins'' but which was a world champion in name and uniform only.
Later that night, an electronic message board outside the ballpark
would report the score as ``Yankees 5, Tampa Bay 1,'' confusing the
1997 World Series winner with a 1998 expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins are that kind of club now, with a stripped-down
roster consisting of 14 rookies, a few cheap players and a $3.2
million veteran, Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pluses?'' the third baseman said in the dugout before the
game, talking about the effects of the May 14 trade that sent him
from the Dodgers to the Marlins, the trade Los Angeles knows as the
Mike Piazza deal. ``The pluses are what I'm trying to make right
now. I'm trying to !ital!make!off! this into a plus.''
</P>
<P>
   For Zeile, a product of Hart PONY League, Hart High in Newhall
(he played in the 1983 Bernie Milligan All-Star Game) and UCLA, the
best thing about his banishment to the worst excuse for a baseball
team is it shouldn't last long. The Marlins, who are downsizing,
will unload Zeile and his major-league-size contract just as they
unloaded four players to the Dodgers and just as they unloaded
Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, 32, is confident he'll be traded to a contender, and
because his contract runs through 1999, he believes that contender
will really want him and not just rent him. In the meantime, he
tries to make the best of a bad lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in the last week, I've resigned myself to the fact I'm
going to be here until the (July 31 trading) deadline,'' Zeile
said, a bat in hand in the Yankee Stadium dugout. ``Now I'm feeling
better about the situation. It's not home, but it's more
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   The pluses?
</P>
<P>
   It's a low-pressure job, that's one good thing, probably.
</P>
<P>
   And it's kind of fun to be the old guy on a team, the one the
rookies come to with questions like, ``What's to do in Chicago?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be wrong, but I think it's important for them to see how
I handle some adversity,'' Zeile said.
</P>
<P>
   And here's another plus: With any luck, by August he'll get to
see his family again. Which is the thing that makes you feel sorry
for Zeile even while you believe Piazza brought this on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza turned down an $80 million contract offer (knowing he'll
get more this winter). Piazza is a single guy living a male fantasy
and if the worst thing about it is getting bounced from Los Angeles
to Miami to New York, well, poor him.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile accepted !ital!less!off! than his market value in December
1996 to play for his hometown team and to raise his son and
daughter with his wife, gymnast Julianne McNamara, in Westlake
Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the personal side of the game and the business that's not
often paid attention to, and most of the time for good reason,'' he
said, careful not to sound like a complaining millionaire.
``(Signing for less with the Dodgers) was my choice and I did not
have a no-trade clause. That's the team's prerogative (to make a
trade).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the irony of the timing. I put the best numbers of
my career last year,'' added Zeile, whose 31 homers and 89 runs
were personal highs, ``and I was off to an even better start this
year. That simple fact is probably what got me traded.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers' May 14 loss to Philadelphia, Zeile was about
to drive home to the house his family was living in temporarily
between the close of escrow on the their old house and the
completion of their new one. Fred Claire asked him to stick around
for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw Fred in the clubhouse, I knew something was
up,'' Zeile said. The players had expected something _ not only
because Piazza's contract stalemate forced the Dodgers to seek a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team was floundering and we knew something was going to be
done. We didn't have a lot of guys who were doing what they were
capable of doing. We were scuffling scoring runs. Eric (Karros) had
just gotten back in the lineup but wasn't having the kind of
production he's used to. In the past, Dodger front-office people
were willing to give it time....
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sad, from the standpoint of a lifelong Dodger fan, that
the Fox influence showed in this trade. It was a move that would
never have been made in the O'Malley era. But Fox came in and paid
a lot of money and they want results.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubhouse trainers' room, Claire told Zeile and Piazza
they'd been traded. They had expected something to be done _ just
not to them.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, the lifelong Dodgers fan, thinks it was a good trade for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, a deal like that doesn't come along more than
once a millennium,'' he said. ``It remains to be seen, if you can
get two All-Stars (Gary Sheffield and Bobby Bonilla), a guy like
(Jim) Eisenreich and a guy like CJ (Charles Johnson). On paper it
seems like a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Good for the Dodgers. Bad for Todd and Julianne.
</P>
<P>
   He's in limbo. ``Dangled,'' as he put it. He waits for the night
Marlins general manager Dave Dombrowski shows up in the clubhouse
and asks him to stick around for 10 minutes. Trades to St. Louis,
Chicago _ Zeile has played for the Cardinals and Cubs before _ or
Texas have been rumored. Any of those would be fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   If he can't be a Dodger, he wants to help somebody be a
champion. Not help somebody tear one apart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 2204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
