<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPAR-FUNERAL-HNS &LR;      06-13 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPAR-FUNERAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FUNERAL OF MURDER VICTIM BECOMES PUBLIC EVENT TO DECRY RACISM
<TEXT>
<P>
   By RICHARD STEWART and T.J. MILLING
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
c. 1998 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
JASPER, Texas _ In a private ceremony that became a public event
Saturday, the family of James Byrd Jr. buried the man whose brutal
murder just outside his hometown became a symbol for racism and
hatred everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's pastor, a high school classmate and other local ministers
shared personal memories. They also shared the pulpit with a
senator, a Cabinet member and nationally known preachers who never
knew Byrd before he was savagely beaten, chained to the bumper of a
pickup truck and dragged almost three miles along a winding country
road.
</P>
<P>
   While those inside spoke of peace, love and healing, an armed
group of black militants marched and swore that any future violence
done to African-Americans would be met with violence.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny church, Greater New Bethel Baptist, which had 59 in
attendance last Sunday on the morning Byrd's body was found, was
packed with almost 300 mourners. At least twice that many sweltered
outside under a large tent.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Byrd's photograph sat on a simple casket flanked with
some of the flowers that filled four rooms of a local funeral home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson said Byrd's death so shocked the country
that it has caused all Americans to think about the ills of hate
and racism. ``This could very well change the state of the
nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson suggested that just as the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier
stands for all those killed in war, a special memorial tomb for
Byrd should be erected. That tomb, he said, could serve as a place
``for blacks and whites to rally, a tomb that says choose
redemption over retaliation.''
</P>
<P>
   He said racism is like glass in a wound suffered by the nation.
``We must heal the wound,'' he said, ``but we must get the glass
out of the wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson urged mourners to ``turn a crucifixion into a
resurrection.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas' U.S. Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, a Republican, said Byrd's
murder and his family's way of coping with it should be an example
to others. ``We are diminished by this act, but from the depths of
our pain, the fog of all our disbelief, we are going to emerge
stronger,'' she said. She praised Byrd's family for asking for
healing and justice, but not retribution. ``We have seen a family
tested,'' she said. ``We are better today because we have seen a
family tested like no other family has been tested.''U.S.
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater read a letter to Byrd's
family from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``People across our nation have been shocked and saddened by
this tragedy,'' Clinton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence and hatred in our society hurt us all, but few have
had to endure its effects as personally as have you and your loved
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater said it is clear that Byrd was brought up in a Christian
family. ``No hate lives in that house,'' he said of the family
home.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Kenneth Lyons, pastor of the New Bethel church, said
that when he first took over as minister of the Jasper church more
than a decade ago, Byrd asked him, ``What do you preach?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I preach Jesus,'' he said, to the shouts of ``Amen'' by some
of the congregation. ``The gates of hell shall not stand against
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be the legacy of Mr. Byrd,'' Lyons said. ``Preach
Jesus, because we've tried everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Other dignitaries in attendance included Houston Mayor Lee Brown
and civil rights activist Al Sharpton of New York, as well as U.S.
Reps. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., and Texas politicians, Sheila
Jackson Lee, D-Houston; Jim Turner, D-Crockett, and Nick Lampson,
D-Beaumont. Earlier this week Lee had announced that Chicago Bulls
forward Dennis Rodman had offered to pay for Byrd's funeral, but
the family had not fully discussed the offer. On Saturday, he added
that Rodman has now pledged $25,000 for a fund for Byrd's family;
Byrd had three children, one still in high school, and one
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen too much hatred, too much killing,'' Jackson Lee
said in front of the jail where the three young white suspects are
being held. ``We must be better and not bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 state and local law enforcement officers,
including Special Weapons and Tactical teams, were stationed around
the city, plus a contingent of FBI agents. The day passed without
violence although there were some tense moments when a group of
black men from the Dallas area, toting shotguns and rifles, marched
through the city.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee called for the commission on race relations to hold
a town hall meeting in Jasper in the coming days and asked the
federal government to take over the prosecution of the suspects,
Shawn Berry, John William ``Bill'' King and Lawrence Russell Brewer
Jr. Congresswoman Waters, who chairs the Congressional Black
Caucus, said crimes like this one should automatically trigger
federal involvement to ``ensure there is swift and tough justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the FBI is heading a multiagency task force
investigation into the killing, and federal authorities are hopeful
that they will be able to prosecute the suspects for a hate crime
with civil rights violations. That would mean the federal death
penalty if a conviction is won.
</P>
<P>
   A phalanx of politicians and officials joined Jackson in calling
for healing and reconciliation while decrying Byrd's slaying as
reprehensible and demanding the severest punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, 49, was walking along Martin Luther King Boulevard when he
was picked up by three men in a pickup truck early Sunday. He was
beaten and chained by his ankles with a towing chain to the truck,
then dragged for nearly three miles and dismembered in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Brother Byrd's body was torn, America's spirit was torn,
and we need to reweave it with equal protection under the law,''
Sharpton said. ``We cannot allow these young men not to be a
national example. This was not a crime against a person. It was a
crime against a people.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston City Councilman Jew Don Boney said too many people have
died as Byrd did, and he demanded action, not just prayer and talk.
Jackson Lee, who compared Byrd to Jesus Christ, called for a
renewed commitment to affirmative action programs. And state Sen.
Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, while praising the city's handling of the
tragedy, said it is an indication that ``something is still sick in
our society.''
</P>
<P>
   By far the most provocative statements came from a group of
armed Black Panthers, street gang members and a Nation of Islam
leader wearing black military-style uniforms. State police stopped
the group of about 20 men at the edge of town, and two came to the
sheriff's department to negotiate. They were escorted to the jail
to address the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black power!'' Khallid Muhammad shouted, his lieutenant
punctuating his words by loudly cocking his shotgun. ``Violence and
racism by the white man in America is just as American as apple or
cherry pie.... The white man is a cold-blooded murderer by
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad condemned Jesse Jackson as a puppet of the White House
and called on blacks to arm themselves for self-defense. He said
his men came to teach local blacks how to patrol and control their
own neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The group marched from the jail to the church, where Byrd's
funeral had been held earlier, and back, outnumbered 3 to 1 by
police and Texas Rangers with the Jasper police chief and the
Jasper County sheriff in the lead. A helicopter circled overhead,
and scores of media representatives documented their every step, as
they shook hands with blacks along the road.
</P>
<P>
   The few locals along the route were polite, but after a week of
spectacle, they said, they wished the Panthers and the media would
go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are they here?'' asked Charlene Renfro, who is black and
lives in Jasper. ``The (Byrd) family wants to heal. They need to
go, and let God take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching the group from the lobby of the sheriff's department,
one of Byrd's cousins wept with frustration and said, ``He would
not have wanted this. He loved people. He would have said, `Let's
come to the table and work this out.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of Byrd's cousins, Pat Butler of Houston, said Byrd had
always said he would someday achieve greatness, but he thought it
would come as a singer. Byrd was known around town for his singing
voice and his trumpet- and piano-playing.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said he would be pleased, and also a little amused, to
find out that his death is causing such a great national reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fitting,'' she said, of the reaction of those who
want his death to help people turn away from hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the armed militants, however, she said, ``Our family
is not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But many black residents from surrounding areas had come to
Jasper Saturday, and many of them seemed to feel a certain
solidarity with the armed marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel Bolton from the nearby town of Center, thought the march
was a good idea that would ``wake up a lot of people.'' And Barbara
Cloudy, also of Center, said it was a racist assumption that where
armed black people were, violence would follow. She said the men
were just ready to defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Barhitte of Jasper, who is white, said the march terrified
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an isolated incident that's got them stirred up,''
she said. ``When you see guns like that, it scares you.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad refused to divulge his group's future plans in Jasper,
calling the media ``white devils.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No wise general expresses his plans before the eyes of his
enemies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Police Chief Harlan Alexander said the militants have a
constitutional right to march as long as they stay peaceful. He
said they also have the right to carry legal firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is East Texas,'' he said. ``Almost every pickup you see
around here has a gun rack in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
