<SLUG> BC-SOC-METROSTARS-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROSTARS BEAT MIAMI, 3-1  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK BELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a game that was soccer's equivalent of an Off Off
Broadway show, the MetroStars defeated the Miami Fusion Saturday
night for the second time in less than a week, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   With the World Cup in full swing in France, Major League Soccer
is left to play on the periphery. The MetroStars (8-6), who are two
games over .500 for the first time in their modest three-year
history, trusted that their fans would turn out at Giants Stadium
after three top-flight Cup games monopolized television for six
hours. Some 15,215 people satisfied their soccer craving, but the
crowd was well below the MetroStars' 22,935 season average, which
is second in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   The threesome of Eduardo Hurtado, Giovanni Savarese, and Mike
Sorber accounted for the MetroStars' goals. Savarese scored 17
minutes into the game after a pass from Sorber led Hurtado through
the Miami defense. Hurtado's hard shot from about 20 yards bounded
off the goal post and directly to Savarese for the easy tap-in.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes into the second half, Sorber sent Savarese down the
right side with another long lead pass. Savarese found Hurtado
unmarked on the left side of the penalty area and his hard,
left-footed shot beat Miami goalkeeper Scott Budnick low to the far
post.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese added his second of the game, and seventh of the
season, off a pass from Sorber 10 minutes later. Sorber's three
assists in a game tied the club record set by Roberto Donadoni in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   A goal in the 88th minute by Miami's Nelson Vargas deprived Tony
Meola of his 17th career MLS shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to have a comfortable victory for once,''
MetroStars Coach Alfonso Mondelo said. ``And, you know, it's really
helped us in a way having World Cup games to watch two or three
times a day. It keeps soccer on our players' brains. It keeps them
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami (5-10) has lost six games in a row while playing without
the Colombian international Carlos Valderrama, who is playing in
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when we were learning to play with him, Valderrama left
the team to play for Colombia,'' Miami Coach Carlos (Cacho) Cordoba
said. ``We have lost him at a crucial moment. Things will change
when he comes back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
