A8234 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MCHALE-LADN     06-13 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCHALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NL WEST, KEEPING COOL PROVES COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers have won seven of 11 after Saturday's
loss to Colorado, but they never have gotten really hot this
season. That is what separates them from the top two teams in the
National League West.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres ran away with the division early, then
dropped to second this past week when the San Francisco Giants won
11 straight. The streak ended Wednesday against the Seattle
Mariners and now the Padres are back on top after winning five in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   It also ended with Giants second baseman Jeff Kent on the 15-day
disabled list with a sprained right knee after Mariners shortstop
Alex Rodriguez made a rough slide into the bag on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez knocked Orel Hershiser out of Wednesday's game with a
line drive off the pitcher's right wrist. He also had a hand in
Barry Bonds leaving Wednesday's game because of tightness in his
calf shortly after being struck by a Bill Swift pitch. Rodriguez
was hit by a pitch in the top of the first, possibly in retaliation
for Kent. Swift reciprocated by hitting Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Real pennant race stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The streak matched the longest for the Giants in 32 years, since
the 1966 team won 12 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants picked up four games and passed the Padres by going
11-0 while San Diego went 7-4. The streak was the longest in the
major leagues this season. The club batted .294, averaging 6.1 runs
and 10.2 hits per game. The Giants hit 12 home runs during the
streak, five of them by Brian Johnson. The pitchers posted a 3.03
earned run average, limiting opponents to a .242 average. The
starters were 9-0 with a 3.71 ERA. The bullpen went 2-0 with eight
saves and a 2.02 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was the Padres' turn. They lost twice to Texas to fall
out of first but rebounded with a 17-8 victory over the Rangers on
Sunday and a sweep of the Cincinnati Reds. The Padres sold 110,000
tickets for Friday and Saturday's games with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   They were in a position to take a dive. Injuries to third
baseman Ken Caminiti, right fielder Tony Gwynn and first baseman
Wally Joyner, coupled with early season slumps by center fielder
Steve Finley, shortstop Chris Gomez and catcher Carlos Hernandez
had helped the Giants wipe out the 6{-game lead the Padres held
over them little more than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Padres learned that Gwynn will probably be out a
week with a pulled calf muscle and that reserve catcher Greg Myers
could be out for as much as two months after chipping a bone in his
left wrist in a collision at Houston with Astros pitcher Sean
Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's slump overshadowed the fact that they're on a pace
to win 100 games and draw 2.36 million fans at home this season.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET HOMECOMING
</P>
<P>
   Jose Canseco, Toronto's 33-year-old veteran outfielder and Miami
resident, ruined the Marlins' chance for their first sweep of the
year when he hit two homers Wednesday. The second was a solo shot
in the top of the 10th inning off reliever Jay Powell that gave the
Blue Jays a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to show the crowd here in Miami that I still
have some pop left,'' Canseco said.
</P>
<P>
   The homers were his 18th and 19th of the season. The first was
classic Canseco, traveling over the 434-foot sign in dead center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day here was very nerve-racking,'' Canseco said. ``I
had about 50, 60 friends and family here and it was the first time
they'd seen me play. So I was nervous, but I calmed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Canseco had almost the entire Blue Jays' team and coaching staff
over for a pre-game barbecue at his 12,000-square foot house that
also includes a 5,000-square foot gym, ivory and Chinese art
collections and an iguana pit packed with four iguanas.
</P>
<P>
   WOEFUL WOHLERS
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox planned to limit Mark Wohlers to
non-pressure situations until his closer could regain command of
his pitches. He probably wishes he had followed through with that
plan Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux was three outs from becoming the National League's
first 10-game winner when Wohlers came in to pitch the ninth with a
5-2 lead over Montreal. But he walked the first hitter and was
pulled. Mike Cather came on and wound up allowing a game-winning
grand slam to Darond Stovall. Wohlers, eight for eight in save
opportunities but shaky for the past month, met with Cox before
last Sunday's game in Baltimore about the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll use him in certain spots and try to get the rust off,''
Cox said. Wohlers was angry Monday and said he should be treated
like any other player who's struggling. ``I've been in every save
situation possible since 1995,'' he said. ``I'm a closer, I'm going
to be a closer and I want the ball in the ninth inning. Since '91,
I've seen a lot of guys struggle. Guys in the lineup and guys in
the rotation, and they've been allowed to work through it.''
Wohlers' control has been so spotty, eight walks in 62/3 innings
since his return from the disabled list May 24, that Cox doesn't
feel comfortable using him in ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg, who replaced Maddux in the eighth inning, was
expected to receive most of the save opportunities until Wohlers
reclaimed his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's been struggling a little with his control. Maybe
if he's not in a pressure situation, it might be a better way to
get the kinks out,'' Ligtenberg said. ``I don't know if it's
mechanical or what. I think you've got to keep going to him because
he's certainly got the best stuff on the staff. He can be the best
closer in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   NO PUBLICITY STUNT
</P>
<P>
   Brad Radke out-pitched rookie phenom Kerry Wood in Wednesday's
8-0 Minnesota victory that snapped the Cubs' 10-game winning
streak. For Radke, it was his third complete game and first shutout
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But he was the forgotten one heading into this pitching matchup,
even though he won 20 games last year for the lowly Twins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That always happens. If you're a Minnesota Twin, you're going
to get overlooked,'' said outfielder Matt Lawton. ``It's like Todd
Walker. He's a great hitter (.335), but nobody talks about him. If
he was a New York Yankee, he'd be a poster boy all over town. Radke
is like that. I'm sure his day is going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Radke was so masterful that he actually had a three-pitch sixth
inning:
</P>
<P>
   Brant Brown lofted a fastball for an easy fly to right . . . .
Mickey Morandini skied another fastball into an easy fly to center
. . . . and Sammy Sosa, looking to homer in his sixth consecutive
game, was badly fooled on a hanging slider and grounded meekly to
third.
</P>
<P>
   Radke retired the final 14 Cubs in order, including Sosa on
another ground ball to third with the crowd standing to finish it
off.
</P>
<P>
   HE SAID, HE SAID
</P>
<P>
   Was there some bad blood last Sunday when Boston's Pedro
Martinez struck Mike Piazza on the wrist with a fastball? The two
were teammates with the Dodgers, and after last Sunday it sounds
like they never were very close.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was quoted in the Boston Herald saying, ``(Bleep)
Piazza,'' after Piazza questioned whether Martinez was throwing at
him.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza responded by saying: ``I thought it was pretty funny....
All the money in the world can't buy any class. I don't think
there's any excuse for language like that in the papers. Maybe he
should invest in some lessons in etiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who has a six-year, $75-million contract, then said,
``What class is he talking about? He's talking about class? He was
a millionaire since he was a kid. But I can tell you the fans can't
say anything bad against me. What class? Education? School? He's
not a better person than me. You can make your own judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, insisting on the last word, said, ``I think it's
ridiculous for him to make it into a background thing.... If he's
got a problem with me, he knows where to find me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT &LR;      06-13 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURYK MOVES TO NINE-UNDER IN THE BUICK CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., eliminated earlier, this story is now restored)  
 (HLW)  
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISON, N.Y. _ It was a long, rainy day at the Buick Classic,
the kind of day that tested everyone's patience.
</P>
<P>
   Players spent more time in the clubhouse than on the golf
course. Spectators spent more time watching rain than watching
golf. Twenty-seven golfers decided they had better things to do and
withdrew, while two others were disqualified for missing tee times.
</P>
<P>
   However, when second-round play finally resumed after a rain
delay of almost six hours, Jim Furyk took advantage of the soft
greens, firing at pins and seizing the lead before play was
suspended by darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a sizzling eight-under-par 63, the best round of the
tournament so far, Furyk moved to nine under for the tournament
(133) and took a one-stroke lead over Kevin Sutherland, the
first-round leader. J.P. Hayes was alone in third place at seven
under par, with five holes still left to finish in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 26 players were still on the course when play was
suspended, and they will return to complete the second round at 8
a.m. on Sunday. A decision will be made Sunday on whether to
shorten the tournament to 54 holes. With the U.S. Open starting on
Thursday in San Francisco, players are eager to make the
cross-country trip, and they do not want to stay until Monday. And
with a possibility of more rain on Sunday, the tournament would
probably be fortunate to get 54 holes in.
</P>
<P>
   For Furyk, one of the game's most consistent players, it was
another example of how low he can go when he finds a groove. In
March at the Doral-Ryder Open, Furyk shot a 10-under par 62 in
windy conditions, one of the best rounds on tour this year.
Saturday's round was also impressive, as Furyk sustained momentum
and concentration despite the delays and miserable conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wake up in the morning, look outside and hope it's an
ugly day, but I've shot some good rounds in bad conditions,'' Furyk
said. ``I don't really complain or get a bad attitude. And when you
get a day like this, it's easier to pick up shots. When you get
perfect weather, everyone is shooting the lights out.''
</P>
<P>
   Furyk has six top 10 finishes this year, including fourth place
at the Masters and second place at the Mastercard Colonial. But he
has not won since the 1996 United Airlines Hawaiian Open, and he
hoped that his drought was about to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you win a golf tournament it helps your confidence,
but whether I win or not, I have a tough test ahead of me next
week,'' said Furyk, whose 63 was one shot off the tournament record
of 62 set by Jimmy Wright in 1976. ``But I'm not looking ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Fleisher, who will turn 50 in October, also enjoyed a
strong day, shooting his second consecutive 68 to move to six under
par, just three strokes off the lead. Fleisher is preparing for the
Senior PGA Tour, which he referred to as ``life after death.'' And
while his only victory on the PGA Tour came in the New England
Classic in 1991, he proved Saturday that he can still compete with
the younger generation when he is sharp.
</P>
<P>
   After a half-hour fog delay in the morning, play was stopped by
rain and lightning at 11:35 a.m., and did not resume until 5:30
p.m. The first delay occurred when Furyk was about to tee off on
the first hole, and the second delay came when he was on the eighth
green. But when he returned to the course, he was in a zone. His
bogey-free round included eight birdies, and he shot a 31 on the
back nine. He made a 50-foot putt for birdie at No. 11 to keep his
momentum going, but for the most part, he relied on accurate drives
and approach shots that left him short putts for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   While Furyk is not one of the tour's longest hitters, he
consistently hits fairways, and his putting stroke is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sutherland shot a one-under-par 70 Saturday after
opening with a 64. So while Sutherland is still in contention,
Furyk will start Sunday as the man to beat, no matter how many
holes are left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure guys don't want to play Monday, but I have to do
whatever the tour decides,'' Furyk said. ``I can't really control
that. I just have to keep concentrating on my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
