u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-MEXICO-H     06-13 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-MEXICO-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mexico rewards fans with stirring triumph
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LYON, France _ They began the show about seven hours before the
5:30 p.m. World Cup kickoff _ thousands of them, all over town,
``warming up,'' as the fellow standing in the middle of the
Bellecour plaza and holding a half-empty bottle of tequila called
it.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast with Jose Cuervo.
</P>
<P>
   The remarkable turnout of Mexican faithful here was nothing if
not enthusiastic. It was nothing if not truly faithful.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican fans were an awesome sight around town and at scenic
44,000-seat Stade Gerland, loudly singing the national anthem in
unison, chanting, screaming and filling probably 35,000 of the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so happy seeing my Mexican people in the stands,''
midfielder Alberto Garcia Aspe said. ``To hear them and see them
when we're so far from home, it was something I won't forget my
entire life. They probably broke open their wallets to get here.
They came a long way for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mexico's team, seemingly embattled and beaten in recent
weeks, came a long way during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's stunningly impressive 3-1 victory over South Korea in
a Group E opener was nothing if not appropriate compensation for a
legion of Mexican fans expecting the worst, but hoping for the
best.
</P>
<P>
   They got Mexico's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a big step forward today,'' said forward Luis
Hernandez, who scored two of Mexico's goals. ``To walk out there
and see the stands in nothing but red, white and green was great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did they all come from?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Mexico's fans seemed to attack Stade Gerland from every
direction, much like the previously struggling Mexican team did in
an unexpected show of force and cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks preceding Saturday's game, which some expected
South Korea to win, Mexico looked frustrated and in disarray,
losing to a pair of Under-23 teams and being routed 5-2 by Norway.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican team also seemed to fall into a state of transition
at the worst of times, after firing coach Bora Milutinovic and
replacing him with Manuel Lapuente, who caught more criticism than
Milutinovic ever did.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, everything turned out beautifully for the
Mexicans, who turned a 1-0 halftime deficit, which came thanks to
an unlucky bounce off one of their player's head, into domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We improved today,'' said Lapuente, whose team gained three
points with group matches remaining against Belgium and the
Netherlands. ``We can't be confused because it was just one step.
But I'm happier today than I was yesterday. I'm happier today than
I was last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it would have been difficult to find anyone who could
believe the Mexican team would so control a South Korean squad
known for tough defense and protecting leads.
</P>
<P>
   And because South Korea took a 1-0 lead in the first half when a
free kick from 30 yards away bounced off Mexico's Duilio Davino's
head and into the net, South Korea seemed to be in perfect shape to
pack the defense and take the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they scored that goal, it was difficult on all of us,''
Hernandez said. ``We felt our hearts fall. We were disappointed
because we were playing better than them, but the good thing was we
didn't lose our heads. We stayed determined.''
</P>
<P>
   And two minutes after the goal, Mexico caught the break that
seemed to launch it into high gear. Ha Seok-ju, who scored South
Korea's goal, tackled Jesus Ramirez hard from behind and earned a
red card from referee Gunter Benko of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico immediately began pushing the ball forward with the
one-man advantage. From that point, Mexico outshot South Korea 12-3
and scored all three goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're losing and playing better than the other team, you
can go crazy trying to score and tie it,'' Hernandez said. ``But we
stayed in control and we gained confidence after (the red card).
That's what did it for us. Offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The tying goal came off a corner kick, when substitute Ricardo
Pelaez nicked the ball on a header attempt but snared the rebound
and slammed it into the net in the 51st minute.
</P>
<P>
   Next came an impressive ad-lib goal by Hernandez, who trapped a
pass too close to the right post to get off a strong kick but
managed to chip the ball with his heel between the upright and
Korean goalie Kim Byung-ji in the 75th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to win the Cup, there's no other reason to come,''
Hernandez said. ``That's why we're here, to win. You do whatever it
takes so long as you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez's second goal, in the 84th minute, provided the
insurance that sent the Mexican faithful into a frenzy again. It
was more of a conventional blast from outside the box the keeper
could not handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played this well in a while,'' Hernandez said.
``(Friday) we talked about playing our best game and we had high
expectations. There are some people who don't think we have a very
good team. But we know we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely has Mexico looked better than it did Saturday. Besides
the 12-3 shots edge over the final 60-plus minutes, Mexico
dominated ball possession even before the red card, earning more
corner kicks, more shots and getting two nice saves from goalie
Jorge Campos.
</P>
<P>
   The victory also was Mexico's first in a World Cup tournament in
Europe. In eight previous World Cup games on European soil, Mexico
had lost five and tied three. They had been outscored 18-4.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday was a different show _ in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory, many of Mexico's fans waited outside the
stadium doors to cheer their heroes even more. In the train
stations, the subways, the plazas, the cheering went through the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a day that all of Mexico needed,'' Hernandez said.
``You could tell when we were struggling that we had it in us to
play better. Today we played very good. Maybe our luck is
changing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
