u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-13 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Jazz tries to take Bulls by the horns
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ It's funny how the road to immortality can be
marred by the occasional pothole of imperfection.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan and the Chicago Bulls will go down in history as
the greatest sports dynasty of the '90s and one of the best ever.
But even Jordan isn't immune to failure.
</P>
<P>
   Or doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And, rest assured, doubt is precisely what is creeping into the
heads of Jordan and the rest of the Bulls as the NBA Finals
switches back to Utah's Delta Center tonight. The Great Salt Fakes,
as they had been called in Chicago before Game 5, now have more
than a glimmer of hope.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying that Chicago still has control of the series,
leading 3-2. The Bulls have two chances to win one and even though
they have to win their sixth title in eight years on Utah's court,
it is there series to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz would have to do what no team has done before in the
NBA Finals _ come back from a 3-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, trying to keep their reputation as a confident,
too-cool-to-lose squad, believes the 83-81 hiccup in Game 5 was
just that _ a one-time aberration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody should remember it was a two-point win by the
Jazz,'' Chicago coach Phil Jackson said. ``You don't want to throw
out the baby with the bath water. We're fine. It's not a dramatic
thing that we lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Dramatic? No. Surprising? A little. Momentum-shifting? No doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to make the trip back to Utah,'' said Scottie
Pippen, who came up 2-for-16 small in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Too late. The Bulls were beaten convincingly in the second half
of Game 5 and therefore will have to prove their greatness again on
somebody else's court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still kicking,'' John Stockton said. ``We're going back
home, something we worked hard for all season long.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is no place in the NBA more difficult to play at than
the Delta Center. It's louder, more raucous and hungrier than any
other arena, even Chicago's United Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz is 8-2 at home during the playoffs, although it bungled
Game 2 there against the Bulls. Now that Utah has kept its foot
wedged between the Bulls and the door to the throne room, Sloan's
troops expect more from themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go home now with the home-court advantage,'' Utah center
Greg Ostertag said. ``We've played pretty well at home this year. I
think we're kind of anticipating a different attitude there.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if Ostertag would have a little different
attitude. He was benched in favor of Antoine Carr in Game 5,
basically because Carr ``can catch the basketball,'' coach Jerry
Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the third quarter, they started Carr and he really was the
difference in the game outside of Malone,'' Jackson said. ``He was
their fourth option coming off the bench, and they finally found
one that did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr's contributions helped. But the two things that made the
biggest difference in Game 5 were Malone's 39-point eruption and
the Jazz's ability to confound Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Bryon Russell, who has been a misfit on offense this series,
handled Jordan virtually throughout the game and he did a nice job
of keeping a hand in his face. Jordan shot 9-for-26 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They switched and put him on me continuously,'' Jordan said.
``No (Jeff) Hornacek at all, which was one of the adjustments they
made. Now we'll make adjustments going into the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's will to win was, for one night, matched by Malone. He
torched Luc Longley and Dennis Rodman with equal disregard.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has been known for his ability to hit hot streaks that
last for weeks. And since there's only a maximum of four more days
left in the Finals, the Bulls have to be concerned that Malone took
an initial step into a zone on Friday and will continue there
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when we're good, that's what we do,'' said Stockton of
Malone's big Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Pippen had been a legitimate MVP candidate in the
series before he laid his big egg Friday. His shooting was pitiful,
although he did have 11 rebounds to go with 11 assists. If he had
made a few shots, the Bulls would have been crowned by now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pippen has to hope he's not starting a stretch where he
can't find the basket. His career has been peppered by stretches
where his shooting deserts him.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, however, said he will demand that his team not panic,
that the Bulls remember that they played the Jazz well in both
games in Utah to start this series. All they need is one more
supreme effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tough night (in Game 5),'' he said. ``They were very
good with their hands, stripping the ball. They were quick to the
ball and Malone got going. But we were game. And we had our
opportunities right to the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``They matched us small ball, so to speak, with Malone starting
at center and Carr playing a lot. And we got a little enchanted
with the 3-point line. Twenty shots is a little much for us as a
team from the 3-point line.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3-point line has been a strong ally for the Bulls throughout
the series, not only because they've been able to make those shots,
but because the Jazz hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5, the Jazz fired up only five shots from downtown,
making one.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. Maybe Utah has stumbled onto something.
</P>
<P>
   Playing smart. Playing sensational, helping defense. Fighting
every step of the way. Not settling for the easy way out, like
shooting 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a do-or-die situation, you have to scratch and
claw,'' Hornacek said. ``We can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes they can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
