</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVESNOTE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mazzone sits down with Wohlers, Cather
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone didn't waste any
time doing some damage control after Friday night's bullpen fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Mazzone spoke privately with both Mark Wohlers and
Mike Cather, the pair making a mess of the ninth inning as Montreal
overcame a three-run deficit to win 7-5. Wohlers opened the inning
with a walk, was pulled and Cather came on and eventually gave up a
grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Mark that we're not giving up on him,'' Mazzone said.
``Mike answered his own question. He said he was out there trying
to strike everyone out and as long as I have known him he has been
a guy that tries to get ground balls. When you are trying to strike
everyone out, you are putting too much pressure on yourself, trying
to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers is the biggest concern because it's doubtful this club
can win it all without a dominant closer Mazzone said the problem
with Wohlers is he can not get comfortable with his release point
of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying different things,'' Mazzone said. ``I'm not smart
enough to give you a timetable on when he will feel comfortable. It
might be overnight, it might be a couple of weeks. I just know that
the key is to get Mark in there and get him doing well so he walks
away feeling good. This is difficult emotionally on him.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the problems of the bullpen, it doesn't appear the
Braves are going to make any moves outside the organization to
improve it. At least not now.
</P>
<P>
   When general manager John Schuerholz was asked about the bullpen
Saturday, he said, ``It's a question that comes after a bad night
... it's like the vultures. I think they will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has been talking to other clubs about bullpen help,
Schuerholz said emphatically, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   That may change if there are a few more nights like Friday. One
player the Braves might be able to get is Reds closer Jeff Shaw,
who is third in the league with 17 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Announcer DL
</P>
<P>
   Braves announcer Skip Caray remains at his home with a back
injury and could be out for a while. The Braves replaced Caray
Friday night with TNT basketball studio announcer Ernie Johnson
Jr., but on Saturday they had to make another addition because Joe
Simpson missed the game to attend his daughter's high school
graduation. So Daron Sutton, the son of Braves announcer Don
Sutton, joined his father in the radio booth while Johnson and Pete
Van Wieren did television the entire game. Speaking of Johnson, he
has a busy schedule ahead of him with the NBA draft on June 24 and
next month's Goodwill Games. But listening to Johnson Friday, it
was hard to tell he hasn't done baseball in a while. Like his
father Ernie Sr. he is the consummate professional. As far as the
Suttons, it was their first major league game together and said the
veteran Don, ``So why am I nervous?''
</P>
<P>
   Interleague numbers
</P>
<P>
   The first segment of interleague play is over and the National
League won 43-41. The Braves, which split their six games, led all
teams in homers with 11 while Texas had the best batting average
(.318). Interestingly, the Diamondbacks scored the most runs (41)
while the Mets had the best ERA (2.13). Braves first baseman Andres
Galarraga hit four homers in interleague games as well as Sammy
Sosa for the Cubs and Mo Vaughn for Boston. Galarraga was also tops
in RbIs with 11 along with Albert Belle of the White Sox. The best
average was Anaheim's Darin Erstad (.625).
</P>
<P>
   Neagle the TV star
</P>
<P>
   Denny Neagle, who is doing a 30-minute television show with
Dothan (Al.) media personality David Meckley, is drawing good
reviews. Currently, the show can be seen just in Alabama, but
Meckley said that Atlanta-based cable outlet Media One has asked
for tapes which means it may be on the air here later this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
