<HEADER>
A8250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORDON-COX     06-13 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORDON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeff Gordon: The man nascar fans love to hate
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- This was supposed to be a treat for Winston Cup fans.
The drivers in last weekend's NASCAR race at Richmond were
introduced and paraded slowly around the track in an open
convertible.
</P>
<P>
   As Jeff Gordon reached the backstretch, David Watson cupped his
hands to his lips and let out a prolonged, ``Boooooo.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's a jerk,'' Watson explained. ``Because he wins too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the 103,000 fans at the track echoed those
sentiments. By the time Gordon reached pit road, he had been booed
in every section of the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours later, Gordon's race ended early, when Rusty Wallace
bumped Gordon's car and sent it spinning into the wall. When Gordon
climbed out of his crumpled vehicle, the fans went wild, gleefully
jumping up and down with fists in the air, as if their team had
just scored the winning touchdown in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon claimed he didn't hear the boos. After two years of this
kind of treatment, he has become numb to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really notice their reaction,'' Gordon said several
days later. ``I wouldn't pay any attention to it, if I did. Dale
Earnhardt once told me, 'Just listen for the noise, wave and
smile.' There are some drivers who don't get any reaction. I look
at it as the price of success.''
</P>
<P>
   Success has never been a problem for the 27-year-old Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first Winston Cup title at age 24. He added another
championship last year. In fact, since 1995, Gordon has become a
dominant figure in the sport, with 30 victories and 67 top-five
finishes.
</P>
<P>
   That type of success in any sport normally breeds hero-worship.
But not in NASCAR. Fans boo his introduction; they boo his frequent
victories; they cheer his misfortune. They attack him from the
Internet, where 10 Web sites are devoted to Gordon-bashing.
</P>
<P>
   So what has Gordon done to deserve this? Fans say he wins too
often; he's too young to dominate NASCAR; he whines too much; he's
reckless on the track; and he's too clean-cut for the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they want any new, young guy to dominate,'' said
veteran driver Darrell Waltrip, who went through a similar
experience in the 1970s, when he began winning big on the NASCAR
scene. ``When somebody comes in and starts to beat their heroes,
they're basically beating that fan. It's like he's going up and
beating that fan up real bad. So they react to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as the boos began to grow, Gordon seemed mystified.
``In a way, I feel like I understand it,'' he said, ``and in other
ways, I feel like I don't.'' In 1998, he has become all too
familiar with the sounds.
</P>
<P>
   He said he isn't hurt by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if somebody comes up to my face and I'm with my wife,
then I think that's taking it a little too far,'' he said. ``But
that doesn't really happen very often, if any. You just grit your
teeth and say, 'Hey, it's not personal.' They don't even know me or
my wife. These fans are very unique, very loyal to their driver,
their sponsor, to their manufacturer. Sometimes they have strange
ways of showing it. I don't think there needs to be a reaction by
me. I just kind of let it roll off my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon takes solace in the fact that he does have support in
some circles. But that support group often is dwarfed by the
critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who cheer for me, because I know the
numbers in my fan club, about 20,000,'' Gordon said. ``I know a lot
of people are buying T-shirts and hats and things. But there are
people out there who don't pull for me, too. I don't expect
everybody in the grandstand to be a fan. As long as I'm winning
races and we're doing what we're doing on the race track, I'm
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the anti-Gordon fans are miserable.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's qualifying in Richmond, Travis Womble wore his
special T-shirt, made by a friend. It had the No. 24 (Gordon's car
number) on the front with a circled banned sign. ``Anybody But
Jeff!!'' was written on the back. Womble was one of several
volunteer firefighters from nearby Mechanicsville, who were sitting
high in Turn 4 to cheer their favorites, Rusty Wallace and Dale
Earnhardt. They also came to vent on Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hate Gordon,'' Womble said. ``We just can't stand him.
He wrecks our favorite drivers. He cries about every little thing
that happens to him. He's a dirty driver. Not all the time, but a
lot of times, yes. Last year or the year before at Bristol, he ran
into the back of Rusty just to pass him. Plus, I just can't stand
the fact that he wins every race.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention Gordon to these firemen, and you fan their flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gordon was a Ford man all his life,'' Steve Phillips said.
``Ford was going to set him up in Winston Cup, and he jumped to
Chevrolet. I don't think that's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you listen to the scanner,'' Chris Goodman said, ``he
complains the whole race about how bad the car is. Then the last
10-20 laps, he'll come back and win it. So people will think he won
the race with a bad car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got an awesome team,'' Mike Bohannon said. ``If you put
him in anybody else's car, he couldn't do anything. Plus, everybody
on the track has earned the right to be there; they've flipped end
over end. He hasn't even had a bad wreck yet and gotten hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if Gordon had a house in Mechanicsville that was on
fire? ``Legally, we'd have to put it out,'' Womble said, ``but I
don't think we'd want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason the anti-Gordonites are more obvious these
days is the communal nature of fans. Most races draw more than
100,000 spectators. They arrive 12 hours early for a convenient
parking spot. They need something to pass the time, besides eating
and drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Before last Saturday's race, Jay Faison walked through the
Richmond Fairgrounds parking area with a crude anti-Gordon sign.
``I think people hate him 'cause he's just too good,'' Faison said.
``Have you seen the guy with the Gordon toilet seat?''
</P>
<P>
   That would belong to John Denbek, a truck driver from Richmond,
who wears an earring in his left ear bearing a miniature No. 6 and
a tiny Mark Martin car.
</P>
<P>
   Denbek has carried a toilet seat with Gordon's picture in the
middle to races at Darlington, Rockingham and Richmond. He's poking
fun at Gordon's 1996 championship loss. Last weekend, Denbek
created a new display, a cardboard cutout of Gordon, with a
pacifier in his mouth, painted tears coming from his eyes and a
plastic diaper fastened at his waist. Gordon is holding a taped-on
trophy shaped like a gas can. It's a knock on his loss at Dover the
week before when he gave up the lead late to stop for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The cardboard Gordon carries a sign: ``Nobody likes a crybaby. I
should know.'' For most of the afternoon, it became a photo
opportunity for fans. At times, the waiting line was 20 deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a hate thing,'' Denbek said. ``It's just something we
poke fun at. NASCAR fans are probably the best fans, next to
baseball and football. But in our society, everybody hates a
winner. Like the Bulls, they look at it as, `When are they going to
lose?' We do this just to have some fun. I've only heard one person
disagree. He said, 'There may be a fight here tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   The parking-lot critics are tame compared to those on the
Internet. Some of the Web pages are downright vulgar, with gutter
humor and drawings. The commentary sounds like it comes from
``Jerry Springer'' rejects. A favorite feature includes photos of
the Gordon car in various wrecks and on fire.
</P>
<P>
   There are essays on ``Why I Hate Jeff.'' There are jokes (``Why
does Jeff Gordon never hit the wall? The wall ain't got no numbers
on it''). and top-10 lists (``Why Gordon Won't Repeat As Champ'').
The tamest of the 10 is NFAJG, the official ``NASCAR Fans Against
Jeff Gordon'' page. It includes jokes, photos, messages from
non-fans, a running soap opera and merchandise (T-shirts for
$19.50; stickers of a devilish-looking kid urinating on the No. 24
for $5).
</P>
<P>
   It is the work of Barrett Bonnar, a high school student in Nova
Scotia, Canada, who claims the site gets 2,200 visitors a day. He
started the site a year ago as a joke. He didn't think it would
become so popular.
</P>
<P>
   Among his visitors were some legal folks from DuPont, Gordon's
sponsor, who objected to the doctored drawing of the car hood that
spells out, ``DuPunk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, I'm not real sure why I dislike him,'' Bonnar
said. ``Fact is, when he first came onto the circuit I kind of
liked him 'cause he had a cool car. Then he started winning and
with that came the attitude. That's the worst: 'Where's the money?'
Then he started driving dirty and got super cocky. I just hate his
car, wife, voice, car number and everything about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon contends that this backlash is all the price of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our mistakes don't get overlooked,'' he said.
``They get brought up to the top. Some people just don't like
success. You look at Michael Jordan and the Bulls. When they went
to Utah, I guarantee you not everybody sitting in that arena was
cheering for Michael Jordan and the Bulls. NASCAR is unique. There
are no home fields; we play on a floor that has 43 teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if people boo me because they think I win too much, I can
live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
