<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elliott looks to get back on track at Michigan
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Saying ``there's a Ford in your future'' is no
wild exaggeration when it comes to racing at Michigan Speedway
where a Ford driver has won 11 times in the last 15 races.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder then, that another Ford is odds on to be driven into
Victory Lane at the end of today's Miller Lite 400 . Six of them
start in the top 10, including Bill Elliott's, who leads all active
drivers with seven career victories here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michigan's been very good to me in the past, and I think it
can be again if we can just continue and not have any more
problems,'' said Elliott, referring to back-to-back, bone-jarring
accidents at Talladega and California that totaled good race cars
and beat him up physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like Dover (two weeks ago) was a good accomplishment
for us because I had a better car there than what the driver was.
The driver gave out and that's all there was to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott was seventh in Winston Cup points before crashing at
Talladega and slipped to 11th the next week as a result of the
California disaster. He's since dropped to 11th, several times
turning the wheel over to standby drivers midway through the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michigan will be good for us if we can just continue
on and not have any more problems,'' Elliott said Friday after
qualifying sixth with a speed of 180.764 mph, his best start since
a seventh at Martinsville six races ago.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's last victory came in the 1994 Southern 500 at
Darlington, more than 100 races ago. He finished second behind
Ernie Irvan last year and has been one of the fastest cars here
this week in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good, raceable track even though it's gone through a
lot of change over the years with pavement, the radial tires and
all that stuff,'' said Elliott who last won here in 1989. ``It's
got a little bit of speedway and a little bit of short track on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott will have formidable competition within the Ford Taurus
brigade. Dale Jarrett, who starts second, has two victories here;
third-place starter Rusty Wallace is a four-time winner; and Mark
Martin has three.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton starts on the pole in a Pontiac, which has been to
Victory Lane here only once, in 1989 by Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   The last General Motors car to win was Bobby Labonte, who swept
both races in 1995 in a Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't overlook Jeff Gordon,'' Elliott said. ``Looking at
Dover, he led the whole race and it didn't seem like there was
another Chevrolet even close. He ran out of gas at the end, but man
he was strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
