<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett finds his comfort zone
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. -- For Dale Jarrett, it has been a long, long
way from Daytona to Michigan. Three races into the season, he was
27th in the Winston Cup driver standings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 14 races, he's tied for fourth with Mark Martin, 53
points behind leader Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on a pretty good run of late,'' said Jarrett in the
understatement of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Since finishing 40th at Las Vegas, Jarrett has two victories _
Darlington and Dover _ and added seconds at Atlanta and Richmond to
go with four other top fives.
</P>
<P>
   He had a chance to add another victory last Saturday if Terry
Labonte hadn't rooted him out of his groove on the last lap at
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``As upset as we were with not winning the race, after we had
time to calm down and look at everything, we made quite a jump for
a short track,'' Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett hasn't spoken to Labonte since the incident, but when he
does there will be no altercation. It's over and done with as far
as he is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen Terry and didn't have the opportunity after the
race,'' Jarrett said.''We were getting ready to go home, while he
was celebrating and going to the pressbox afterward. We'll go on
racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've raced against each other for a lot of years, and I have
a tremendous amount of respect for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett can afford to take that attitude. He expects this year's
points race will be somewhat like the 1992 battle, which came down
to the final laps, when the late Alan Kulwicki beat Bill Elliott by
10 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got six of us within 100 points of each other now, and
then you've got Bobby Labonte not that far back where he can still
be a factor,'' Jarrett said. ``A number of us have a lot of top
fives and top 10s out of the 13 races, but we've got some DNFs in
there also, except for Jeremy (Mayfield), who has finished every
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he doesn't have a victory yet and Rusty (Wallace) has been
sort of the same way,'' he said. ``So you have people going about
it in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be a great battle, going to be a lot of
fun for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's down the road. Jarrett has turned his attention to
today's Miller Lite 400 on a track where he's won twice. But he
hasn't won the Miller Lite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track is more of a handling track than one of
horsepower,'' said Jarrett, who won the DeVilbiss 400 in 1991 and
'96. ``I've been here with cars that maybe didn't have the best
engines there, but you could get through the corners. And that's
the key because the corners are so sweeping here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the best engines in the world, and I've been here
with some, but not gotten through the corners and not been a
front-running car. So to me, handling is a lot more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be key.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
