<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-NOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drivers eager for Pepsi night run
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- ``Incredible.'' That's the response from Winston Cup
drivers who have tested under the lights at Daytona International
Speedway in preparation for the inaugural night running of the
Pepsi 400 on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lights are fantastic,'' said Rusty Wallace, who is
searching for his first Winston Cup victory at Daytona
International Speedway. ``Night racing is here to stay. The cars
like it, the fans like it, and the track surface remains
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics expressed a concern that on a two-mile track, there
will be long spaces of shadows that could be dangerous. But Wallace
doesn't believe it will be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cars run so close together at Daytona that you won't be
able to get much light between them, no matter what type of
lighting system you use,'' he said. ``Let's face it, it's going to
be a great one, one we'll all remember.''
</P>
<P>
   In two practice sessions, Mike Skinner posted the fastest speed,
189.873 mph, followed by Wallace's 189.394 and Loy Allen's 189.277.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be fantastic,'' said Daytona Beach resident Mark Martin.
``The feeling that you get at night is more exciting _ it's the
whole atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Roush No. 1
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Burton's Busch series victory in Richmond last week,
Jack Roush has accumulated 181 career victories as a car owner,
more than any other owner in the modern era. He has 29 Winston Cup
victories, 29 Busch victories, seven in the Craftsman Truck
division, 69 Trans Am and 47 IMSA since 1984. Only Roger Penske
comes close to Roush, with 133.
</P>
<P>
   Jetting around
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Jet Motorsports is on the move without Darrell Waltrip.
Phil Hammer has been named crew; they've added the June 28 Sears
Point event to the schedule with Ron Hornaday at the wheel; the
team roster has grown from 22 to 37 since late March, and the team
is on course to meet its target of having 13 complete cars by Aug.
1, in time for the Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Around the tracks
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt was the keynote speaker at the National Press
Club's newsmaker luncheon earlier this week. It was the first time
a NASCAR driver has been invited. . . . Jimmy Spencer has four top
10 finishes this year, three more than a year ago at this time. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   Busch
</P>
<P>
   Upside, downside
</P>
<P>
   Now that Pikes Peak is on the Busch circuit, Shane Hall said,
it's good and bad. ``There's an upside and a downside in running on
a new track the first time without the Winston Cup teams around,''
Hall said. ``The upside to having them around is their experience
and their willingness to share knowledge. On the downside, they
usually have some pretty good race cars of their own, and that
makes good runs by the Busch guys even more difficult. So, it's
pretty much a guessing game when they're not around at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome
</P>
<P>
   The welcome mat was out for the Busch teams at Pikes Peak.
Several local residents served as Good Ambassadors, making sure the
teams had everything they needed. Towns people were ready with
suggestions for the best places to eat, the best entertainment and
general directions.
</P>
<P>
   Craftsman trucks
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Two Craftsman Truck drivers, Scot Walters and Mike Bliss, were
injured in the Pronto Auto Parts 400k at Texas Motor Speedway on
June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Walters suffered a severe cut on his chin, requiring three
layers of stitches to close the wound. He also underwent a series
of tests and X-rays on his head and neck, all of which showed only
deep bruising.
</P>
<P>
   Bliss broke a shoulder on the third lap, when he hit the inside
retaining wall. He'll be out four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Off week
</P>
<P>
   The truckers take a break this week before gearing up for a
grinding week at Bristol on June 20. Jack Sprague holds the points
lead with 1,300, 77 ahead of Ron Hornaday. Joe Rutman is third, 107
behind the leader. ... Tammy Jo Kirk finished 15th, a lap down, and
collected $10,575 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
