<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So what's so bad about the spice girls?
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- We strive for enlightenment, plan to read great
books. We listen to NPR and speculate about the future of Social
</P>
<P>
   Security and peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   And in spite of it all, we can name the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   It's a chilling thought: Baby. Posh. Sporty. Scary and the
recently departed Ginger. You can't pick up a magazine, flip on the
radio or even surf the Web without stumbling across their perky
faces, blabbering on about Girl Power (``Gul Powah'' as it sounds
tripping off their south London tongues) or prancing to lyrics such
as ``ziga-zig-aaaah.''
</P>
<P>
   As distasteful as it is to admit, the very triviality of these
gals has somehow mesmerized (some might say numbed) our collective
consciousness. It's similar to stopping the remote control on late
night infomercials about the Miracle Mop or the Banjo Minnow
fishing lure _ we can't believe we're watching, but we stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Like a big bowl of potato chips, the Spice Girls are what they
are: junk food. They're a cheap thrill, a shallow romp in sequins
and skintight dresses whose only mission is to entertain.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   As long as you keep it in perspective, not a thing.
</P>
<P>
   When they roll into Lakewood Amphitheatre on Thursday, the
Spices are well into their 15 minutes. They've had two huge albums,
a string of state-of-the-art videos, a movie and more media
attention than when man landed on the moon. Little girls adore
them. Parents chuckle and remember cutting out pictures of Bobby
Sherman and David Cassidy. In its very meaninglessness, the group
serves a purpose _ a fleeting diversion from the realities of
day-to-day life.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples: In the best-selling Pocket Spice books, Ginger
Spice shares her thoughts: ``My favorite word is existentialism.
But I don't know what it means, and I can't even pronounce it.''
Calling from Oslo, Norway, to promote the Atlanta show, the first
of 30 phone interviews she was doing that morning, Baby Spice
chants her well-rehearsed lines like a mantra: ``We're such great
friends. We wanted to show that we're strong and independent.'' At
the Virgin Records Web site (www.virginrecords.com), it's possible
to pull up individual interviews with the Spices. Ginger, who's
still featured on the site despite quitting the band two weeks ago,
trumped up like a tart with bright orange hair, dangling her 4-inch
heels over the armrest of a chair, says, ``Imagine, me, going to
all these pahr-ties meeting people like Lahra Dern.''
</P>
<P>
   What's really amazing about the Spice Girls is that this group
of giggly, working-class waifs has managed to take mindless dance
music and turn it into a platform for perhaps the biggest exercise
in celebrity for celebrity's sake that we have seen in decades.
They are pet rocks and Sea-Monkeys for our time. Fame isn't the
byproduct for these girls, it's the goal. As they said themselves
in their vanity film ``Spice World'': ``It's not any good, but it's
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ignoring the hype, the Spice Girls embraced their
manufactured nicknames to the point they have become cartoon
characters of these personas. It's a concept straight out of the
Mattel marketing department, each Spice becoming a living/
</P>
<P>
   breathing Pocket Pal that little girls can dress up and hang
their budding self-images on like dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, the music became secondary. The first
album, 1997's ``Spice,'' was actually a fun exercise in
unapologetic pop, spawning the hit singles ``Wannabe,'' ``Say
You'll Be There'' and ``Two Become One.'' The girls have
tenaciously claimed all along that they really, really did write
all the tunes themselves, which were as good as anything Madonna
has ever churned out. And let's face it: At least they admit they
are poseurs, unlike U2's Bono or the ubiquitous pop queen Jewel.
</P>
<P>
   The real magic of this goofy group isn't in their glitzy,
Vegas-style stage show or their inane prattle. (We all know Sporty,
Scary, Ginger, Posh and Baby are going to fade into pop obscurity
as our daughters grow up and get on with the serious business of
life.) It's on the faces of the little girls who have decided to
hop on the Spice Girls like a quick carnival ride. Of course, it'll
be over in a couple of minutes. It has no particularly redeeming
social value. But, like childhood or a spend-the-night-party, it's
over fairly quickly _ and it sure can be a lot of fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
