<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rugged rough at Olympic rewards straight shooters
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Relentless, rugged rough and a tender back. Not a
pleasant combination at any time. At a U.S. Open, it could be
disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Fed by more than 100 days of rain from El Nino, the Olympic
Club's overseeded ryegrass rough is destined for a major role at
this year's U.S. Open, which begins Thursday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The United States Golf Association is said to be considering
limits on high-tech equipment. Hope the deep-faced, titanium
weed-whacker won't be eliminated. Getting a blade through Olympic's
rough, let alone a sand wedge, has been a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And how are a few of golf's major stars preparing for the
agronomical nightmare? Not ideally, by any means. When U.S. Open
defending champion Ernie Els withdrew from the Buick Classic on
Thursday, he joined a disturbing list of players treating back
problems so close to the season's second major championship.
</P>
<P>
   If Justin Leonard is smart, he's already on a preventive
exercise program. Of 1997's four majors winners, he's the only one
still unscathed. Tiger Woods, Davis Love III and now Els are either
hurting from or treating back ailments. Throw in two-time 1998
winner Fred Couples, who herniated a disk in 1994, and Paul
Azinger, who missed 55 days this year with a back ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for those in spasm, this is a week for hoping, not
healing. Olympic is, after all, the same place where a player lost
his ball after a free drop during the 1957 U.S. Open. Olympic's
rough will be seven inches deep in spots and almost as dense as the
grasses that made up Congressional's off-the-fairway stuff last
year. San Francisco is always a cool, damp area prone to fog, which
adds to the heaviness of the grass. A good forecast for next week _
sunny in the mid-70s, for a change _ could help dry things out.
</P>
<P>
   Nasty rough is nothing new for Olympic, which isn't overly long
for an Open course (6,797 yards) and must be protected. During a
practice round in 1987, Andy Bean gave superintendent John Fleming
an ovation when he saw his mowers chugging through the rough. ``I'd
never seen anybody cut the rough during a U.S. Open,'' Bean said.
</P>
<P>
   Players nursing back problems would be wise to maintain caution
in the rough. In the past, Woods has not demonstrated a tendency to
chip out and accept a bogey. This week, he might not have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the difficulty of the course set-up are the bunkers.
Filled with new, fluffier sand _ not the thin, packed-down stuff
that Olympic's members usually see _ the bunkers will be prone to
buried lies and widespread grumbling. With deep-faced bunkers and
tiny greens, sand saves will be coveted.
</P>
<P>
   Tight and tough, like any Open course, Olympic will place those
straight drivers of the golf ball _ such as Leonard, Colin
Montgomerie, Jim Furyk and Mark O'Meara _ in improved positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The USGA requires you to play smart golf, control golf,'' said
O'Meara, the Masters champion. ``In 1987 the rough was very penal.
I think the players understand that and look forward to that
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
