<HEADER>
A8259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEIR-COX     06-13 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exploitation in a `fishbowl' existence
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- On a recent visit to Atlanta, Australian director
Peter Weir shared a few thoughts on his hit film, the comedy-drama
``The Truman Show,'' starring Jim Carrey as a man who realizes his
entire life has been a TV show and everyone he knows is an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Among the many interesting ideas in this movie is the notion
of one man's life as public commodity. That certainly reverberates
with our culture of celebrity and gossip, and the way people are
forced to live in fishbowls.
</P>
<P>
   A:It's extraordinary, the way it's accelerated in the last five
years. Last year, during the cutting period, the horror of
(Princess) Diana's death caused you to realize that even if you
hadn't bought all those magazines, you couldn't get away from it.
Just going to the local store, you'd see her on the magazine cover
with whatever her latest episode was _ as if it were a soap opera
with a spectacular end episode: the death of a princess.
</P>
<P>
   So it was interesting to me to have the audience cut into ``The
Truman Show,'' to see their reactions, and then their shock toward
the end. It was only then that they began to think, this man might
die. There was a reality here that had not been acknowledged, which
was the whole lie of his existence and his dreadful exploitation.
You were reminded, that was Diana. We're the very people who had
bought all the magazines and newspapers, who were very angry with
the paparazzi. But they were working for us. There were so many
ironies there.
</P>
<P>
   Q:You're right, Diana was like a long-running character in our
lives since we first heard of her.
</P>
<P>
   A:Even the Gulf War I think had that quality because of the
curious nature of the images we were seeing from gun cameras and so
forth. It was like a strange game. The idea that people were being
killed was pretty remote. It was a world event. We were all
watching, and (Gulf War commander Norman) Schwarzkopf became the
star of that. It was like a successful war series. Then came the
O.J. trial.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So considering how media-ized we are, ``The Truman Show''
isn't such a big jump.
</P>
<P>
   A:That's also why the town was photographed the way it was, and
the clothing very carefully thought about. It's all stylized, the
best of '30s and '40s clothing. So (Christof, the producer, played
by Ed Harris in the film) is also trying to teach the world a
better way to be, which is part of his vanity.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What about this story resonated with you?
</P>
<P>
   A:It seemed to be a totally fresh story, with old elements
combined in a very new way. You can't really come up with new
emotions. ... Someone said to me the other day, ``It's a really
strange film.'' And I said, ``No, it isn't.'' The emotional strands
are very traditional: love, the search for truth, the search for
freedom. But the context is bizarre. It's the times we're living
with. That's its newness as a film. It's one of the first films to
deal extensively with the rapid change in information technology
essentially, and the disturbance to our concept of the difference
between what is real and unreal.
</P>
<P>
   Q:It must have been a headache to the Paramount marketing
department.
</P>
<P>
   A:Yes, it's almost impossible. ... To just roll it out among all
the summer films (without extensive word-of-mouth screenings) would
have made it an unfortunate question mark: ``What is that? Is it a
comedy? I hear it isn't.'' It would have gotten lost in a confusion
that would seem to be coming off the film itself.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Did you have any concern about restraining or modulating
Carrey's performance?
</P>
<P>
   A:Yes, but I didn't want to inhibit him. He was looking for
change. He felt that ``Liar Liar'' would be one step, and ``The
Truman Show'' would be the next one in terms of his constituency,
demonstrating a broader range than the farcical comedies.
</P>
<P>
   I'd had some experience with Robin Williams (in ``Dead Poets
Society''). But I don't want to get the reputation of being the man
who removes the comedy from comic actors. (``Truman'' screenwriter)
Andrew Niccol said, ``You'll become a sort of directorial
chiropractor for comics _ he sort of straightens them out and sends
them on. One price for tragedy, another price for a drama.'' But,
as with Robin, I didn't want to deny Jim's talent for humor.
Sometimes Jim would say, ``I think I could try this in a bigger
way.'' And I'd say, ``Great, it's only film.'' Every other time, it
was useful, but just as often it was too much. But the worst thing
in the world for an actor is to pretend that there are some rules
that the director knows and you have to confine yourself to it,
instead of saying, ``Who knows? We have the blueprint of the
script, we can always go back and shoot the scene as it's written.
But what if we try something else?'''
</P>
<P>
   Q:(The film was shot in Seaside, the planned development resort
city in the Florida panhandle) What time of year did you shoot?
</P>
<P>
   A:Just the turn of the year, winter, which is why we could get
the town.
</P>
<P>
   Q:It's a strange town. It does look like a nutty film set.
</P>
<P>
   A:Robert Davis, its developer, compares it to Bath, (England).
He says a resort town really benefits from a degree of
theatricality. You leave your more mundane world behind, including
your problems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
