<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wrist watch
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The more the merrier. That's the sentiment of women
all over town who are slipping into something cheap and slinky: the
newly popular guitar string bracelets that you buy _ and wear _ by
the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   At stores such as the Limited, these gold-and silver-toned
bracelets sell at $10 for a pack of 20. That's the going rate for
them as well at the Beth Ann Image and Accessory Boutique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you put on, the stronger the statement they make,''
said the boutique's owner, Beth Ann Taratoot. ``The rage among
those customers of mine who can afford it is to buy 50 or more.''
</P>
<P>
   The guitar string bracelets _ alternately referred to as
``slinkies'' _ come in a thicker version that costs $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Limited and Beth Ann's, they're also sold at
Saks Fifth Avenue and Erika Reade Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-98 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980613.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8263 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLES14-COX     06-13 2386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The healing art of stories
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Robert M. Coles strides across the Emory University
campus, on his way to give a lecture at the venerable Glenn
Memorial United Methodist Church, when his steps bring him to a
steep gully, cut by a swift, murky creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's swim it,'' he says, with an impish grin. ``I'd love to
arrive dirty and disheveled.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time that the Harvard University
professor, a recipient of this year's Presidential Medal of
Freedom, has departed from the beaten path.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he was headed toward a low-key life as a child
psychiatrist when Coles encountered a white mob trying to scare the
life out of a little black girl named Ruby Bridges. The civil
rights movement loomed in front of him. He jumped in.
</P>
<P>
   As he followed Ruby and other students who were integrating
Southern schools in the 1960s, he abandoned his career and found
his life's work. His stated plan was to study how children handled
the stress of integration. His real focus, however, became the
psyche of the country, as America went through what his mentor Erik
Erikson would call an identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of Crisis,'' the monumental series of books that
sprang from Coles' experiences in the South, won the Pulitzer Prize
in 1973 and anointed Coles America's counselor at large.
</P>
<P>
   Through his writings on the moral, spiritual and political lives
of children, and his books about migrant workers, Eskimos, Indians,
teen parents, the elderly and many other subjects (more than 60
books at last count), Coles became the conscience of a generation
and one of the most significant social historians since James Agee,
author of ``Let Us Now Praise Famous Men.'' Catholic priest and
writer Andrew Greeley has called him a ``secular saint'' _
terminology that makes Coles distinctly ill at ease.
</P>
<P>
   This is a confirmed Yankee, with a honking Boston accent to
prove it. (In Coles' mouth, ``Harvard'' rhymes with ``avid.'') But
he never left the South completely behind. For 20 years, he has
taught part time at Duke University, and in 1988 he co-founded
Duke's Center for Documentary Studies, with Atlanta photographer
Alex Harris and William Chafe, now Duke's dean of arts and
sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Among the publications created by the center is the visually
stunning magazine DoubleTake, a large-format quarterly collection
of photography, reportage, fiction and poetry that is Coles and
Harris' special brainchild. Established in 1995, it has won raves,
including a National Magazine Award for general excellence this
year for featuring work such as the photographs of Helen Levitt,
the poetry of Seamus Heaney, and writing by John McPhee and Joyce
Carol Oates.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's 60,000 readers _ roughly the same kind of folks
who tune in to National Public Radio _ expect an earthy mixture of
the well-known and the obscure. Early issues balanced a newly
discovered short story by Flannery O'Connor with a remarkable essay
and drawings by a 7-year-old named Kristin Graves, who explained in
heartbreaking language the story of her mother's death in an
automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTake, says Coles, is an extension of his Duke classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old teacher; I've got a new classroom,'' he says. ``How
many can come to a lecture, 400 or 500? And DoubleTake reaches
60,000. It's a wonderful educational opportunity. I used to write
for The New Yorker under William Shawn, and he said, `I regard
myself as a teacher, principally.'''
</P>
<P>
   He teaches documentary work not by handing his students a tape
recorder, but by shoving them into a new world. It could be a
public housing project, or a migrant labor camp or a mountain
shack, but it's probably someplace where undergrads paying $25,000
a year in tuition rarely go. He shows them how to get lost in
someone else's story.
</P>
<P>
   Coming South
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Coles. The tale is one he repeats for all of his
classes, at Duke and Harvard, and he tells it again to a group of
faculty and graduate students during this same Emory visit in May.
</P>
<P>
   Disheveled, if not dirty, Coles, 68, radiates a Peter Falkian
charm as he paces before the audience assembled in the Emory
student center: His shirt sleeves are rolled up to reveal hairy,
muscular forearms, his face bristling with permanent 5 o'clock
shadow. He seems to have combed his unpredictable salt-and-pepper
mane with a Mixmaster.
</P>
<P>
   The voice is as cranky as a New England winter, softened by a
set of flannel vocal chords. The jacket and tie are missing. (His
children forced this self-described slob to buy a new suit in
January so he would look presentable at the White House while
receiving the Medal of Freedom from President Clinton.)
</P>
<P>
   He tells the group about being drafted as a young psychiatrist
and stationed at Keesler Air Force Base in Biloxi, Miss., when he
first realized that there was a revolution going on under his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been in the Force for a year, and I had paid no attention
to any of this stuff, even though I was a reasonably well-educated
person from all these snotty schools up North,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then one Sunday afternoon in 1960, Coles rode his bicycle home
along U.S. 90 in Biloxi, where he saw whites attacking blacks who'd
trespassed on ``their'' beach. The incident riveted him, as did the
experience during a visit to New Orleans, when he saw the
6-year-old Ruby Bridges kneel in the midst of a mob and pray for
her attackers.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't get these moments out of his mind, and he was
desperate to do something about them. ``Something was happening to
me, some kind of moral crisis, not to mention personal crisis, as I
was trying to figure out what to do with my life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The moments became a touchstone for him. The moral courage of
the little girl in the starched white dress was a central image of
``Children of Crisis,'' and an image that Coles returns to
frequently in his writings. He spun the tale again in 1995 with a
popular children's book, ``The Story of Ruby Bridges,'' the
proceeds of which benefit the Ruby Bridges Education Foundation.
(Disney made it into a TV special this year.) As Ruby changed his
life, so did his attention change hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have kids all over the country that see me as this great
role model,'' says Ruby Bridges Hall, now a mother of four in New
Orleans. ``It humbles me.''
</P>
<P>
   An active observer
</P>
<P>
   Coles also studied the children who integrated Atlanta schools
in the early '60s, while he lived in the Vinings area and attended
All Saints Episcopal Church in Midtown. He says that he learned
much from Atlanta news papermen Gene Patterson andRalph McGill.
``Never mind all this social science crap,'' he says, with typical
bluntness. ``They taught me how to go talk to people and interview
them in their homes, where they lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from acting the detached observer during those years, Coles
put his own life on the line. In the summer of 1964, he and his
wife, Jane Hallowell Coles, were staying at a safe house in McComb,
Miss., when a bomb destroyed the structure. ``Then the police came
and arrested us all, like we were the ones who dynamited our own
house,'' says a laughing Coles. He and his wife were shaken but
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   And if he hadn't been sent to Biloxi? ``If that hadn't happened
to me, I'd have an office somewhere on Brattle Street,'' he says.
Then adds, with a curl of the lip, ``I'd be treating gifted,
troubled, Harvard students.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Coles didn't seem destined for the conventional
career arc. He remembers when his mother, Sandra, a hard-headed
descendant of Yankee abolitionists, took him out of elementary
school one day to see her hero Franklin D. Roosevelt as his
motorcade came through Boston. Little Bobby's teacher objected, but
his mother was firm. ``He'll remember this long after he forgets
everything he learned in school,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Boston Latin, Coles studied literature at Harvard,
writing his thesis on the doctor/poet William Carlos Williams.
Coles sent him a copy, and Williams was impressed (``Not bad, for a
Harvard student,'' he wrote) and suggested Coles try medicine:
``Lots to keep you busy, and lots to make you think.''
</P>
<P>
   But Coles was a mediocre medical student; he was ready to quit
when his mother chided him for his selfish ennui. ``Why don't you
go work in a soup kitchen?'' she asked. ``That will be one way for
you to see what a lucky life you've had.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, working two summers during the early 1950s at a shelter
operated by Catholic activist Dorothy Day. She inspired Coles to
write her biography (``Dorothy Day: A Radical Devotion'') and
showed him the kind of life that he would strive toward, a life
consumed with service.
</P>
<P>
   Coles completed the training to become a pediatrician but
changed to psychiatry. Like his mentor, Williams, Coles became
better known for his writing than his work in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Real stories
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston, Coles is sometimes referred to as Robert ``Never
an Unpublished Thought'' Coles. Certainly his literary output, all
written in ballpoint pen on yellow legal pads, is prodigious.
</P>
<P>
   His writing, Coles freely admits, is a device to keep him out of
faculty meetings, which he abhors. Though he is perched at the top
of the university heap, Coles has a thinly veiled contempt for the
stuffy world of the academy. (Just ask him about intellectuals: ``I
hate the word! I hate the people!'' Or about Ivy League professors:
``Stuck-up big shots.'')
</P>
<P>
   He especially holds suspect the rhetoric of social science.
``Such abstractions as `ghetto neighborhood' or `culturally
deprived child' or `socially marginal this' and `something else
that,' I'm trying to rescue myself and the people I write about
from these overwrought and sometimes fatuous generalizations,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   His role models are Dickens, Tolstoy and Steinbeck,
documentarians who portrayed their societies in complex,
contradictory detail. ``I favor their leadership rather than the
leadership that populates our universities in the name of social
science,'' he says. ``Novelists and short story writers do it out
of their imagination. The only difference is, I do it in connection
with the concreteness of real people.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles, the James Agee professor of social ethics at Harvard,
draws on these novelists in his popular Harvard course, ``A
Literature of Social Reflection,'' which students jokingly call
``Guilt 105,'' because of its emphasis on ethics and morality.
Undergrads hellbent on careers in law and business are treated to
the writings of George Orwell, Ralph Ellison, Flannery O'Connor and
others, and some find their goals changing.
</P>
<P>
   Former student Tom Kelley, now a director of community programs
at the Center for Documentary Studies, took Coles' courses as a
Harvard undergrad. ``I was mystified by his approach. He gets up
and he just tells stories. What's the theme? How can I critique
this? That's not how aggressive young pre-med students are taught
to think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I blame Bob Coles for my mediocre grade point
average,'' says Jay Woodruff, a former DoubleTake staffer and
currently a senior editor at Esquire magazine, who studied with
Coles in the early 1980s. ``I was very affected by his perspective
on the world. It gave me a convenient excuse to care a lot less
about things like midterms.''
</P>
<P>
   William Chafe, a historian and chronicler of the civil rights
movement, has observed Coles' ability to create believers, to move
young people toward idealism. ``I've known Bob for 15 years,'' says
Chafe. ``He is a charismatic figure. He inspires people, makes them
want to do exciting work, with a passion that's all-consuming.''
</P>
<P>
   A life of service
</P>
<P>
   The center at Duke has given Coles access to a new group of
followers, in particular, the readers of DoubleTake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those genius people who needs to have a challenge
at every turn,'' says Isabel Geffner, DoubleTake's associate
publisher. ``That's a wonderful lesson in how to grow up and grow
older: When you're in your 60s, by God, start a magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite winning awards and getting large infusions of cash from
donors _ including a $10 million grant from the Lyndhurst
Foundation of Chattanooga _ DoubleTake is losing about $2 million a
year. ``I think we've got a year or two,'' says Coles, whose office
is, aptly, decorated with wall-size blowups of children's drawings.
``If we pull it off, we'll continue. If we don't, it will be a
noble experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's not in Durham, N.C., Coles directs the magazine from
his Harvard office (in FDR's old room at Adams House), running up a
heavy Federal Express bill as photos and proofs are shipped back
and forth. During the early hours he works on his next two books,
editing a collection of the writings of German theologian Dietrich
Bonhoeffer and writing a book to be called ``Moral Leadership,''
about the character of such exemplars as Bonhoeffer and Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   That he lets his associates run the Center for Documentary
Studies when he's not around is in keeping with his laissez-faire
organizational style. Harris remembers an early collaboration, when
Coles invited him to New Mexico and Alaska to shoot photographs for
what would become two books, ``The Old Ones of New Mexico'' (1973)
and ``The Last and First Eskimos'' (1978). ``I had just heard him
mesmerize a room, and I thought, `This guy is going to show me the
way.' It turns out he was interested in what I was going to find
there,'' Harris says. ``Not what he was going to teach me.'' While
the center still doesn't offer a degree or even a major, it offers
what Coles believes is a powerful tool, useful to students in all
disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   And that is, he says, ``first-hand awareness of how people live,
uncluttered by jargon, unmediated by high-falutin' theoretical
talk. They'll remember voices, they'll remember sights, they'll be
able to pull together portraits of individuals, be able to think in
reasonably clear language about fellow human beings, how they live,
what they want out of life.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll be able to hear the stories that are all around them.
It's Coles' prescription for a good life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
