<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLES14-SIDE-COX     06-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLES14-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Center at Duke University documents people behind the problems
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The teenagers hanging out on Franklin Street have
that scary look. Pierced noses. Strange haircuts. Grungy clothes.
They're panhandling pedestrians and smoking cigarettes and
otherwise acting like a bunch of punks. ``Nobody's happy here,''
says regular scene-maker Jessica Turner, 16.
</P>
<P>
   But Claire Trask sees something different. The Duke University
senior has been photographing these Chapel Hill kids for eight
months. She's had them over to her house, fielded distraught phone
calls from their parents, visited their crash pads. She has spied
the little children hiding behind the tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   And you can see it in the photo essay she has assembled for a
class with the Center for Documentary Studies. Of choosing music
for her slide show, she says, ``I could have put it with the
Beastie Boys, and people would have said, `These kids are going to
pot.' But I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Trask, 22, chose Nat King Cole, singing ``L-O-V-E,''
and the street scene became a love story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veil dropped,'' says Alex Harris, co-founder of the
center. ``You carry in your mind a picture of what you're going to
do. How do you get rid of those pictures and really react to what's
in front of you? It takes time; it takes forming a relationship
with
</P>
<P>
   people.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1988 with support from the Lyndhurst Foundation, the
center has been training future Walker Evanses in its classes for
undergraduates, while pursuing a titanic research project on the
lives of black Southerners during the Jim Crow years.
</P>
<P>
   That project, called ``Behind the Veil,'' draws on 1,800 hours
of interviews in 25 communities and 10 states, completed over eight
years with the help of 50 graduate students from several North
Carolina schools. From it will flow several books and a special
archive of material at the John Hope Franklin Research Center,
which should support doctoral research for years to come, said
project leader William Chafe.
</P>
<P>
   Connected with the Veil undertaking is a service program called
Community Stories, through which summer interns train young people
in inner-city neighborhoods to also become documentarians, to take
oral histories from elders in the community. ``We want to teach
kids to be better thinkers,'' says coordinator Delia Gamble. Adds
Harris, ``They find it helps strengthen community identity,
strengthens bonds between young and old.''
</P>
<P>
   The center is also a publishing house. In addition to DoubleTake
magazine, it has produced a dozen high-quality books that
concentrate on the kind of personalized social inquiry favored by
co-founder Robert Coles. Recent titles include the 1998 book
``Closing: The Life and Death of American Factory'' _ the story, in
words and pictures, of the death of a Mebane, N.C., furniture
factory and ``The Youngest Parents,'' a 1997 Coles book about
teenagers with children of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The first in what is to be a series of yearly documentary film
festivals, sponsored by the center in May, attracted such noted
filmmakers as Ken Burns and Albert Maysles.
</P>
<P>
   This interlocking web of activities operates out of a homey
19th-century country manor just off the Duke campus, with rocking
chairs on the porch and _ small wonder _ gorgeous photographs on
every wall.
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the door and down the uneven boards of the front
hall are ghostly black-and-white images from the hills of Chiapas,
Mexico. In a new $1.5 million wing connected to the house are
classrooms, lecture halls and an impromptu gallery of
self-portraits from patients at a mental health facility.
</P>
<P>
   DoubleTake magazine is the center's best-known product. The
spring issue's interview with rocker Bruce Springsteen, by Will
Percy, had an unusual genesis. Percy's uncle, the late novelist
Walker Percy, had a lasting influence on Coles with his 1961 novel
``The Moviegoer.'' (Coles even uses the protagonist's name as his
e-mail moniker.) It turns out that Walker Percy was also a fan of
Springsteen's. The elder Percy wrote to Springsteen in 1989 and,
though the musician didn't respond at the time, he began reading
the novelist's work, eventually corresponding with Percy's widow.
(Percy died in 1990.) In the interview, Springsteen talks about
populism, folk culture and how books, including Percy's work, have
affected his music.
</P>
<P>
   Often the outreach, teaching and publishing arms of the center
work in synergy. Wendy Ewald, a MacArthur Prize-winning
photographer based in New York, offers a course sponsored by the
center called ``Literacy Through Photography,'' which gives cameras
to Durham school kids and then prompts them to write about their
images. Ewald's work has also been featured in several issues of
the magazine, including a haunting series of images that resulted
when she asked youngsters to take photographs of their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name another magazine that would publish that,'' says Esquire
magazine senior editor and former DoubleTake staffer Jay Woodruff.
``They're almost the conscience of the culture out there, doing
God's work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
