<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-13 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOES-COX     06-13 0347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These shoes are beauties but no beasts on the feet
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Stuart Weitzman designs ``killer'' shoes that are
actually quite harmless.
</P>
<P>
   The New York designer, who counts Cindy Crawford and Tipper Gore
among his clients, puts foam padding in his stilettos, rubber soles
on his loafers and suede linings in his pumps. Another fan, Rosie
O'Donnell, wore his comfy black heels to last week's Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent appearance at Phipps Plaza's Bob Ellis Shoes
boutique to showcase his $150-$200 shoes for fall, Weitzman said:
``My firm is known for making pretty, comfortable shoes that fit. I
would not risk my reputation by making a fabulous-looking shoe that
hurts.'' Between fittings with customers, the designer chatted with
Style:
</P>
<P>
   Q:Any innovations in the footwear business?
</P>
<P>
   A:High-tech materials. This fall, I'm designing with Gore-Tex
that's been a staple in outerwear for a number of years. It's a
man-made fabric that breathes and is waterproof, making it ideal
for footwear. Also I'm using suede that's been laminated with
Lycra. It stretches and fits like a glove.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How do you feel about being copied by other designers?
</P>
<P>
   A:On one hand, it's discouraging. On the other, it forces me to
be more creative. Also, if other shoe manufacturers don't copy my
designs, I'm not doing my job.
</P>
<P>
   Q:How many collections do you produce each season and where are
your shoes made?
</P>
<P>
   A:I design three lines a year for a total of 550 styles. I spend
half the year in Spain, where my shoes are made in my own
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Q:About how many shoes do you sell each year?
</P>
<P>
   A:I sell over 1 million pairs a year, in store boutiques and in
six free-standing stores. The Bob Ellis store sells the most
Weitzman shoes _ 10,000 pairs a year.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Do you visit Atlanta often?
</P>
<P>
   A:Atlanta is my adopted home, since my wife's family, the
Gershons, live here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
