<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT MARLINS, 7-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Mike Piazza has helped the Mets win consistently since
his arrival three weeks ago. Now, it seems, they can do it all on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   With the All-Star catcher sitting out Saturday night's game
because of a mild right shoulder strain, the Mets had to find a way
to win without him. And they did, unleashing a seven-run third
inning and cruising to a 7-4 victory over the Florida Marlins
before a crowd of 31,887 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are now 37-26, with victories in three of their last
four games.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's neck stiffened after a collision with Gregg Zaun on a
tag play at the plate on Friday night. The soreness ultimately
settled in his right shoulder, and he was examined by the Marlins'
physician, George Caldwell. Piazza is listed as day to day.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets reacted as if they now are in a winning groove, Piazza
or no Piazza. Especially against these cellar-dwelling Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   On the Mets' last visit here, they produced a nine-run inning
and a six-run inning. Saturday night, the magic number was seven.
</P>
<P>
   The third inning began with Rey Ordonez's double to the
left-field wall. Alberto Castillo, the fill-in catcher, walked, and
pitcher Rick Reed sacrificed them up a base. Next, Brian McRae
missed a home run down the right-field line by several inches
before walking.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo then singled in two runs, and Carlos Baerga and
John Olerud followed with run-producing singles of their own to
make it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   With two men on, Butch Huskey ended any suspense this game might
have by riding Brian Meadows' first pitch 440 feet over the
center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had fallen behind in the first inning when Edgar
Renteria singled with one out and Mark Kotsay sent a 1-0 fastball
from Reed 368 feet into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   That two-run bulge held up until the Mets' third-inning
explosion, which included five hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reed (8-3) survived the rocky beginning to win for
the seventh time in his last eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   And he came within two outs of his second straight complete
game. He retired the first Marlin in the ninth inning but then
walked Todd Zeile and allowed a run-scoring double by Cliff Floyd.
After walking Derrek Lee, Reed was replaced by Manager Bobby
Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   On came the venerable save specialist John Franco in a
history-making appearance. This was his 401st game as a Met, tying
the record set by Tom Seaver.
</P>
<P>
   Franco induced Zaun to pop up to Alfonzo at third base, and then
he struck out Dave Berg on a 2-2 pitch to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which had been vocal in wishing for a Florida
comeback, let out a loud ``whoosh'' when Franco blazed the final
pitch by Berg.
</P>
<P>
   It was Franco's 15th save of the season and the 373rd of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Reed allowed seven hits and walked two while striking out eight,
and he was particularly sharp for the four innings preceding the
ninth. The victory means he will be sending another $2,000 to the
Diabetes Association of America _ an agreement he made before the
season for each victory.
</P>
<P>
   Reed has become the iron man of the Mets' staff, pitching at
least 7 innings in 11 of his 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have come to expect good things of him every time out,''
Valentine said. ``He keeps us in games.''
</P>
<P>
   For Huskey, this was a continuation of his hot hitting against
the Marlins. He had driven in five runs in an inning during the
last trip here.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won four of five games here against the Marlins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
