r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSADA-AZR &LR;      06-13 2462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSADA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LA POSADA RESTORATION AIMS TO PUT WINSLOW BACK ON TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSLOW, Ariz. _ This little desert town, famous as an outpost
on Route 66 and immortalized in a pop song, is a community whose
life is hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, business folk and sen timental fools are hoping the
ghosts of the Harvey Girls will tip the scales toward rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Winslow is La Po sada, a luxury hotel built in
1930 to accommodate passengers of the At chison, Topeka and Santa
Fe Rail way. Once the town's very soul, the resort welcomed
well-heeled visitors from as far away as New York City, fed them,
lodged them and intro duced them to the Wild West.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the many Harvey Houses that dotted the countryside, it
was staffed by a bevy of hard-working women nicknamed for Fred
Harvey, the hospitality baron whose empire served America's
railroads.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1930s and '40s, the glamorous La Posada enjoyed a
whirlwind love affair with its neigh bors, serving as a community
center and point of pride for the city that was supposed to be
northern Arizo na's boomtown.
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday, the hotel welcomed the rich and famous: Clark
Gable and Carole Lombard, Douglas Fair banks and Mary Pickford,
Charles and Anne Morrow Lindbergh, Gary Cooper, Jimmy Durante, John
Wayne, Howard Hughes, Will Rog ers, Harry Truman, Franklin Roose
velt and Japanese royalty.
</P>
<P>
   But La Posada was not just for tourists. To the good people of
Winslow, it was a showplace where they could don their finery, dine
in elegance, have their photograph taken in front of a wishing well
and watch strangers pour from the trains that thundered into town.
</P>
<P>
   It must have been magnificent.
</P>
<P>
   Then fate turned cruel. Time and neglect devastated the
community. Like many a small town (population 10,000), Winslow
began to sustain the ravages of progress.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, upstart neighbor Flagstaff, home of North
ern Arizona University, surpassed Winslow and became the state's
gateway to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow's airport, in 1948 the largest commercial airport in Ari
zona _ three major runways and nine TWA transcontinental flights
landing every day _ was displaced by airstrips in bigger cities.
</P>
<P>
   Although La Posada's charm was undeniable, it was never much of
a moneymaker. With railway transpor tation on the decline, it
closed as a hotel in 1957, a scant 27 years after it opened.
</P>
<P>
   Route 66 once burrowed through downtown, drawing traffic and con
ferring celebrity status on cities along the famous cruiseway. In
1978, newly built Interstate 40 by passed the main streets of
Winslow, scuttling tourism and traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The town was nearly given over to the drunks who flopped outside
cowboy bars and dozed in the streets. Winslow seemed destined to go
the way of so many moribund hamlets stationed along Route 66.
</P>
<P>
   But like another famous Arizona city, Winslow was a town too
tough to die. A spark of life remained. Two women fanned that
spark, and flames ignited. Today, the commu nity again is poised to
take its place among choice Arizona destinations.
</P>
<P>
   The ghosts of the Harvey Girls have become guardian angels. Led
by a $5 million restoration of La Po sada, Winslow is being
rejuvenated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of the renaissance,'' says Marie LaMar, one of
the two women credited with helping to re vive Winslow. ``It's all
part of this huge effort to take back our town.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, Bill Elzey, mayor at the time, asked Janice Griffith,
curator of the town's Old Trails Museum, to save La Posada.
Griffith was shocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know it was in danger,'' she told Elzey.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, who has lived in Wins low since childhood, discovered
that the venerable property was indeed in danger. Headquarters of
the Santa Fe Railway since shutting down as a hotel, it had been
consigned to the company's ``disposal list.''
</P>
<P>
   A death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Its beauty faded, the former fa vorite of Hollywood stars had
fallen from grace _ lawns as dry as the desert, interior archways
filled in to create office space, splendid fur nishings long since
sold to buyers in Albuquerque. Even the wishing well was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith panicked.
</P>
<P>
   La Posada, she says, is ``the best thing we've got. It's a
landmark. It's a glorious place. We need it.''
</P>
<P>
   With four other concerned citi zens, including LaMar, Griffith
formed the La Posada Foundation. With help from a lawyer, she won
the hotel a spot on the National Registry of Historic Places. &QL; 
WINSLOW'S WHITE KNIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Then she began to look for a white knight. She found Allan Af
feldt.
</P>
<P>
   The energetic young man from Ir vine, Calif., had an
all-but-disserta tion doctorate in cognitive sciences, a background
as an international peace activist and an eye toward his toric
preservation. He had met his wife, artist Tina Mion, when she was a
member of an American peace delegation in the Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   He was also chairman of the board of EOS, an architectural think
tank concerned with eco-architec ture and sustainable resources.
When the National Registry pub lished its 1993 list of most endan
gered buildings, one entry, La Posada, caught his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Affeldt knew it had been de signed by Mary Elizabeth Jane
Colter, a reknowned architect who became Fred Harvey's lead
designer. She also had created such Harvey properties as Hopi
House, El Tovar and Phantom Ranch at the Grand Canyon, and La Fonda
in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was Affeldt's turn to panic. How could a Colter design
be marked for destruction? He and Mion jumped on a plane.
</P>
<P>
   In Griffith's eyes, Affeldt arrived in Winslow on a white horse.
She and her foundation had already fended off unsatisfactory offers
to turn La Posada into a military school, a college, a public
health service hospital and even _ gulp _ a casino.
</P>
<P>
   She met with and dismissed sev eral developers who didn't share
her vision of preserving La Posada's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid they'd turn it into a sushi bar,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But although she was wary of the worldly man from California _
``He was different from us'' _ she found his respect for La Posada
comforting.
</P>
<P>
   And, she says frankly, ``He was the only game in town.''
</P>
<P>
   With the promise of a $500,000 Department of Transportation-ad
ministered grant and an historic re habilitation tax credit,
Griffith welcomed Affeldt's decision to buy the property from the
railroad and restore it to its former glory. &QL; 
RETURNING TOWN'S SOUL
</P>
<P>
   As Affeldt began to implement his plan, the town held its
breath. Could La Posada become what it had once been _ the heart
and soul and livelihood of Winslow?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this has always been the thing that has been the
catalyst for resurrection,'' Griffith says. ``La Posada was a large
piece of Wins low's soul. As a historian, I'm con scious of what it
takes to sustain people. . . . What it takes is a sense of
community and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   When La Posada died, she says, ``The city lost a major chunk of
its soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Affeldt was determined to restore Winslow's soul. If he didn't
yet have all the money needed to complete the four-year project _
an esti mated $5 million, or five times that of its original
construction cost _ he certainly had the passion. He loved
beautiful buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's art,'' he says. ``I don't care if it's new or old.
There's no reason something you live in can't be art. We need that
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Posada is an extraordinary treasure. There's nothing like
this in northern Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   He embraced Colter's concept. For each property she designed,
she created an imaginary history. La Po sada, she fancied, had been
an 18th-century hacienda owned by a wealthy Spanish don. Guests of
the 75-room hotel were guests of the family.
</P>
<P>
   She established a carpentry shop on the premises where craftsmen
hand-fashioned the hotel's furniture. The interior was decorated
with reli gious icons _ not only Catholic symbols but artifacts
from the Ana zasi and Hopi cultures, tokens of pagan and Wica
worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very spiritualistic place,'' Affeldt says. ``There is a
sense of benevolence here. It's full of spiri tual energy.''
</P>
<P>
   After interviewing more than a dozen architectural firms,
Affeldt chose van dijk Pace Westlake, a Cleveland-based company
with of fices in Phoenix. The firm's exqui site renovation of the
Orpheum Theatre in downtown Phoenix im pressed him.
</P>
<P>
   The architects in turn were im pressed to find the hotel of
sound construction, thanks to Colter's in sistence on a sturdy
support system of reinforced concrete. What's miss ing is
compliance with some por tions of the Americans With Disabilities
Act. That will be cor rected. &QL; 
OPEN FOR BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   With about a third of its renova tion completed, La Posada is
trading in her railroad coveralls for her old party dress. Open for
business, the hotel boasts a remodeled lobby and public areas in
the Colter style. Lawns are green again. Furniture is once more
being crafted on site _ by Affeldt's brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   China used for the hotel's conti nental breakfast is a
reproduction of that used on the old AT&AMP;SF line and is inspired by
1,000-year-old Hopi designs. Along with other high-quality items
such as Indian crafts and T-shirts, pieces of the china are
available in the tiny hotel gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Six guest rooms _ including doubles and suites _ now welcome
guests. Within two months, an addi tional 17 will be available. By
the end of the year, a total of 40 rooms will be open.
</P>
<P>
   Savvy travelers can take advan tage of La Posada as a
work-in-progress: Current rates range from $65 to $85 per night.
The whole ho tel can be rented for special events for $1,000 a day.
</P>
<P>
   When restoration is complete, and La Posada becomes a boutique
hotel of 50 rooms, rates will reflect its luxury status.
</P>
<P>
   During the war, La Posada's din ing room catered to soldiers
heading across country on troop trains. Ci vilians were left to
forage at the nearby snack shop, where they could get a Spam
sandwich and chips for 25 cents, coffee for a nickel.
</P>
<P>
   When Santa Fe officials took over the property, they gutted the
dining room. Because an in-house restau rant is vital to any
upscale hotel, Affeldt is seeking a chef-restaura teur who could
fashion a kitchen to his own liking. Affeldt plans to have it
operating by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith and LaMar are hoping to bring back some of La Posada's
lost treasures. After the hotel closed, most of its furnishings
were sold in Albuquerque _ a quicker destina tion than Phoenix.
Their return would be appreciated, Griffith says.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith also has taken on the task of establishing a park,
Standing on the Corner Park _ at Second Street and Kinsley, just a
few blocks from the hotel. The park will commemo rate Take It Easy,
the song Jackson Browne wrote with Glenn Frey after a stopover in
town. It was recorded in 1972 by the pop group the Ea gles, of
which Frey was a member.
</P>
<P>
   The catchy opening line, ``Stand ing on a corner in Winslow,
Arizona . . .'' has drawn visitors from all over the world and
inspired the T-shirts Griffith sells at Old Trails Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Browne has promised to help dedicate the park when it opens.
</P>
<P>
   With two years to go before La Posada is fully restored, the
people of Winslow are already feeling pride in the possibilities it
brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the big thing happening in town now,'' says Affeldt,
who has hosted such on-property events as antique-car shows,
elder-hostel pro grams and crafts classes. ``It's not just
marketing. We want it to be a community center again.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffith sees Affeldt as a friend and savior who has endeared
him self to the residents of Winslow. Side by side one balmy night,
they chow down on home-cooked food at a potluck supper honoring a
woman born at La Posada 67 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Repelled by the misguided buyers she feared would destroy her be
loved resort, Griffith is gratified that Affeldt has not tried to
foist un conventional ideas on a town steeped in tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really is giving us the bene fit of his experience,'' she
says. `We've seen our landmark come back. We're pleased with what
we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The potluck that honors Patricia Dooms Flanigan welcomes back a
woman who lived for seven years at La Posada as the daughter of the
first general manager, Omar Dooms. When her father died in 1938,
she moved away but returned every summer until she was 14. She now
lives with her husband in Carthage, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   On a nostalgic visit to La Posada in 1965, she was dismayed to
find that her beautiful home had gone corporate. Lovely murals were
ob scured by dropped ceilings. Railroad clerks were working where
Harvey Girls once coddled guests.
</P>
<P>
   Crushed, Flanigan vowed never to return.
</P>
<P>
   Then she heard about the work Griffith and LaMar were doing. In
trigued, she told her husband she had to see for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to come back, and I had to come back now,'' she
says. ``It was pulling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her eyes sparkle as she looks around at the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incredible what has hap pened,'' she says. ``I can't
begin to tell you what joy I've seen in what is happening. It's
been an epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   Epiphanies do not come cheap. Affeldt is still seeking investors
to foot the bill for the remainder of his project. He promises that
time will reward their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   He is negotiating to buy and ren ovate the old opera house in
down town Winslow. And the former headquarters of the Hubbell
Trading Post, also downtown, is being pur chased by Winslow, which
will run it jointly as a museum with a Native American cooperative
and the origi nal donor of the land.
</P>
<P>
   Such urban renewal would cer tainly turn Winslow into a major
tourist destination, Affeldt says, ac commodating visitors headed
for Canyon de Chelly, the Painted Des ert, Monument Valley, the
Grand Canyon and Meteor Crater.
</P>
<P>
   The Sante Fe (now merged with the Burlington Northern) continues
to operate out of a wing at La Po sada and runs 90 freight trains
through town every day. Amtrak op erates a passenger line that
stops twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a city on the slide for many years,'' Affeldt says.
``We had to convince people that not only La Posada but the city
was worth sav ing. If this all gets done, this real estate
quadruples in five years.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMar, a retired real-estate bro ker whose mother was a Harvey
Girl at the Havasu in Seligman, finds her town's rebirth something
of a miracle. Once despairing, she feels Winslow's soul is now in
safe hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision is coming back. La Posada is an example of how a
com munity wants to feel good about it self and how the people have
supported it,'' she says. ``We are the stewards of what we have.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
